tions===\n{{Certification Table Top}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=Italy|type=single|artist=David Bowie|title=Heroes|award=Gold|certyear=2016|salesamount=7,500|certref=<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fimi.it/app/uploads/GfK_Certificazioni-Single-Digital_wk-01-2016.pdf |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160117100122/http://www.fimi.it/app/uploads/GfK_Certificazioni-Single-Digital_wk-01-2016.pdf |language=Italian |access-date=17 January 2016 |archivedate=17 January 2016 |format=PDF |title=Certificazione Singoli Digitali dalla settimana 1 del 2010 alla settimana 1 del 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=United Kingdom|type=single|artist=David Bowie|title=Heroes|award=Platinum|salesamount=600,000|relyear=1977|certyear=2020}}<ref>https://www.bpi.co.uk/bpi-awards/ {{Webarchive|url=https://www.webcitation.org/5mr0Evm3j?url=http://www.bpi.co.uk/certifiedawards/search.aspx |date=17 January 2010 }} type david bowie heroes and search</ref>\n{{Certification Table Bottom|nosales=true|noshipments=true|streaming=true}}\n\n==Live versions==\n* Prior to the single release of {{\"'}}Heroes{{'\"}}, Bowie first performed the song on the final episode of friend [[Marc Bolan|Marc Bolan's]] [[Granada Television]] series ''[[Marc (TV series)|Marc]]'' (filmed 7 September 1977, broadcast 28 September 1977,<ref name=\"Davidbowie.com\">{{cite news|url=http://www.davidbowie.com/news/heroes-single-forty-years-old-today-57331|title='Heroes' single is forty years old today|date=23 September 2017|work=Davidbowie.com|accessdate=23 September 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170929111200/http://www.davidbowie.com/news/heroes-single-forty-years-old-today-57331|archive-date=29 September 2017|url-status=}}</ref> after Bolan's funeral). This particular version, released as a 7\" picture disc, on 22 September 2017,<ref name=\"Davidbowie.com\"/> has an alternate backing track that was recorded with Bolan playing lead guitar and the [[T.Rex (band)|T.Rex]] line up of [[Dino Dines]] on keyboards, and the rhythm section of [[Herbie Flowers]] on bass and [[Tony Newman (drummer)|Tony Newman]] on drums.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Campbell|first1=Irving|title=A Guide to the Outtakes of Marc Bolan|date=2007|publisher=Great Horse|location=Wellington, New Zealand|isbn=978-0-473-12076-4|page=179|edition=1<!-- |accessdate=6 August 2015 -->}}</ref> Coincidentally, prior to joining T.Rex, Flowers and Newman were a part of Bowie's rhythm section on the ''[[Diamond Dogs]]'' album and [[Diamond Dogs Tour|its tour]], documented on the live album ''[[David Live]]''.\n* Bowie performed the song when he appeared on [[Bing Crosby|Bing Crosby's]] 1977 [[Christmas]] TV special, ''[[Bing Crosby's Merrie Olde Christmas]]''. In the performance, filmed on 11 September 1977, Bowie sang over a prerecorded backing track.\n* Performances from the [[Isolar II \u2013 The 1978 World Tour|Isolar II Tour]] have been released on ''[[Stage (David Bowie album)|Stage]]'' (1978) and ''[[Welcome to the Blackout (Live London '78)|Welcome to the Blackout]]'' (2018).<ref>{{cite web |last1=Erlewine |first1=Stephen Thomas |authorlink1=Stephen Thomas Erlewine |title=''Stage'' \u2013 David Bowie |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/stage-mw0000193055 |publisher=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=12 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190805090901/https://www.allmusic.com/album/stage-mw0000193055 |archive-date=5 August 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Erlewine |first1=Stephen Thomas |authorlink1=Stephen Thomas Erlewine |title=''Welcome to the Blackout (Live London '78)'' \u2013 David Bowie |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/welcome-to-the-blackout-live-london-78-mw0003173016 |publisher=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=12 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191117143206/https://www.allmusic.com/album/welcome-to-the-blackout-live-london-78-mw0003173016 |archive-date=17 November 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* Bowie performed the song live on his [[Serious Moonlight Tour]] in 1983, as seen in [[Serious Moonlight (1983 film)|the 1984 concert video of that tour]] and as heard on the live album ''Serious Moonlight (Live '83)'', which was part of the 2018 box set ''[[Loving the Alien (1983\u20131988)]]'' and was released separately in 2019.\n* The rendition at [[Live Aid]] in 1985 has been described as \"the best version of 'Heroes' [Bowie] had ever sung\".<ref>David Buckley (1999). Op Cit: p.424</ref> This performance featured [[Thomas Dolby]] on keyboards.\n* Bowie performed the song live on his [[Glass Spider Tour]], as seen in [[Glass Spider|the 1988 concert video of that tour]].\n* The song was performed at [[The Freddie Mercury Tribute Concert]] in 1992 by Bowie, [[Mick Ronson]] and [[Brian May]], [[Roger Taylor (Queen drummer)|Roger Taylor]], and [[John Deacon]] \u2013 the surviving members of [[Queen (band)|Queen]].\n* An acoustic version of the song was played in 1996 at The Bridge School Benefit Concert at the Shoreline Amphitheater in Mountain View, California, and later released on ''The Bridge School Benefit Concert'' album.\n* Bowie's 25 June 2000 performance of the song at the [[Glastonbury Festival]] was released in 2018 on ''[[Glastonbury 2000]]''.\n* The song was performed by Bowie at [[The Concert for New York City]] on 20 October 2001. Before Bowie opened the concert he was asked to perform {{\"'}}Heroes{{'\"}}. He said it wasn't appropriate as it was a love song, so he opened with a solo version of Paul Simon's \"America\", and then performed {{\"'}}Heroes{{'\"}} with the house band led by Paul Shaffer.\n* Bowie performed the song live during the [[A Reality Tour]] in 2003, and a performance from November of that year was released on [[A Reality Tour (film)|a DVD]] in 2004, and later on [[A Reality Tour (album)|an album]], released in 2010.\n\n==Other releases==\n* The edited 7-inch single, running at 3:32 mins and backed with \"V-2 Schneider\", was released separately in English, French (''\u00abH\u00e9ros\u00bb'') and German (''\u201eHelden\u201c''). All three of these cuts plus \"V-2 Schneider\" were released together as an Australian 4-track 7-inch.\n* The complete English version as it appeared on the album was released as a Spanish [[12-inch single]].\n* A version featuring the German single edit spliced into the second half of the full-length English track (''\"Heroes\"/\u201eHelden\u201c'') appeared on the German pressing of the LP and is also available on Bowie's [[Christiane F. (album)|soundtrack]] to the film ''[[Christiane F.&nbsp;\u2013 Wir Kinder vom Bahnhof Zoo|Christiane F.]]'' and on the ''[[Rare (David Bowie album)|Rare]]'' album.  A corresponding English/French version (''\"Heroes\"/\u00abH\u00e9ros\u00bb'') appeared on the French pressing of the LP.\n* The song has appeared, almost invariably in single edit form, on numerous Bowie compilations:\n** ''Chameleon'' (Australia and New Zealand 1979)\n** ''[[Best of Bowie (1980 version)|The Best of Bowie]]'' (1980)\n** ''[[Fame and Fashion]]'' (1984) \u2013 album version\n** ''[[Sound + Vision (box set)|Sound + Vision]]'' (1989) \u2013 ''\u201eHelden\u201c''\n** ''[[Changesbowie]]'' (1990)\n** ''[[Bowie: The Singles 1969-1993]]'' (1993)\n** ''[[The Singles Collection (David Bowie album)|The Singles Collection]]'' (1993)\n** ''[[The Best of David Bowie 1974/1979]]'' (1998)\n** ''[[Best of Bowie]]'' (2002) \u2013 ''\u201eHelden\u201c'' on German/Swiss/Austrian edition\n** ''[[The Platinum Collection (David Bowie album)|The Platinum Collection]]'' (2005/2006)\n** ''[[Nothing Has Changed]]'' (2014)\n** ''[[Bowie Legacy]]'' (2016)\n* It was released as a picture disc in the [[RCA Records|RCA]] ''Life Time'' picture disc set.\n* The German (''\u201eHelden\u201c'') and French (''\u00abH\u00e9ros\u00bb'') versions of the single, as well as the English/German (''\"Heroes\"/\u201eHelden\u201c'') and English/French (\"Heroes\"/\u00abH\u00e9ros\u00bb) versions of the album track, were included on an [[Extended play|EP]] in the 2017 boxed set ''[[A New Career in a New Town (1977\u20131982)]]''. The single version of the song was included on ''Re:Call 3'', part of the same compilation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.davidbowie.com/news/new-career-new-town-1977-1982-57146|title=A NEW CAREER IN A NEW TOWN (1977 \u2013 1982) - David Bowie Latest News|date=22 July 2016|publisher=DavidBowie.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170728195724/http://www.davidbowie.com/news/new-career-new-town-1977-1982-57146|archive-date=28 July 2017|url-status=|accessdate=29 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Cover versions==\n* [[Oasis (band)|Oasis]] recorded a version of the song as a B-Side for the lead single, [[D'You Know What I Mean?]] to the album [[Be Here Now (album)|Be Here Now]].\n* [[The Wallflowers]] recorded a version of the song for the [[Godzilla: The Album|soundtrack]] to the 1998 film ''[[Godzilla (1998 film)|Godzilla]]''. This version peaked at number 10 on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Alternative Songs|Modern Rock Tracks]] chart in 1998, as well as number 27 on the ''Billboard'' [[Hot 100 Airplay]] chart and number 23 on the ''Billboard'' [[Top 40 Mainstream]] chart.<ref>[http://www.billboard.com/charts/1998-05-23/alternative-songs Alternative Songs] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140703013147/http://www.billboard.com/charts/1998-05-23/alternative-songs |date=3 July 2014 }}. Billboard.com. Retrieved 11 August 2012.</ref>\n* The 2001 musical film ''[[Moulin Rouge!]]'' includes a duet cover version from [[Ewan McGregor]] and [[Nicole Kidman]] as the penultimate song in the \"Elephant Love Medley\".\n*Swiss Metal band [[Celtic Frost]] recorded a cover of the song for their 1990 album ''[[Vanity/Nemesis]]''.\n* [[Apocalyptica]] recorded {{\"'}}Helden{{'\"}}, the German version of the song for their album ''[[Worlds Collide (Apocalyptica album)|Worlds Collide]]'' (2007), featuring [[Till Lindemann]] of [[Rammstein]] on vocals.\n* For the 2009 benefit album ''[[War Child Presents Heroes]]'', [[TV on the Radio]] recorded a version after Bowie himself nominated the band to cover it, in keeping with the album's theme of \"placing faith in the next generation\".\n* ''[[The X Factor (UK TV series)|The X Factor]]'' [[List of The X Factor finalists (UK series 7)|finalists]] released a version for charity in 2010, which reached number one on the [[Irish Singles Chart|Irish]], [[Scottish Singles and Albums Charts|Scottish]] and [[UK Singles Chart]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.chart-track.co.uk/index.jsp?c=p%2Fmusicvideo%2Fmusic%2Farchive%2Findex_test.jsp&ct=240001&arch=t&lyr=2010&year=2010&week=47 |title=Top 100 Singles, Week Ending 25 November 2010 |publisher=[[Chart-Track]] |accessdate=7 December 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303180011/http://www.chart-track.co.uk/index.jsp?c=p%2Fmusicvideo%2Fmusic%2Farchive%2Findex_test.jsp&ct=240001&arch=t&lyr=2010&year=2010&week=47 |archive-date=3 March 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/charts/scottish-singles-chart/20101128/41/|title=Official Scottish Singles Sales Chart Top 100 28 November 2010 - 04 December 2010|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=11 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161010061318/http://www.officialcharts.com/charts/scottish-singles-chart/20101128/41/|archive-date=10 October 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/charts/singles-chart/20101128/7501/|title=Official Singles Chart Top 100 28 November 2010 - 04 December 2010|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=11 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160203150742/http://www.officialcharts.com/charts/singles-chart/20101128/7501/|archive-date=3 February 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* [[Peter Gabriel]] released an orchestral reinterpretation for his 2010 album ''[[Scratch My Back]]'', also appearing in the third episode of the first season and the eighth episode of the third season of the [[Netflix]] series ''[[Stranger Things]]'' and on the official soundtrack, and on the soundtrack for the film ''[[Lone Survivor]]''.\n* In [[The X Factor U.S.]], finalists [[Melanie Amaro]] and [[Josh Krajcik]] covered this song as a duet.\n* In 2014, actress [[Jessica Lange]] recorded a cover of the song for the season finale of ''[[American Horror Story: Freak Show]]'' entitled \"[[Curtain Call (American Horror Story)|Curtain Call]]\".\n* [[Depeche Mode]] released an official cover and video for the 40th anniversary of the song's release, with lead singer [[Dave Gahan]] stating, \"Bowie is the one artist who I've stuck with since I was in my early teens. His albums are always my go-to on tour and covering {{'\"}}Heroes{{\"'}} is paying homage to Bowie.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Trendell|first1=Andrew|title=Depeche Mode share official cover of David Bowie\u2019s \"Heroes\" to mark track\u2019s 40th anniversary|url=http://www.nme.com/news/depeche-mode-share-official-cover-david-bowies-heroes-mark-tracks-40th-anniversary-2143717|work=[[NME]]|date=22 September 2017|access-date=22 September 2017|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6Py4HGol5?url=http://www.allaccess.com/hot-modern-ac/future-releases|archive-date=30 May 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* [[King Crimson]] recorded a version for their five-track EP ''Heroes: Live in Europe 2016''.<ref>{{cite web | url= http://teamrock.com/news/2017-04-28/king-crimson-to-release-ep-featuring-david-bowies-heroes | title= King Crimson to release EP featuring David Bowie\u2019s Heroes | work= teamrock.com | date= 28 April 2017 | accessdate= 25 September 2017 | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20170926095720/http://teamrock.com/news/2017-04-28/king-crimson-to-release-ep-featuring-david-bowies-heroes | archive-date= 26 September 2017 | url-status= live }}</ref> It won \"Video of the Year\" at the 2017 [[Prog (magazine)|Progressive Music Awards]].<ref>{{cite web | url= http://teamrock.com/news/2017-09-15/marillion-anathema-steve-hackett-among-progressive-music-award-winners | title= Marillion, Anathema, Steve Hackett among Progressive Music Award winners | work= teamrock.com | date= 14 September 2017 | accessdate= 25 September 2017 | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180322173853/http://teamrock.com/news/2017-09-15/marillion-anathema-steve-hackett-among-progressive-music-award-winners | archive-date= 22 March 2018 | url-status= live }}</ref>\n* [[Coldplay]] performed the song as a tribute to Bowie on their [[A Head Full of Dreams Tour]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/7439089/coldplay-head-full-of-dreams-stadium-farewell-tour-chris-martin-david-bowie-metlife-stadium | title=Coldplay Launches A Head Full of Dreams Tour With Vivid Colors, Multiple Stages, David Bowie Tribute & More | work=billboard.com | date=17 July 2016 | accessdate=18 June 2018 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180618084346/https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/7439089/coldplay-head-full-of-dreams-stadium-farewell-tour-chris-martin-david-bowie-metlife-stadium | archive-date=18 June 2018 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n* [[Mot\u00f6rhead]] released official cover for their 2017 album ''[[Under C\u00f6ver]]''.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Daly|first1=Rhian|title=Listen to Mot\u00f6rhead\u2019s cover of David Bowie's 'Heroes'|url=http://www.nme.com/news/music/listen-motorhead-david-bowie-cover-heroes-2120658|work=[[NME]]|date=23 November 2017|access-date=23 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201033122/http://www.nme.com/news/music/listen-motorhead-david-bowie-cover-heroes-2120658|archive-date=1 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*[[Blondie (band)|Blondie]] covered {{\"'}}Heroes{{'\"}} on the album ''Uncut 2003.03: Starman''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://musicbrainz.org/release/f7dfaccb-ed66-4663-84ab-3385cb9ada3c |title=Archived copy |access-date=31 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181031214832/https://musicbrainz.org/release/f7dfaccb-ed66-4663-84ab-3385cb9ada3c |archive-date=31 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n*[[Gang of Youths]] released a cover of {{\"'}}Heroes{{'\"}} as a non-album single,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/au/album/heroes-single/1294149479|title=Heroes \u2013 single|website=iTunes Australia|accessdate=15 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180416073529/https://itunes.apple.com/au/album/heroes-single/1294149479|archive-date=16 April 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> featured in the trailer for the 2017 film ''[[Justice League (2017 film)|Justice League]]''.\n*[[Hollywood Vampires (band)|Hollywood Vampires]], a supergroup featuring [[Alice Cooper]], [[Joe Perry (musician)|Joe Perry]], and [[Johnny Depp]], released a cover of {{\"'}}Heroes{{'\"}} on their 2019 album ''Rise'', with Depp performing lead vocals for the track.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/rise/1459328488 |title=Archived copy |access-date=25 June 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190704102318/https://music.apple.com/us/album/rise/1459328488 |archive-date=4 July 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n;Notes\n{{Notelist}}\n\n;Citations\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n;Sources\n* {{Cite book|last=Buckley|first=David|title=Strange Fascination \u2013 David Bowie: The Definitive Story|year=2000|origyear=1999|publisher=Virgin|location=London|isbn=0-7535-0457-X}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Carr|first=Roy|authorlink=Roy Carr|author2=Murray, Charles Shaar|author2-link=Charles Shaar Murray|title=David Bowie: An Illustrated Record|year=1981|publisher=Avon|location=New York|isbn=0-380-77966-8}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Pegg|first=Nicholas|authorlink=Nicholas Pegg|title=The Complete David Bowie|year=2004|origyear=2000|publisher=Reynolds & Hearn|location=London|isbn=1-903111-14-5}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|david-bowie|heroes}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{David Bowie singles}}\n{{The Wallflowers}}\n{{Children in Need}}\n{{The X Factor}}\n{{Gang of Youths}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Heroes}}\n[[Category:1977 singles]]\n[[Category:Song recordings with Wall of Sound arrangements]]\n[[Category:David Bowie songs]]\n[[Category:Gang of Youths songs]]\n[[Category:Interscope Records singles]]\n[[Category:Irish Singles Chart number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Oasis (band) songs]]\n[[Category:RCA Records singles]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by David Bowie]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Tony Visconti]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Brian Eno]]\n[[Category:Songs written by David Bowie]]\n[[Category:Songs about Berlin]]\n[[Category:Berlin Wall in fiction]]\n[[Category:The Wallflowers songs]]\n[[Category:The X Factor (British TV series)]]\n[[Category:UK Singles Chart number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Protest songs]]\n[[Category:1977 songs]]\n", "text_old": "{{Redirect|\"Heroes\" (song)|other songs of the same name|Heroes (disambiguation)#Songs{{!}}Heroes}}\n{{pp-move-indef|small=yes}}\n{{short description|1977 song by David Bowie}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=January 2020}}\n{{use British English|date=May 2013}}\n{{Infobox song\n| name       = {{-'}}Heroes{{'-}}\n| cover      = Heroes by David Bowie UK vinyl single.jpg\n| border     = yes\n| caption    = One of A-side labels of UK vinyl single\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[David Bowie]]\n| album      = [[\"Heroes\" (David Bowie album)|\"Heroes\"]]\n| B-side     = [[V-2 Schneider]]\n| released   = {{Start date|1977|09|23|df=yes}}\n| format     = {{hlist|[[7-inch single|7-inch]]|[[12-inch single|12-inch]]}}\n| recorded   = July\u2013August 1977\n| studio     = [[Hansa Tonstudio|Hansa Studio by the Wall]] (West Berlin)\n| genre      = <!--Please source any added genres in the prose-->[[Art rock]]\n| length     = {{unbulleted list|{{Duration|m=6|s=07}} (album)|{{Duration|m=3|s=32}} (single)}}\n| label      = [[RCA Records|RCA]]\n| writer     = {{hlist|David Bowie|[[Brian Eno]]}}\n| producer   = {{hlist|David Bowie|[[Tony Visconti]]}}\n| prev_title = [[Be My Wife]]\n| prev_year  = 1977\n| next_title = [[Beauty and the Beast (David Bowie song)|Beauty and the Beast]]\n| next_year  = 1978\n| misc       = {{External music video|{{YouTube|lXgkuM2NhYI|{{\"'}}Heroes{{'\"}} }}\n }}\n}}\n\n\"'''{{-'}}Heroes{{'-}}'''\"{{efn|The quotation marks are part of the title. On some single releases, the title does not include the quotes.}} is a song by English musician [[David Bowie]]. It was co-written by Bowie and [[Brian Eno]], produced by Bowie and [[Tony Visconti]], and recorded in July and August 1977 at [[Hansa Tonstudio|Hansa Studio by the Wall]]. It was released on 23 September 1977 as the lead single from his [[\"Heroes\" (David Bowie album)|12th studio album of the same name]], backed with the song \"[[V-2 Schneider]]\". A product of Bowie's [[Berlin Trilogy|\"Berlin\" period]], the track was not a huge hit in the United Kingdom or United States after its release, but it has since become one of his [[signature song]]s. In January 2016, following Bowie's death, the song reached a new peak of number 12 in the [[UK Singles Chart]]. {{\"'}}Heroes{{'\"}} has been cited as Bowie's second-most covered song after \"[[Rebel Rebel]]\".<ref name=\"The Complete David Bowie\">[[Nicholas Pegg]] (2000). ''The Complete David Bowie'': pp. 90\u201392</ref>\n\nInspired by the sight of Bowie's producer-engineer Tony Visconti embracing his lover by the [[Berlin Wall]], the song tells the story of two lovers, one from [[East Berlin|East]] and one from [[West Berlin]]. Bowie's performance of {{\"'}}Heroes{{'\"}} on [[Berlin Wall#David Bowie, 1987|June 6, 1987]], at the German [[Reichstag building|Reichstag]] in [[West Berlin]] has been considered a catalyst to the later [[fall of the Berlin Wall]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2016/01/david-bowie-death/423483/|work=The Atlantic|last=Ford|first=Matt|accessdate=11 January 2016|date=11 January 2016|title=Remembering David Bowie|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160112083919/http://www.theatlantic.com/entertainment/archive/2016/01/david-bowie-death/423483/|archive-date=12 January 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.vox.com/2016/1/11/10749546/david-bowie-berlin-wall-heroes|work=Vox|last=Fisher|first=Max|accessdate=11 January 2016|date=11 January 2016|title=David Bowie at the Berlin Wall: the incredible story of a concert and its role in history|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160113052820/http://www.vox.com/2016/1/11/10749546/david-bowie-berlin-wall-heroes|archive-date=13 January 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.the-berlin-wall.com/videos/david-bowie-plays-berlin-711/|publisher=Rundfunk Berlin-Brandenburg|accessdate=11 January 2016|date=9 November 2014|title=The Berlin Wall \u2013 A multimedia history: David Bowie plays Berlin|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160114015829/http://www.the-berlin-wall.com/videos/david-bowie-plays-berlin-711/|archive-date=14 January 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Following his [[Death of David Bowie|death]] in January 2016, the German government thanked Bowie for \"helping to bring down the Wall\", adding \"you are now among Heroes\".<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://foreignpolicy.com/2016/01/11/germany-to-david-bowie-thank-you-for-helping-to-bring-down-the-berlin-wall/ |title=Germany to David Bowie: Thank You for Helping to Bring Down the Berlin Wall |magazine=Foreign Policy |date=11 January 2016 |accessdate=12 October 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161004130922/http://foreignpolicy.com/2016/01/11/germany-to-david-bowie-thank-you-for-helping-to-bring-down-the-berlin-wall/ |archive-date=4 October 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n{{\"'}}Heroes{{'\"}} has received numerous accolades since its release, as seen with its inclusion on lists ranking the \"greatest songs\" compiled by various music publications; ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' named the song the 46th greatest ever, and ''[[NME]]'' named it the 15th greatest.<ref>{{cite magazine | url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/lists/the-500-greatest-songs-of-all-time-20110407/david-bowie-heroes-20110525 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050101013301/http://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/_/id/6596661/500songs|archive-date=1 January 2005|title=The 500 Greatest Songs of All Time \u2013 November 2003|accessdate=26 September 2016 |magazine=Rolling Stone}}</ref><ref name=\"NME500\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rocklistmusic.co.uk/nme_500_greatest_songs_2014.htm|accessdate=15 February 2016|work=NME|title=NME The 500 Greatest Songs of All Time, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160218133410/http://www.rocklistmusic.co.uk/nme_500_greatest_songs_2014.htm|archive-date=18 February 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Pitchfork Media\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rocklistmusic.co.uk/steveparker/pitchfork.htm|title=The Pitchfork 500: Our Guide to the Greatest Songs from Punk to the Present|accessdate=15 January 2016|publisher=Pitchfork Media|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160108135757/http://www.rocklistmusic.co.uk/steveparker/Pitchfork.htm|archive-date=8 January 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Bowie scholar David Buckley has written that {{\"'}}Heroes{{'\"}} \"is perhaps pop's definitive statement of the potential triumph of the human spirit over adversity\".<ref>{{cite book|author=David Buckley|title=David Bowie: The Music and The Changes|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lboSCgAAQBAJ&pg=PT63|year=2015|publisher=Omnibus Press|isbn=978-1-78323-617-6|page=63|access-date=22 August 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302054741/https://books.google.com/books?id=lboSCgAAQBAJ&pg=PT63|archive-date=2 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Title and lyrics==\nThe song title is a reference to the 1975 track \"[[Neu! '75|Hero]]\" by German [[krautrock]] band [[Neu!]],<ref>Mat Snow (2007). \"Making Heroes\", ''[[Mojo (magazine)|MOJO]] 60 Years of Bowie'': p.69</ref> whom Bowie and Eno admired. It was one of the early tracks recorded during the album sessions, but remained an instrumental until towards the end of production.<ref name=\"The Complete David Bowie\"/> The quotation marks in the title of the song, a deliberate affectation, were designed to impart [[Scare quotes|an ironic quality]] on the otherwise romantic or triumphant words and music.<ref name=\"Bowie: An Illustrated Record\">[[Roy Carr]] & [[Charles Shaar Murray]] (1981). ''Bowie: An Illustrated Record'': pp.90\u201392</ref><ref>Robert Matthew-Walker ''David Bowie, theatre of music'' 1985 p46 \"The use of quotation marks possibly implies that the \"Heroes\" are not to be taken too seriously.\"</ref><ref>Chris Welch ''David Bowie: changes, 1970\u20131980'' 1999 p116 \"The use of quotation marks around the title meant that Bowie felt there was something ironic about being a rock 'n' roll hero to his fans, while he kept his own emotional life as far distant and remote and private as possible.\"</ref><ref>[http://members.ol.com.au/rgriffin/GoldenYears/Heroes.html ''NME'' interview in 1977 with Charles Shaar Murray] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070703073201/http://members.ol.com.au/rgriffin/GoldenYears/Heroes.html |date=3 July 2007 }}. Retrieved from ''Bowie: Golden Years'' 20 February 2007.</ref>\n\nProducer [[Tony Visconti]] took credit for inspiring the image of the lovers kissing \"by [[Berlin Wall|the wall]]\", when he and backing vocalist Antonia Maass ''(Maa\u00df)'' embraced in front of Bowie as he looked out of the [[Hansa Tonstudio|Hansa Studio]] window.<ref name=\"Strange Fascination\">David Buckley (1999). ''Strange Fascination \u2013 David Bowie: The Definitive Story'': pp.323\u2013326</ref> Bowie claimed that the protagonists were based on an anonymous young couple, but Visconti, who was married to [[Mary Hopkin]] at the time, contends that Bowie was protecting him and his affair with Maass. Bowie confirmed this in 2003, over two decades after Visconti and Hopkin's eventual divorce.<ref name=\"The Complete David Bowie\" />\n\n==Music==\nBowie said that the \"plodding tempo and rhythm\" were inspired by the [[The Velvet Underground|Velvet Underground]] song \"[[I'm Waiting for the Man]]\".<ref>{{cite book|last1=Buckley|first1=DAvid|title=Strange Fascination: David Bowie: The Definitive Story|date=2005|publisher=Virgin Books|isbn=978-0753510025|page=280|edition=Revised|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vk-I_ZM_PfwC&pg=PA280|access-date=20 May 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307014430/https://books.google.com/books?id=vk-I_ZM_PfwC&pg=PA280|archive-date=7 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nRichard Buskin of ''[[Sound on Sound]]'' described {{\"'}}Heroes{{'\"}} as a \"highly [[Experimental music|experimental]] piece of [[art rock]]\".<ref name=\":0\" /> The music, co-written by Bowie and Eno, has been likened to a [[Wall of Sound]] production, a forceful and noisy arrangement of guitars, percussion and synthesizers.<ref name=\"Strange Fascination\" /> Eno said the song always \"sounded grand and heroic\" and that he had \"that very word \u2013 heroes \u2013 in my mind\" even before Bowie wrote the lyrics.<ref name=\"The Complete David Bowie\" /> The backing track consists of a conventional arrangement of [[piano]], [[bass guitar]], rhythm [[guitar]] and [[Drum kit|drums]]. The other parts consist of [[synthesizer]] parts by Eno using an [[Electronic Music Studios (London) Ltd|EMS]] [[VCS3]] to produce detuned low-frequency drones, with the beat frequencies from the three [[oscillators]], producing a juddering effect. In addition, [[King Crimson]] guitarist [[Robert Fripp]] generated an unusual sustained sound by allowing his guitar to [[Audio feedback|feed back]] and sitting at different positions in the room to alter the [[pitched feedback|pitch of the feedback]]. Visconti mixed out Dennis Davis' [[Bass drum|kick drum]], stating that the track \"seemed to plod\" with it but had a more energetic feel without it.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n===Vocal gating progression===\nBowie's vocal was recorded with a \"multi-latch\" system devised by Visconti that creatively misused [[noise gate|gating]].<ref>Hodgson, Jay (2010). ''Understanding'', p.88. {{ISBN|978-1-4411-5607-5}}.</ref> Three microphones were used to capture the vocal, with one microphone nine inches from Bowie, one 20&nbsp;feet away and one 50&nbsp;feet away. Each microphone was muted as the next one was triggered. As the music built, Bowie was forced to sing at increased volumes to overcome the gating effect, leading to an increasingly impassioned vocal performance as the song progresses.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite magazine | url=http://www.soundonsound.com/sos/Oct04/articles/classictracks.htm | title=Classic Tracks: Heroes | magazine=[[Sound on Sound]] | date=October 2004 | accessdate=17 November 2018 | author=Buskin, Richard | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160526195658/http://www.soundonsound.com/sos/Oct04/articles/classictracks.htm | archive-date=26 May 2016 | url-status=live }}</ref> Jay Hodgson writes, ''\"Bowie's performance thus grows in intensity precisely as ever more ambience infuses his delivery until, by the final verse, he has to shout just to be heard&nbsp;... The more Bowie shouts just to be heard, in fact, the further back in the mix Visconti's multi-latch system pushes his vocal tracks, creating a stark metaphor for the situation of Bowie's doomed lovers\"''.<ref>Hodgson (2010), p.89.</ref>\n\n==Release==\n{{\"'}}Heroes{{'\"}} was released in a variety of languages and lengths (\"a collector's [[wet dream]]\" in the words of ''[[NME]]'' editors [[Roy Carr]] and [[Charles Shaar Murray]]<ref name=\"Bowie: An Illustrated Record\"/>). In contrast to the bewildering audio situation, the video (directed by [[Nicholas Ferguson|Nick Ferguson]]<ref name=\"The Complete David Bowie\"/>) was a stark and simple affair, the singer captured performing the song in what appeared to be a single take with multiple cameras, swaying in front of a spotlight that created a monotone and near-silhouette effect.\n\n==Reception and legacy==\nDespite a large promotional push, including Bowie's first live ''[[Top of the Pops]]'' appearance since 1973,<ref name=\"Strange Fascination\"/> {{\"'}}Heroes{{'\"}} reached only number 24 in the UK charts, and failed to make the US [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]].\nIn Italy, the song was certified gold by the [[Federation of the Italian Music Industry]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fimi.it/up/files/pdfddm/GfK_Certificazioni%20Single%20Digital_wk%2002-2014.pdf |publisher=[[Federation of the Italian Music Industry]] |language=Italian |accessdate=19 January 2014 |archivedate=19 January 2014 |title=Certificazione Singoli Digitali dalla settimana 1 del 2009 alla settimana 2 del 2014 |format=PDF |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/6MkO3thjx?url=http://www.fimi.it/up/files/pdfddm/GfK_Certificazioni%20Single%20Digital_wk%2002-2014.pdf |url-status=live  }}</ref>\n\nWriting for ''NME'' on its release, [[Charlie Gillett]] slated the record, saying: \"Well he had a pretty good run for our money, for a guy who was no singer. But I think his time has been and gone, and this just sounds weary. Then again, maybe the ponderous heavy riff will be absorbed on the radio, and the monotonous feel may just be hypnotic enough to drag people into buying it. I hope not.\"<ref>{{cite journal|last=Gillett|first=Charlie|date=15 October 1977|title=Singles reviews|journal=NME|pages=12\u201313}}</ref> Despite the poor review it featured at number 6 in the NME's end of year critics poll for 1977.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rocklistmusic.co.uk/1977.html|title=NME Singles 1977|publisher=Rocklistmusic.co.uk|accessdate=21 September 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171009064051/http://www.rocklistmusic.co.uk/1977.html|archive-date=9 October 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nLater assessments were more favourable. In February 1999, ''[[Q (magazine)|Q]]'' magazine listed {{\"'}}Heroes{{'\"}} as one of the 100 greatest singles of all time as voted by the readers. In March 2005, the same magazine placed it at number 56 in its list of the 100 Greatest Guitar Tracks. In 2004, ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' rated {{\"'}}Heroes{{'\"}} number 46 in its list of [[The 500 Greatest Songs of All Time]]. It was included in 2008's ''The [[Pitchfork Media]] 500: Our Guide to the Greatest Songs from Punk to the Present''.  John J. Miller of ''[[National Review]]'' rated {{\"'}}Heroes{{'\"}} number 21 on a list of \"the 50 greatest [[conservative]] rock songs\"<ref>John J. Miller (26 May 2006). [http://www.nationalreview.com/article/217737/rockin-right-john-j-miller \"Rockin' the Right\", ''National Review Online''] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150630202528/http://www.nationalreview.com/article/217737/rockin-right-john-j-miller |date=30 June 2015 }}. Retrieved 20 February 2007.</ref> due to its [[anti-Soviet]] political context. It has also become a [[gay anthem]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ephemeralmag.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/Natasha-Eves.pdf|title=I\u2019m Not Perfect: the role of Grace Jones and David Bowie in aiding the dissemination of queer subjectivities|last=Eves|first=Natasha|date=December 2015|work=Ephemeral Magazine|publisher=Goldsmiths, University of London|accessdate=11 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304113914/http://ephemeralmag.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/12/Natasha-Eves.pdf|archive-date=4 March 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.laweekly.com/news/queer-town-the-gay-wedding-in-beverly-hills-2386735|title=Queer Town: The Gay Wedding in Beverly Hills|last=McDonald|first=Patrick Range|date=16 June 2008|newspaper=LA Weekly|accessdate=11 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304115221/http://www.laweekly.com/news/queer-town-the-gay-wedding-in-beverly-hills-2386735|archive-date=4 March 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> ''[[Uncut (magazine)|Uncut]]'' placed {{\"'}}Heroes{{'\"}} at number 1 in its 30 greatest Bowie songs in 2008.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.uncut.co.uk/features/david-bowies-30-best-songs-66458|title=David Bowie's 30 best songs|date=March 2008|work=Uncut|accessdate=11 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160224185624/http://www.uncut.co.uk/features/david-bowies-30-best-songs-66458|archive-date=24 February 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n[[Moby]] has said that {{\"'}}Heroes{{'\"}} is one of his favourite songs ever written, calling it \"inevitable\" that his music would be influenced by the song,<ref name=EW02>{{Citation | last = Gordinier | first = Jeff| title = Loving the Aliens | magazine = [[Entertainment Weekly]] | issue = 656 | date = 31 May 2002 | pages = 26\u201334}}</ref> and [[Dave Gahan]], the lead singer of [[Depeche Mode]], was hired into the band when band founder [[Vince Clarke]] heard him singing {{\"'}}Heroes{{'\"}} at a jam session.<ref name=D93>{{Citation | last=Shaw | first=William | title=In The Mode | journal=[[Details (magazine)|Details magazine]] |date=April 1993 | pages=90\u201395, 168}}</ref>\n\nBowie regularly performed the song in concert.\n\n==Later use of the song==\n* In 2009, the song was played over the [[closing credits]] of both the documentary ''[[The Cove (film)|The Cove]]'', and ''[[What Goes Up]]'', and also featured in that film, important to the plot's message.\n* In May 2010, the song was played over the extended closing credits of the final episode of ''[[Ashes to Ashes (TV series)|Ashes to Ashes]]'', in keeping with the various David Bowie allusions throughout that series (and its predecessor ''[[Life on Mars (UK TV series)|Life on Mars]]'').\n* In 2012 the track was played as athletes from [[Great Britain]] entered the Olympic Stadium during the [[2012 Summer Olympics opening ceremony]], and after medal ceremonies during the Olympics.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/07/28/sports/olympics/in-olympic-opening-ceremony-britain-asserts-its-eccentric-identity.html|title=A Five-Ring Opening Circus, Weirdly and Unabashedly British|work=[[The New York Times]]|author=Sarah Lyall|date=27 July 2012|accessdate=28 July 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120728021456/http://www.nytimes.com/2012/07/28/sports/olympics/in-olympic-opening-ceremony-britain-asserts-its-eccentric-identity.html|archive-date=28 July 2012|url-status=live}}</ref> It was also used as the Great Britain Paralympic team entered the stadium during the opening ceremony on 29 August 2012. \n* The same year, it was featured in the film ''[[The Perks of Being a Wallflower (film)|The Perks of Being a Wallflower]]''.<ref name=\"Wallflower Discogs\">{{cite web | url= http://www.discogs.com/Various-The-Perks-Of-Being-A-Wallflower/master/565244 | title= Various  \u2013 The Perks of Being A Wallflower: Tracklist | author= <!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> | website= [[Discogs]] | accessdate= 12 January 2016 | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20160310211313/https://www.discogs.com/Various-The-Perks-Of-Being-A-Wallflower/master/565244 | archive-date= 10 March 2016 | url-status= live }}</ref> First heard on a pick-up truck radio by the main characters, the song is important to both \"flying through the tunnel\" scenes and played over the [[closing credits]].\n* In 2013, the song was featured in the [[Daniel Radcliffe]] horror fantasy film, ''[[Horns (film)|Horns]]''.\n* In 2014, the song was featured in the premiere trailer for the Brazilian film ''[[Praia do Futuro (film)|Praia do Futuro]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2014/film/reviews/berlin-film-review-praia-do-futuro-1201098056/|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|accessdate=13 April 2014|title=Berlin Film Review: 'Praia do Futuro'|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140407045509/http://variety.com/2014/film/reviews/berlin-film-review-praia-do-futuro-1201098056/|archive-date=7 April 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> The song was also played in \"[[You Don't Have to Live Like a Referee]]\", an episode of ''[[The Simpsons]]'' as Lisa is trying to figure out how to make Homer into a hero for a speech contest at school.\n* In the days following Bowie's death in January 2016, the song was streamed on Spotify more than any other Bowie song.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2016/01/12/upshot/david-bowie-songs-that-fans-are-listening-most-heroes-starman-major-tom.html|publisher=The New York Times Company|work=The New York Times|title=The David Bowie Song That Fans Are Listening to Most: 'Heroes'|author=Quoctrung Bui|author2=Josh Katz|author3=Jasmine C. Lee|date=12 January 2016|access-date=26 February 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170227081938/https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2016/01/12/upshot/david-bowie-songs-that-fans-are-listening-most-heroes-starman-major-tom.html|archive-date=27 February 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> On [[Twitter]] the [[Foreign Office (Germany)|German Foreign Office]] paid homage to Bowie for \"helping to bring down the [[Berlin Wall|wall]]\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/GermanyDiplo/status/686498183669743616?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw|title=GermanForeignOffice on Twitter|quote=Good-bye, David Bowie. You are now among #Heroes. Thank you for helping to bring down the #wall. youtu.be/YYjBQKIOb-w #RIPDavidBowie|author=GermanForeignOffice @GermanyDiplo|work=[[Foreign Office (Germany)|German Foreign Office]]|date=11 January 2016|publisher=[[Twitter]]|access-date=13 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160308191559/https://twitter.com/GermanyDiplo/status/686498183669743616?ref_src=twsrc%5Etfw|archive-date=8 March 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.marketwatch.com/story/death-of-david-bowie-sparks-howls-of-anguish-across-social-media-2016-01-11|title=David Bowie death triggers tributes from Iggy Pop, Madonna \u2013 even the Vatican and the German government|author=Barbara Kollmeyer|work=MarketWatch|accessdate=19 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171019113815/http://www.marketwatch.com/story/death-of-david-bowie-sparks-howls-of-anguish-across-social-media-2016-01-11|archive-date=19 October 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> It reached a new peak of number 12 in the UK after Bowie's death.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/how-the-loss-of-david-bowie-impacted-the-uk-charts-this-week__13564/|title=How the loss of David Bowie impacted the UK charts|accessdate=19 January 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160118082220/http://www.officialcharts.com/chart-news/how-the-loss-of-david-bowie-impacted-the-uk-charts-this-week__13564/|archive-date=18 January 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* In 2017, the song was played at the end of the series finale of animated television series ''[[Regular Show]]''.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.avclub.com/tvclub/epic-emotional-regular-show-finale-anything-248411 |title=The epic, emotional Regular Show finale is anything but |last=Thurm |first=Eric |newspaper=[[The A.V. Club]] |publication-date=16 January 2017 |access-date=10 February 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170211160622/http://www.avclub.com/tvclub/epic-emotional-regular-show-finale-anything-248411 |archive-date=11 February 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* In 2019, a cover of David Bowie's \"Heroes\" by Peter Gabriel (which has been used by the show once before, in episode 3 of the first season) was played at the end of Stranger Things' season 3, episode 8 \"Chapter Eight: The Battle of Starcourt\". It was also used in the 2020 [[Star Trek: Short Treks]] episode [[Star Trek: Short Treks#Season 2 (2019\u201320)|Children of Mars]].\n* The 2019 film, ''[[Jojo Rabbit]]'' uses Bowie's German version of the song (''\"Helden\"'') during the final scene and closing credits.\n\n===Use in advertising===\nThe song has been used in advertising, gracing efforts by [[Microsoft]], [[Kodak]], CGU Insurance, [[HBO]] Ol\u00e9 (HBO Latin America) and various sporting promoters throughout the world. It was also used as the intro to the [[video game]] ''[[NHL series|NHL 99]]'', released in 1998. {{\"'}}Heroes{{'\"}} also appears as downloadable content in the [[music video game]] series ''[[Rock Band (series)|Rock Band]]'' in a three-song pack along with other Bowie songs \"[[Moonage Daydream]]\" and \"[[Queen Bitch]]\". The Australian television [[mockumentary]] ''[[We Can Be Heroes: Finding The Australian of the Year]]'' (title outside Australia: ''The Nominees'') took its title from {{\"'}}Heroes{{'\"}}. A cover of the single was used as [[ITV (TV network)|ITV]]'s theme song for its coverage of the [[2006 FIFA World Cup]].\n\n==Accolades==\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Publication\n! Country\n! Accolade\n! Year\n! style=\"text-align:center;\"|Rank\n|-\n| ''[[TIME]]''\n| United States\n| \"All-Time 100 Songs\"<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://entertainment.time.com/2011/10/24/the-all-time-100-songs/slide/all/|title=All-TIME 100 Songs|accessdate=15 February 2016|magazine=TIME|date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160202123951/http://entertainment.time.com/2011/10/24/the-all-time-100-songs/slide/all/|archive-date=2 February 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| 2011\n| {{n/a}}\n|-\n| ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n| United States\n| \"[[The 500 Greatest Songs of All Time]]\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/_/id/6596661/500songs|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20051226133912/https://www.rollingstone.com/news/story/_/id/6596661/500songs|url-status=dead|archive-date=26 December 2005|title=Rolling Stone : 500 Greatest Songs|date=26 December 2005|access-date=7 August 2018}}</ref>\n| 2003\n| 46\n|-\n| ''[[NME]]''\n| United Kingdom\n| \"100 Greatest Singles of All Time\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nme.com/news/103493.htm |title=100 Greatest Singles of All Time |accessdate=16 February 2016 |work=NME|url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060427035859/http://www.nme.com/news/103493.htm |archivedate=27 April 2006 }}</ref>\n| 2002\n| 5\n|-\n| ''[[NME]]''\n| United Kingdom\n| \"500 Greatest Songs of All Time\"<ref name=\"NME500\"/>\n| 2014\n| 15\n|-\n| ''[[NME]]''\n| United Kingdom\n| \"100 Greatest Songs of NME's Lifetime...So Far\"<ref name=\"NME60\">{{cite web|url=http://www.rocklistmusic.co.uk/nme_60years.htm#greatest100|accessdate=15 February 2016|work=NME|title=60 Years of the NME|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160215071436/http://www.rocklistmusic.co.uk/nme_60years.htm#greatest100|archive-date=15 February 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| 2012\n| 3\n|-\n| ''[[NME]]''\n| United Kingdom\n| \"NME Readers Best Tracks of the Last 60 Years\"<ref name=\"NME60\"/>\n| 2012\n| 16\n|-\n| ''[[NME]]''\n| United Kingdom\n| \"Best tracks of the 1970s\"<ref name=\"NME60\"/>\n| 2014\n| 4\n|-\n| ''[[NME]]''\n| United Kingdom\n| \"David Bowie's 40 Greatest Songs\"<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.nme.com/photos/david-bowie-s-40-greatest-songs-as-decided-by-nme-and-friends/361814#/photo/1| title=David Bowie's 40 Greatest Songs| accessdate=18 February 2016| work=NME| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160224083823/http://www.nme.com/photos/david-bowie-s-40-greatest-songs-as-decided-by-nme-and-friends/361814#/photo/1| archive-date=24 February 2016| url-status=live}}</ref>\n| 2014\n| 1\n|-\n| ''[[Mojo Magazine]]''\n| United Kingdom\n| \"The 100 Greatest Singles of All Time\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rocklistmusic.co.uk/mojo_p2.htm|accessdate=15 February 2016|work=Mojo|title=Mojo 100 Greatest Singers of All Time|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303203836/http://www.rocklistmusic.co.uk/mojo_p2.htm|archive-date=3 March 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| 1997\n| 34\n|-\n| ''[[Sounds (magazine)|Sounds]]''\n| United Kingdom\n| \"All Time Top 100 Singles\"<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.rocklistmusic.co.uk/sound100.html | title=All Time Top 100 Singles | accessdate=16 February 2016 | publisher=Sounds | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303222357/http://www.rocklistmusic.co.uk/sound100.html | archive-date=3 March 2016 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n| 1985\n| 2\n|-\n| ''[[Q (magazine)|Q]]''\n| United Kingdom\n| \"Q Readers Top 100 Singles of All Time\"<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.rocklistmusic.co.uk/qlistspage2.html| title=Q Readers Top 100 Singles of All Time| accessdate=15 January 2016| publisher=Q| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160624171206/http://www.rocklistmusic.co.uk/qlistspage2.html| archive-date=24 June 2016| url-status=live}}</ref>\n| 1999\n| 36\n|-\n| ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n| United States\n| \"[[The Pitchfork 500]]\"<ref name=\"Pitchfork Media\"/>\n|2008\n| {{n/a}}\n|-\n| ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n| United States\n| \"The 200 Best Songs of the 1970s\"<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://pitchfork.com/features/lists-and-guides/9935-the-200-best-songs-of-the-1970s/?page=10 |title=Archived copy |access-date=20 December 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170701190817/http://pitchfork.com/features/lists-and-guides/9935-the-200-best-songs-of-the-1970s/?page=10 |archive-date=1 July 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n| 2016\n| 6\n|-\n| ''[[Radio X (United Kingdom)|Radio X]]''\n| United Kingdom\n| \"The Top 1,000 Songs of All Time\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.radiox.co.uk/x-lists/top-1000-songs/100-to-1-best-songs-ever/david-bowie-heroes/|title=The Top 1,000 Songs of All Time|accessdate=15 January 2016|publisher=Radio X|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151103231948/http://www.radiox.co.uk/x-lists/top-1000-songs/100-to-1-best-songs-ever/david-bowie-heroes/|archive-date=3 November 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|2010\n|24\n|-\n| ''[[Radio X (United Kingdom)|Radio X]]''\n| United Kingdom\n| \"Best of British\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://charts.radiox.co.uk/best-of-british-2016/chart/|title=Best of British|accessdate=31 March 2016|publisher=Radio X|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160331085552/http://charts.radiox.co.uk/best-of-british-2016/chart/|archive-date=31 March 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|2016\n|7\n|-\n| ''[[Uncut (magazine)|Uncut]]''\n| United Kingdom\n| \"David Bowie's 30 best songs\"<ref>{{cite magazine|url=http://www.uncut.co.uk/features/david-bowies-30-best-songs-66458|title=David Bowie\u2019s 30 best songs|accessdate=15 January 2016|magazine=Uncut|date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160224185624/http://www.uncut.co.uk/features/david-bowies-30-best-songs-66458|archive-date=24 February 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| 2008\n| 1\n|}\n\n<small>N/A designates unordered lists.</small>\n\n==Track listing==\nAll tracks written by [[David Bowie]] and [[Brian Eno]], except where noted.\n===7\" vinyl===\n* RCA / PB 11121<ref name=\"7 inch\">{{Cite AV media notes|title=''\"\"Heroes\"\"''|others=[[David Bowie]]|year=1977|publisher=[[RCA Records|RCA Victor]]|location=UK|type=7\" single liner notes|id=PB 1121}}</ref>\n# \"'Heroes'\" \u2013 3:38\n# \"[[V-2 Schneider]]\" (Bowie) \u2013 3:10\n\n===12\" vinyl===\n* RCA / JD-11151 (US promo)<ref name=\"12 inch\">{{Cite AV media notes|title=''\"\"Heroes\"\"''|others=[[David Bowie]]|year=1977|publisher=[[RCA Records|RCA Victor]]|location=US|type=12\" single liner notes|id=JD-11151}}</ref>\n# \"'Heroes'\" <small>(Album version)</small> \u2013 6:07\n# \"'Heroes'\" <small>(Single version)</small> \u2013 3:29\n\n* RCA / PC-9821 (Germany)<ref name=\"German 12-inch release\">{{Cite AV media notes|title=''\"\"Heroes\"\"''|others=[[David Bowie]]|year=1977|publisher=[[RCA Records|RCA Victor]]|location=Germany|type=Single liner notes|id=PC-9821}}</ref>\n# \"'Heroes'\" / \"'Helden'\" <small>(English/German version)</small> \u2013 6:09\n# \"'Heroes'\" / \"'H\u00e9ros'\" <small>(English/French version)</small> \u2013 6:09\n\n==Production credits==\n* [[Record producer|Producer]]s:\n** [[Tony Visconti]]\n** [[David Bowie]]\n* [[Musician]]s:\n** David Bowie: [[singing|lead vocals]], [[piano]], [[ARP Solina String Ensemble]], [[Chamberlin]], percussion\n** [[Robert Fripp]]: [[lead guitar]]\n** [[Carlos Alomar]]: [[rhythm guitar]]\n** [[George Murray (musician)|George Murray]]: [[bass guitar]]\n** [[Dennis Davis]]: [[drum kit|drums]]\n** [[Brian Eno]]: [[EMS VCS 3|EMS VCS 3 synthesizer]], [[guitar]] treatments\n** Tony Visconti: [[backing vocals]], [[tambourine]], tape reel as percussion<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p03g18sx?ns_mchannel=social& |title=BBC Arts - BBC Arts, Breaking down David Bowie's Heroes - track by track |website=Bbc.co.uk |accessdate=12 October 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160126080256/http://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p03g18sx?ns_mchannel=social& |archive-date=26 January 2016 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Charts and certifications==\n\n===Charts===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n!Chart (1977\u201378)\n!Peak<br/>position\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"|Australia ([http://www.austchartbook.com.au/ AMR])\n|align=\"center\"|11\n|-\n{{Singlechart|Austria|19|accessdate=15 January 2016|song=Heroes|artist=David Bowie|rowheader=true}}\n|-\n{{Singlechart|Flanders|17|accessdate=17 January 2016|song=Heroes|artist=David Bowie|rowheader=true}}\n|-\n{{Singlechart|Ireland2|8|accessdate=19 January 2020|song=Heroes|rowheader=true|refname=sc_Ireland_David_Bowie_1977}}\n|-\n{{Singlechart|Dutch100|9|accessdate=15 January 2016|song=Heroes|artist=David Bowie|rowheader=true}}\n|-\n{{Singlechart|New Zealand|35|accessdate=21 January 2016|song=Heroes|artist=David Bowie|rowheader=true}}\n|-\n{{Singlechart|United Kingdom|24|accessdate=15 January 2016|song=Heroes|artist=David Bowie|rowheader=true|date=5 November 1977|refname=sc_United_Kingdom_David_Bowie_1977}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| US ''[[Record World]]'' Singles Chart 101\u2013150<ref>{{cite book |last=Whitburn |first=Joel |date=2015 |title=The Comparison Book |location=Menonomee Falls, Wisconsin |publisher=Record Research Inc. |page=57 |isbn=978-0-89820-213-7}}</ref>\n| align=\"center\"| 126\n|}\n\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n!Chart (2016)\n!Peak<br/>position\n|-\n{{Singlechart|Australia|36|accessdate=17 January 2016|song=Heroes|artist=David Bowie|rowheader=true}}\n|-\n{{Singlechart|Austria|14|accessdate=15 January 2016|song=Heroes|artist=David Bowie|rowheader=true}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardeurodigital|3|artist=David Bowie|rowheader=true}}\n|-\n{{Singlechart|France|9|accessdate=17 January 2016|song=Heroes|artist=David Bowie|rowheader=true}}\n|-\n{{Singlechart|Germany2|19|accessdate=17 January 2016|song=Heroes|artist=David Bowie|rowheader=true|songid=6856}}\n|-\n{{Singlechart|Ireland2|29|accessdate=19 January 2020|song=Heroes (Re-entry)|rowheader=true|refname=sc_Ireland_David_Bowie_2016}}\n|-\n{{Singlechart|Italy|17|accessdate=16 January 2016|song=Heroes|artist=David Bowie|rowheader=true}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"|Japan Hot Overseas (''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'')<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.billboard-japan.com/charts/detail?a=d_and_a_overseas&year=2016&month=01&day=25|title=''Billboard'' Japan Hot Overseas|language=Japanese|publisher=Billboard Japan|date=18 January 2016|accessdate=18 February 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170219011653/http://www.billboard-japan.com/charts/detail?a=d_and_a_overseas&year=2016&month=01&day=25|archive-date=19 February 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|18\n|-\n{{Singlechart|Dutch100|47|accessdate=15 January 2016|song=Heroes|artist=David Bowie|rowheader=true}}\n|-\n{{Singlechart|New Zealand|34|accessdate=21 January 2016|song=Heroes|artist=David Bowie|rowheader=true}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"|Portugal ([[Associa\u00e7\u00e3o Fonogr\u00e1fica Portuguesa|AFP]])<ref>{{cite web|url=http://portuguesecharts.com/archive.asp?todo=show&woche=02&jahr=2016&sparte=s|title=Portuguesecharts - David Bowie - Heroes|website=portuguesecharts.com|id=Hung Medien|accessdate=18 February 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160412123705/http://www.portuguesecharts.com/archive.asp?todo=show&woche=02&jahr=2016&sparte=s|archive-date=12 April 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n|align=\"center\"|32\n|-\n{{singlechart|Scotland|8|date=20160121|rowheader=true}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Spain|20|artist=David Bowie|song=Heroes|rowheader=true}}\n|-\n{{Singlechart|Sweden|37|accessdate=17 January 2016|song=Heroes|artist=David Bowie|rowheader=true}}\n|-\n{{Singlechart|Switzerland|17|accessdate=17 January 2016|song=Heroes|artist=David Bowie|rowheader=true}}\n|-\n{{Singlechart|United Kingdom|12|accessdate=15 January 2016|song=Heroes|artist=David Bowie|rowheader=true|date=14 January 2016|refname=sc_United_Kingdom_David_Bowie_2016}}\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardrocksongs|11|artist=David Bowie|rowheader=true|accessdate=21 January 2016}}\n|}\n\n===Certifications===\n{{Certification Table Top}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=Italy|type=single|artist=David Bowie|title=Heroes|award=Gold|certyear=2016|salesamount=7,500|certref=<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fimi.it/app/uploads/GfK_Certificazioni-Single-Digital_wk-01-2016.pdf |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160117100122/http://www.fimi.it/app/uploads/GfK_Certificazioni-Single-Digital_wk-01-2016.pdf |language=Italian |access-date=17 January 2016 |archivedate=17 January 2016 |format=PDF |title=Certificazione Singoli Digitali dalla settimana 1 del 2010 alla settimana 1 del 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref>}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=United Kingdom|type=single|artist=David Bowie|title=Heroes|award=Platinum|salesamount=600,000|relyear=1977|certyear=2020}}<ref>https://www.bpi.co.uk/bpi-awards/ {{Webarchive|url=https://www.webcitation.org/5mr0Evm3j?url=http://www.bpi.co.uk/certifiedawards/search.aspx |date=17 January 2010 }} type david bowie heroes and search</ref>\n{{Certification Table Bottom|nosales=true|noshipments=true|streaming=true}}\n\n==Live versions==\n* Prior to the single release of {{\"'}}Heroes{{'\"}}, Bowie first performed the song on the final episode of friend [[Marc Bolan|Marc Bolan's]] [[Granada Television]] series ''[[Marc (TV series)|Marc]]'' (filmed 7 September 1977, broadcast 28 September 1977,<ref name=\"Davidbowie.com\">{{cite news|url=http://www.davidbowie.com/news/heroes-single-forty-years-old-today-57331|title='Heroes' single is forty years old today|date=23 September 2017|work=Davidbowie.com|accessdate=23 September 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170929111200/http://www.davidbowie.com/news/heroes-single-forty-years-old-today-57331|archive-date=29 September 2017|url-status=}}</ref> after Bolan's funeral). This particular version, released as a 7\" picture disc, on 22 September 2017,<ref name=\"Davidbowie.com\"/> has an alternate backing track that was recorded with Bolan playing lead guitar and the [[T.Rex (band)|T.Rex]] line up of [[Dino Dines]] on keyboards, and the rhythm section of [[Herbie Flowers]] on bass and [[Tony Newman (drummer)|Tony Newman]] on drums.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Campbell|first1=Irving|title=A Guide to the Outtakes of Marc Bolan|date=2007|publisher=Great Horse|location=Wellington, New Zealand|isbn=978-0-473-12076-4|page=179|edition=1<!-- |accessdate=6 August 2015 -->}}</ref> Coincidentally, prior to joining T.Rex, Flowers and Newman were a part of Bowie's rhythm section on the ''[[Diamond Dogs]]'' album and [[Diamond Dogs Tour|its tour]], documented on the live album ''[[David Live]]''.\n* Bowie performed the song when he appeared on [[Bing Crosby|Bing Crosby's]] 1977 [[Christmas]] TV special, ''[[Bing Crosby's Merrie Olde Christmas]]''. In the performance, filmed on 11 September 1977, Bowie sang over a prerecorded backing track.\n* Performances from the [[Isolar II \u2013 The 1978 World Tour|Isolar II Tour]] have been released on ''[[Stage (David Bowie album)|Stage]]'' (1978) and ''[[Welcome to the Blackout (Live London '78)|Welcome to the Blackout]]'' (2018).<ref>{{cite web |last1=Erlewine |first1=Stephen Thomas |authorlink1=Stephen Thomas Erlewine |title=''Stage'' \u2013 David Bowie |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/stage-mw0000193055 |publisher=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=12 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190805090901/https://www.allmusic.com/album/stage-mw0000193055 |archive-date=5 August 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Erlewine |first1=Stephen Thomas |authorlink1=Stephen Thomas Erlewine |title=''Welcome to the Blackout (Live London '78)'' \u2013 David Bowie |url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/welcome-to-the-blackout-live-london-78-mw0003173016 |publisher=[[AllMusic]] |accessdate=12 March 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191117143206/https://www.allmusic.com/album/welcome-to-the-blackout-live-london-78-mw0003173016 |archive-date=17 November 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n* Bowie performed the song live on his [[Serious Moonlight Tour]] in 1983, as seen in [[Serious Moonlight (1983 film)|the 1984 concert video of that tour]] and as heard on the live album ''Serious Moonlight (Live '83)'', which was part of the 2018 box set ''[[Loving the Alien (1983\u20131988)]]'' and was released separately in 2019.\n* The rendition at [[Live Aid]] in 1985 has been described as \"the best version of 'Heroes' [Bowie] had ever sung\".<ref>David Buckley (1999). Op Cit: p.424</ref> This performance featured [[Thomas Dolby]] on keyboards.\n* Bowie performed the song live on his [[Glass Spider Tour]], as seen in [[Glass Spider|the 1988 concert video of that tour]].\n* The song was performed at [[The Freddie Mercury Tribute Concert]] in 1992 by Bowie, [[Mick Ronson]] and [[Brian May]], [[Roger Taylor (Queen drummer)|Roger Taylor]], and [[John Deacon]] \u2013 the surviving members of [[Queen (band)|Queen]].\n* An acoustic version of the song was played in 1996 at The Bridge School Benefit Concert at the Shoreline Amphitheater in Mountain View, California, and later released on ''The Bridge School Benefit Concert'' album.\n* Bowie's 25 June 2000 performance of the song at the [[Glastonbury Festival]] was released in 2018 on ''[[Glastonbury 2000]]''.\n* The song was performed by Bowie at [[The Concert for New York City]] on 20 October 2001. Before Bowie opened the concert he was asked to perform {{\"'}}Heroes{{'\"}}. He said it wasn't appropriate as it was a love song, so he opened with a solo version of Paul Simon's \"America\", and then performed {{\"'}}Heroes{{'\"}} with the house band led by Paul Shaffer.\n* Bowie performed the song live during the [[A Reality Tour]] in 2003, and a performance from November of that year was released on [[A Reality Tour (film)|a DVD]] in 2004, and later on [[A Reality Tour (album)|an album]], released in 2010.\n\n==Other releases==\n* The edited 7-inch single, running at 3:32 mins and backed with \"V-2 Schneider\", was released separately in English, French (''\u00abH\u00e9ros\u00bb'') and German (''\u201eHelden\u201c''). All three of these cuts plus \"V-2 Schneider\" were released together as an Australian 4-track 7-inch.\n* The complete English version as it appeared on the album was released as a Spanish [[12-inch single]].\n* A version featuring the German single edit spliced into the second half of the full-length English track (''\"Heroes\"/\u201eHelden\u201c'') appeared on the German pressing of the LP and is also available on Bowie's [[Christiane F. (album)|soundtrack]] to the film ''[[Christiane F.&nbsp;\u2013 Wir Kinder vom Bahnhof Zoo|Christiane F.]]'' and on the ''[[Rare (David Bowie album)|Rare]]'' album.  A corresponding English/French version (''\"Heroes\"/\u00abH\u00e9ros\u00bb'') appeared on the French pressing of the LP.\n* The song has appeared, almost invariably in single edit form, on numerous Bowie compilations:\n** ''Chameleon'' (Australia and New Zealand 1979)\n** ''[[Best of Bowie (1980 version)|The Best of Bowie]]'' (1980)\n** ''[[Fame and Fashion]]'' (1984) \u2013 album version\n** ''[[Sound + Vision (box set)|Sound + Vision]]'' (1989) \u2013 ''\u201eHelden\u201c''\n** ''[[Changesbowie]]'' (1990)\n** ''[[Bowie: The Singles 1969-1993]]'' (1993)\n** ''[[The Singles Collection (David Bowie album)|The Singles Collection]]'' (1993)\n** ''[[The Best of David Bowie 1974/1979]]'' (1998)\n** ''[[Best of Bowie]]'' (2002) \u2013 ''\u201eHelden\u201c'' on German/Swiss/Austrian edition\n** ''[[The Platinum Collection (David Bowie album)|The Platinum Collection]]'' (2005/2006)\n** ''[[Nothing Has Changed]]'' (2014)\n** ''[[Bowie Legacy]]'' (2016)\n* It was released as a picture disc in the [[RCA Records|RCA]] ''Life Time'' picture disc set.\n* The German (''\u201eHelden\u201c'') and French (''\u00abH\u00e9ros\u00bb'') versions of the single, as well as the English/German (''\"Heroes\"/\u201eHelden\u201c'') and English/French (\"Heroes\"/\u00abH\u00e9ros\u00bb) versions of the album track, were included on an [[Extended play|EP]] in the 2017 boxed set ''[[A New Career in a New Town (1977\u20131982)]]''. The single version of the song was included on ''Re:Call 3'', part of the same compilation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.davidbowie.com/news/new-career-new-town-1977-1982-57146|title=A NEW CAREER IN A NEW TOWN (1977 \u2013 1982) - David Bowie Latest News|date=22 July 2016|publisher=DavidBowie.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170728195724/http://www.davidbowie.com/news/new-career-new-town-1977-1982-57146|archive-date=28 July 2017|url-status=|accessdate=29 September 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Cover versions==\n* [[Oasis (band)|Oasis]] recorded a version of the song as a B-Side for the lead single, [[D'You Know What I Mean?]] to the album [[Be Here Now (album)|Be Here Now]].\n* [[The Wallflowers]] recorded a version of the song for the [[Godzilla: The Album|soundtrack]] to the 1998 film ''[[Godzilla (1998 film)|Godzilla]]''. This version peaked at number 10 on the ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' [[Alternative Songs|Modern Rock Tracks]] chart in 1998, as well as number 27 on the ''Billboard'' [[Hot 100 Airplay]] chart and number 23 on the ''Billboard'' [[Top 40 Mainstream]] chart.<ref>[http://www.billboard.com/charts/1998-05-23/alternative-songs Alternative Songs] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140703013147/http://www.billboard.com/charts/1998-05-23/alternative-songs |date=3 July 2014 }}. Billboard.com. Retrieved 11 August 2012.</ref>\n* The 2001 musical film ''[[Moulin Rouge!]]'' includes a duet cover version from [[Ewan McGregor]] and [[Nicole Kidman]] as the penultimate song in the \"Elephant Love Medley\".\n*Swiss Metal band [[Celtic Frost]] recorded a cover of the song for their 1990 album ''[[Vanity/Nemesis]]''.\n* [[Apocalyptica]] recorded {{\"'}}Helden{{'\"}}, the German version of the song for their album ''[[Worlds Collide (Apocalyptica album)|Worlds Collide]]'' (2007), featuring [[Till Lindemann]] of [[Rammstein]] on vocals.\n* For the 2009 benefit album ''[[War Child Presents Heroes]]'', [[TV on the Radio]] recorded a version after Bowie himself nominated the band to cover it, in keeping with the album's theme of \"placing faith in the next generation\".\n* ''[[The X Factor (UK TV series)|The X Factor]]'' [[List of The X Factor finalists (UK series 7)|finalists]] released a version for charity in 2010, which reached number one on the [[Irish Singles Chart|Irish]], [[Scottish Singles and Albums Charts|Scottish]] and [[UK Singles Chart]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.chart-track.co.uk/index.jsp?c=p%2Fmusicvideo%2Fmusic%2Farchive%2Findex_test.jsp&ct=240001&arch=t&lyr=2010&year=2010&week=47 |title=Top 100 Singles, Week Ending 25 November 2010 |publisher=[[Chart-Track]] |accessdate=7 December 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160303180011/http://www.chart-track.co.uk/index.jsp?c=p%2Fmusicvideo%2Fmusic%2Farchive%2Findex_test.jsp&ct=240001&arch=t&lyr=2010&year=2010&week=47 |archive-date=3 March 2016 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/charts/scottish-singles-chart/20101128/41/|title=Official Scottish Singles Sales Chart Top 100 28 November 2010 - 04 December 2010|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=11 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161010061318/http://www.officialcharts.com/charts/scottish-singles-chart/20101128/41/|archive-date=10 October 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.officialcharts.com/charts/singles-chart/20101128/7501/|title=Official Singles Chart Top 100 28 November 2010 - 04 December 2010|publisher=[[Official Charts Company]]|accessdate=11 July 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160203150742/http://www.officialcharts.com/charts/singles-chart/20101128/7501/|archive-date=3 February 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* [[Peter Gabriel]] released an orchestral reinterpretation for his 2010 album ''[[Scratch My Back]]'', also appearing in the third episode of the first season and the eighth episode of the third season of the [[Netflix]] series ''[[Stranger Things]]'' and on the official soundtrack, and on the soundtrack for the film ''[[Lone Survivor]]''.\n* In [[The X Factor U.S.]], finalists [[Melanie Amaro]] and [[Josh Krajcik]] covered this song as a duet.\n* In 2014, actress [[Jessica Lange]] recorded a cover of the song for the season finale of ''[[American Horror Story: Freak Show]]'' entitled \"[[Curtain Call (American Horror Story)|Curtain Call]]\".\n* [[Depeche Mode]] released an official cover and video for the 40th anniversary of the song's release, with lead singer [[Dave Gahan]] stating, \"Bowie is the one artist who I've stuck with since I was in my early teens. His albums are always my go-to on tour and covering {{'\"}}Heroes{{\"'}} is paying homage to Bowie.\"<ref>{{cite news|last1=Trendell|first1=Andrew|title=Depeche Mode share official cover of David Bowie\u2019s \"Heroes\" to mark track\u2019s 40th anniversary|url=http://www.nme.com/news/depeche-mode-share-official-cover-david-bowies-heroes-mark-tracks-40th-anniversary-2143717|work=[[NME]]|date=22 September 2017|access-date=22 September 2017|archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6Py4HGol5?url=http://www.allaccess.com/hot-modern-ac/future-releases|archive-date=30 May 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* [[King Crimson]] recorded a version for their five-track EP ''Heroes: Live in Europe 2016''.<ref>{{cite web | url= http://teamrock.com/news/2017-04-28/king-crimson-to-release-ep-featuring-david-bowies-heroes | title= King Crimson to release EP featuring David Bowie\u2019s Heroes | work= teamrock.com | date= 28 April 2017 | accessdate= 25 September 2017 | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20170926095720/http://teamrock.com/news/2017-04-28/king-crimson-to-release-ep-featuring-david-bowies-heroes | archive-date= 26 September 2017 | url-status= live }}</ref> It won \"Video of the Year\" at the 2017 [[Prog (magazine)|Progressive Music Awards]].<ref>{{cite web | url= http://teamrock.com/news/2017-09-15/marillion-anathema-steve-hackett-among-progressive-music-award-winners | title= Marillion, Anathema, Steve Hackett among Progressive Music Award winners | work= teamrock.com | date= 14 September 2017 | accessdate= 25 September 2017 | archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20180322173853/http://teamrock.com/news/2017-09-15/marillion-anathema-steve-hackett-among-progressive-music-award-winners | archive-date= 22 March 2018 | url-status= live }}</ref>\n* [[Coldplay]] performed the song as a tribute to Bowie on their [[A Head Full of Dreams Tour]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/7439089/coldplay-head-full-of-dreams-stadium-farewell-tour-chris-martin-david-bowie-metlife-stadium | title=Coldplay Launches A Head Full of Dreams Tour With Vivid Colors, Multiple Stages, David Bowie Tribute & More | work=billboard.com | date=17 July 2016 | accessdate=18 June 2018 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180618084346/https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/7439089/coldplay-head-full-of-dreams-stadium-farewell-tour-chris-martin-david-bowie-metlife-stadium | archive-date=18 June 2018 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n* [[Mot\u00f6rhead]] released official cover for their 2017 album ''[[Under C\u00f6ver]]''.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Daly|first1=Rhian|title=Listen to Mot\u00f6rhead\u2019s cover of David Bowie's 'Heroes'|url=http://www.nme.com/news/music/listen-motorhead-david-bowie-cover-heroes-2120658|work=[[NME]]|date=23 November 2017|access-date=23 November 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201033122/http://www.nme.com/news/music/listen-motorhead-david-bowie-cover-heroes-2120658|archive-date=1 December 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*[[Blondie (band)|Blondie]] covered {{\"'}}Heroes{{'\"}} on the album ''Uncut 2003.03: Starman''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://musicbrainz.org/release/f7dfaccb-ed66-4663-84ab-3385cb9ada3c |title=Archived copy |access-date=31 October 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181031214832/https://musicbrainz.org/release/f7dfaccb-ed66-4663-84ab-3385cb9ada3c |archive-date=31 October 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n*[[Gang of Youths]] released a cover of {{\"'}}Heroes{{'\"}} as a non-album single,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/au/album/heroes-single/1294149479|title=Heroes \u2013 single|website=iTunes Australia|accessdate=15 April 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180416073529/https://itunes.apple.com/au/album/heroes-single/1294149479|archive-date=16 April 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> featured in the trailer for the 2017 film ''[[Justice League (2017 film)|Justice League]]''.\n*[[Hollywood Vampires (band)|Hollywood Vampires]], a supergroup featuring [[Alice Cooper]], [[Joe Perry (musician)|Joe Perry]], and [[Johnny Depp]], released a cover of {{\"'}}Heroes{{'\"}} on their 2019 album ''Rise'', with Depp performing lead vocals for the track.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/rise/1459328488 |title=Archived copy |access-date=25 June 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190704102318/https://music.apple.com/us/album/rise/1459328488 |archive-date=4 July 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n;Notes\n{{Notelist}}\n\n;Citations\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n;Sources\n* {{Cite book|last=Buckley|first=David|title=Strange Fascination \u2013 David Bowie: The Definitive Story|year=2000|origyear=1999|publisher=Virgin|location=London|isbn=0-7535-0457-X}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Carr|first=Roy|authorlink=Roy Carr|author2=Murray, Charles Shaar|author2-link=Charles Shaar Murray|title=David Bowie: An Illustrated Record|year=1981|publisher=Avon|location=New York|isbn=0-380-77966-8}}\n* {{Cite book|last=Pegg|first=Nicholas|authorlink=Nicholas Pegg|title=The Complete David Bowie|year=2004|origyear=2000|publisher=Reynolds & Hearn|location=London|isbn=1-903111-14-5}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{MetroLyrics song|david-bowie|heroes}}<!-- Licensed lyrics provider -->\n\n{{David Bowie singles}}\n{{The Wallflowers}}\n{{Children in Need}}\n{{The X Factor}}\n{{Gang of Youths}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Heroes}}\n[[Category:1977 singles]]\n[[Category:Song recordings with Wall of Sound arrangements]]\n[[Category:David Bowie songs]]\n[[Category:Gang of Youths songs]]\n[[Category:Interscope Records singles]]\n[[Category:Irish Singles Chart number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Number-one singles in Scotland]]\n[[Category:Oasis (band) songs]]\n[[Category:RCA Records singles]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by David Bowie]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Tony Visconti]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Brian Eno]]\n[[Category:Songs written by David Bowie]]\n[[Category:Songs about Berlin]]\n[[Category:Berlin Wall in fiction]]\n[[Category:The Wallflowers songs]]\n[[Category:The X Factor (British TV series)]]\n[[Category:UK Singles Chart number-one singles]]\n[[Category:Protest songs]]\n[[Category:1977 songs]]\n", "name_user": "2601:1c2:4100:ec0:494f:a99b:31c8:61b8", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%22Heroes%22_(David_Bowie_song)"}
{"title_page": "Riverside Church", "text_new": "{{Distinguish|Riverside Baptist Church}}\n{{good article}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox church\n|name                   = Riverside Church\n|fullname               =\n|image                  = Riverside Church2.JPG\n|imagesize              =\n|imagelink              =\n|imagealt               =\n|landscape              =\n|caption                =\n|pushpin map            = Manhattan#New York City#New York#United States\n|pushpin label position =\n|pushpin map alt        =\n|pushpin mapsize        =\n|map caption            =\n|coordinates            = {{Coord|40|48|43|N|73|57|47|W|type:landmark|display=inline,title}}\n|osgraw                 = \n|osgridref              =\n|location               = [[New York City]]\n|country                = United States\n|denomination           = [[Interdenominational]], [[American Baptist Churches USA|American Baptist]], [[United Church of Christ]]\n|previous denomination  =\n|churchmanship          =\n|membership             = 1,750<ref name=\"NYT-Butler-2019\" />\n|attendance             =\n|website                =\n|former name            = Mulberry Street Baptist Church<br>Fifth Avenue Baptist Church<br>Park Avenue Baptist Church\n|bull date              =\n|founded date           =\n|founder                =\n|dedication             =\n|dedicated date         = \n|consecrated date       =\n|cult                   =\n|relics                 =\n|events                 =\n|past bishop            =\n|people                 =\n|status                 =\n|functional status      =\n|heritage designation   = [[National Register of Historic Places]], [[New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission]]\n|designated date        =\n|architect              = [[Allen & Collens]] and [[Henry C. Pelton]]\n|architectural type     = [[Gothic Revival architecture|Neo-Gothic]]\n|style                  =\n|groundbreaking         = November 21, 1927\n|completed date         = October 5, 1930\n|construction cost      =\n|closed date            =\n|demolished date        =\n|capacity               = 2,100\n|length                 = <!-- {{convert|}} -->\n|width                  = <!-- {{convert|}} -->\n|width nave             = {{convert|89|ft}}\n|height                 = <!-- {{convert|}} -->\n|diameter               = <!-- {{convert|}} -->\n|other dimensions       =\n|floor count            = 22\n|floor area             = <!-- {{convert|}} -->\n|dome quantity          =\n|dome height outer      = <!-- {{convert|}} -->\n|dome height inner      = <!-- {{convert|}} -->\n|dome dia outer         = <!-- {{convert|}} -->\n|dome dia inner         = <!-- {{convert|}} -->\n|spire quantity         =\n|spire height           = {{convert|392|ft}}\n|materials              =\n|bells                  = 74\n|bells hung             = [[carillon]]\n|bell weight            = <!-- {{CwtQtrLb to kg|}} -->\n|parish                 =\n|deanery                =\n|archdeaconry           =\n|episcopalarea          =\n|archdiocese            =\n|metropolis             =\n|diocese                =\n|province               =\n|presbytery             =\n|synod                  =\n|circuit                =\n|district               =\n|division               =\n|subdivision            =\n|logo                   =\n|logosize               =\n|logolink               =\n|logoalt                =\n|embedded =\n{{Infobox NRHP\n| embed = yes\n| name                 = Riverside Church\n| nrhp_type            =\n| location             = 478, 490 Riverside Dr. & 81 Claremont Ave., [[New York City]]\n| built                = 1930 (main building)<br>1957 (MLK Wing)<br>1962 (conversion of Stone Gym)\n| architect            = [[Allen & Collens]], [[H.C. Pelton]] (main building)<br>[[Collens, Willis & Beckonert]] (MLK Wing)<br>[[Louis E. Jallade]] (Stone Gym)\n| architecture         = [[Late Gothic Revival]]\n| added                = December 12, 2012<ref name=\"nrhp\" />\n| designated_nrhp_type =\n| visitation_num       =\n| visitation_year      =\n| refnum               = 12001036\n| website              = <!-- {{URL|www.example.com}} -->\n| mpsub                =\n| designated_other2 = NYC Landmark\n| designated_other2_date = May 16, 2000<ref name=\"NYCL p. 1\" />\n| designated_other2_number = 2037\n| designated_other2_abbr = NYCL\n| designated_other2_color = #FFE978\n| designated_other2_link = New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Riverside Church''' is a Baptist and Congregationalist church in the [[Morningside Heights, Manhattan|Morningside Heights]] neighborhood of [[Manhattan]] in [[New York City]]. It is located on the block bounded by [[Riverside Drive (Manhattan)|Riverside Drive]], [[Claremont Avenue]], and 120th and 122nd Streets, near [[Columbia University]]'s Morningside Heights campus and across from [[Grant's Tomb]]. An [[interdenominational]] church, it is associated with the [[American Baptist Churches USA]] and the [[United Church of Christ]]. The church was conceived by philanthropist businessman [[John D. Rockefeller Jr.]], a Baptist, in conjunction with Presbyterian minister [[Harry Emerson Fosdick]] as a large, interdenominational church in Morningside Heights, a neighborhood surrounded by numerous academic institutions.\n\nThe original building, opened in 1930, was designed by Henry C. Pelton and [[Allen & Collens]] in the [[Neo-Gothic architecture|Neo-Gothic]] style. It contains a [[nave]] consisting of five [[Bay (architecture)|architectural bays]]; a [[chancel]] at the front of the nave; a 22-story, {{Convert|392|ft|m|-tall|abbr=|adj=mid}} tower above the [[nave]]; a [[narthex]] and [[chapel]]; and a [[cloister]]ed passageway that connects to the eastern entrance on Claremont Avenue. The main feature of the church is the 74-bell [[carillon]] near the top of the tower, dedicated to John Rockefeller Jr.'s mother [[Laura Spelman Rockefeller]]. A seven-story wing to the south of the original building was built in 1959 to a design by Collens, Willis & Beckonert, and renamed for [[Martin Luther King Jr.]] in 1985. The Stone Gym, to the southeast, was built in 1915 as a dormitory designed by Louis E. Jallade, and was converted to a gym in 1962.\n\nA focal point of global and national activism since its inception, Riverside Church has a long history of [[social justice]], in adherence to Fosdick's original vision of an \"interdenominational, interracial, and international\" church.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 1\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|2000|ps=.|p=1}}</ref> Riverside Church's congregation includes more than forty ethnic groups. It was designated as a city landmark by the [[New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission]] in 2000,<ref name=\"NYCL p. 1\" /> and was listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 2012.<ref name=\"nrhp\">{{cite web|title=National Register of Historic Places Weekly Lists for 2012|url=https://www.nps.gov/subjects/nationalregister/upload/weekly-list-2012-national-register-of-historic-places.pdf|publisher=[[U.S. National Park Service]]|date=December 28, 2012|accessdate=February 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\n{{TOC limit|4}}\n\n== History ==\n\n=== Context ===\n==== Congregation ====\nSeveral small [[Baptists|Baptist]] congregations were founded in Manhattan after the [[American Revolutionary War]], including the Mulberry Street Baptist Church, established in 1823 by a group of 16 congregants.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 2\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|2000|ps=.|p=2}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|ps=.|Pendo|1957|p=9}}</ref> The church occupied at least three locations in the [[Lower East Side]], and two additional locations on [[Broadway (Manhattan)|Broadway]] in [[Midtown Manhattan]], before moving to a more permanent site at [[Fifth Avenue]] and 46th Street in the 1860s.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 2\" /> The businessman [[William Rockefeller]] was the first of several [[Rockefeller family]] members to attend the Fifth Avenue Baptist Church, and became a major financial backer of the church in the 1870s.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 2\" /><ref>{{harvnb|ps=.|Pendo|1957|p=22}}</ref> Such was the family's involvement that William and his brother [[John D. Rockefeller]] later became trustees of the church, and many of the church's services were held at the Rockefellers' home nearby.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 2\" /><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pCgaAAAAYAAJ|title=John D. Rockefeller: The Heroic Age of American Enterprise|last=Nevins|first=A.|publisher=C. Scribner's Sons|year=1940|series=John D. Rockefeller: The Heroic Age of American Enterprise|page=455|access-date=November 3, 2019|issue=v. 1}}</ref>\n\nWhen Cornelius Woelfkin became the church's minister in 1912, he started leading the church toward a more [[modernism#Main period|modernist]] direction.<ref>{{harvnb|Paris et al.|2004|ps=.|p=18}}</ref> By the early 20th century, Fifth Avenue was seeing growing commercial development, and the church building became dilapidated.<ref>{{harvnb|ps=.|Pendo|1957|p=40}}</ref> The congregation sold off their old headquarters in 1919<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1919/05/30/archives/fifth-av-baptists-sell-church-home-property-long-in-the-market-is.html|title=Fifth Av. Baptists Sell Church Home; Property, Long in the Market, Is Purchased by Michael Dreicer|last=|first=|date=May 30, 1919|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 3, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> and bought land at [[Park Avenue]] and 63rd Street the following year.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1920/11/06/archives/new-apartment-for-park-avenue-two-large-parcels-acquired-at-the.html|title=New Apartment For Park Avenue; Two Large Parcels Acquired at the Southeast Corner of Sixty-third Street|last=|first=|date=November 6, 1920|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 3, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> John Rockefeller's son [[John D. Rockefeller Jr.]] funded half of the projected $1&nbsp;million cost.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 2\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1917/05/08/archives/rockefeller-aids-new-church-fund-offers-to-add-50-per-cent-to.html|title=Rockefeller Aids New Church Fund; Offers to Add 50 Per Cent. to Amount Raised by Fifth Av. Baptist Congregation|last=|first=|date=May 8, 1917|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 3, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The new church, dubbed the \"Little Cathedral\", was designed by Henry C. Pelton in partnership with Francis R. Allen and Charles Collens.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 2\" /> The final service in the Fifth Avenue location was held on April 3, 1922,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1922/04/03/archives/final-service-held-in-5th-av-church-dr-cornelius-woelfkin-reviews.html|title=Final Service Held In 5th Av. Church; Dr. Cornelius Woelfkin Reviews Baptist Congregation's History of 91 Years|last=|first=|date=April 3, 1922|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 3, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> and the renamed Park Avenue Baptist Church held its first class in the new location the next week.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 2\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1922/04/09/archives/rockefeller-class-in-new-home-today-park-avenue-baptist-church-will.html|title=Rockefeller Class In New Home Today; Park Avenue Baptist Church Will Occupy Edifice of 64th Street for the First Time.|last=|first=|date=April 9, 1922|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 3, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n==== Progressive ideology ====\nIn 1924, John D. Rockefeller Jr. donated $500,000 to the [[Cathedral of St. John the Divine]] in [[Morningside Heights, Manhattan|Morningside Heights]], further uptown in Manhattan, in an unsuccessful attempt to influence the cathedral's ideology in a progressive direction.<ref name=\"Dolkart pp. 70-71\">{{harvnb|Dolkart|1998|ps=.|pp=70&ndash;71}}</ref> The following January, Harry E. Edmonds\u2014leader of the [[International House of New York|International House]] in Morningside Heights, for whose construction Rockefeller had provided funds\u2014wrote to Rockefeller to propose creating a new church in the neighborhood. Edmonds suggested that progressive pastor [[Harry Emerson Fosdick]] head such a church. Rockefeller then told the Park Avenue Baptist Church's leaders about the plan, after which he hired an agent to look at the planned church site.<ref name=\"Dolkart p. 72\">{{harvnb|Dolkart|1998|ps=.|p=72}}</ref>\n\nWoelfkin quit in mid-May 1925 and Rockefeller Jr. immediately started looking for a new minister,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1925/05/11/archives/dr-woelfkin-quits-park-avenue-pulpit-resigns-after-40-years-in.html|title=Dr. Woelfkin Quits Park Avenue Pulpit; Resigns After 40 Years in Baptist Ministry, 13 of Which Were at His Present Post.|date=May 11, 1925|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 3, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> ultimately deciding on Fosdick.<ref name=\"Dolkart p. 72\" /><ref name=\"NYCL p. 3\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|2000|ps=.|p=3}}</ref><ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 19\">{{harvnb|Paris et al.|2004|ps=.|p=19}}</ref> Fosdick had declined Rockefeller's offers several times,<ref name=\"Dolkart p. 72\" /> explaining that he did not \"want to be known as the pastor of the richest man in the country.\"<ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 19\" /> Fosdick stated that he would accept the minister position under the conditions that the church move to Morningside Heights, follow a policy of [[religious liberalism]], remove the requirement that members had to be [[Baptism|baptized]], and have the church be [[Nondenominational Christianity|nondenominational]].<ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 19\" /><ref name=\"Dolkart p. 73\">{{harvnb|Dolkart|1998|ps=.|p=73}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1925/05/16/archives/dr-fosdick-called-by-park-av-baptists-insists-on-changes-stipulates.html|title=Dr. Fosdick Called By Park Av. Baptists Insists On Changes; Stipulates That Church Shall Not Demand Baptism by Immersion|last=|first=|date=May 16, 1925|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 3, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> At the end of May 1925, Fosdick finally agreed to become minister of the Park Avenue Baptist Church.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 3\" /><ref name=\"Dolkart p. 73\" /><ref name=\"Miller p. 162\">{{harvnb|Miller|1985|ps=.|p=162}}</ref><ref name=\"NYT-FosdickAccepts-1925\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1925/05/29/archives/dr-fosdick-accepts-call-will-create-a-liberal-church-praises.html|title=Dr. Fosdick Accepts Call; Will Create A Liberal Church|last=|first=|date=May 29, 1925|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 3, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Only 15% of congregants voted against Fosdick's appointment.<ref>{{harvnb|ps=.|Dolkart|1998|p=383, note 157}}</ref>\n\nUnder Fosdick's leadership, the congregation doubled in size by 1930.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 3\" /><ref>{{harvnb|Pendo|1957|ps=.|p=49}}</ref> The new members were diverse: of the 158 people who joined in the year after Fosdick became minister, about half were not Baptists.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 3\" /><ref>{{harvnb|ps=.|Miller|1985|p=201}}</ref> Though some existing congregants had doubts about whether the Park Avenue Baptist Church should move from its recently completed edifice, the church's board, which was in favor of the relocation, stated that congregants would not have to pay any of the costs for the new church.<ref name=\"Dolkart p. 383\">{{harvnb|Dolkart|1998|ps=.|p=383, note 157}}</ref>\n\n=== Planning and construction ===\n\n==== Site selection ====\n[[File:Riverside Ch back jeh.jpg|thumb|Claremont Avenue view]]\nMorningside Heights, where the new church was to be located, was quickly being developed as a residential neighborhood surrounded by numerous higher-education institutions, including [[Union Theological Seminary (New York City)|Union Theological Seminary]] and [[International House of New York]].<ref name=\"Dolkart p. 1\">{{harvnb|ps=.|Dolkart|1998|p=1}}</ref><ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|2000|ps=.|p=4}}</ref> The development had been spurred by the presence of [[Riverside Park (Manhattan)|Riverside Park]] and [[Riverside Drive (Manhattan)|Riverside Drive]] nearby, as well as the construction of the [[New York City Subway]]'s [[IRT Broadway\u2013Seventh Avenue Line|Broadway\u2013Seventh Avenue Line]] (the modern-day {{NYCS trains|Broadway-Seventh north}}) under [[Broadway (Manhattan)|Broadway]].<ref name=\"NYCL p. 3\" /><ref name=\"Dolkart p. 1\" /> Rockefeller briefly considered a location on [[Morningside Drive (Manhattan)|Morningside Drive]], on the eastern edge of Morningside Heights. However, he ultimately decided on a site at the southeast corner of Riverside Drive and 122nd Street on the neighborhood's western border, which overlooked Riverside Park to the west and [[Sakura Park|Claremont Park]] to the north.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\" /><ref name=\"Dolkart p. 74\">{{harvnb|Dolkart|1998|ps=.|p=74}}</ref> Rockefeller felt that the Riverside Drive site was more easily visible, since it abutted the [[Hudson River]] and would be seen by recreational users of Riverside Drive.<ref name=\"Dolkart p. 74\" />\n\nIn May 1925, Rockefeller finalized his purchase of the new church's site at Riverside Drive.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1925/05/26/archives/rockefeller-jr-buys-plot-uptown-block-on-morningside-drive.html|title=Rockefeller Jr. Buys Plot Uptown; Block on Morningside Drive Considered Logical Location for Edifice Asked by Fosdick|last=|first=|date=May 26, 1925|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 3, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> That July, he exchanged his previous purchase of a plot on Morningside Drive for another plot on Riverside Drive.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1925/07/25/archives/fosdicks-church-to-go-up-on-drive-rockefeller-exchanges-morningside.html|title=Fosdick's Church to Go Up on Drive; Rockefeller Exchanges Morningside Plot for Site Near Grant's Tomb|last=|first=|date=July 25, 1925|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 5, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Shortly afterward, he acquired yet more land, after which he had a frontage of {{Convert|250|ft|m|abbr=}} on Riverside Drive for the new church.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1925/08/08/archives/rockefeller-adds-to-plot-for-church-acquires-twelvestory-apartment.html|title=Rockefeller Adds to Plot for Church; Acquires Twelve-Story Apartment House on Riverside Drive, Making Frontage of 250 Feet|last=|first=|date=August 8, 1925|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 5, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> At the time of the acquisition, three apartment buildings and two mansions occupied the church's future site. Rockefeller wished to keep the apartments in place for several years to fund the church's eventual construction.<ref name=\"Dolkart p. 74\" />\n\n==== Planning ====\nRockefeller was the chairman of the committee tasked with creating a new building for the church. Hoping to avoid publicity, he did not host an architectural competition, but instead, privately asked several architectural firms to submit plans for the building.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\" /><ref name=\"Dolkart p. 75\">{{harvnb|Dolkart|1998|ps=.|p=75}}</ref>{{efn|These firms included [[McKim, Mead & White]], [[Allen & Collens]], [[Henry C. Pelton]], [[Ralph Adams Cram]], and [[York and Sawyer]].<ref>{{harvnb|Dolkart|1998|ps=.|pp=75\u201376}}</ref>}} Rockefeller tried to downplay his role in the planning and construction process, asking that his name not be mentioned in media reports or discussion of the church, though with little success.<ref name=\"Dolkart p. 73\" /> His role in the selection process raised concerns from church trustees such as Fosdick, who believed that such close financial involvement could place the church in \"a very vulnerable position\".<ref>{{harvnb|ps=.|Miller|1985|p=204}}</ref><ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\" /> [[John Roach Straton]], reverend of the [[Calvary Baptist Church (Manhattan)|Calvary Baptist Church]] on [[57th Street (Manhattan)|57th Street]] in Midtown Manhattan, criticized Rockefeller's involvement and mockingly suggested that it be called the [[Socony]] Church, after the oil company headed by the Rockefellers.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1925/06/08/archives/straton-criticizes-fosdicks-church-thinks-it-means-rockefellers.html|title=Straton Criticizes Fosdick's Church; Thinks It Means Rockefellers Hereafter Will Have Their Own Sanctuary|last=|first=|date=June 8, 1925|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 5, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>  George S. Chappell, writing in ''[[The New Yorker]]'' under the pseudonym \"T-Square\", joked that the project \"was known to most secular minds as the Rockefeller Cathedral.\"''<ref name=\"Dolkart p. 73\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Chappell|first=George S. (T-Square)|date=November 29, 1930|title=The Sky Line|journal=The New Yorker|volume=6|pages=82}}</ref>''\n\nNeither Rockefeller nor Fosdick had strict requirements for the church's architectural style. Rockefeller only asked that the new building include space for the Park Avenue Baptist Church's [[carillon]], which he had donated.<ref name=\"Dolkart p. 75\" /> Most of the plans entailed a church facing 122nd Street and wrapping around the existing apartment buildings on the site. The exception was a plan by [[Allen & Collens]] and [[Henry C. Pelton]], who had designed the Park Avenue Baptist Church. Their plan called for a [[Gothic Revival architecture|Gothic Revival]] church with its main entrance on the side, facing Riverside Drive, with a bell tower as well as apartment towers for the neighboring [[Union Theological Seminary (New York City)|Union Theological Seminary]].<ref name=\"Dolkart p. 76\">{{harvnb|Dolkart|1998|ps=.|p=76}}</ref> The building committee removed the apartment towers from the church plan, and Allen, Collens, and Pelton were selected to design the new church in February 1926.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\" /><ref name=\"Dolkart p. 76\" /><ref name=\"NYT-Rockefeller-Plans-1926\" /> As part of the plans, there would be a {{Convert|375|ft|m|-tall|abbr=|adj=mid}} [[bell tower]] (later changed to {{convert|392|ft}}), a 2,400-seat auditorium, and athletic rooms. The building would occupy a lot {{Convert|100|ft||abbr=}} wide by {{Convert|225|ft||abbr=}} long.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\" /><ref name=\"NYT-Rockefeller-Plans-1926\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1926/02/12/archives/rockefeller-plans-4000000-church-on-riverside-drive-400foot-gothic.html|title=Rockefeller Plans $4,000,000 Church On Riverside Drive; 400-Foot Gothic Campanile Will House the Carillon, Close to Grant's Tomb|last=|first=|date=February 12, 1926|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 5, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Since there was no room for a chapel in the original plans, Rockefeller proposed trading land with the Union Theological Seminary. In May 1926, Rockefeller gave Union an apartment building on 99 Claremont Avenue, to the northeast of the church. In exchange, Riverside Church received a small plot to its south, allowing for the construction of the chapel as well as a proposed [[cloister]] passage to Claremont Avenue.<ref name=\"Dolkart p. 77\">{{harvnb|Dolkart|1998|ps=.|p=77}}</ref>\n\nRockefeller chose to delay the construction process until after the leases of the site's existing tenants expired in October.<ref name=\"NYT-Rockefeller-Plans-1926\" /> The official plans were filed with the [[New York City Department of Buildings]] in November 1926.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1926/11/02/archives/rockefeller-plan-for-church-is-filed-4000000-edifice-of-park-av.html|title=Rockefeller Plan for Church is Filed; $4,000,000 Edifice of Park Av. Baptists Will Rise on Riverside Drive|last=|first=|date=November 2, 1926|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 5, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The congregation voted to approve the building plans that December, at a cost of $4&nbsp;million.<ref name=\"NYT-Plans-Approved-1926\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1926/12/27/archives/baptists-approve-4000000-plans-for-fosdick-church-razing-starts-on.html|title=Baptists Approve $4,000,000 Plans For Fosdick Church; Razing Starts on the Site for Edifice to Be Built to Endure for Generations|last=|first=|date=December 27, 1926|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 4, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Pelton and Collens then went to France, driving over {{Convert|2500|mi||abbr=}} within the country to look for churches upon which to model Riverside Church's design.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 5\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|2000|ps=.|p=5}}</ref><ref name=\"Carder p. 5\">{{harvnb|ps=.|Carder|1930|p=5}}</ref>  They eventually selected the 13th-century [[Chartres Cathedral]] as their inspiration.<ref name=\"NYT-Plans-Approved-1926\" /><ref name=\"NYCL p. 5\" /><ref name=\"Carder p. 9\">{{harvnb|ps=.|Carder|1930|p=9}}</ref>\n\n==== Construction ====\n[[File:General_Grant_National_Memorial,_The_Riverside_Church,_and_The_Interchurch_Center_(8026589050)_(2).jpg|thumb|Riverside Church (center), [[Grant's Tomb]] (left), and [[The Interchurch Center]] (right) from the Hudson River]]\nMarc Eidlitz & Son, Inc. were hired as the contractors of the new Riverside Drive church.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 6\" /> On November 21, 1927, the church's ceremonial [[cornerstone]] was laid, marking the start of construction.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 6\" /><ref name=\"NYT-Cornerstone-1927\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1927/11/21/archives/cornerstone-laid-for-fosdick-church-hundreds-witness-ceremony-in.html|title=Cornerstone Laid For Fosdick Church; Hundreds Witness Ceremony in Drive at Foundation of $4,000,000 Edifice|last=|first=|date=November 21, 1927|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 5, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref name=\"Dolkart p. 80\">{{harvnb|Dolkart|1998|ps=.|p=80}}</ref> The cornerstone featured items such as Woelfkin's Bible and ''New York Times'' articles about the new church.<ref name=\"NYT-Cornerstone-1927\" /><ref name=\"NYCL p. 12\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|2000|ps=.|p=12}}</ref> The Park Avenue church building, as well as three adjacent rowhouses, was sold for $1.5&nbsp;million in April 1928.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 6\" /> The same month, the Park Avenue Baptist Church's official monthly newsletter announced that its existing 53-bell carillon would be expanded to 72 bells upon its relocation to Riverside Drive, making it the largest set of bells in the world.<ref name=\"D&C-Chimes-1928\">{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/38645319/|title=Largest Chimes for Park Avenue Church|date=April 24, 1928|work=Democrat and Chronicle|access-date=November 8, 2019|page=4|via=newspapers.com {{open access}}}}</ref>\n\nThree fires occurred in late 1928 after wooden scaffolding around the church was ignited.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/38486841/|title=Rockefeller Pays Visit to Ruins at Church Fire|date=December 23, 1928|work=New York Daily News|access-date=November 5, 2019|page=318|via=newspapers.com {{open access}}}}</ref> One of these fires, on December 22, 1928, caused $1&nbsp;million in damages and almost completely destroyed the interior, though the exterior remained mostly intact. Much of the damages were covered by an insurance policy placed on the building.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1928/12/22/archives/night-fire-sweeps-riverside-church-as-100000-look-on-flames-raging.html|title=Night Fire Sweeps Riverside Church As 100,000 Look On; Flames Raging In Rockefeller's Riverside Church|date=December 22, 1928|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 4, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/38486753/|title=Fire Guts 'Rockefeller Church'; Huge Edifice Reduced to Black Shell|date=December 22, 1928|work=Brooklyn Citizen|access-date=November 5, 2019|page=1|via=newspapers.com {{open access}}}}</ref> Shortly after the December 1928 fire, Rockefeller announced that he would continue with construction after insurance claims were settled.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1928/12/24/archives/rockefeller-church-to-resume-building-work-to-proceed-on-burned.html|title=Rockefeller Church To Resume Building; Work to Proceed on Burned Riverside Edifice as Soon as Insurance is Settled|last=|first=|date=December 24, 1928|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 4, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The fire delayed the completion of the interior by six months.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 12\" /><ref>{{harvnb|Miller|1985|ps=.|p=208}}</ref> In February 1929, the congregation began seeking donations to continue construction. Rockefeller donated $1.5&nbsp;million, which when combined with the proceeds from the Park Avenue building's sale, provided $3&nbsp;million in funds.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1929/02/19/archives/seek-gifts-to-build-riverside-church-trustees-planning-endowment.html|title=Seek Gifts to Build Riverside Church; Trustees, Planning Endowment Fund, Say Contributions Will Be Welcomed|last=|first=|date=February 19, 1929|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 4, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Construction of a mortuary at the Riverside Drive church was approved in March 1929.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1929/03/23/archives/mortuary-chapel-in-riverside-church-rockefeller-approves-feature.html|title=Mortuary Chapel in Riverside Church; Rockefeller Approves Feature for New Edifice of Park Avenue Congregation|last=|first=|date=March 23, 1929|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 4, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> While construction was ongoing, the congregation temporarily relocated to Temple Beth-El on Fifth Avenue and 76th Street for nine months starting in July 1929.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 6\" />\n\nThe first portion of the new church building, the assembly hall under the auditorium, opened in October 1929.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1929/10/03/archives/first-unit-opened-in-riverside-church-precommunion-service-is-held.html|title=First Unit Opened In Riverside Church; Pre-Communion Service Is Held in Assembly Hall of New Rockefeller Edifice|last=|first=|date=October 3, 1929|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 3, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Miller|1985|ps=.|p=205}}</ref> That December, Fosdick formally filed plans to rename the church from \"Park Avenue Baptist Church\" to \"Riverside Church\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1929/12/12/archives/fosdick-church-drops-baptist-from-title-changes-name-to-the.html|title=Fosdick Church Drops Baptist From Title; Changes Name to the Riverside Church|last=|first=|date=December 12, 1929|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 5, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>  The bell was hoisted to the top of the tower's carillon in early September 1930,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1930/09/07/archives/will-hoist-22ton-bell-riverside-church-to-complete-carillon-on.html|title=Will Hoist 22-Ton Bell; Riverside Church to Complete Carillon on Tuesday|last=|first=|date=September 7, 1930|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 6, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> and the tower was completed later that month, with the first [[Sunday school]] class being held there on September 29.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1930/09/29/archives/memorial-tower-opened-riverside-church-sunday-school-classes-held.html|title=Memorial Tower Opened; Riverside Church Sunday School Classes Held There.|date=September 29, 1930|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 5, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The church was completed a week later, on October 5.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 6\" /><ref name=\"Dolkart p. 80\" /><ref name=\":0\">{{harvnb|Paris et al.|2004|ps=.|p=137}}</ref>  On that date, the first service in the altar was attended by 3,200 people, and though all of the space in the nave and basement was filled, thousands more wished to enter.<ref name=\"Dolkart p. 80\" /><ref name=\":0\" /> The next month, officials received two oil paintings from Rockefeller Jr.'s collection.<ref name=\"NYT-Paintings-1930\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1930/11/01/archives/reveal-rockefeller-gift-riverside-church-executives-tell-of.html|title=Reveal Rockefeller Gift; Riverside Church Executives Tell of Receiving Two Paintings|last=|first=|date=November 1, 1930|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 6, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The first officers of Riverside Church were elected in December 1930<ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 19\" /> and the church was formally dedicated with an interdenominational service two months later.<ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 19\" /><ref name=\"NYT-Carillon-1931\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1931/02/12/archives/riverside-carillon-is-heard-miles-away-notes-of-72-bells-ring-out.html|title=Riverside Carillon is Heard Miles Away; Notes of 72 Bells Ring Out as Denominational Leaders Laud Spirit of Church|last=|first=|date=February 12, 1931|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 8, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The total cost of construction was estimated at $4&nbsp;million.<ref name=\"NYT-Pew-Phones-1930\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1930/09/27/archives/riverside-church-puts-in-pew-phones-equipment-available-to-aid.html|title=Riverside Church Puts in Pew Phones; Equipment Available to Aid Hearing in All Parts of New Edifice|last=|first=|date=September 27, 1930|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 8, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> In the early years of the new building, journalists tended to refer to the church in association with either Rockefeller or Fosdick, although the former sought to reduce emphasis on his role at the church.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 7\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|2000|ps=.|p=7}}</ref> Riverside Church's completion sharply contrasted with the Cathedral of St. John the Divine, which remained incomplete after almost four decades.<ref name=\"Dolkart p. 81\">{{harvnb|Dolkart|1998|ps=.|p=81}}</ref>\n\nDespite the completion of Riverside Church, Rockefeller felt that the surroundings still needed to be improved.<ref name=\"Dolkart p. 81\" /> He announced in 1932 that he would pay for a $350,000 landscaping of the adjacent [[Sakura Park]], which at the time stood decrepit.<ref name=\"Dolkart p. 81\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1932/02/09/archives/claremont-park-to-be-beautified-rockefeller-to-pay-350000-for.html|title=Claremont Park to be Beautified; Rockefeller to Pay $350,000 for Improvement of City Plot at Riverside Church|date=February 9, 1932|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 5, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Rockefeller hired the [[Olmsted Brothers]] to renovate the park,<ref name=\"Dolkart p. 82\">{{harvnb|Dolkart|1998|ps=.|p=82}}</ref> and the project was completed two years later.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1934/05/26/archives/claremont-park-is-opened-to-public-twoacre-tract-on-riverside-drive.html|title=Claremont Park is Opened to Public; Two-Acre Tract on Riverside Drive Improved by Rockefeller at Cost of $315,000.|date=May 26, 1934|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 5, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Additionally, when Union Theological Seminary announced that it would build a new apartment building at 99 Claremont Avenue. Rockefeller offered to exchange his neighboring apartment building at 122nd Street and Claremont Avenue for the lots south of the church, which were owned by the seminary. The land was swapped in 1931 after Rockefeller offered to finance part of the dormitory's construction.<ref name=\"Dolkart p. 82\" /> In 1935, the land under the church was deeded to Rockefeller,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1935/06/16/archives/riverside-church-deeded-formal-transfer-of-land-by-rockefeller-is.html|title=Riverside Church Deeded; Formal Transfer of Land by Rockefeller Is Placed on Record.|date=June 16, 1935|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 5, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> and he also purchased a lot at Riverside Drive and 122nd Street from [[St. Luke's Hospital (New York City)|St. Luke's Hospital]], so that he now owned all of the land along the eastern side of Riverside Drive between 120th and 122nd Streets.<ref name=\"Dolkart p. 83\">{{harvnb|Dolkart|1998|ps=.|p=83}}</ref> Ultimately, Rockefeller spent a total of $10.5&nbsp;million toward land acquisitions and church construction.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 7\" />\n\n=== Use ===\n\n==== 1930s through mid-1960s ====\n[[File:Riverside Church, New York City (2014) - 12.JPG|thumb|Memorial inscription to [[John D. Rockefeller Jr.]], who funded much of the church's construction|alt=Memorial inscription to John D. Rockefeller Jr., who funded much of the church's construction]]\nThe completion of the new church building at Morningside Heights resulted in a steady increase in the congregation's membership. By May 1946, the congregation had 3,500 members, 800 more than twenty years previously. According to a brochure issued by the church, \"soon every room [...] was in use seven days a week\", and enrollment at the church's Sunday school had increased correspondingly.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 7\" />\n\nRiverside Church became a community icon and a religious center of Morningside Heights. By 1939, the church had more than 200 persons on its staff in both part-time and full-time positions, and over 10,000 people a week were being served by the church's various social and religious services, athletic events, and employment programs.<ref name=\"WPA1939\" /> In addition to its highly attended Sunday morning service, Riverside Church hosted [[Confirmation|Communion]] services every first Sunday afternoon, as well as Ministry of Music services on other Sunday afternoons. The Riverside Guild, the young-adult fellowship, held worship services during Sunday evenings. Weddings and funerals were also hosted at the church.<ref>{{harvnb|Paris et al.|2004|ps=.|pp=67\u201370}}</ref> The [[United States Naval Reserve Midshipmen's School]] at Columbia started using Riverside Church for services in 1942, drawing 2,000 attendees on average.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 7\" /> The Midshipmen's School continued to hold its services at the church until October 1945.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 7\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1945/10/22/archives/navy-school-thanks-riverside-church.html|title=Navy School Thanks Riverside Church|date=October 22, 1945|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 8, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nIn June 1945, Fosdick announced that he would step down as senior minister, effective the following May.<ref name=\"NYT-Fosdick-1945\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1945/06/06/archives/fosdick-to-quit-riverside-church-retirement-date-set-for-may-1946.html|title=Fosdick to Quit Riverside Church; Retirement Date Set for May, 1946; Announcement Made at Joint Meeting of Deacons and Trustees--Founder and Pastor of the Church Since 1930|last=Studio|first=The New York Times|date=June 6, 1945|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 8, 2019|last2=1943|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> This spurred a search for a new pastor, and in March 1946, Robert James McCracken was named for the position.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1946/03/28/archives/riverside-church-names-new-pastor-in-new-riverside-church-offices.html|title=Riverside Church Names New Pastor; in New Riverside Church Offices|last=McDowell|first=Rachel K.|date=March 28, 1946|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 8, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> McCracken officially became the senior pastor of Riverside Church that October.<ref name=\"NYT-McCracken-1946\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1946/10/03/archives/riverside-church-installs-pastor-new-riverside-church-pastor.html|title=Riverside Church Installs Pastor; New Riverside Church Pastor Installed|date=October 3, 1946|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 8, 2019|url-status=live|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> As Fosdick and McCracken held each other in mutual respect, the transition between ministers went smoothly.<ref name=\"Paris et al. pp. 74-75\">{{harvnb|Paris et al.|2004|ps=.|pp=74\u201375}}</ref> Over the next two decades as senior pastor, McCracken continued Fosdick's policy of religious liberalism.<ref name=\"Paris et al. pp. 74-75\" /><ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 34\">{{harvnb|Paris et al.|2004|ps=.|p=34}}</ref> Halfway through McCracken's tenure, in 1956, the church conducted an internal report and found that the organizational structure was disorganized, and that most staff did not feel that any single person was in charge. As a result, six councils were created and placed under the purview of the deacons and trustees.<ref name=\"Paris et al. pp. 43-44\">{{harvnb|Paris et al.|2004|ps=.|pp=43\u201344}}</ref> The councils partitioned power into \"a series of mini-kingdoms\", as a later pastor, Ernest T. Campbell, described it.<ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 46\">{{harvnb|Paris et al.|2004|ps=.|p=46}}</ref>\n\nConstruction on the Martin Luther King Jr. Wing, to the south of the existing church, started in 1955. The seven-story wing was designed by Collens, Willis & Beckonert, successors to Allen & Collens; its $15&nbsp;million cost was funded by Rockefeller.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 7\" /><ref name=\"Dolkart p. 83\" /> The wing was dedicated in December 1959 and contained additional facilities for the church's programs.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 7\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1959/12/07/archives/new-8story-wing-opens-at-riverside.html|title=New 8-Story Wing Opens at Riverside|date=December 7, 1959|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 9, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref name=\"NYDN-Wing-1959\">{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/38718458/|title=Dedicate Riverside Church Wing|date=December 7, 1959|work=New York Daily News|access-date=November 9, 2019|page=165|via=newspapers.com {{open access}}}}</ref> A {{Convert|15|ft||abbr=|adj=on}} \"dummy\" antenna had been placed on top of Riverside Church's 392-foot-tall carillon earlier that year, to determine whether it could be used by Columbia University's radio station, [[WKCR-FM|WKCR]] (89.9 FM), though the antenna was strongly opposed by parishioners and the local community.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1959/01/09/archives/riverside-church-is-aroused-by-trial-radio-aerial-on-roof.html|title=Riverside Church Is Aroused By Trial Radio Aerial on Roof|date=January 9, 1959|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 9, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Nevertheless, the church decided to place an antenna atop the carillon for its own radio station, the top of the antenna being {{Convert|440|ft|m|abbr=}} above ground level.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1960/12/28/archives/new-fm-station-on-air-here-jan-1-wrvr-will-be-sponsored-by.html|title=New FM Station on Air Here Jan 1; WRVR Will Be Sponsored by Riverside Church|last=Shepard|first=Richard F.|date=December 28, 1960|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 9, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Riverside Church started operating the radio station [[WLTW|WRVR]] (106.7 [[FM broadcasting|FM]]) in 1961, and continued to operate it until 1976.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 7\" /> Additionally, Riverside Church's congregation voted to merge with the [[United Church of Christ]] in 1960.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1960/12/08/archives/riverside-church-acting-on-merger-meets-to-ratify-constitution-of.html|title=Riverside Church Acting on Merger; Meets to Ratify Constitution of United Church of Christ -- 2d Consolidation Urged|date=December 8, 1960|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 9, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The Stone Gym, a preexisting Union Theological Seminary building southeast of the original church, was purchased by Rockefeller and then reopened as a community facility in April 1962, after a five-year renovation.<ref name=\"NPS p. 3\">{{harvnb|National Park Service|2012|ps=.|p=3}}</ref><ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 255\">{{harvnb|Paris et al.|2004|ps=.|p=255}}</ref> McCracken announced in April 1967 that he would leave his position as senior minister, citing health issues.<ref name=\"NYT-McCracken-1967\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1967/04/24/archives/dr-mccracken-to-leave-pulpit-after-two-decades-at-riverside.html|title=Dr. McCracken to Leave Pulpit After Two Decades at Riverside|last=Dugan|first=George|date=April 24, 1967|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 9, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n==== Late 1960s through 1990s ====\n[[File:Riverside Church, New York City (2014) - 02.JPG|thumb|left|[[Archivolt]]s in the front doorway]]\nErnest T. Campbell became pastor in November 1968.<ref name=\"Paris et al. pp. 45-47\">{{harvnb|Paris et al.|2004|ps=.|pp=45\u201347}}</ref><ref name=\"NYT-Campbell-1968\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1968/11/18/archives/dr-campbell-is-installed-at-riverside-church-predecessor-dr.html|title=Dr. Campbell Is Installed at Riverside Church; Predecessor, Dr. McCracken, Gives Him the Charge Dr. Marney Calls in Sermon for 'Vast Repentance'|last=Dugan|first=George|date=November 18, 1968|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 9, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Less than a year after Campbell became senior minister, civil rights leader [[James Forman]] interrupted a sermon at Riverside Church, citing it as one of several churches from which black Americans could ask [[Reparations for slavery|reparations]] for [[Slavery in the United States|slavery]].<ref name=\"NYT-Budget-1970\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1970/02/01/archives/riverside-church-has-money-woes-20000-short-of-its-budget-goal.html|title=Riverside Church Has Money Woes|date=February 1, 1970|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 9, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref name=\"Paris et al. pp. 89-91\">{{harvnb|Paris et al.|2004|ps=.|pp=89\u201391}}</ref> This led to the church releasing its financial figures for the first time in 1970, which valued the building at $86&nbsp;million and the total [[financial endowment]] of $18&nbsp;million,<ref name=\"NYT-Budget-1970\" /> as well as the creation of a $450,000 Fund for Social Justice to disburse reparations over three years.<ref name=\"Paris et al. pp. 89-91\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1970/03/02/archives/riverside-church-will-give-150000-a-year-to-the-poor.html|title=Riverside Church Will Give $150,000 a Year to the Poor|date=March 2, 1970|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 9, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Further, following a 1972 metropolitan mission study, several ministries were formed at Riverside, aimed toward ameliorating social conditions in the New York City area.<ref>{{harvnb|Paris et al.|2004|ps=.|p=206}}</ref> Campbell's tenure was marked by several controversial sermons,<ref name=\"Paris et al. pp. 89-91\" /> as well as increasing conflicts among the church's boards, councils, and staff.<ref name=\"Paris et al. pp. 45-47\" /> In June 1976, Campbell resigned suddenly, having felt that his style of leadership was not sufficient to reconcile these disagreements.<ref name=\"Paris et al. pp. 45-47\" /><ref name=\"NYT-Campbell-1976\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1976/06/25/archives/campbell-quits-ministry-at-the-riverside-church.html|title=Campbell Quits Ministry At the Riverside Church|last=Briggs|first=Kenneth A.|date=June 25, 1976|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 9, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The same month saw the installment of the church's first female pastor, Evelyn Newman.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1976/06/07/archives/riverside-church-installs-its-first-woman-as-pastor.html|title=Riverside Church Installs Its First Woman as Pastor|last=Spiegel|first=Irving|date=June 7, 1976|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 9, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nBy a vote in August 1977, [[William Sloane Coffin]] was selected as the next senior minister of Riverside Church.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1977/08/15/archives/riverside-church-vote-approves-coffin-as-minister.html|title=Riverside Church Vote Approves Coffin as Minister|last=Wedemeyer|first=Dee|date=August 15, 1977|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 9, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Coffin officiated his first service in November 1977.<ref name=\"NYT-Coffin-1977\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1977/11/07/archives/dr-coffin-has-a-lively-first-service-at-riverside.html|title=Dr. Coffin Has a Lively First Service at Riverside|last=Dunning|first=Jennifer|date=November 7, 1977|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 9, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> At this point, the congregation's size had been declining for several years. However, after Coffin's selection as senior minister, membership had increased to 2,627 by the end of 1979, and total annual attendance for morning services rose from 49,902 in 1976 to 71,536 in 1978.<ref name=\"NYT-Coffin-1979\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1979/12/31/archives/coffin-and-his-liberal-pulpit-renew-legacy-of-controversy-a.html|title=Coffin and His 'Liberal Pulpit' Renew Legacy of Controversy|last=Briggs|first=Kenneth A.|date=December 31, 1979|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 9, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Coffin's tenure was also marked by theologically liberal sermons, many of which were controversial,<ref name=\"NYT-Coffin-1979\" /><ref name=\"Paris et al. pp. 106-107\">{{harvnb|Paris et al.|2004|ps=.|pp=106\u2013107}}</ref> though he was more traditional in his worship<!--, emphasizing Sunday morning service over other services-->.<ref name=\"Paris et al. pp. 106-107\" /><!-- This era also saw [[Channing E. Phillips]], the first [[African-American]] major-party [[President of the United States|U.S. presidential nominee]], being hired as minister of planning and coordination.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/11/12/obituaries/channing-e-phillips-dies-at-59-minister-and-civil-rights-leader.html|title=Channing E. Phillips Dies at 59; Minister and Civil Rights Leader|last=McQuiston|first=John T.|date=November 12, 1987|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 10, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>--> Coffin announced his intention to resign in July 1987 to become the president of disarmament organization SANE/Freeze,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/07/20/nyregion/coffin-resigns-to-praise-and-criticism.html|title=Coffin Resigns to Praise and Criticism|last=Goldman|first=Ari L.|date=July 20, 1987|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 9, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> and held his last sermon that December.<ref name=\"NYT-Coffin-1987\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/12/21/nyregion/dr-coffin-says-goodbye-to-riverside.html|title=Dr. Coffin Says Goodbye to Riverside|last=Marriott|first=Michel|date=December 21, 1987|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 9, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nRiverside Church formed a committee, which conducted a nationwide search for their next senior minister over the next year. In February 1989, the committee chose [[James A. Forbes]], a professor at nearby Union Theological Seminary, for the position.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1989/02/01/nyregion/riverside-chooses-new-minister.html|title=Riverside Chooses New Minister|last=Goldman|first=Ari L.|date=February 1, 1989|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 10, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref name=\"Paris et al. pp. 108-109\">{{harvnb|Paris et al.|2004|ps=.|pp=108\u2013109}}</ref> The congregation then voted almost unanimously to approve Forbes's selection, thereby making him the church's first black senior minister.<ref name=\"Paris et al. pp. 108-109\" /><ref name=\"NYT-Forbes-1989\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1989/02/06/nyregion/members-elect-a-new-pastor-at-riverside.html|title=Members Elect A New Pastor At Riverside|last=Goldman|first=Ari L.|date=February 6, 1989|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 10, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> At the time, between one-fourth and one-third of the congregation was black or Hispanic.<ref name=\"NYT-Forbes-1989\" /> However, tensions soon developed between Forbes and executive minister David Dyson over matters ranging from Forbes's sermon lengths to his musical choices. The tensions grew to the point that a [[Mediation|mediator]] was enlisted after Forbes tried to fire Dyson.<ref name=\"NYT-Forbes-1992\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/05/18/nyregion/riverside-s-pastor-at-center-of-turmoil.html|title=Riverside's Pastor at Center of Turmoil|last=Goldman|first=Ari L.|date=May 18, 1992|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 10, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The dispute was resolved when Dyson resigned in October 1992.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/10/11/nyregion/update-tension-lessens-as-minister-leaves-riverside-church.html|title=Update; Tension Lessens as Minister Leaves Riverside Church|date=October 11, 1992|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 10, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nIn 1996, Riverside Church started conducting a study on the building's current use and services,<ref name=\"NYT-Alter-1998\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/01/25/nyregion/neighborhood-report-upper-west-side-alter-riverside-church-like-redoing-chartres.html|title=Neighborhood Report: Upper West Side; Alter Riverside Church? Like Redoing Chartres, Foes Say|last=Allon|first=Janet|date=January 25, 1998|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 10, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> and the following October, Body Lawson, Ben Paul Associated Architects and Planners published their Riverside Church Master Plan.<ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 175\">{{harvnb|Paris et al.|2004|ps=.|p=175}}</ref> The plan included a major addition on Riverside Church's eastern side, which included the relocation of the Claremont Avenue entrance, paving of the forecourt, reconfiguration of the cloister lobby, and construction of a seven-story building over the gymnasium. This was controversial among many congregants, who started a petition to ask the [[New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission]] (NYCLPC) to designate the church so that the original appearance of that entrance could not be altered.<ref name=\"NYT-Alter-1998\" /> In December 1998, the congregation voted to officially nominate the church for landmark status.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/12/06/nyregion/neighborhood-report-morningside-heights-solomonic-landmarking-decision-riverside.html|title=Neighborhood Report: Morningside Heights; A Solomonic Landmarking Decision at Riverside Church|last=Siegal|first=Nina|date=December 6, 1998|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 11, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The congregation chose to nominate only the original church building, excluding the Martin Luther King Jr. Wing, despite preservationists' requests that the entire structure be considered for landmark designation. The NYCLPC approved landmark status for the original church in May 2000.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/05/17/nyregion/riverside-church-gets-landmark-status.html|title=Riverside Church Gets Landmark Status|last=Siegal|first=Nina|date=May 17, 2000|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 11, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n==== 21st century ====\n[[File:Sakura-Park-New-York-with-Riverside-Church.jpg|thumb|Viewed from [[Sakura Park]], directly to the north]]\nTwo controversies involving Riverside Church arose in the early 2000s. The first involved a sexual-abuse allegation against the director of a basketball program at the church, while the second concerned an allegation that the church's finances were being mismanaged due to a $32&nbsp;million decrease in the endowment between 2000 and 2002.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/07/21/nyregion/riverside-minister-faces-an-internal-challenge-again.html|title=Riverside Minister Faces an Internal Challenge, Again|last=Wakin|first=Daniel J.|date=July 21, 2002|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 11, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The accused basketball director resigned in 2002,<ref>{{Cite news|last=Feuer|first=Alan|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/05/01/nyregion/church-basketball-director-leaves-after-abuse-charge.html|title=Church Basketball Director Leaves After Abuse Charge|date=2002-05-01|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-02-29|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> while the controversy over finances was prolonged through several years of court cases, although the New York Supreme Court had dismissed a lawsuit over the topic.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Konigsberg|first=Eric|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/06/10/nyregion/10riverside.html|title=With an Exit, a Historic Church at a Crossroads|date=2007-06-10|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-02-29|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Forbes announced his retirement in September 2006<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/09/18/nyregion/minister-of-riverside-church-to-step-down.html|title=Minister of Riverside Church to Step Down|last=Barron|first=James|date=September 18, 2006|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 11, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> and held his last sermon in June 2007. By that time, the church had 2,700 congregants, though the congregation was then primarily black and Hispanic.<ref name=\"NYT-Forbes-2007\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/06/10/nyregion/10riverside.html|title=With an Exit, a Historic Church at a Crossroads|last=Konigsberg|first=Eric|date=June 10, 2007|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 10, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> At that time, the church had a $14&nbsp;million annual operating budget and a paid staff of 130.<ref name=\"NYT-Rebuilding-2007\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/05/05/us/05religion.htmle|title=Riverside Takes On the Task of Rebuilding a Church|last=Freedman|first=Samuel G.|date=May 5, 2007|work=The New York Times|accessdate=April 9, 2009|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nAnother nationwide, year-long search commenced, and in August 2008, it was announced that Brad Braxton had been selected as the sixth senior minister of Riverside Church.<ref name=\"NYT8408\" /> His tenure was marked by theological disputes, with congregants disagreeing over whether the church should take a fundamentalist or progressive position, as well as a lawsuit over his high annual salary, which a church spokesperson stated was $457,000. In June 2009, he submitted his letter of resignation due to these disputes.<ref name=\"NYT-Braxton-2009\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/riverside-church-pastor-resigned-accusations-misappropriation-article-1.379032|title=Riverside Church Pastor resigned under accusations of misappropriation|last=Gonzalez|first=Juan|date=July 1, 2009 |website=New York Daily News|access-date=November 11, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gothamist.com/news/controversial-riverside-church-pastor-resigns|title=Controversial Riverside Church Pastor Resigns|last=Del Signore|first=John|date=June 30, 2009|website=Gothamist|publisher=New York Public Radio|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=November 11, 2019}}</ref> Over the next five years, Riverside Church did not have a senior minister, and its congregation size decreased to 1,670 in 2014, representing a loss of over a thousand congregants since 2007.<ref name=\"NYT-Butler-2014\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/06/09/nyregion/riverside-church-elects-amy-butler-as-new-senior-minister.html|title=After Period of Turmoil, Riverside Church Elects New Leader|last=Otterman|first=Sharon|date=June 8, 2014|work=The New York Times|access-date=July 16, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> During this period, in 2012, the church and its annexes were listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]].<ref name=\"nrhp\" />\n\n[[Amy Butler (minister)|Amy K. Butler]] was selected as the church's seventh senior minister in June 2014, becoming the first woman to hold that job.<ref name=\"NYT-Butler-2014\" /> In September 2018, it was announced that Riverside would buy the neighboring [[McGiffert Hall]] at Claremont Avenue and 122nd Street for $45&nbsp;million. The dormitory was located on land that had been donated by John Rockefeller Jr. to the Union Theological Seminary, and under the donation agreement, the church had the [[Right of first refusal|right of first offer]] to buy the building should it ever come up for sale.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2018/09/18/riverside-church-to-buy-neighboring-dorm-for-45m/|title=Riverside Church to buy neighboring dorm for $45M|last=Weiss|first=Lois|date=September 19, 2018|website=New York Post|language=en|access-date=November 11, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://therealdeal.com/2018/09/19/thanks-to-john-d-rockefeller-this-church-beat-out-a-developer-for-a-45m-dorm/|title=Riverside Church {{!}} Union Theological Seminary {{!}} 97 Claremont|date=September 19, 2018|website=The Real Deal New York|language=en-US|access-date=November 11, 2019}}</ref> In July 2019, the church's governing council announced that Butler's contract would not be renewed. At the time, the Church Council and Butler released a joint letter stating that Butler's resignation was mutual. A former church council member later described how Butler was fired after she and several other female staff members had been the victim of sexual harassment by another former council member, Dr. Edward Lowe.<ref name=\"NYT-Butler-2019\">{{cite news|last=Rojas|first=Rick|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/11/nyregion/riverside-church-nyc-sexual-harassment.html|title=Pastor's Exit Exposes Cultural Rifts at a Leading Liberal Church|date=July 11, 2019|work=The New York Times|access-date=July 12, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/social-issues/riverside-church-congregants-call-for-reinstatement-of-first-female-minister-after-her-dismissal-following-a-sex-shop-visit/2019/07/14/1c2c23da-a632-11e9-86dd-d7f0e60391e9_story.html|title=Riverside Church congregants call for reinstatement of first female minister after her exit following a sex shop visit|last=Natanson|first=Hannah|date=July 15, 2019|website=The Washington Post|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-29}}</ref> The former council member claimed that despite the Council previously launching an extensive investigation into Lowe's conduct, the Council had not conducted as thorough of an investigation into allegations against Butler before voting to break off contract negotiations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://baptistnews.com/article/the-stained-glass-cliff-and-the-riverside-church-a-double-standard-for-our-first-female-senior-minister/|title=The stained-glass cliff and the Riverside Church: a double standard for our first female senior minister|date=2019-10-17|website=Baptist News Global|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-26}}</ref> However, media outlets later reported that Butler had taken subordinate staffers to a sex-themed shop during a conference in Minneapolis, and in so doing, bought female subordinates vibrators and waved a church credit card as she paid for the spree.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2019/07/11/pastor-out-at-famed-riverside-church-after-sex-toy-harassment-accusations/|title=Pastor Our at Famed Riverside Church|date=2019-07-11|website=New York Post|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref>\n\n== Design ==\n[[File:Grants Tomb Riverside Church NY1.jpg|thumb|alt=A landscape of Riverside Park; behind the park's trees is the tower of Riverside Church, at center|The tower of Riverside Church (center) rises above the tree-line of [[Riverside Park (Manhattan)|Riverside Park]]. [[Grant's Tomb]] (left) and [[the Interchurch Center]] (right) can also be seen.]]\nRiverside Church takes up a {{Convert|454|x|100|ft|abbr=|adj=on}} lot<ref name=\"NYCL p. 8\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|2000|ps=.|p=8}}</ref> between [[Riverside Drive (Manhattan)|Riverside Drive]] to the west, 122nd Street to the north, [[Claremont Avenue]] to the east, and 120th Street to the south.<ref name=\"Nash 1999\">{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/manhattanskyscra00nash_0|url-access=registration|title=Manhattan skyscrapers|last=Nash|first=Eric|publisher=Princeton Architectural Press|year=1999|isbn=978-1-56898-181-9|location=New York|page=[https://archive.org/details/manhattanskyscra00nash_0/page/69 69]|oclc=40298497}}</ref> Riverside Church's main architects, Henry C. Pelton, Francis R. Allen, and Charles Collens, created the general plan for the church.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 1\" /> Pelton was most involved with tactical planning, while Collens was most involved in the Gothic detail.<ref name=\"Dolkart p. 77\" /> Sculptural elements were designed by [[Robert Garrison (sculptor)|Robert Garrison]] and carried out by local studios such as the [[Piccirilli Brothers]],<ref name=\"NYCL p. 5\" /><ref>{{harvnb|ps=.|Paris et al.|2004|p=148}}</ref> while the interior was designed by [[Burnham Hoyt]].<ref name=\"NYCL p. 6\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|2000|ps=.|p=6}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1960/04/08/archives/burnham-hoyt-73-dies-architect-designed-interior-of-riverside.html|title=Burnham Hoyt, 73, Dies; Architect Designed Interior of Riverside Church|last=|first=|date=April 8, 1960|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 9, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The Martin Luther King Jr. (MLK) Wing to the south of the original building was designed by Collens, Willis & Beckonert, while the Stone Gym to the southeast was designed by Louis E. Jallade.<ref name=\"NPS p. 3\" /> {{As of|2017||df=}}, Riverside Church is the tallest church in the United States (and among the [[List of tallest churches in the world|tallest churches in the world]]),<ref>{{Cite book |last=Levitt |first=Ellen |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=A1y9CQAAQBAJ&pg=PA228 |title=Walking Manhattan: 30 Strolls Exploring Cultural Treasures, Entertainment Centers, and Historical Sites in the Heart of New York City |date=2015-06-30 |publisher=Wilderness Press |isbn=978-0-89997-763-8 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book |last=Bauman |first=Robert |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3wOQDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA92 |title=Fighting to Preserve a Nation's Soul: America's Ecumenical War on Poverty |date=2019 |publisher=University of Georgia Press |isbn=978-0-8203-5487-3 |page=92 |language=en}}</ref> with a tower rising {{convert|392|ft}}.<ref name=\"Dolkart p. 77\" /><ref name=\"NYT-Plans-Approved-1926\" /><ref name=\"D&C-Chimes-1928\" />\n\nPelton and Collens chose a [[Gothic architecture|Gothic architectural]] style for Riverside Church's exterior; by contrast, the internal structure incorporated modern [[Curtain wall (architecture)|curtain walls]] and a steel frame.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 5\" /><ref name=\"Dolkart p. 79\">{{harvnb|Dolkart|1998|ps=.|p=79}}</ref> Fosdick later said that the exterior Gothic style was suited to \"make people pray\", and that the church had \"not outgrown Gothic\" in that regard.<ref>{{harvnb|ps=.|Miller|1985|p=211}}</ref> Riverside Church's design is partially derived from France's [[Chartres Cathedral]], but also draws from several Gothic churches in France and Spain.<ref name=\"NYT-Plans-Approved-1926\" /><ref>{{harvnb|Carder|1930|p=9}}; {{harvnb|Dolkart|1998|pp=78&ndash;79}}; {{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|2000|p=5}}; {{harvnb|National Park Service|2012|p=12}}; {{harvnb|Paris et al.|2004|ps=.|p=140}}</ref> Pelton and Collens said that Chartres would provide the \"fundamental principles\" for the design of Riverside Church, but that Chartres and Riverside would have a completely different outline.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 5\" /><ref name=\"Carder p. 9\" /> The features inspired by Chartres included the detailing of the three Riverside Drive entrances, as well as the lack of decorative elements on the facade, except for the stained glass windows on the walls and the sculptural elements around each portal. The massive single bell tower was inspired by the two western towers at Chartres.<ref name=\"NYT-Plans-Approved-1926\" /><ref name=\"NYCL p. 5\" /> The rest of the facade consists of [[Indiana Limestone]].<ref name=\"NYCL p. 8\" />\n\nUpon Riverside Church's completion, its design received both praise and criticism.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 7\" /> ''The American Architect'' published pieces in mid-1931 that featured a critical viewpoint from Columbia architecture professor [[Walter A. Taylor]], and a rebuttal from architect Charles Crane, who had worked on the project with Pelton. While Taylor believed that the design should have been more [[Modernist architecture|modernist]],<ref name=\"Dolkart p. 79\" /><ref>{{cite journal|last=Taylor|first=Walter|date=June 1931|title=A Criticism ... of the Riverside Church|url=|journal=American Architect|volume=139|pages=32|via=}}</ref> Crane defended Pelton's Gothic design as being \"fundamentally Christian\".<ref name=\"Dolkart p. 79\" /><ref>{{cite journal|last=Crane|first=Charles|date=July 1931|title=Why We Made It Gothic|url=|journal=American Architect|volume=140|pages=26|via=}}</ref> The writers of the 1939 ''[[American Guide Series|WPA Guide]] to New York City'' said that the tower's features make the \"building itself seem smaller than it is, so that its scale is scarcely impressive, even when seen at close range.\"<ref name=\"WPA1939\">{{cite fednyc|pages=387\u2013389}}</ref> Other critics called the building's exterior overly opulent,<ref name=\"AIA5\">{{Cite aia5|page=505}}</ref> and one critic stated that when considered along the progressive ideology, the Gothic design \"can only be interpreted as an outward confession that religion is dead.\"<ref name=\"Dolkart p. 80\" /> Conversely, ''[[The New York Sun]]'' referred to the building as among the \"most outstanding additions\" to New York City's [[church architecture]] \"in recent years\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=The Churches of New York, No. 26: Riverside|last=|first=|date=May 16, 1931|work=New York Sun|access-date=|page=7}}</ref> Eric Nash, in his book ''Manhattan Skyscrapers'', called Riverside Church \"Manhattan's last great eclectic skyscraper\",<ref name=\"Nash 1999\" /> while the ''[[AIA Guide to New York City]]'' dubbed the church \"easily the most prominent architectural work along the [[Hudson River|Hudson (River)]] from [[Midtown Manhattan|midtown]] to the [[George Washington Bridge]]\".<ref name=\"AIA5\" />\n\n== Architectural features ==\n\n=== Main building ===\nThe main structure is centered around the church's [[nave]], which is aligned on a north\u2013south axis, closer to Riverside Avenue on the western portion of the block. The [[chapel]] and [[narthex]] are located to the south, closer to 120th Street, while the [[chancel]] (which contains the altar) and [[ambulatory]] are located to the north, closer to 122nd Street.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 8\" />\n\n==== Facade ====\n[[File:The Riverside Church.jpg|thumb|The northern [[facade]] of Riverside Church, seen from 122nd Street at the eastern side of the [[ambulatory]]]]\nThe western facade of the nave runs along Riverside Drive.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 8\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 4\" /> At the time of Riverside Church's construction, the church did not own the lots along 120th Street to the south. As a result, the three entrances are on the west, facing Riverside Drive, rather than at the back of the nave to the south, as in other churches. The entrances are located atop a small flight of steps leading from the street.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 5\" /><ref name=\"Carder p. 5\" /> The west-facing main entrance, below the tower's base, is through a set of double wooden doors with recessed wooden panel.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 8\" /> The figures sculpted in the concentric [[archivolt]]s of the doorway represent leading religious, scientific, and philosophical figures, while an elaborate [[Tympanum (architecture)|tympanum]] is located below the arches (see {{Section link||Sculpted elements}}).<ref name=\"NYCL p. 5\" /><ref name=\"Paris et al. pp. 155-156\">{{harvnb|Paris et al.|2004|ps=.|pp=155\u2013156}}</ref> To the south is the entrance to the narthex, which contains a single door.<ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 156\" /> Directly south of the narthex entrance is another double-door entrance leads to the chapel,<ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 156\">{{harvnb|Paris et al.|2004|ps=.|p=156}}</ref><ref name=\"NPS p. 15\">{{harvnb|National Park Service|2012|ps=.|p=15}}</ref> and contains two archivolts and a simpler tympanum.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 8\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 4\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 15\" /> The northern portion of the western facade, adjacent to the nave, contains five sets of windows (see {{Section link||Nave}}).<ref name=\"NYCL p. 6\" /><ref name=\"Carder p. 18\" />\n\nThe view of the southern facade is mostly blocked by the MLK Wing to the south. The top portions of four narrow, arched stained-glass windows can be seen above the hip roof of the structure that connects the two sections. Above these stained glass windows are three recessed, arched windows topped by a pediment containing a circular window.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 8\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 4\" />\n\nThe eastern facade is similar to the western facade, in that it also has five groupings of windows facing the nave.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 6\" /><ref name=\"Carder p. 18\" /> However, much of this facade is blocked by McGiffert Hall, which faces directly onto Claremont Avenue and 122nd Street.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 9\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 6\">{{harvnb|National Park Service|2012|ps=.|p=6}}</ref> On the eastern facade of the nave is a cloistered passageway leading to Claremont Avenue (see {{Section link||Cloister passageway}}).<ref name=\"NPS p. 3\" /><ref name=\"NYCL p. 9\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|2000|ps=.|p=9}}</ref> A rose window is located on the eastern facade above the cloister section.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 8\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 4\" />\n\nThe northern facade surrounds the chancel and ambulatory. An arched entrance called the \"Woman's Porch\" is located in the western (left) portion of the north facade and contains carvings of biblical women. Above the entrance arch is an ornate [[belt course]], followed by two lancet windows.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 9\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 5\">{{harvnb|National Park Service|2012|ps=.|p=5}}</ref> Another entrance is located in the eastern (right) portion of the north facade.<ref name=\"NPS p. 5\" /> Between the two entrances is the ambulatory, with two tiers of window groupings, each with a rose window above a pair of lancet windows. The lower section has three sets of windows, while the upper [[clerestory]] section has five sets of windows. Vertical [[buttress]]es, which separate each window grouping, end in [[finial]]s above the roofline.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 9\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 5\" />\n\n==== Nave ====\n[[File:Interior of Riverside Church 01.JPG|thumb|The [[nave]] (foreground) looking toward the [[chancel]] (background)]]\nThe nave takes a Gothic model inspired by France's [[Albi Cathedral]],<ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 147\">{{harvnb|Paris et al.|2004|ps=.|p=147}}</ref> and measures {{Convert|100|ft||abbr=}} high by {{Convert|89|ft||abbr=}} wide and {{Convert|215|ft||abbr=}} long.<ref name=\"NPS p. 7\">{{harvnb|National Park Service|2012|ps=.|p=7}}</ref> The width between the overhanging clerestory walls is {{Convert|60|ft||abbr=}}.<ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 147\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 7\" /><ref name=\"Dolkart p. 79\" /> The low and wide form of the nave is inspired by southern French and Spanish churches.<ref name=\"Dolkart pp. 78-79\">{{harvnb|Dolkart|1998|ps=.|pp=78&ndash;79}}</ref> The nave contains a metal roof, whose base is surrounded by a shallow [[Arcade (architecture)|arcade]].<ref name=\"NYCL p. 8\" /> Its interior contains an Indiana limestone finish, while the ceilings of its vaults are lined with [[Guastavino tile|Guastavino terracotta tiles]], and its floor is made of marble.<ref name=\"NPS p. 7\" />\n\nThe nave's western and eastern walls comprise three main vertical sections, which are split by buttresses.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 8\" /> Along the bottom portion of the nave (adjacent to the aisles), there are five architectural bays each on the western and eastern walls, with each bay containing a pointed-arch window.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 6\" /><ref name=\"Carder p. 18\">{{harvnb|Carder|1930|ps=.|p=18}}</ref><ref name=\"NPS p. 8\">{{harvnb|National Park Service|2012|ps=.|p=8}}</ref> Above the stained-glass windows, each bay contains a [[triforium]] gallery with three [[colonette]]s, followed by two adjacent [[lancet window]]s in the [[clerestory]], and topped by a [[rose window]].<ref name=\"NYCL p. 8\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 8\" /><ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 170\" /> Pointed arches, resting on piers that contain [[engaged column]]s, support each of the clerestory bays as well as serve as the bases for the [[Rib vault|ribs]] under the vaulted ceiling.<ref name=\"NPS p. 7\" /> The engaged columns are surmounted by [[Corinthian order|Corinthian capitals]] that are decorated with scenes from the [[Book of Jeremiah]]. The ceilings of the vaults underneath the triforium galleries are faced with Guastavino tile,<ref name=\"NPS p. 8\" /> and contain lighting.<ref name=\"NPS p. 9\">{{harvnb|National Park Service|2012|ps=.|p=9}}</ref>[[File:Riverside Narthex.jpg|thumb|View of the galleries above the [[nave]], looking south. The sculpture at the back wall can be seen, while the [[Riverside Church#Organ|Trompeta Majestatis organ]] on the eastern wall can be seen at left.|alt=|left]]The ceiling of the nave, above the clerestory, is eight stories high.<ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 151\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 13\">{{harvnb|National Park Service|2012|ps=.|p=13}}</ref> It consists of several vaults, which are each divided into four segments by diagonally interlocking [[transverse rib]]s, which do not provide structural support.<ref name=\"NPS p. 8\" /> Eight iron lanterns hang from the transverse ribs and descend to below the level of the triforium gallery.<ref name=\"NPS p. 9\" /> The vaults contain a finish of acoustic Guastavino tiles, which are mostly gray.<ref name=\"NPS p. 8\" /> The tiles above the chancel and the nave's northernmost two bays are brown, because a sealant was applied in that section in 1953 to increase the acoustical reach of the organ, and had turned yellow over time.<ref name=\"NPS p. 9\" />\n\nThe nave was built with a [[seating capacity]] of either 2,408<ref name=\"NYT-Pew-Phones-1930\" /> or 2,500.<ref name=\"Dolkart p. 77\" /> The ground level contains 38 rows of pews, made of oak wood with Gothic decoration, although five additional rows of pews used to exist at the front of the nave.<ref name=\"NPS p. 9\" /> Two seating galleries overhang the back (southern portion) of the nave.<ref name=\"NPS p. 9\" /><ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 151\">{{harvnb|Paris et al.|2004|ps=.|p=151}}</ref> The lower gallery is made of carved wood, with rows of oak pews on a downward slope, and contains a wooden ceiling with nine lamps. The upper gallery is also made of carved wood and contains oak pews on a slope, but does not contain a canopy above it.<ref name=\"NPS p. 10\">{{harvnb|National Park Service|2012|ps=.|p=10}}</ref> The upper gallery is illuminated with four lanterns, similar to the eight above the main section of the nave. Behind the southern wall are six double-tiered niches with stone sculptures of ministers and [[Jacob Epstein]]'s ''Christ in Majesty'' sculpture. The [[Riverside Church#Organ|Trompeta Majestatis organ]] projects from the wall beneath the niches.<ref name=\"NPS p. 11\">{{harvnb|National Park Service|2012|ps=.|p=11}}</ref>\n\n==== Chancel, ambulatory, and apse ====\n[[File:Riverside Apse.jpg|thumb|The [[chancel]], seen from toward the front of the [[nave]]. The chancel screen is located in the background while the choir stalls are in front of the screen. The [[Eucharist|communion]] table, [[Immersion baptism|baptismal]] pool, and altar can be seen in front of the chancel screen's central bay.]]\nThe chancel is located directly to the north of the nave and is raised by a few steps. A limestone railing with 20 [[quatrefoil]] medallions separates the chancel and the nave. The western portion of the rail contains a [[pulpit]] with a wooden canopy and three carved limestone blocks.<ref name=\"NPS p. 9\" /><ref>{{harvnb|Paris et al.|2004|ps=.|p=159}}</ref> A [[labyrinth]] composed of three types of marble, inspired by a similar design at Chartres Cathedral, is inlaid in the middle of the chancel floor. Flanking the labyrinth on either side are four rows of choir stalls, made of oak with carvings of [[Psalms]] texts.<ref name=\"NPS p. 9\" /><ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 162\">{{harvnb|Paris et al.|2004|ps=.|p=162}}</ref> Behind the choir stalls (to the north) is the organ console.<ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 162\" /> A [[communion table]] of [[Caen stone]] is located toward the back of the chancel, in the center. A [[baptism]]al pool is located behind the communion table.<ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 162\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 10\" />\n\nThe back of the chancel contains a convex polygonal wall. The wall includes seven bays, each with three vertical tiers that are a few feet above the corresponding tiers in the nave. The bottom tier contains pointed arches with [[Riverside Church#Chancel screen|an elaborate stone chancel screen]]; the middle tier contains [[arch#Type of arches|cusped arches]] with colonettes; and the top tier serves as the clerestory.<ref name=\"NPS p. 9\" /> The three center bays behind the chancel screen each contain one window group on the lower tier. These window groups each contain two lancet windows topped by a rose window, and are divided by vertical buttresses. The apse clerestory, the upper section of the ambulatory, is recessed slightly inward. The upper section's [[Fenestration (architecture)|fenestration]] is similar in form, in that it each window grouping contains a rose window above a pair of lancet windows, but the window groupings are located on five sides of the polygon.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 9\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 5\" /> The vertical piers of the chancel wall converge above the clerestory level, creating an [[apse]] above the chancel and ambulatory.<ref name=\"NPS p. 10\" />\n\n==== Narthex ====\n[[File:Riverside Church, New York City (2014) - 16.JPG|alt=|left|thumb|The chapel, facing the altar]]\nThe narthex, designed in the late Gothic style with a [[Romanesque architecture|Romanesque]] layout,<ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 156\" /> is located directly south of the nave and can be accessed from the church's West Portal. The narthex is split into four vaults with [[Guastavino tile]]d ceilings, supported by simple limestone columns.<ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 156\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 7\" /> A stone spiral staircase on the west side of the narthex, directly south of the West Portal, leads down to the basement.<ref name=\"NPS p. 7\" /> There are two [[grisaille]] windows and one rose window on each of the western and eastern sides of the narthex.<ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 170\" /> The eastern wall contains four 16th-century lancet windows, previously located in the Park Avenue Baptist Church and were the only windows in Riverside Church not built specifically for the church.<ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 156\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 8\" /> Stairs leading both upward and downward are located on the eastern side of the narthex, while a mortuary chapel is located on the northeastern corner.<ref name=\"NPS p. 8\" /> The mortuary chapel is known as the [[Gethsemane|Gethsemane Chapel]], but prior to 1959 was called the Christ Chapel.<ref name=\"NPS p. 7\" />{{efn|There are two chapels that have been known as the Christ Chapel: the mortuary chapel, which was once known as the Christ Chapel, and the main chapel, which was the second to receive the name Christ Chapel.<ref>{{harvnb|ps=.|National Park Service|2012|pp=7\u20138}}</ref>|name=\"Christ Chapel\"}}\n\n==== Chapel ====\nThe chapel to the south of the narthex, known since 1959 as the Christ Chapel,<ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 156\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 11\" />{{efn||name=\"Christ Chapel\"}} was inspired by the [[Basilica of Saints Nazarius and Celsus]] in France.<ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 156\" /> Its design was inspired by [[Carcassonne Cathedral]]'s pointed [[Romanesque architecture|Romanesque]] nave. Described by architectural historian [[Andrew Dolkart]] as \"earlier than Gothic\", the design is intended to give the impression that the rest of the sanctuary was built after the chapel.<ref name=\"Dolkart p. 79\" /> The chapel is subdivided into four bays and has a [[Barrel vault|barrel-vaulted]] ceiling with Guastavino tiles, while the walls and floor contain a limestone finish. The southern wall, adjacent to the MLK Wing, contains four arched, back-lit stained-glass windows, one in each bay. Double doors to the west lead to Riverside Drive while a passage to the south leads to the MLK Wing.<ref name=\"NPS p. 11\" /> There are [[engaged column]]s on the north and south walls between each of the four bays, as well as eight lanterns hanging from the columns.<ref name=\"NPS p. 12\" />\n\nThe eastern end of the chapel contains an [[altar]], located four steps above the main level of the chapel. There is a [[lectern]] to the right of the altar and a pulpit to the left.<ref name=\"NPS p. 12\" /><ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 158\">{{harvnb|Paris et al.|2004|ps=.|p=158}}</ref> Several sculpted representations are located above the altar.<ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 158\" /> A baptismal pool and a [[reredos]] are located behind the altar, through an arched opening, while an alcove to the narthex is located to the left (north) of the altar.<ref name=\"NPS p. 12\" />\n\n{{Clear left}}\n\n=== Tower and carillon ===\n[[File:Riverside Church Belltower at dusk (5328618641).jpg|thumb|The tower, seen from the east]]\n\nThe {{Convert|392|ft||abbr=|adj=on}} tower was named after [[Laura Spelman Rockefeller]], the mother of John D. Rockefeller Jr.<ref name=\"Dolkart p. 77\" /><ref name=\"NYT-Plans-Approved-1926\" /><ref name=\"D&C-Chimes-1928\" /> The tower contains 21 usable floors, which include 80 classrooms and office rooms.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 7\" /><ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 149\">{{harvnb|Paris et al.|2004|ps=.|p=149}}</ref> There are four elevators in the tower, two that rise only to the 10th floor, and two that go to the 20th floor.<ref name=\"NPS p. 12\" /><ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 149\" /> The 20-floor-tall elevators, rising {{Convert|355|ft||abbr=}}, were described in 1999 as the world's tallest elevators inside a church.<ref name=\"Nash 1999\" /> Two staircases ascend from ground level: one on the western side of the tower, which ends at the ninth floor, and one on the eastern side, which continues to the carillon.<ref name=\"NPS p. 12\" /> Balconies are located at either southern corner on the 8th floor, and on all sides of the 10th floor except the north side.<ref name=\"NPS p. 13\" />\n\nOn the western elevation of the tower's base is the main entrance, flanked by projecting vertical [[Pier (architecture)|piers]] (see {{Section link||Facade}}). Seven arched niches, each containing statues of kings, are located above the main entrance. A large rose window is located above the statuary grouping.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 8\" /> The top of the tower is fitted with [[aircraft warning lights]].<ref name=\"Nash 1999\" /> Above the tenth floor, there are five tiers of window arrangements on each floor, with higher tiers being progressively narrower. From bottom to top, the successive tiers contain 2, 4, 3, 4, and 5 windows on each side. There are narrow canopied niches in each corner of the tower, with one statue inside each niche. At the top of the tower is a conical metal roof.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 9\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 5\" />\n\n==== Tower stories ====\nMost of the tower's stories consist of plaster floors, steel doors, steel window frames, and iron lighting fixtures hanging from each ceiling. There are elevator lobbies with vaulted ceilings on several stories of the tower. On the stories that contain common spaces, including the 9th and 10th floors, the floors are finished with stone, [[terrazzo]], and wood, with wooden doors. Over the years, several spaces have been used by outside entities, who carpeted floors and installed fluorescent lighting fixtures in some office rooms.<ref name=\"NPS p. 13\" />\n\nOriginally, the 4th through 14th floors held Riverside Church's school, while the 15th floor and above contained various staff and clergy offices, as well as spaces for group activities.<ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 151\" /> The 2nd floor connects to the nave's lower seating gallery, while the 3rd floor leads to the upper seating gallery. The 4th through 8th floors are located below the height of the nave's ceiling, and contained the nursery, junior high, and high school departments of the church's school. The 9th and 10th floors included the double-story school kitchen, school offices, and storage rooms over the nave.<ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 151\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 13\" /> The 9th floor also includes a library and wooden furniture in both the kitchen and library.<ref name=\"NPS p. 13\" /> The main structure's roof is located above the 10th floor, and the tower rises independently above that point.<ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 151\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 13\" /> The 11th through 14th floors originally contained the church's elementary school, while the 15th and 16th floors respectively contained the young people's meeting room and the social room.<ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 151\" /> These were later converted into office space, with several floors subdivided and leased out.<ref name=\"NPS p. 13\" /> The 17th through 20th floors include meeting rooms, though the 17th floor also contains offices. The 21st floor includes the carilloneur's studio, and the 22nd floor is devoted to mechanical space.<ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 151\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 13\" />\n\n==== Carillon ====\nThe 23rd floor of the tower contains a three-level [[Belfry (architecture)|belfry]].<ref name=\"NPS p. 12\" /> The belfry houses a [[carillon]] whose final complement of 74&nbsp;bronze bells, at the time of construction the largest carillon of bells in the world, includes the 20-ton, {{Convert|122|in|m|-diameter|abbr=|adj=mid}} [[bourdon (bell)|bourdon]], the world's largest tuned bell.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 7\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/03/23/nyregion/restoring-the-spirit-with-the-sound-of-big-bells-high-over-manhattan.html|title=Restoring the Spirit With the Sound of Big Bells High Over Manhattan|last=Barron|first=James|date=March 22, 2015|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 8, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Though other carillons with more bells have been commissioned,{{efn|The carillon at Hyechon College in [[Daejeon]], South Korea, contains 78 bells.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.carillon.org/eng/dynamic_frame_eng.htm?https://www.carillon.org/eng/actueel/taejon_1.htm |title=World Carillon Federation - Hyechon College |website=www.carillon.org |access-date=March 1, 2020}}</ref> [[Kirk in the Hills]] in [[Bloomfield Township, Oakland County, Michigan]], contains 77 bells.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Rombouts |first=Luc |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jQ-RCAAAQBAJ&pg=PA287 |title=Singing Bronze: A History of Carillon Music |date=2014-05-23 |publisher=Leuven University Press |isbn=978-90-5867-956-7 |page=287 |language=en}}</ref>}} Riverside Church's carillon is still the largest in the world by aggregate weight: the bells and associated mechanisms weight a combined {{Convert|500,000|lb|kg|abbr=}}.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 7\" /><ref name=\"AIA5\" /> Of the carillon's bells, 53 were made for the original Park Avenue church by English founders [[Gillett & Johnston]].<ref name=\"D&C-Chimes-1928\" /><ref name=\"NYCL p. 7\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 13\" /> Another 19 were made for Riverside Church when it opened,<ref name=\"NYCL p. 7\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 13\" /> and two additional bells were added in 1955, whereupon 58 treble bells were replaced by bell founders Van Bergen.<ref name=\"NPS p. 13\" /> The bells were replaced again by [[Whitechapel Bell Foundry]] in 2004.<ref name=\"NPS p. 13\" /> The bells can reportedly be heard from a distance of up to {{Convert|8|mi||abbr=}}.<ref name=\"NYT-Carillon-1931\" /><ref name=\"NYCL p. 7\" />\n\nA mechanical power room and control room are located in the belfry, while the clavier cabin is located at the top, above the carillon.<ref name=\"NPS p. 14\">{{harvnb|National Park Service|2012|ps=.|p=14}}</ref> Due to the weight of the carillon, the heaviest steel beams used in the construction of Riverside Church were used in the tower. The north facade, which overhangs the nave, is supported by a single cross truss that weighs {{Convert|60|ST|LT t|abbr=}}.<ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 149\" /> Outside the carillon, the facade of the tower contains ornate Neo-Gothic detailing, with features such as [[gargoyle]]s.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 9\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 5\" /> There was also a public observation deck on top of the carillon.<ref name=\"AIA5\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 14\" /> The deck was closed after the [[September 11 attacks|September 11, 2001, attacks]] due to security concerns,<ref name=\"AIA5\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 14\" /> but the church resumed tours in January 2020.<ref>{{cite web | last=Clark | first=Roger | title=Riverside Church Bell Tower Tours Return | publisher=Spectrum News NY1 | date=January 6, 2020 | url=https://www.ny1.com/nyc/all-boroughs/news/2020/01/06/riverside-church-bell-tower-tours-return | access-date=February 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Cloister passageway ===\nThe cloister passageway leads from the southern portion of the nave to Claremont Avenue in the east. It contains four pointed-arch bays, each with a Corinthian-style colonette topped by a [[grisaille]] window opening on the south wall.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 9\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 6\" /> The north and south walls also contain stained-glass windows, though the north wall's windows are artificially illuminated. Inside the cloister passageway are five vaults, illuminated by six lanterns.<ref name=\"NPS p. 14\" /> The entrance to the passageway is a small two-story structure with two arched doorways facing Claremont Avenue, and a set of double doors facing a short wheelchair ramp to the south. The top of the cloister entrance's eastern facade contains three niches with figures of [[Theological virtues|Faith, Hope, and Charity]], while the southeast corner contains a figure of [[Maaseiah]].<ref name=\"NPS p. 6\" /><ref name=\"NYCL p. 10\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|2000|ps=.|p=10}}</ref> There is also a gift shop adjacent to the cloister passageway, while sculptures of the architects and builder are located above the doorway leading to the tower's base.<ref name=\"NPS p. 14\" />\n\n=== Martin Luther King Jr. Wing ===\n[[File:Riverside Church at dusk.jpg|thumb|Seen from Riverside Drive; the MLK Wing is located on the right, south of the tower]]\nThe Martin Luther King Jr. (MLK) Wing is a seven-story annex located to the south of the main structure, facing 120th Street along the southern boundary of the plot.<ref name=\"NYDN-Wing-1959\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 14\" /> The MLK Wing is shaped like an \"L\", with the longer arm running north\u2013south adjacent to Riverside Drive, and the shorter arm running west\u2013east next to 120th Street. It connects to the original church building to the north and the Stone Gym to the east. The area between the MLK Wing and the cloister form a small courtyard or [[Garth (architecture)|garth]], which is enclosed on the east by a metal fence.<ref name=\"NPS p. 14\" /> Inside are children's chapels, space for the school, a rooftop recreation area, space for a radio station, community areas such as a gymnasium and assembly room, and a basement with a parking lot.<ref name=\"Dolkart p. 83\" /><ref name=\"NYDN-Wing-1959\" /><ref name=\"NYT-South-1959\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1959/11/23/archives/riverside-church-to-dedicate-wing-south-structure-will-house-school.html|title=Riverside Church to Dedicate Wing; South Structure Will House School, Nursery, Theatre and Radio Station|last=Wicklein|first=John|date=November 23, 1959|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 9, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nThe structure, designed by Collens, Willis and Beckonert and built by Vermilea-Brown,<ref name=\"Dolkart p. 83\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> is a simplified version of Allen and Collens' original church design and was perceived as being \"modern Gothic\".<ref name=\":1\">{{harvnb|Paris et al.|2004|ps=.|p=174}}</ref> It was known simply as the South Wing until 1985, when it was renamed for civil rights leader [[Martin Luther King Jr.]].<ref name=\"NPS p. 3\" /><ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 175\" />\n\n==== Facade ====\nThe facade is clad with Indiana limestone, while the foundation is made of stone and concrete, and the structure is supported by a steel frame. The main entrance is through the chapel doors on Riverside Drive to the west, and there are also entrances to the basement from 120th Street.<ref name=\"NPS p. 14\" /> The basement through second floors of the western facade contains eight architectural bays, each with one small lancet window, which are recessed between projecting buttresses and located under a set of arches. The two outermost bays project slightly outward and do not contain recessed arches. The section of the MLK Wing above the second floor is [[Setback (architecture)|set back]] from Riverside Drive, and the windows on the third through sixth floors are also recessed between buttressed arches, while the seventh-floor windows are flush with the buttresses. The two outermost bays contain two sets of windows instead of a single window on each floor, and project slightly outward.<ref name=\"NPS p. 15\" />\n\nThe southern and eastern facades are designed in a similar fashion to the upper portion of the western facade, in that the seventh-floor windows are flush with the buttresses, while the windows below are located in recessed arched bays. The southern facade contains eight window bays, six of which are recessed. There are no windows into the first or second floors on the westernmost four bays of the southern facade, but the eastern four bays do contain windows into these floors. On the far eastern portion of the southern facade are two pointed-arched openings that lead to the church's underground parking garage (see {{Section link||Basement}}).<ref name=\"NPS p. 16\">{{harvnb|National Park Service|2012|ps=.|p=16}}</ref> The eastern facade is separated into two sections. The section at the end of the \"L\"'s shorter arm contains four recessed window bays. The section next to the north\u2013south axis of the \"L\" contains six window bays, four of which are recessed.<ref name=\"NPS p. 16\" />\n\n==== Interior ====\nThe northern arm of the MLK Wing's first floor includes the South Hall Lobby, which includes a two-story-high [[coffer|coffered ceiling]] supported by a pointed-arch [[Arcade (architecture)|arcade]], as well as walls made of gray plaster. An elevator bank and an auditorium called the South Hall are located south of the lobby. The South Hall's walls are made of wood paneling below limestone, and nine stained-glass lancet windows on the western side. Two mezzanine levels below the South Hall's ceiling are located to the east of the auditorium, while a sealed tunnel leading to [[the Interchurch Center]] across 120th Street is also accessible from the auditorium.<ref name=\"NPS p. 17\">{{harvnb|National Park Service|2012|ps=.|p=17}}</ref>\n\nThe third through seventh floors include classrooms, except for the fifth floor, which contains offices.<ref name=\"NYDN-Wing-1959\" /><ref name=\"NYT-South-1959\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 17\" /> The floors are made of [[terrazzo]] in the hallways and [[resilient flooring]] in the individual rooms (except for the fifth floor rooms, which contain carpeted rooms), and each level contains [[dropped ceiling]]s.<ref name=\"NPS p. 17\" /> Chapels for children are located on the third floor's southwest corner and on the sixth floor's southern side.<ref name=\"NYDN-Wing-1959\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 17\" /> The roof contains a [[Terrace (building)|solarium]] and a play area.<ref name=\"NYDN-Wing-1959\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 18\">{{harvnb|National Park Service|2012|ps=.|p=18}}</ref>\n\n=== Stone Gym ===\n[[File:Riverside Church 007.JPG|thumb|Stone Gym (center), MLK Wing (left), and tower (center-right)]]\nThe Stone Gymnasium is a {{Frac|1|1|2}}-story [[English Gothic architecture|English Gothic]] building located at 120th Street and Claremont Avenue, east of the Martin Luther King Jr. Wing. The gym was built in 1912 to a design by [[Louis E. Jallade]] and originally was used by the Union Theological Seminary. Its architectural details include a facade of schist with limestone decoration, as well as a metal hip roof.<ref name=\"NPS p. 3\" /> The structure measures five bays long on the eastern facade and one bay wide on the southern and northern facades.<ref name=\"NPS p. 18\" /> In 1957, Rockefeller donated the building to the church, and five years later, it reopened as a [[gym]]nasium and community facility.<ref name=\"NPS p. 3\" /><ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 255\" /> The interior contains a basketball court with synthetic flooring, as well as offices and lockers in its northern end.<ref name=\"NPS p. 3\" />\n\n=== Basement ===\nRiverside Church's basement includes several modern amenities such as a 250-seat [[movie theater]] and a gymnasium with a full-size [[basketball court]].<ref name=\"Nash 1999\" /> The section of the basement under the nave contains a double-height ceiling; an assembly hall is located on the south side of this space, while the gymnasium is located on the north side. The assembly hall includes a stone floor and stone walls, with six arched stained-glass windows on the eastern wall and one rectangular stained glass window on the south wall, as well as cabinets that contain two [[Heinrich Hofmann (painter)|Heinrich Hofmann]] paintings (see {{Section link||Paintings}}). It also contains a wooden ceiling supported by stone arches, with lanterns suspended from the ceiling; and a stage in the northern portion. A kitchen is located east of the stage, and a corridor runs adjacent to the western wall of the assembly room and gymnasium.<ref name=\"NPS p. 12\" />\n\nThe basement also originally included a four-lane [[bowling alley]] adjacent to the assembly floor.<ref name=\"Nash 1999\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 12\" /> It was later removed<ref name=\"Nash 1999\" /> and converted into storage space.<ref name=\"NPS p. 12\" /> There is also a two-story parking lot<ref name=\"Dolkart p. 83\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 17\" /> with 150 spaces underneath the MLK Wing.<ref name=\"NYDN-Wing-1959\" /><ref name=\"Nash 1999\" />\n\n== Organs {{anchor|Organ}} ==\nThere are two organs in Riverside Church: one in the chancel and the other in the seating gallery.<ref name=\"NYCAGO\" /> The chancel organ is the 14th&nbsp;largest in the world {{as of|2017|lc=y}}.<ref name=\"Abdolhamidi 2017\">{{cite web|url=https://untappedcities.com/2017/01/24/the-top-10-secrets-of-nycs-riverside-church/|title=The Top 10 Secrets of NYC's Riverside Church|last=Abdolhamidi|first=Shervin|date=January 24, 2017|website=Untapped New York|access-date=November 8, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://nyc-architecture.com/HAR/HAR009.htm |title=New York Architecture - Riverside Church |website=nyc-architecture.com |access-date=March 1, 2020}}</ref> [[Hook and Hastings]] furnished the original chancel organ in 1930,<ref name=\"NYCAGO\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nycago.org/Organs/NYC/html/RiversideChurch.html#AeolianSkinner1118C|title=The Riverside Church|website=New York City Chapter of the American Guild of Organists|access-date=November 17, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 319\">{{harvnb|Paris et al.|2004|ps=.|p=319}}</ref> though it was originally criticized as being mediocre.<ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 319\" /> [[Aeolian-Skinner]] built an [[organ console]] in the chancel in 1948 and replaced the chancel organ in 1953\u20131954.<ref name=\"NYCAGO\" /> At this time, the ceiling above the chancel and the front of the nave was coated with sealant to improve the chancel's acoustic qualities.<ref name=\"NPS p. 9\" /> Another Aeolian-Skinner organ was installed in 1964 within the eastern wall of the nave's seating gallery, and three years later, Anthony A. Bufano installed a five-manual console for the gallery organ.<ref name=\"NYCAGO\" /> [[M. P. Moller]] built another organ for the gallery, the Trompeta Majestatis, in 1978.<ref name=\"NPS p. 11\" /><ref name=\"NYCAGO\" /> Two years later, the chancel received a new principal chorus, with the addition of the Grand Chorus division. In the 1990s, the console was rewired, the chancel organ was cleaned, and the ceiling was covered with ten sealant layers.<ref name=\"NYCAGO\" />\n\nThe Director of Music and organist is Christopher Johnson {{as of|2019|lc=y}}.<ref>{{cite web | title=2019 Summer Organ Series | website=Riverside Church | date=May 7, 2019 | url=https://www.trcnyc.org/2019summerorganseries/ | access-date=November 18, 2019}}</ref> Past organists at the Riverside Church have included [[Virgil Fox]] (1946\u20131965),<ref>{{harvnb|Paris et al.|2004|ps=.|p=320}}</ref> [[Frederick Swann]] (1957\u20131982),<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/08/04/arts/music/04swan.html|title=Frederick Swann at Riverside Church: A Master of the Organ, With the Curtain Pulled Back|last=Schweitzer|first=Vivien|date=August 4, 2006|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 11, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> [[John Walker (organist)|John Walker]] (1979\u20131992),<ref>{{harvnb|Paris et al.|2004|ps=.|p=322}}</ref> and Timothy Smith (1992\u20132008).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.columbia.edu/cu/earl/music_organist.html|title=Music at St. Paul's|work=Office of the University Chaplain|publisher=[[Columbia University]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081229164907/http://www.columbia.edu/cu/earl/music_organist.html|archivedate=December 29, 2008|accessdate=April 9, 2009}}</ref>\n\n== Art and sculpture ==\n\n=== Paintings ===\n[[File:Christ in Gethsemane.jpg|thumb|[[Heinrich Hofmann (painter)|Heinrich Hofmann]], ''[[Agony in the Garden|Christ in Gethsemane]]'', 1886]]\nRiverside Church contains paintings by [[Heinrich Hofmann (painter)|Heinrich Hofmann]] that were purchased by Rockefeller Jr. and donated to the church in November 1930.<ref name=\"NYT-Paintings-1930\" />  ''Christ in the Temple'' (1871) and ''Christ and the Young Rich Man'' (1889) are located in the assembly hall beneath the nave and are usually locked within the cabinets there.<ref name=\"NPS p. 12\">{{harvnb|National Park Service|2012|ps=.|p=12}}</ref> A copy of ''Christ in Gethsemane'' (1890) is located in the Gethsemane chapel.<ref name=\"NPS p. 7\" />\n\n=== Stained glass ===\nRiverside Church's main building contains 51 [[stained glass]] windows, excluding smaller grisaille windows.<ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 170\">{{harvnb|Paris et al.|2004|ps=.|pp=170, 172}} For a diagram showing the layout of the windows, see {{harvnb|Paris et al.|2004|ps=.|p=173}}</ref> These were created in a mosaic style, which was becoming more popular at the time of the church's construction.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 6\" /> Of these, 34 windows are located in the nave, most of which contain religious iconography. Generally, the \"richer\"-colored windows were located on the western side, considered the \"light\" side, while the more muted colors were located on the eastern \"dark\" side.<ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 170\" />\n\nTwo French glassmakers, Jacques Simon from [[Reims Cathedral]] and Charles Lorin from Chartres Cathedral, were hired to create the glass for the clerestory windows in the nave.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 6\" /><ref name=\"Carder p. 18\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 8\" />   Lorin designed the stained-glass windows on the western side of the clerestory while Simon designed the windows on the eastern side. Both sets of windows depict general religious and government themes, and they incorporate secular iconography as well as depictions of non-Christians.<ref name=\"NPS p. 8\" /> The clerestory windows closely resemble those at Chartres, and contain a rose with [[lancet window]]s.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 6\" /><ref name=\"Carder p. 18\" /> The other windows in the nave were created by [[Reynolds, Francis and Rohnstock]], a [[Boston]]-based firm, and depict over 138 scenes from both religious and non-religious contexts.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 6\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 8\" /> The three groups of stained glass windows in the apse were created by [[Harry Wright Goodhue]],<ref name=\"NYCL p. 6\" /> as were the nine stained glass windows in the South Hall.<ref name=\"NPS p. 17\" />\n\n=== Mosaics ===\n[[Gregor T. Goethals]] created two mosaics for the fourth and seventh floors of the MLK Wing. The fourth-floor mosaic shows the [[Old Testament]] while the seventh-floor mosaic shows the Creation.<ref name=\"NPS p. 17\" />\n\n=== Sculpted elements ===\n\n==== Exterior elements ====\n[[File:Riverside Church doorway (4684840329).jpg|thumb|Front doorway at the base of the tower. At the bottom are [[archivolt]]s (directly under the arch), [[Tympanum (architecture)|tympanum]], and [[jamb]]s (bottom, to either side of the doors). At the top is the circular [[rose window]], and niches with the sculptures of [[King of Rome#Kings of Rome (753\u2013509 BC)|seven kings]]]]\nThe most prominent sculptural details are located on the Riverside Drive facade. The main entrance, located beneath the tower, is topped by five concentric [[archivolt]]s, with sculptures of [[Jesus]]'s [[Followers of Christ|followers]] and [[Prophets of Christianity|prophets]] inlaid within each section of the archivolts.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 5\" /> The third arch of the main entrance contains depictions of philosophers including [[Ralph Waldo Emerson]], [[Immanuel Kant]], and [[Pythagoras]], while the second arch depicts scientists like [[Albert Einstein]], [[Charles Darwin]], and [[Hippocrates]].<ref name=\"NYCL p. 5\" /><ref name=\"Dolkart p. 80\" /> Other figures depict the 12 months of the year.<ref name=\"Paris et al. pp. 155-156\" /> The columns framing the door [[jamb]]s, located under the archivolts, are also decorated with capitals and gargoyles at the top and bottom, and a single figure in the middle. A seated figure of Christ is located in the [[tympanum (architecture)|tympanum]] above the doors and below the archivolts, and is flanked by the symbols of the [[Four Evangelists|Evangelists]].<ref name=\"NYCL p. 8\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 4\">{{harvnb|National Park Service|2012|ps=.|p=4}}</ref>\n\nWhen Riverside Church was completed, there was controversy over the inclusion of Einstein, a Jewish man who was still alive when the church was constructed, as the other figures represented figures who had since died.<ref name=\"Carder p. 18\" /><ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 154\">{{harvnb|Paris et al.|2004|ps=.|p=154}}</ref> The publication ''Church Monthly'' said that during construction, the committee tasked with the church's iconography had proposed 20 scientists to be depicted on the facade, of which Einstein was not part.<ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 154\" /> However, the faculty had unanimously decided that Einstein should be included, as he was indisputably one of 14 \"leading scientists of all time\".<ref name=\"Carder p. 18\" />\n\nThe chapel entrance, located on Riverside Drive south of the main entrance, contains two archivolts supported by two sets of columns. The archivolts contain symbols of the [[zodiac]], and the second archivolt contains an elaborate decorative molding. A tympanum relief below the archivolts depicts the [[Mary, mother of Jesus|Virgin Mary]] flanked by two [[angel]]s who are mirror images of each other.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 8\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 4\" />\n\nIn addition, sculpted elements are placed within niches spread across the church's facade. Above the main entrance on the western facade, there are sculptures of seven kings.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 8\" /> More statues are located within niches in the tower itself,<ref name=\"NYCL p. 9\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 5\" /> as well as in niches on the facade of the cloister entrance to the east.<ref name=\"NPS p. 6\" /><ref name=\"NYCL p. 10\" /> Also placed on the facade are gargoyles, located outside the carillon near the top of the tower.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 9\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 5\" /> The northern section of the nave's roof contains a bronze statue, ''Angel of the Resurrection'', which depicts a trumpeter atop a pedestal.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 8\" />\n\n==== Interior elements ====\nThe various carvings inside different portions of the church correspond to the respective uses of these portions. For instance, the 20 quatrefoil medallions inscribed on the chancel railing depict the typical \"interests, emphases, activities, rites, and ceremonies\" that are conducted within the chancel.<ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 162\" /> Around the pulpit are ten [[Old Testament]] prophets.<ref name=\"NPS p. 9\" /><ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 162\" /> Above the nave, the southern wall of the upper seating gallery contains multi-tiered niches, whose upper tiers contain sculpted figures of ministers. The center two niches contain a cast of Epstein's gilded-plaster sculpture ''Christ in Majesty''.<ref name=\"NPS p. 11\" />\n\n{{Anchor|Chancel screen}}There is a seven-paneled [[chancel screen]] at the back of the chancel, carved in [[Caen stone]].<ref name=\"NPS p. 9\" /> It depicts numerous influential figures such as the composer [[Johann Sebastian Bach]], the U.S. president [[Abraham Lincoln]], the artist [[Michelangelo]], the social reformer [[Florence Nightingale]], and the author [[Booker T. Washington]].<ref name=\"NYCL p. 6\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 10\" /> From left to right, the panels depict physicians, teachers, prophets, humanitarians, missionaries, reformers, and lovers-of-beauty.<ref name=\"NPS p. 10\" /><ref>{{harvnb|Paris et al.|2004|ps=.|p=164}}</ref>\n\nAbove the doorway between the cloister and the tower base are statues of architects Henry Pelton and Charles Collens, as well as general contractor Robert Eidlitz.<ref name=\"NPS p. 14\" />\n\n<div align=\"center\">\n<gallery heights=\"250\" mode=\"packed\" caption=\"Carving details\">\nFile:Riverside-Church-sculpture.jpg|Stone carving detail\nFile:Riverside-Church-sculpture-4.png|Several sculptures like these adorn the church\nFile:Interior of Riverside Church 05.JPG|Sculpted figures inside the gallery\n</gallery></div>\n\n=== Sculpture ===\nWhen the Martin Luther King Jr. Wing was built, [[Jacob Epstein]]'s sculpture ''Madonna and Child'' was placed in the courtyard between the MLK Wing and the cloistered entrance.<ref name=\"NPS p. 17\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1959/12/30/archives/church-gets-madonna-by-epstein.html|title=Church Gets Madonna by Epstein|date=December 30, 1959|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 9, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The sculpture was originally commissioned in 1927.<ref name=\"NPS p. 17\" /><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TzlIAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA1|title=Sculpture of Jacob Epstein: The Eisenberg-Robbins Collection|last=Epstein|first=J.|author2=Corcoran Gallery of Art|publisher=Corcoran Gallery of Art|year=1973|series=Sculpture of Jacob Epstein: The Eisenberg-Robbins Collection|page=1|access-date=November 17, 2019|issue=2}}</ref>\n\n== Social services ==\n[[File:Correctionalfacilityvolunteers.JPG|thumb|Some of Riverside's Prison Ministry volunteers at a prison]]The church was conceived as a complex social services center from the outset, with meeting rooms and classrooms, a daycare center, a kindergarten, library, auditorium and gym. It was described by ''[[The New York Times]]'' in 2008 as \"a stronghold of activism and political debate throughout its 75-year history&nbsp;... influential on the nation's religious and political landscapes.\"<ref name=\"NYT8408\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/08/04/nyregion/04riverside.html?_r=1&scp|title=Riverside Church Selects a New Leader|last=Buettner|first=Russ|date=August 4, 2008|work=The New York Times|accessdate=August 4, 2008|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Riverside Church continues to provide various social services, including a [[food bank]], barber training, clothing distribution, a shower project, and confidential [[HIV tests]] and HIV counseling.<ref name=\"Riverside Church Ministries\">{{cite web|url=https://www.trcnyc.org/ministries/|title=Ministries|website=Riverside Church|access-date=November 15, 2019}}</ref> In 2007, the ''Times'' said that Riverside has frequently \"been likened to the Vatican for America\u2019s mainstream Protestants.\"<ref name=\"NYT-Rebuilding-2007\" />\n\n=== Social justice ministries ===\n\n==== Charity and shelter ====\nRiverside has two prisoner-related ministries. Riverside's Prison Ministry and Family Advocacy Program conducts worship services in the [[New York State Department of Corrections and Community Supervision]]; helps prisoners and their families; links prisoners to their communities; holds various workshops, [[support group]]s, and events; and lobbies for [[prison reform]] and humane [[legislation]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.trcnyc.org/ministries/prisonministry/|title=Prison Ministry|date=November 20, 2017|website=Riverside Church|access-date=November 18, 2019}}</ref> Riverside's Coming Home ministry helps prisoners after they have been released.<ref name=\"RpcVv\">{{cite web|url=https://www.trcnyc.org/ministries/cominghome/|title=Riverside Coming Home|website=Riverside Church|access-date=November 18, 2019}}</ref> The prison ministries date from 1971, when the Council on Christian Social Relations created a [[prison reform]] and [[Rehabilitation (penology)|rehabilitation]] task force.<ref>{{harvnb|Paris et al.|2004|ps=.|p=207}}</ref>\n\nRiverside's Coming Home ministry, founded in 1985, deals with [[homelessness in New York City]].<ref name=\"RpcVv\" /> Riverside's advocacy of the homeless originated from a similar ministry, the Clothing Room and Food Pantry, which was a subdivision of the Social Services Department. The church began sheltering homeless people overnight from 1984 until 1994, when it was closed due to the decreasing homeless population and a staff shortage.<ref>{{harvnb|Paris et al.|2004|ps=.|pp=217\u2013218}}</ref>\n\nRiverside participated in the [[Sanctuary movement]] during the 1980s, being among numerous congregations nationwide that sheltered and assisted [[Undocumented immigrants of New York City|undocumented immigrants]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1984/10/02/nyregion/riverside-church-gives-sanctuary.html|title=Riverside Church Gives Sanctuary|last=Briggs|first=Kenneth A.|date=1984-10-02|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-11-18|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> As part of the New Sanctuary Coalition, volunteers at Riverside Church and other participating houses of worship assist detained [[asylum seekers]] and those on [[parole]] from [[immigration detention]].<ref>{{cite web | title=Welcome to New Sanctuary Coalition | website=New Sanctuary Coalition | date=July 1, 2018 | url=https://www.newsanctuarynyc.org/ | access-date=November 18, 2019}}</ref> In 2011, as part of a movement called [[Occupy Faith]], Riverside Church donated tents to [[Occupy Wall Street]] protesters, as well as sheltered them during cold or inclement weather and after the evacuation of [[Zuccotti Park]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/11/18/nyregion/occupy-wall-street-protesters-even-in-churches-cant-escape-watch-of-police.html|title=Occupy Wall Street Protesters, Even in Churches, Can't Escape Watch of Police|last=Otterman|first=Sharon|date=November 17, 2011|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 11, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n==== Social and cultural ====\n[[File:Riverside Pride Float.JPG|thumb|Riverside's Pride Parade Float|alt=]]\n\nRiverside Church's [[LGBT]] ministry is named [[Maranatha]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.trcnyc.org/ministries/maranathatrc/|title=Maranatha|website=Riverside Church|access-date=November 18, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1985/05/26/nyregion/sex-issue-divides-riverside-church.html|title=Sex Issue Divides Riverside Church|date=May 26, 1985|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 18, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> It was founded in 1978 in response to growing demand from gay and lesbian congregants.<ref name=\"Paris et al. pp. 220-221\">{{harvnb|Paris et al.|2004|ps=.|pp=220\u2013221}}</ref> Maranatha hosts several activities, workshops, and events, and marches annually in the [[NYC Pride March]].<ref name=\"Paris et al. pp. 220-221\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=//columbiaspectator.com/2012/02/13/riverside-church-celebrates-30-years-pro-lgbt-ministry/|title=Riverside Church celebrates 30 years of pro-LGBT ministry|last=|first=|date=February 13, 2012|website=Columbia Daily Spectator|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=November 18, 2019}}</ref> In the 1980s, when the [[HIV/AIDS in New York City|HIV/AIDS epidemic in New York City]] was at its peak, there was some backlash against Maranatha, as the LGBT community was negatively associated with the epidemic. These events led to the founding of the separate [[HIV/AIDS]] ministry,<ref>{{harvnb|Paris et al.|2004|ps=.|p=222}}</ref> which hosts a support forum; provides testing, counseling, and referral programs; and collaborates with several other programs.<ref name=\"Riverside Church Ministries\" />\n\nRiverside Church's African Fellowship and Ministry sponsors educational forums about issues facing the continent of Africa and advocates on behalf of [[African diaspora]].<ref name=\"Riverside Church Ministries\" /> The Sharing and Densford Funds advocate on behalf of [[Native Americans in the United States]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.trcnyc.org/ministries/sharingfund/|title=Sharing & Densford Funds|website=Riverside Church|access-date=November 18, 2019}}</ref> Other ministries at Riverside include support groups for [[South Africa]]ns and for [[Hispanic and Latino Americans]].<ref name=\"Riverside Church Ministries\" />\n\n==== Other activism ====\nRiverside has several other social justice ministries. The Beloved Earth ministry is an [[environmentalist]] ministry with a focus on [[Individual and political action on climate change|climate change activism]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.trcnyc.org/ministries/belovedearth/|title=Beloved Earth|website=Riverside Church|access-date=November 18, 2019}}</ref> The Wellbotics ministry helps the families of cancer patients.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.trcnyc.org/ministries/wellbotics/|title=Wellbotics|website=Riverside Church|access-date=November 18, 2019}}</ref> Riverside also has several pacifist task forces. The Anti-Death Penalty Task Force is in [[opposition to capital punishment in the United States]]. An \"Overcoming Violence\" task force is dedicated to fostering dialogue with the [[New York City Police Department]].<ref name=\"Riverside Church Ministries\" /> Riverside Church also participates in the [[National Religious Campaign Against Torture]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.trcnyc.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/torture.pdf|title=The Riverside Church Statement On Torture And Policies Enabling Torture|publisher=Riverside Church|date=April 2017|access-date=November 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Former programming ===\nWhen Riverside Church's Martin Luther King Jr. Wing was completed in 1959, it included space for a radio station planned by the church.<ref name=\"NYDN-Wing-1959\" /> The [[Federal Communications Commission]] (FCC) granted the church a FM broadcasting license in 1960,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1960/07/21/archives/riverside-church-gets-fm.html|title=Riverside Church Gets FM|date=July 21, 1960|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 9, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> and the following year, Riverside Church started operating the radio station [[WLTW|WRVR]] (106.7 [[FM broadcasting|FM]]).<ref name=\"NYCL p. 7\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1961/01/08/archives/growth-of-fm-new-radio-station-of-riverside-church-illustrates.html|title=Growth of FM; New Radio Station of Riverside Church Illustrates Diversity of System|last=Gould|first=Jack|date=January 8, 1961|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 9, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/61-OCR/1961-01-23-BC-OCR-Page-0053.pdf|title=Riverside Church fm station on-the-air|date=January 23, 1961|page=53|accessdate=March 3, 2019|periodical=Broadcasting}}</ref> WRVR originally broadcast from Riverside Church's carillon before being relocated to the [[Empire State Building]] in 1971 to increase the range of the broadcast signal. Originally a noncommercial station, WRVR broadcast sermons, as well as programming from cultural and higher-education institutions in New York City.<ref>{{harvnb|Paris et al.|2004|ps=.|pp=209\u2013213}}</ref> However, WRVR incurred a net loss for Riverside Church each year, and in 1971, was turned into a \"limited commercial operation\", which also failed to be profitable.<ref name=\"Paris et al. pp. 214-216\">{{harvnb|Paris et al.|2004|ps=.|pp=214\u2013216}}</ref> Riverside Church decided to sell its radio station in 1975,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/75-OCR/1975-07-07-BC-OCR-Page-0025.pdf|title=In brief|date=July 7, 1975|page=27|accessdate=March 3, 2019|periodical=Broadcasting}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1975/07/04/archives/station-wrvrfm-sold-to-sonderling-by-riverside-church.html|title=Station WRVR\u2010FM Sold to Sonderling By Riverside Church|date=July 4, 1975|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 8, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> the sale being finalized the following year.<ref name=\"Paris et al. pp. 214-216\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1976/10/28/archives/sonderlings-purchase-of-wrvr-from-church-approved-by-fcc.html|title=Sonderling's Purchase of WRVR From Church Approved by F.C.C.|date=October 28, 1976|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 8, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nStarting in November 1976, Riverside Church hosted the Riverside Dance Festival. The program was a continuation of previous dance ministries hosted by the church, and normally offered 34 weeks of programming from over 60 dance companies.<ref>{{harvnb|Paris et al.|2004|ps=.|p=326}}</ref> The program ended in June 1987 because of a $900,000 funding shortfall.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/02/10/arts/riverside-dance-to-close.html|title=Riverside Dance to Close|last=Dunning|first=Jennifer|date=February 10, 1987|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 9, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n==Called senior ministers {{Anchor|Clergy}}==\n[[File:Harry Emerson Fosdick.jpg|thumb|[[Harry Emerson Fosdick]]]]\nIn chronological order, the called senior ministers at Riverside Church have been:\n* [[Harry Emerson Fosdick]] (1925\u20131945)<ref name=\"NYT-FosdickAccepts-1925\" /><ref name=\"NYT-Fosdick-1945\" />\n* Robert J. McCracken (1946\u20131967)<ref name=\"NYT-McCracken-1946\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1967/05/25/archives/mcracken-bids-riverside-adieu-congregation-gives-retiring-minister.html|title=M'Cracken Bids Riverside Adieu; Congregation Gives Retiring Minister $10,000 Born in Scotland|last=Adams|first=Val|date=May 25, 1967|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 9, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n* Ernest T. Campbell (1968\u20131976)<ref name=\"NYT-Campbell-1968\" /><ref name=\"NYT-Campbell-1976\" />\n* [[William Sloane Coffin]] (1977\u20131987)<ref name=\"NYT-Coffin-1977\" /><ref name=\"NYT-Coffin-1987\" />\n* [[James A. Forbes]] (1989\u20132007)<ref name=\"NYT-Forbes-1989\" /><ref name=\"NYT-Forbes-2007\" />\n* Brad R. Braxton (2008\u20132009)<ref name=\"NYT8408\" /><ref name=\"NYT-Braxton-2009\">{{cite news|last=Vitello|first=Paul|date=June 30, 2009|title=Pastor at Riverside Church Ends Stormy Tenure With Unexpected Resignation|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/07/01/nyregion/01pastor.html|work=The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331 |access-date=July 17, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Amy Butler (minister)|Amy Butler]] (2014\u20132019)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/2864118/meet-riverside-churchs-first-female-pastor/|title=Meet Riverside Church's First Female Pastor|last=Berenson|first=Tessa|date=|website=Time|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=November 11, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/social-issues/riverside-church-congregants-call-for-reinstatement-of-first-female-minister-after-her-dismissal-following-a-sex-shop-visit/2019/07/14/1c2c23da-a632-11e9-86dd-d7f0e60391e9_story.html|title=Riverside Church Congregants Call for Reinstatement of First Female Minister after Her Exit Following a Sex Shop Visit|last=Natanson|first=Hannah|date=July 15, 2019|work=Washington Post|access-date=July 16, 2019|location=}}</ref>\n\n== Notable speakers ==\n\nOn April 4, 1967, [[Martin Luther King Jr.]] gave a speech at Riverside called [[Beyond Vietnam: A Time to Break Silence]], where he voiced his opposition to the [[Vietnam War]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thekingcenter.org/archive/document/letter-robert-j-mccracken-mlk|title=Letter from Robert J McCracken to MLK|publisher=[[King Center for Nonviolent Social Change]]|accessdate=April 12, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last=Scruggs | first=Afi-Odelia | title=Beyond Vietnam: The MLK speech that caused an uproar | website=USA Today | date=January 13, 2017 | url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation-now/2017/01/13/martin-luther-king-jr-beyond-vietnam-speech/96501636/ | access-date=November 19, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title=Martin Luther King, Jr.,'s Searing Antiwar Speech, Fifty Years Later | website=The New Yorker |date=2017-04-03 | url=https://www.newyorker.com/culture/culture-desk/martin-luther-king-jr-s-searing-antiwar-speech-fifty-years-later | access-date=November 19, 2019}}</ref> The Rev. [[Jesse Jackson]] gave the eulogy at [[Jackie Robinson]]'s funeral service in 1972.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1972/10/28/archives/new-jerjey-pages-but-on-that-dash-is-where-we-live-sports-of-the.html|title=But on That Dash Is Where We Live|date=October 28, 1972|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 10, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> [[Nelson Mandela]], anti-apartheid activist and later South African president, spoke at Riverside in 1991 following his release from prison.<ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 55\">{{harvnb|Paris et al.|2004|ps=.|p=55}}</ref>  [[Secretary-General of the United Nations]] [[Kofi Annan]] spoke there after the September 11, 2001 attacks,<ref>{{cite book | last=Welch | first=R. | last2=Penn | first2=E. | title=New York: A Pictorial Celebration | publisher=Sterling Pub. | year=2007 | isbn=978-1-4027-2383-4 | url=https://archive.org/details/newyorkpictorial0000welc | url-access=registration | access-date=February 29, 2020 | page=[https://archive.org/details/newyorkpictorial0000welc/page/80 80]}}</ref> and former U.S. president [[Bill Clinton]] spoke at the church in 2004.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/08/30/us/republicans-convention-new-york-clintons-after-sharing-white-house-sharing.html|title=The Republicans: The Convention In New York - The Clintons; After Sharing the White House, Sharing a Critique of the G.O.P.|last=Hernandez|first=Raymond|date=August 30, 2004|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 10, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2004/ALLPOLITICS/09/03/clinton.tests/|title=Bill Clinton awaits heart surgery next week|last=|first=|date=September 4, 2004|website=CNN|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=November 10, 2019}}</ref> Speakers have also included theologians such as [[Paul Tillich]], who taught nearby,<ref>{{harvnb|Paris et al.|2004|ps=.|p=279}}</ref> as well as [[Reinhold Niebuhr]].<ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 55\" /> Other past speakers include civil-rights activists [[Cesar Chavez]];<ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 55\" /> human-rights activist [[Desmond Tutu]];<ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 55\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://spectatorarchive.library.columbia.edu/?a=d&d=cs19880421-01.2.4&|title=Desmond Tutu will speak at Riverside Church April 29|last=|first=|date=April 21, 1988|website=Columbia Spectator|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=November 10, 2019}}</ref> Cuban president [[Fidel Castro]];<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/nov/27/fidel-castro-new-york-malcolm-x|title=Fidel Castro in the US: cars, cigars and a meeting with Malcolm X|last=Smith|first=David|date=November 27, 2016|work=The Guardian|access-date=November 10, 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> the [[14th Dalai Lama]];<ref name=\"NYT-Forbes-2007\" /> and [[Abdullah II of Jordan]].<ref name=\"NYT-Forbes-2007\" />\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of Baptist churches]]\n* [[List of New York City Designated Landmarks in Manhattan above 110th Street]]\n* [[National Register of Historic Places listings in Manhattan above 110th Street]]\n\n== References ==\n=== Notes ===\n{{notelist}}\n\n=== Citations ===\n{{reflist}}\n\n=== Sources ===\n{{refbegin}}\n# {{Cite book|title=Architecture and symbolism of the Riverside Church|last=Carder|first=Eugene Clayton|last2=Church monthly (N.Y.)|date=1930|publisher=Riverside Church|location=New York|language=English|oclc=3940539|ref={{harvid|Carder|1930}}}}\n# {{cite morningside|ref=harv}}\n# {{cite web|url=https://s3.amazonaws.com/NARAprodstorage/lz/electronic-records/rg-079/NPS_NY/12001036.pdf|title=Historic Structures Report: Riverside Church|date=December 21, 2012|publisher=[[National Register of Historic Places]], [[National Park Service]]|ref={{harvid|National Park Service|2012}}}}\n# {{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/harryemersonfosd0000mill|url-access=registration|title=Harry Emerson Fosdick: Preacher, Pastor, Prophet|last=Miller|first=R.M.|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=1985|isbn=978-0-19-536523-8|page=|ref={{harvid|Miller|1985}}}}\n# {{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jtoegDGyJcgC|title=The History of the Riverside Church in the City of New York|last=Paris|first=Peter J.|last2=Cook|first2=John Wesley|last3=Hudnut-Beumler|first3=James|last4=Mamiya|first4=Lawrence|last5=Tisdale|first5=Leonora Tubbs|last6=Weisenfeld|first6=Judith|publisher=NYU Press|year=2004|isbn=978-0-8147-6836-5|series=Religion, Race, and Ethnicity|location=|pages=|ref={{harvid|Paris et al.|2004}}}}\n# {{Cite book|title=A Brief History of The Riverside Church|last=Pendo|first=Mina|publisher=Riverside Church|year=1957|isbn=|location=|pages=|ref={{harvid|Pendo|1957}}}}\n# {{cite web|url=http://s-media.nyc.gov/agencies/lpc/lp/2037.pdf|title=The Riverside Church|date=May 16, 2000|website=|publisher=[[New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission]]|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=|ref={{harvid|Landmarks Preservation Commission|2000}}}}\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Commons category-inline|Riverside Church}}\n* {{Official website|https://www.trcnyc.org}}\n\n{{National Register of Historic Places in New York}}\n\n[[Category:Baptist churches in New York City]]\n[[Category:Buildings associated with the Rockefeller family]]\n[[Category:Churches in Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Churches completed in 1930]]\n[[Category:Morningside Heights, Manhattan]]\n[[Category:New York City Designated Landmarks in Manhattan]]\n[[Category:Properties of religious function on the National Register of Historic Places in Manhattan]]\n[[Category:United Church of Christ churches in New York City]]\n", "text_old": "{{good article}}\n{{Distinguish|Riverside Baptist Church}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox church\n|name                   = Riverside Church\n|fullname               =\n|image                  = Riverside Church2.JPG\n|imagesize              =\n|imagelink              =\n|imagealt               =\n|landscape              =\n|caption                =\n|pushpin map            = Manhattan#New York City#New York#United States\n|pushpin label position =\n|pushpin map alt        =\n|pushpin mapsize        =\n|map caption            =\n|coordinates            = {{Coord|40|48|43|N|73|57|47|W|type:landmark|display=inline,title}}\n|osgraw                 = \n|osgridref              =\n|location               = [[New York City]]\n|country                = United States\n|denomination           = [[Interdenominational]], [[American Baptist Churches USA|American Baptist]], [[United Church of Christ]]\n|previous denomination  =\n|churchmanship          =\n|membership             = 1,750<ref name=\"NYT-Butler-2019\" />\n|attendance             =\n|website                =\n|former name            = Mulberry Street Baptist Church<br>Fifth Avenue Baptist Church<br>Park Avenue Baptist Church\n|bull date              =\n|founded date           =\n|founder                =\n|dedication             =\n|dedicated date         = \n|consecrated date       =\n|cult                   =\n|relics                 =\n|events                 =\n|past bishop            =\n|people                 =\n|status                 =\n|functional status      =\n|heritage designation   = [[National Register of Historic Places]], [[New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission]]\n|designated date        =\n|architect              = [[Allen & Collens]] and [[Henry C. Pelton]]\n|architectural type     = [[Gothic Revival architecture|Neo-Gothic]]\n|style                  =\n|groundbreaking         = November 21, 1927\n|completed date         = October 5, 1930\n|construction cost      =\n|closed date            =\n|demolished date        =\n|capacity               = 2,100\n|length                 = <!-- {{convert|}} -->\n|width                  = <!-- {{convert|}} -->\n|width nave             = {{convert|89|ft}}\n|height                 = <!-- {{convert|}} -->\n|diameter               = <!-- {{convert|}} -->\n|other dimensions       =\n|floor count            = 22\n|floor area             = <!-- {{convert|}} -->\n|dome quantity          =\n|dome height outer      = <!-- {{convert|}} -->\n|dome height inner      = <!-- {{convert|}} -->\n|dome dia outer         = <!-- {{convert|}} -->\n|dome dia inner         = <!-- {{convert|}} -->\n|spire quantity         =\n|spire height           = {{convert|392|ft}}\n|materials              =\n|bells                  = 74\n|bells hung             = [[carillon]]\n|bell weight            = <!-- {{CwtQtrLb to kg|}} -->\n|parish                 =\n|deanery                =\n|archdeaconry           =\n|episcopalarea          =\n|archdiocese            =\n|metropolis             =\n|diocese                =\n|province               =\n|presbytery             =\n|synod                  =\n|circuit                =\n|district               =\n|division               =\n|subdivision            =\n|logo                   =\n|logosize               =\n|logolink               =\n|logoalt                =\n|embedded =\n{{Infobox NRHP\n| embed = yes\n| name                 = Riverside Church\n| nrhp_type            =\n| location             = 478, 490 Riverside Dr. & 81 Claremont Ave., [[New York City]]\n| built                = 1930 (main building)<br>1957 (MLK Wing)<br>1962 (conversion of Stone Gym)\n| architect            = [[Allen & Collens]], [[H.C. Pelton]] (main building)<br>[[Collens, Willis & Beckonert]] (MLK Wing)<br>[[Louis E. Jallade]] (Stone Gym)\n| architecture         = [[Late Gothic Revival]]\n| added                = December 12, 2012<ref name=\"nrhp\" />\n| designated_nrhp_type =\n| visitation_num       =\n| visitation_year      =\n| refnum               = 12001036\n| website              = <!-- {{URL|www.example.com}} -->\n| mpsub                =\n| designated_other2 = NYC Landmark\n| designated_other2_date = May 16, 2000<ref name=\"NYCL p. 1\" />\n| designated_other2_number = 2037\n| designated_other2_abbr = NYCL\n| designated_other2_color = #FFE978\n| designated_other2_link = New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission\n}}\n}}\n\n'''Riverside Church''' is a Baptist and Congregationalist church in the [[Morningside Heights, Manhattan|Morningside Heights]] neighborhood of [[Manhattan]] in [[New York City]]. It is located on the block bounded by [[Riverside Drive (Manhattan)|Riverside Drive]], [[Claremont Avenue]], and 120th and 122nd Streets, near [[Columbia University]]'s Morningside Heights campus and across from [[Grant's Tomb]]. An [[interdenominational]] church, it is associated with the [[American Baptist Churches USA]] and the [[United Church of Christ]]. The church was conceived by philanthropist businessman [[John D. Rockefeller Jr.]], a Baptist, in conjunction with Presbyterian minister [[Harry Emerson Fosdick]] as a large, interdenominational church in Morningside Heights, a neighborhood surrounded by numerous academic institutions.\n\nThe original building, opened in 1930, was designed by Henry C. Pelton and [[Allen & Collens]] in the [[Neo-Gothic architecture|Neo-Gothic]] style. It contains a [[nave]] consisting of five [[Bay (architecture)|architectural bays]]; a [[chancel]] at the front of the nave; a 22-story, {{Convert|392|ft|m|-tall|abbr=|adj=mid}} tower above the [[nave]]; a [[narthex]] and [[chapel]]; and a [[cloister]]ed passageway that connects to the eastern entrance on Claremont Avenue. The main feature of the church is the 74-bell [[carillon]] near the top of the tower, dedicated to John Rockefeller Jr.'s mother [[Laura Spelman Rockefeller]]. A seven-story wing to the south of the original building was built in 1959 to a design by Collens, Willis & Beckonert, and renamed for [[Martin Luther King Jr.]] in 1985. The Stone Gym, to the southeast, was built in 1915 as a dormitory designed by Louis E. Jallade, and was converted to a gym in 1962.\n\nA focal point of global and national activism since its inception, Riverside Church has a long history of [[social justice]], in adherence to Fosdick's original vision of an \"interdenominational, interracial, and international\" church.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 1\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|2000|ps=.|p=1}}</ref> Riverside Church's congregation includes more than forty ethnic groups. It was designated as a city landmark by the [[New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission]] in 2000,<ref name=\"NYCL p. 1\" /> and was listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 2012.<ref name=\"nrhp\">{{cite web|title=National Register of Historic Places Weekly Lists for 2012|url=https://www.nps.gov/subjects/nationalregister/upload/weekly-list-2012-national-register-of-historic-places.pdf|publisher=[[U.S. National Park Service]]|date=December 28, 2012|accessdate=February 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\n{{TOC limit|4}}\n\n== History ==\n\n=== Context ===\n==== Congregation ====\nSeveral small [[Baptists|Baptist]] congregations were founded in Manhattan after the [[American Revolutionary War]], including the Mulberry Street Baptist Church, established in 1823 by a group of 16 congregants.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 2\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|2000|ps=.|p=2}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|ps=.|Pendo|1957|p=9}}</ref> The church occupied at least three locations in the [[Lower East Side]], and two additional locations on [[Broadway (Manhattan)|Broadway]] in [[Midtown Manhattan]], before moving to a more permanent site at [[Fifth Avenue]] and 46th Street in the 1860s.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 2\" /> The businessman [[William Rockefeller]] was the first of several [[Rockefeller family]] members to attend the Fifth Avenue Baptist Church, and became a major financial backer of the church in the 1870s.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 2\" /><ref>{{harvnb|ps=.|Pendo|1957|p=22}}</ref> Such was the family's involvement that William and his brother [[John D. Rockefeller]] later became trustees of the church, and many of the church's services were held at the Rockefellers' home nearby.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 2\" /><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pCgaAAAAYAAJ|title=John D. Rockefeller: The Heroic Age of American Enterprise|last=Nevins|first=A.|publisher=C. Scribner's Sons|year=1940|series=John D. Rockefeller: The Heroic Age of American Enterprise|page=455|access-date=November 3, 2019|issue=v. 1}}</ref>\n\nWhen Cornelius Woelfkin became the church's minister in 1912, he started leading the church toward a more [[modernism#Main period|modernist]] direction.<ref>{{harvnb|Paris et al.|2004|ps=.|p=18}}</ref> By the early 20th century, Fifth Avenue was seeing growing commercial development, and the church building became dilapidated.<ref>{{harvnb|ps=.|Pendo|1957|p=40}}</ref> The congregation sold off their old headquarters in 1919<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1919/05/30/archives/fifth-av-baptists-sell-church-home-property-long-in-the-market-is.html|title=Fifth Av. Baptists Sell Church Home; Property, Long in the Market, Is Purchased by Michael Dreicer|last=|first=|date=May 30, 1919|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 3, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> and bought land at [[Park Avenue]] and 63rd Street the following year.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1920/11/06/archives/new-apartment-for-park-avenue-two-large-parcels-acquired-at-the.html|title=New Apartment For Park Avenue; Two Large Parcels Acquired at the Southeast Corner of Sixty-third Street|last=|first=|date=November 6, 1920|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 3, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> John Rockefeller's son [[John D. Rockefeller Jr.]] funded half of the projected $1 million cost.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 2\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1917/05/08/archives/rockefeller-aids-new-church-fund-offers-to-add-50-per-cent-to.html|title=Rockefeller Aids New Church Fund; Offers to Add 50 Per Cent. to Amount Raised by Fifth Av. Baptist Congregation|last=|first=|date=May 8, 1917|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 3, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The new church, dubbed the \"Little Cathedral\", was designed by Henry C. Pelton in partnership with Francis R. Allen and Charles Collens.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 2\" /> The final service in the Fifth Avenue location was held on April 3, 1922,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1922/04/03/archives/final-service-held-in-5th-av-church-dr-cornelius-woelfkin-reviews.html|title=Final Service Held In 5th Av. Church; Dr. Cornelius Woelfkin Reviews Baptist Congregation's History of 91 Years|last=|first=|date=April 3, 1922|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 3, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> and the renamed Park Avenue Baptist Church held its first class in the new location the next week.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 2\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1922/04/09/archives/rockefeller-class-in-new-home-today-park-avenue-baptist-church-will.html|title=Rockefeller Class In New Home Today; Park Avenue Baptist Church Will Occupy Edifice of 64th Street for the First Time.|last=|first=|date=April 9, 1922|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 3, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n==== Progressive ideology ====\nIn 1924, John D. Rockefeller Jr. donated $500,000 to the [[Cathedral of St. John the Divine]] in [[Morningside Heights, Manhattan|Morningside Heights]], further uptown in Manhattan, in an unsuccessful attempt to influence the cathedral's ideology in a progressive direction.<ref name=\"Dolkart pp. 70-71\">{{harvnb|Dolkart|1998|ps=.|pp=70&ndash;71}}</ref> The following January, Harry E. Edmonds\u2014leader of the [[International House of New York|International House]] in Morningside Heights, for whose construction Rockefeller had provided funds\u2014wrote to Rockefeller to propose creating a new church in the neighborhood. Edmonds suggested that progressive pastor [[Harry Emerson Fosdick]] head such a church. Rockefeller then told the Park Avenue Baptist Church's leaders about the plan, after which he hired an agent to look at the planned church site.<ref name=\"Dolkart p. 72\">{{harvnb|Dolkart|1998|ps=.|p=72}}</ref>\n\nWoelfkin quit in mid-May 1925 and Rockefeller Jr. immediately started looking for a new minister,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1925/05/11/archives/dr-woelfkin-quits-park-avenue-pulpit-resigns-after-40-years-in.html|title=Dr. Woelfkin Quits Park Avenue Pulpit; Resigns After 40 Years in Baptist Ministry, 13 of Which Were at His Present Post.|date=May 11, 1925|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 3, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> ultimately deciding on Fosdick.<ref name=\"Dolkart p. 72\" /><ref name=\"NYCL p. 3\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|2000|ps=.|p=3}}</ref><ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 19\">{{harvnb|Paris et al.|2004|ps=.|p=19}}</ref> Fosdick had declined Rockefeller's offers several times,<ref name=\"Dolkart p. 72\" /> explaining that he did not \"want to be known as the pastor of the richest man in the country.\"<ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 19\" /> Fosdick stated that he would accept the minister position under the conditions that the church move to Morningside Heights, follow a policy of [[religious liberalism]], remove the requirement that members had to be [[Baptism|baptized]], and have the church be [[Nondenominational Christianity|nondenominational]].<ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 19\" /><ref name=\"Dolkart p. 73\">{{harvnb|Dolkart|1998|ps=.|p=73}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1925/05/16/archives/dr-fosdick-called-by-park-av-baptists-insists-on-changes-stipulates.html|title=Dr. Fosdick Called By Park Av. Baptists Insists On Changes; Stipulates That Church Shall Not Demand Baptism by Immersion|last=|first=|date=May 16, 1925|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 3, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> At the end of May 1925, Fosdick finally agreed to become minister of the Park Avenue Baptist Church.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 3\" /><ref name=\"Dolkart p. 73\" /><ref name=\"Miller p. 162\">{{harvnb|Miller|1985|ps=.|p=162}}</ref><ref name=\"NYT-FosdickAccepts-1925\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1925/05/29/archives/dr-fosdick-accepts-call-will-create-a-liberal-church-praises.html|title=Dr. Fosdick Accepts Call; Will Create A Liberal Church|last=|first=|date=May 29, 1925|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 3, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Only 15% of congregants voted against Fosdick's appointment.<ref>{{harvnb|ps=.|Dolkart|1998|p=383, note 157}}</ref> \n\nUnder Fosdick's leadership, the congregation doubled in size by 1930.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 3\" /><ref>{{harvnb|Pendo|1957|ps=.|p=49}}</ref> The new members were diverse: of the 158 people who joined in the year after Fosdick became minister, about half were not Baptists.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 3\" /><ref>{{harvnb|ps=.|Miller|1985|p=201}}</ref> Though some existing congregants had doubts about whether the Park Avenue Baptist Church should move from its recently completed edifice, the church's board, which was in favor of the relocation, stated that congregants would not have to pay any of the costs for the new church.<ref name=\"Dolkart p. 383\">{{harvnb|Dolkart|1998|ps=.|p=383, note 157}}</ref>\n\n=== Planning and construction ===\n\n==== Site selection ====\n[[File:Riverside Ch back jeh.jpg|thumb|Claremont Avenue view]]\nMorningside Heights, where the new church was to be located, was quickly being developed as a residential neighborhood surrounded by numerous higher-education institutions, including [[Union Theological Seminary (New York City)|Union Theological Seminary]] and [[International House of New York]].<ref name=\"Dolkart p. 1\">{{harvnb|ps=.|Dolkart|1998|p=1}}</ref><ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|2000|ps=.|p=4}}</ref> The development had been spurred by the presence of [[Riverside Park (Manhattan)|Riverside Park]] and [[Riverside Drive (Manhattan)|Riverside Drive]] nearby, as well as the construction of the [[New York City Subway]]'s [[IRT Broadway\u2013Seventh Avenue Line|Broadway\u2013Seventh Avenue Line]] (the modern-day {{NYCS trains|Broadway-Seventh north}}) under [[Broadway (Manhattan)|Broadway]].<ref name=\"NYCL p. 3\" /><ref name=\"Dolkart p. 1\" /> Rockefeller briefly considered a location on [[Morningside Drive (Manhattan)|Morningside Drive]], on the eastern edge of Morningside Heights. However, he ultimately decided on a site at the southeast corner of Riverside Drive and 122nd Street on the neighborhood's western border, which overlooked Riverside Park to the west and [[Sakura Park|Claremont Park]] to the north.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\" /><ref name=\"Dolkart p. 74\">{{harvnb|Dolkart|1998|ps=.|p=74}}</ref> Rockefeller felt that the Riverside Drive site was more easily visible, since it abutted the [[Hudson River]] and would be seen by recreational users of Riverside Drive.<ref name=\"Dolkart p. 74\" /> \n\nIn May 1925, Rockefeller finalized his purchase of the new church's site at Riverside Drive.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1925/05/26/archives/rockefeller-jr-buys-plot-uptown-block-on-morningside-drive.html|title=Rockefeller Jr. Buys Plot Uptown; Block on Morningside Drive Considered Logical Location for Edifice Asked by Fosdick|last=|first=|date=May 26, 1925|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 3, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> That July, he exchanged his previous purchase of a plot on Morningside Drive for another plot on Riverside Drive.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1925/07/25/archives/fosdicks-church-to-go-up-on-drive-rockefeller-exchanges-morningside.html|title=Fosdick's Church to Go Up on Drive; Rockefeller Exchanges Morningside Plot for Site Near Grant's Tomb|last=|first=|date=July 25, 1925|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 5, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Shortly afterward, he acquired yet more land, after which he had a frontage of {{Convert|250|ft|m|abbr=}} on Riverside Drive for the new church.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1925/08/08/archives/rockefeller-adds-to-plot-for-church-acquires-twelvestory-apartment.html|title=Rockefeller Adds to Plot for Church; Acquires Twelve-Story Apartment House on Riverside Drive, Making Frontage of 250 Feet|last=|first=|date=August 8, 1925|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 5, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> At the time of the acquisition, three apartment buildings and two mansions occupied the church's future site. Rockefeller wished to keep the apartments in place for several years to fund the church's eventual construction.<ref name=\"Dolkart p. 74\" />\n\n==== Planning ====\nRockefeller was the chairman of the committee tasked with creating a new building for the church. Hoping to avoid publicity, he did not host an architectural competition, but instead, privately asked several architectural firms to submit plans for the building.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\" /><ref name=\"Dolkart p. 75\">{{harvnb|Dolkart|1998|ps=.|p=75}}</ref>{{efn|These firms included [[McKim, Mead & White]], [[Allen & Collens]], [[Henry C. Pelton]], [[Ralph Adams Cram]], and [[York and Sawyer]].<ref>{{harvnb|Dolkart|1998|ps=.|pp=75\u201376}}</ref>}} Rockefeller tried to downplay his role in the planning and construction process, asking that his name not be mentioned in media reports or discussion of the church, though with little success.<ref name=\"Dolkart p. 73\" /> His role in the selection process raised concerns from church trustees such as Fosdick, who believed that such close financial involvement could place the church in \"a very vulnerable position\".<ref>{{harvnb|ps=.|Miller|1985|p=204}}</ref><ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\" /> [[John Roach Straton]], reverend of the [[Calvary Baptist Church (Manhattan)|Calvary Baptist Church]] on [[57th Street (Manhattan)|57th Street]] in Midtown Manhattan, criticized Rockefeller's involvement and mockingly suggested that it be called the [[Socony]] Church, after the oil company headed by the Rockefellers.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1925/06/08/archives/straton-criticizes-fosdicks-church-thinks-it-means-rockefellers.html|title=Straton Criticizes Fosdick's Church; Thinks It Means Rockefellers Hereafter Will Have Their Own Sanctuary|last=|first=|date=June 8, 1925|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 5, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>  George S. Chappell, writing in ''[[The New Yorker]]'' under the pseudonym \"T-Square\", joked that the project \"was known to most secular minds as the Rockefeller Cathedral.\"''<ref name=\"Dolkart p. 73\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Chappell|first=George S. (T-Square)|date=November 29, 1930|title=The Sky Line|journal=The New Yorker|volume=6|pages=82}}</ref>''\n\nNeither Rockefeller nor Fosdick had strict requirements for the church's architectural style. Rockefeller only asked that the new building include space for the Park Avenue Baptist Church's [[carillon]], which he had donated.<ref name=\"Dolkart p. 75\" /> Most of the plans entailed a church facing 122nd Street and wrapping around the existing apartment buildings on the site. The exception was a plan by [[Allen & Collens]] and [[Henry C. Pelton]], who had designed the Park Avenue Baptist Church. Their plan called for a [[Gothic Revival architecture|Gothic Revival]] church with its main entrance on the side, facing Riverside Drive, with a bell tower as well as apartment towers for the neighboring [[Union Theological Seminary (New York City)|Union Theological Seminary]].<ref name=\"Dolkart p. 76\">{{harvnb|Dolkart|1998|ps=.|p=76}}</ref> The building committee removed the apartment towers from the church plan, and Allen, Collens, and Pelton were selected to design the new church in February 1926.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\" /><ref name=\"Dolkart p. 76\" /><ref name=\"NYT-Rockefeller-Plans-1926\" /> As part of the plans, there would be a {{Convert|375|ft|m|-tall|abbr=|adj=mid}} [[bell tower]] (later changed to {{convert|392|ft}}), a 2,400-seat auditorium, and athletic rooms. The building would occupy a lot {{Convert|100|ft||abbr=}} wide by {{Convert|225|ft||abbr=}} long.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 4\" /><ref name=\"NYT-Rockefeller-Plans-1926\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1926/02/12/archives/rockefeller-plans-4000000-church-on-riverside-drive-400foot-gothic.html|title=Rockefeller Plans $4,000,000 Church On Riverside Drive; 400-Foot Gothic Campanile Will House the Carillon, Close to Grant's Tomb|last=|first=|date=February 12, 1926|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 5, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Since there was no room for a chapel in the original plans, Rockefeller proposed trading land with the Union Theological Seminary. In May 1926, Rockefeller gave Union an apartment building on 99 Claremont Avenue, to the northeast of the church. In exchange, Riverside Church received a small plot to its south, allowing for the construction of the chapel as well as a proposed [[cloister]] passage to Claremont Avenue.<ref name=\"Dolkart p. 77\">{{harvnb|Dolkart|1998|ps=.|p=77}}</ref> \n\nRockefeller chose to delay the construction process until after the leases of the site's existing tenants expired in October.<ref name=\"NYT-Rockefeller-Plans-1926\" /> The official plans were filed with the [[New York City Department of Buildings]] in November 1926.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1926/11/02/archives/rockefeller-plan-for-church-is-filed-4000000-edifice-of-park-av.html|title=Rockefeller Plan for Church is Filed; $4,000,000 Edifice of Park Av. Baptists Will Rise on Riverside Drive|last=|first=|date=November 2, 1926|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 5, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The congregation voted to approve the building plans that December, at a cost of $4 million.<ref name=\"NYT-Plans-Approved-1926\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1926/12/27/archives/baptists-approve-4000000-plans-for-fosdick-church-razing-starts-on.html|title=Baptists Approve $4,000,000 Plans For Fosdick Church; Razing Starts on the Site for Edifice to Be Built to Endure for Generations|last=|first=|date=December 27, 1926|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 4, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Pelton and Collens then went to France, driving over {{Convert|2500|mi||abbr=}} within the country to look for churches upon which to model Riverside Church's design.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 5\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|2000|ps=.|p=5}}</ref><ref name=\"Carder p. 5\">{{harvnb|ps=.|Carder|1930|p=5}}</ref>  They eventually selected the 13th-century [[Chartres Cathedral]] as their inspiration.<ref name=\"NYT-Plans-Approved-1926\" /><ref name=\"NYCL p. 5\" /><ref name=\"Carder p. 9\">{{harvnb|ps=.|Carder|1930|p=9}}</ref>\n\n==== Construction ====\n[[File:General_Grant_National_Memorial,_The_Riverside_Church,_and_The_Interchurch_Center_(8026589050)_(2).jpg|thumb|Riverside Church (center), [[Grant's Tomb]] (left), and [[The Interchurch Center]] (right) from the Hudson River]]\nMarc Eidlitz & Son, Inc. were hired as the contractors of the new Riverside Drive church.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 6\" /> On November 21, 1927, the church's ceremonial [[cornerstone]] was laid, marking the start of construction.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 6\" /><ref name=\"NYT-Cornerstone-1927\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1927/11/21/archives/cornerstone-laid-for-fosdick-church-hundreds-witness-ceremony-in.html|title=Cornerstone Laid For Fosdick Church; Hundreds Witness Ceremony in Drive at Foundation of $4,000,000 Edifice|last=|first=|date=November 21, 1927|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 5, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref name=\"Dolkart p. 80\">{{harvnb|Dolkart|1998|ps=.|p=80}}</ref> The cornerstone featured items such as Woelfkin's Bible and ''New York Times'' articles about the new church.<ref name=\"NYT-Cornerstone-1927\" /><ref name=\"NYCL p. 12\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|2000|ps=.|p=12}}</ref> The Park Avenue church building, as well as three adjacent rowhouses, was sold for $1.5 million in April 1928.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 6\" /> The same month, the Park Avenue Baptist Church's official monthly newsletter announced that its existing 53-bell carillon would be expanded to 72 bells upon its relocation to Riverside Drive, making it the largest set of bells in the world.<ref name=\"D&C-Chimes-1928\">{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/38645319/|title=Largest Chimes for Park Avenue Church|date=April 24, 1928|work=Democrat and Chronicle|access-date=November 8, 2019|page=4|via=newspapers.com {{open access}}}}</ref>\n\nThree fires occurred in late 1928 after wooden scaffolding around the church was ignited.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/38486841/|title=Rockefeller Pays Visit to Ruins at Church Fire|date=December 23, 1928|work=New York Daily News|access-date=November 5, 2019|page=318|via=newspapers.com {{open access}}}}</ref> One of these fires, on December 22, 1928, caused $1 million in damages and almost completely destroyed the interior, though the exterior remained mostly intact. Much of the damages were covered by an insurance policy placed on the building.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1928/12/22/archives/night-fire-sweeps-riverside-church-as-100000-look-on-flames-raging.html|title=Night Fire Sweeps Riverside Church As 100,000 Look On; Flames Raging In Rockefeller's Riverside Church|date=December 22, 1928|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 4, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/38486753/|title=Fire Guts 'Rockefeller Church'; Huge Edifice Reduced to Black Shell|date=December 22, 1928|work=Brooklyn Citizen|access-date=November 5, 2019|page=1|via=newspapers.com {{open access}}}}</ref> Shortly after the December 1928 fire, Rockefeller announced that he would continue with construction after insurance claims were settled.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1928/12/24/archives/rockefeller-church-to-resume-building-work-to-proceed-on-burned.html|title=Rockefeller Church To Resume Building; Work to Proceed on Burned Riverside Edifice as Soon as Insurance is Settled|last=|first=|date=December 24, 1928|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 4, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The fire delayed the completion of the interior by six months.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 12\" /><ref>{{harvnb|Miller|1985|ps=.|p=208}}</ref> In February 1929, the congregation began seeking donations to continue construction. Rockefeller donated $1.5 million, which when combined with the proceeds from the Park Avenue building's sale, provided $3 million in funds.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1929/02/19/archives/seek-gifts-to-build-riverside-church-trustees-planning-endowment.html|title=Seek Gifts to Build Riverside Church; Trustees, Planning Endowment Fund, Say Contributions Will Be Welcomed|last=|first=|date=February 19, 1929|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 4, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Construction of a mortuary at the Riverside Drive church was approved in March 1929.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1929/03/23/archives/mortuary-chapel-in-riverside-church-rockefeller-approves-feature.html|title=Mortuary Chapel in Riverside Church; Rockefeller Approves Feature for New Edifice of Park Avenue Congregation|last=|first=|date=March 23, 1929|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 4, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> While construction was ongoing, the congregation temporarily relocated to Temple Beth-El on Fifth Avenue and 76th Street for nine months starting in July 1929.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 6\" />\n\nThe first portion of the new church building, the assembly hall under the auditorium, opened in October 1929.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1929/10/03/archives/first-unit-opened-in-riverside-church-precommunion-service-is-held.html|title=First Unit Opened In Riverside Church; Pre-Communion Service Is Held in Assembly Hall of New Rockefeller Edifice|last=|first=|date=October 3, 1929|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 3, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{harvnb|Miller|1985|ps=.|p=205}}</ref> That December, Fosdick formally filed plans to rename the church from \"Park Avenue Baptist Church\" to \"Riverside Church\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1929/12/12/archives/fosdick-church-drops-baptist-from-title-changes-name-to-the.html|title=Fosdick Church Drops Baptist From Title; Changes Name to the Riverside Church|last=|first=|date=December 12, 1929|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 5, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>  The bell was hoisted to the top of the tower's carillon in early September 1930,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1930/09/07/archives/will-hoist-22ton-bell-riverside-church-to-complete-carillon-on.html|title=Will Hoist 22-Ton Bell; Riverside Church to Complete Carillon on Tuesday|last=|first=|date=September 7, 1930|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 6, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> and the tower was completed later that month, with the first [[Sunday school]] class being held there on September 29.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1930/09/29/archives/memorial-tower-opened-riverside-church-sunday-school-classes-held.html|title=Memorial Tower Opened; Riverside Church Sunday School Classes Held There.|date=September 29, 1930|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 5, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The church was completed a week later, on October 5.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 6\" /><ref name=\"Dolkart p. 80\" /><ref name=\":0\">{{harvnb|Paris et al.|2004|ps=.|p=137}}</ref>  On that date, the first service in the altar was attended by 3,200 people, and though all of the space in the nave and basement was filled, thousands more wished to enter.<ref name=\"Dolkart p. 80\" /><ref name=\":0\" /> The next month, officials received two oil paintings from Rockefeller Jr.'s collection.<ref name=\"NYT-Paintings-1930\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1930/11/01/archives/reveal-rockefeller-gift-riverside-church-executives-tell-of.html|title=Reveal Rockefeller Gift; Riverside Church Executives Tell of Receiving Two Paintings|last=|first=|date=November 1, 1930|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 6, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The first officers of Riverside Church were elected in December 1930<ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 19\" /> and the church was formally dedicated with an interdenominational service two months later.<ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 19\" /><ref name=\"NYT-Carillon-1931\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1931/02/12/archives/riverside-carillon-is-heard-miles-away-notes-of-72-bells-ring-out.html|title=Riverside Carillon is Heard Miles Away; Notes of 72 Bells Ring Out as Denominational Leaders Laud Spirit of Church|last=|first=|date=February 12, 1931|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 8, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The total cost of construction was estimated at $4 million.<ref name=\"NYT-Pew-Phones-1930\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1930/09/27/archives/riverside-church-puts-in-pew-phones-equipment-available-to-aid.html|title=Riverside Church Puts in Pew Phones; Equipment Available to Aid Hearing in All Parts of New Edifice|last=|first=|date=September 27, 1930|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 8, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> In the early years of the new building, journalists tended to refer to the church in association with either Rockefeller or Fosdick, although the former sought to reduce emphasis on his role at the church.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 7\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|2000|ps=.|p=7}}</ref> Riverside Church's completion sharply contrasted with the Cathedral of St. John the Divine, which remained incomplete after almost four decades.<ref name=\"Dolkart p. 81\">{{harvnb|Dolkart|1998|ps=.|p=81}}</ref>\n\nDespite the completion of Riverside Church, Rockefeller felt that the surroundings still needed to be improved.<ref name=\"Dolkart p. 81\" /> He announced in 1932 that he would pay for a $350,000 landscaping of the adjacent [[Sakura Park]], which at the time stood decrepit.<ref name=\"Dolkart p. 81\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1932/02/09/archives/claremont-park-to-be-beautified-rockefeller-to-pay-350000-for.html|title=Claremont Park to be Beautified; Rockefeller to Pay $350,000 for Improvement of City Plot at Riverside Church|date=February 9, 1932|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 5, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Rockefeller hired the [[Olmsted Brothers]] to renovate the park,<ref name=\"Dolkart p. 82\">{{harvnb|Dolkart|1998|ps=.|p=82}}</ref> and the project was completed two years later.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1934/05/26/archives/claremont-park-is-opened-to-public-twoacre-tract-on-riverside-drive.html|title=Claremont Park is Opened to Public; Two-Acre Tract on Riverside Drive Improved by Rockefeller at Cost of $315,000.|date=May 26, 1934|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 5, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Additionally, when Union Theological Seminary announced that it would build a new apartment building at 99 Claremont Avenue. Rockefeller offered to exchange his neighboring apartment building at 122nd Street and Claremont Avenue for the lots south of the church, which were owned by the seminary. The land was swapped in 1931 after Rockefeller offered to finance part of the dormitory's construction.<ref name=\"Dolkart p. 82\" /> In 1935, the land under the church was deeded to Rockefeller,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1935/06/16/archives/riverside-church-deeded-formal-transfer-of-land-by-rockefeller-is.html|title=Riverside Church Deeded; Formal Transfer of Land by Rockefeller Is Placed on Record.|date=June 16, 1935|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 5, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> and he also purchased a lot at Riverside Drive and 122nd Street from [[St. Luke's Hospital (New York City)|St. Luke's Hospital]], so that he now owned all of the land along the eastern side of Riverside Drive between 120th and 122nd Streets.<ref name=\"Dolkart p. 83\">{{harvnb|Dolkart|1998|ps=.|p=83}}</ref> Ultimately, Rockefeller spent a total of $10.5 million toward land acquisitions and church construction.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 7\" />\n\n=== Use ===\n\n==== 1930s through mid-1960s ====\n[[File:Riverside Church, New York City (2014) - 12.JPG|thumb|Memorial inscription to [[John D. Rockefeller Jr.]], who funded much of the church's construction|alt=Memorial inscription to John D. Rockefeller Jr., who funded much of the church's construction]]\nThe completion of the new church building at Morningside Heights resulted in a steady increase in the congregation's membership. By May 1946, the congregation had 3,500 members, 800 more than twenty years previously. According to a brochure issued by the church, \"soon every room [...] was in use seven days a week\", and enrollment at the church's Sunday school had increased correspondingly.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 7\" />\n\nRiverside Church became a community icon and a religious center of Morningside Heights. By 1939, the church had more than 200 persons on its staff in both part-time and full-time positions, and over 10,000 people a week were being served by the church's various social and religious services, athletic events, and employment programs.<ref name=\"WPA1939\" /> In addition to its highly attended Sunday morning service, Riverside Church hosted [[Confirmation|Communion]] services every first Sunday afternoon, as well as Ministry of Music services on other Sunday afternoons. The Riverside Guild, the young-adult fellowship, held worship services during Sunday evenings. Weddings and funerals were also hosted at the church.<ref>{{harvnb|Paris et al.|2004|ps=.|pp=67\u201370}}</ref> The [[United States Naval Reserve Midshipmen's School]] at Columbia started using Riverside Church for services in 1942, drawing 2,000 attendees on average.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 7\" /> The Midshipmen's School continued to hold its services at the church until October 1945.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 7\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1945/10/22/archives/navy-school-thanks-riverside-church.html|title=Navy School Thanks Riverside Church|date=October 22, 1945|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 8, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nIn June 1945, Fosdick announced that he would step down as senior minister, effective the following May.<ref name=\"NYT-Fosdick-1945\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1945/06/06/archives/fosdick-to-quit-riverside-church-retirement-date-set-for-may-1946.html|title=Fosdick to Quit Riverside Church; Retirement Date Set for May, 1946; Announcement Made at Joint Meeting of Deacons and Trustees--Founder and Pastor of the Church Since 1930|last=Studio|first=The New York Times|date=June 6, 1945|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 8, 2019|last2=1943|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> This spurred a search for a new pastor, and in March 1946, Robert James McCracken was named for the position.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1946/03/28/archives/riverside-church-names-new-pastor-in-new-riverside-church-offices.html|title=Riverside Church Names New Pastor; in New Riverside Church Offices|last=McDowell|first=Rachel K.|date=March 28, 1946|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 8, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> McCracken officially became the senior pastor of Riverside Church that October.<ref name=\"NYT-McCracken-1946\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1946/10/03/archives/riverside-church-installs-pastor-new-riverside-church-pastor.html|title=Riverside Church Installs Pastor; New Riverside Church Pastor Installed|date=October 3, 1946|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 8, 2019|url-status=live|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> As Fosdick and McCracken held each other in mutual respect, the transition between ministers went smoothly.<ref name=\"Paris et al. pp. 74-75\">{{harvnb|Paris et al.|2004|ps=.|pp=74\u201375}}</ref> Over the next two decades as senior pastor, McCracken continued Fosdick's policy of religious liberalism.<ref name=\"Paris et al. pp. 74-75\" /><ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 34\">{{harvnb|Paris et al.|2004|ps=.|p=34}}</ref> Halfway through McCracken's tenure, in 1956, the church conducted an internal report and found that the organizational structure was disorganized, and that most staff did not feel that any single person was in charge. As a result, six councils were created and placed under the purview of the deacons and trustees.<ref name=\"Paris et al. pp. 43-44\">{{harvnb|Paris et al.|2004|ps=.|pp=43\u201344}}</ref> The councils partitioned power into \"a series of mini-kingdoms\", as a later pastor, Ernest T. Campbell, described it.<ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 46\">{{harvnb|Paris et al.|2004|ps=.|p=46}}</ref> \n\nConstruction on the Martin Luther King Jr. Wing, to the south of the existing church, started in 1955. The seven-story wing was designed by Collens, Willis & Beckonert, successors to Allen & Collens; its $15 million cost was funded by Rockefeller.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 7\" /><ref name=\"Dolkart p. 83\" /> The wing was dedicated in December 1959 and contained additional facilities for the church's programs.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 7\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1959/12/07/archives/new-8story-wing-opens-at-riverside.html|title=New 8-Story Wing Opens at Riverside|date=December 7, 1959|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 9, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref name=\"NYDN-Wing-1959\">{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/38718458/|title=Dedicate Riverside Church Wing|date=December 7, 1959|work=New York Daily News|access-date=November 9, 2019|page=165|via=newspapers.com {{open access}}}}</ref> A {{Convert|15|ft||abbr=|adj=on}} \"dummy\" antenna had been placed on top of Riverside Church's 392-foot-tall carillon earlier that year, to determine whether it could be used by Columbia University's radio station, [[WKCR-FM|WKCR]] (89.9 FM), though the antenna was strongly opposed by parishioners and the local community.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1959/01/09/archives/riverside-church-is-aroused-by-trial-radio-aerial-on-roof.html|title=Riverside Church Is Aroused By Trial Radio Aerial on Roof|date=January 9, 1959|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 9, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Nevertheless, the church decided to place an antenna atop the carillon for its own radio station, the top of the antenna being {{Convert|440|ft|m|abbr=}} above ground level.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1960/12/28/archives/new-fm-station-on-air-here-jan-1-wrvr-will-be-sponsored-by.html|title=New FM Station on Air Here Jan 1; WRVR Will Be Sponsored by Riverside Church|last=Shepard|first=Richard F.|date=December 28, 1960|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 9, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Riverside Church started operating the radio station [[WLTW|WRVR]] (106.7 [[FM broadcasting|FM]]) in 1961, and continued to operate it until 1976.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 7\" /> Additionally, Riverside Church's congregation voted to merge with the [[United Church of Christ]] in 1960.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1960/12/08/archives/riverside-church-acting-on-merger-meets-to-ratify-constitution-of.html|title=Riverside Church Acting on Merger; Meets to Ratify Constitution of United Church of Christ -- 2d Consolidation Urged|date=December 8, 1960|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 9, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The Stone Gym, a preexisting Union Theological Seminary building southeast of the original church, was purchased by Rockefeller and then reopened as a community facility in April 1962, after a five-year renovation.<ref name=\"NPS p. 3\">{{harvnb|National Park Service|2012|ps=.|p=3}}</ref><ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 255\">{{harvnb|Paris et al.|2004|ps=.|p=255}}</ref> McCracken announced in April 1967 that he would leave his position as senior minister, citing health issues.<ref name=\"NYT-McCracken-1967\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1967/04/24/archives/dr-mccracken-to-leave-pulpit-after-two-decades-at-riverside.html|title=Dr. McCracken to Leave Pulpit After Two Decades at Riverside|last=Dugan|first=George|date=April 24, 1967|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 9, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n==== Late 1960s through 1990s ====\n[[File:Riverside Church, New York City (2014) - 02.JPG|thumb|left|[[Archivolt]]s in the front doorway]]\nErnest T. Campbell became pastor in November 1968.<ref name=\"Paris et al. pp. 45-47\">{{harvnb|Paris et al.|2004|ps=.|pp=45\u201347}}</ref><ref name=\"NYT-Campbell-1968\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1968/11/18/archives/dr-campbell-is-installed-at-riverside-church-predecessor-dr.html|title=Dr. Campbell Is Installed at Riverside Church; Predecessor, Dr. McCracken, Gives Him the Charge Dr. Marney Calls in Sermon for 'Vast Repentance'|last=Dugan|first=George|date=November 18, 1968|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 9, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Less than a year after Campbell became senior minister, civil rights leader [[James Forman]] interrupted a sermon at Riverside Church, citing it as one of several churches from which black Americans could ask [[Reparations for slavery|reparations]] for [[Slavery in the United States|slavery]].<ref name=\"NYT-Budget-1970\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1970/02/01/archives/riverside-church-has-money-woes-20000-short-of-its-budget-goal.html|title=Riverside Church Has Money Woes|date=February 1, 1970|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 9, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref name=\"Paris et al. pp. 89-91\">{{harvnb|Paris et al.|2004|ps=.|pp=89\u201391}}</ref> This led to the church releasing its financial figures for the first time in 1970, which valued the building at $86 million and the total [[financial endowment]] of $18 million,<ref name=\"NYT-Budget-1970\" /> as well as the creation of a $450,000 Fund for Social Justice to disburse reparations over three years.<ref name=\"Paris et al. pp. 89-91\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1970/03/02/archives/riverside-church-will-give-150000-a-year-to-the-poor.html|title=Riverside Church Will Give $150,000 a Year to the Poor|date=March 2, 1970|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 9, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Further, following a 1972 metropolitan mission study, several ministries were formed at Riverside, aimed toward ameliorating social conditions in the New York City area.<ref>{{harvnb|Paris et al.|2004|ps=.|p=206}}</ref> Campbell's tenure was marked by several controversial sermons,<ref name=\"Paris et al. pp. 89-91\" /> as well as increasing conflicts among the church's boards, councils, and staff.<ref name=\"Paris et al. pp. 45-47\" /> In June 1976, Campbell resigned suddenly, having felt that his style of leadership was not sufficient to reconcile these disagreements.<ref name=\"Paris et al. pp. 45-47\" /><ref name=\"NYT-Campbell-1976\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1976/06/25/archives/campbell-quits-ministry-at-the-riverside-church.html|title=Campbell Quits Ministry At the Riverside Church|last=Briggs|first=Kenneth A.|date=June 25, 1976|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 9, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The same month saw the installment of the church's first female pastor, Evelyn Newman.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1976/06/07/archives/riverside-church-installs-its-first-woman-as-pastor.html|title=Riverside Church Installs Its First Woman as Pastor|last=Spiegel|first=Irving|date=June 7, 1976|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 9, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nBy a vote in August 1977, [[William Sloane Coffin]] was selected as the next senior minister of Riverside Church.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1977/08/15/archives/riverside-church-vote-approves-coffin-as-minister.html|title=Riverside Church Vote Approves Coffin as Minister|last=Wedemeyer|first=Dee|date=August 15, 1977|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 9, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Coffin officiated his first service in November 1977.<ref name=\"NYT-Coffin-1977\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1977/11/07/archives/dr-coffin-has-a-lively-first-service-at-riverside.html|title=Dr. Coffin Has a Lively First Service at Riverside|last=Dunning|first=Jennifer|date=November 7, 1977|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 9, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> At this point, the congregation's size had been declining for several years. However, after Coffin's selection as senior minister, membership had increased to 2,627 by the end of 1979, and total annual attendance for morning services rose from 49,902 in 1976 to 71,536 in 1978.<ref name=\"NYT-Coffin-1979\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1979/12/31/archives/coffin-and-his-liberal-pulpit-renew-legacy-of-controversy-a.html|title=Coffin and His 'Liberal Pulpit' Renew Legacy of Controversy|last=Briggs|first=Kenneth A.|date=December 31, 1979|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 9, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Coffin's tenure was also marked by theologically liberal sermons, many of which were controversial,<ref name=\"NYT-Coffin-1979\" /><ref name=\"Paris et al. pp. 106-107\">{{harvnb|Paris et al.|2004|ps=.|pp=106\u2013107}}</ref> though he was more traditional in his worship<!--, emphasizing Sunday morning service over other services-->.<ref name=\"Paris et al. pp. 106-107\" /><!-- This era also saw [[Channing E. Phillips]], the first [[African-American]] major-party [[President of the United States|U.S. presidential nominee]], being hired as minister of planning and coordination.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/11/12/obituaries/channing-e-phillips-dies-at-59-minister-and-civil-rights-leader.html|title=Channing E. Phillips Dies at 59; Minister and Civil Rights Leader|last=McQuiston|first=John T.|date=November 12, 1987|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 10, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>--> Coffin announced his intention to resign in July 1987 to become the president of disarmament organization SANE/Freeze,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/07/20/nyregion/coffin-resigns-to-praise-and-criticism.html|title=Coffin Resigns to Praise and Criticism|last=Goldman|first=Ari L.|date=July 20, 1987|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 9, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> and held his last sermon that December.<ref name=\"NYT-Coffin-1987\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/12/21/nyregion/dr-coffin-says-goodbye-to-riverside.html|title=Dr. Coffin Says Goodbye to Riverside|last=Marriott|first=Michel|date=December 21, 1987|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 9, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nRiverside Church formed a committee, which conducted a nationwide search for their next senior minister over the next year. In February 1989, the committee chose [[James A. Forbes]], a professor at nearby Union Theological Seminary, for the position.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1989/02/01/nyregion/riverside-chooses-new-minister.html|title=Riverside Chooses New Minister|last=Goldman|first=Ari L.|date=February 1, 1989|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 10, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref name=\"Paris et al. pp. 108-109\">{{harvnb|Paris et al.|2004|ps=.|pp=108\u2013109}}</ref> The congregation then voted almost unanimously to approve Forbes's selection, thereby making him the church's first black senior minister.<ref name=\"Paris et al. pp. 108-109\" /><ref name=\"NYT-Forbes-1989\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1989/02/06/nyregion/members-elect-a-new-pastor-at-riverside.html|title=Members Elect A New Pastor At Riverside|last=Goldman|first=Ari L.|date=February 6, 1989|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 10, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> At the time, between one-fourth and one-third of the congregation was black or Hispanic.<ref name=\"NYT-Forbes-1989\" /> However, tensions soon developed between Forbes and executive minister David Dyson over matters ranging from Forbes's sermon lengths to his musical choices. The tensions grew to the point that a [[Mediation|mediator]] was enlisted after Forbes tried to fire Dyson.<ref name=\"NYT-Forbes-1992\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/05/18/nyregion/riverside-s-pastor-at-center-of-turmoil.html|title=Riverside's Pastor at Center of Turmoil|last=Goldman|first=Ari L.|date=May 18, 1992|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 10, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The dispute was resolved when Dyson resigned in October 1992.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1992/10/11/nyregion/update-tension-lessens-as-minister-leaves-riverside-church.html|title=Update; Tension Lessens as Minister Leaves Riverside Church|date=October 11, 1992|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 10, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nIn 1996, Riverside Church started conducting a study on the building's current use and services,<ref name=\"NYT-Alter-1998\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/01/25/nyregion/neighborhood-report-upper-west-side-alter-riverside-church-like-redoing-chartres.html|title=Neighborhood Report: Upper West Side; Alter Riverside Church? Like Redoing Chartres, Foes Say|last=Allon|first=Janet|date=January 25, 1998|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 10, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> and the following October, Body Lawson, Ben Paul Associated Architects and Planners published their Riverside Church Master Plan.<ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 175\">{{harvnb|Paris et al.|2004|ps=.|p=175}}</ref> The plan included a major addition on Riverside Church's eastern side, which included the relocation of the Claremont Avenue entrance, paving of the forecourt, reconfiguration of the cloister lobby, and construction of a seven-story building over the gymnasium. This was controversial among many congregants, who started a petition to ask the [[New York City Landmarks Preservation Commission]] (NYCLPC) to designate the church so that the original appearance of that entrance could not be altered.<ref name=\"NYT-Alter-1998\" /> In December 1998, the congregation voted to officially nominate the church for landmark status.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1998/12/06/nyregion/neighborhood-report-morningside-heights-solomonic-landmarking-decision-riverside.html|title=Neighborhood Report: Morningside Heights; A Solomonic Landmarking Decision at Riverside Church|last=Siegal|first=Nina|date=December 6, 1998|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 11, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The congregation chose to nominate only the original church building, excluding the Martin Luther King Jr. Wing, despite preservationists' requests that the entire structure be considered for landmark designation. The NYCLPC approved landmark status for the original church in May 2000.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2000/05/17/nyregion/riverside-church-gets-landmark-status.html|title=Riverside Church Gets Landmark Status|last=Siegal|first=Nina|date=May 17, 2000|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 11, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n==== 21st century ====\n[[File:Sakura-Park-New-York-with-Riverside-Church.jpg|thumb|Viewed from [[Sakura Park]], directly to the north]]\nTwo controversies involving Riverside Church arose in the early 2000s. The first involved a sexual-abuse allegation against the director of a basketball program at the church, while the second concerned an allegation that the church's finances were being mismanaged due to a $32 million decrease in the endowment between 2000 and 2002.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/07/21/nyregion/riverside-minister-faces-an-internal-challenge-again.html|title=Riverside Minister Faces an Internal Challenge, Again|last=Wakin|first=Daniel J.|date=July 21, 2002|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 11, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The accused basketball director resigned in 2002,<ref>{{Cite news|last=Feuer|first=Alan|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/05/01/nyregion/church-basketball-director-leaves-after-abuse-charge.html|title=Church Basketball Director Leaves After Abuse Charge|date=2002-05-01|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-02-29|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> while the controversy over finances was prolonged through several years of court cases, although the New York Supreme Court had dismissed a lawsuit over the topic.<ref>{{Cite news|last=Konigsberg|first=Eric|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/06/10/nyregion/10riverside.html|title=With an Exit, a Historic Church at a Crossroads|date=2007-06-10|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-02-29|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Forbes announced his retirement in September 2006<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/09/18/nyregion/minister-of-riverside-church-to-step-down.html|title=Minister of Riverside Church to Step Down|last=Barron|first=James|date=September 18, 2006|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 11, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> and held his last sermon in June 2007. By that time, the church had 2,700 congregants, though the congregation was then primarily black and Hispanic.<ref name=\"NYT-Forbes-2007\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/06/10/nyregion/10riverside.html|title=With an Exit, a Historic Church at a Crossroads|last=Konigsberg|first=Eric|date=June 10, 2007|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 10, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> At that time, the church had a $14&nbsp;million annual operating budget and a paid staff of 130.<ref name=\"NYT-Rebuilding-2007\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2007/05/05/us/05religion.htmle|title=Riverside Takes On the Task of Rebuilding a Church|last=Freedman|first=Samuel G.|date=May 5, 2007|work=The New York Times|accessdate=April 9, 2009|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nAnother nationwide, year-long search commenced, and in August 2008, it was announced that Brad Braxton had been selected as the sixth senior minister of Riverside Church.<ref name=\"NYT8408\" /> His tenure was marked by theological disputes, with congregants disagreeing over whether the church should take a fundamentalist or progressive position, as well as a lawsuit over his high annual salary, which a church spokesperson stated was $457,000. In June 2009, he submitted his letter of resignation due to these disputes.<ref name=\"NYT-Braxton-2009\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nydailynews.com/new-york/riverside-church-pastor-resigned-accusations-misappropriation-article-1.379032|title=Riverside Church Pastor resigned under accusations of misappropriation|last=Gonzalez|first=Juan|date=July 1, 2009 |website=New York Daily News|access-date=November 11, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gothamist.com/news/controversial-riverside-church-pastor-resigns|title=Controversial Riverside Church Pastor Resigns|last=Del Signore|first=John|date=June 30, 2009|website=Gothamist|publisher=New York Public Radio|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=November 11, 2019}}</ref> Over the next five years, Riverside Church did not have a senior minister, and its congregation size decreased to 1,670 in 2014, representing a loss of over a thousand congregants since 2007.<ref name=\"NYT-Butler-2014\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/06/09/nyregion/riverside-church-elects-amy-butler-as-new-senior-minister.html|title=After Period of Turmoil, Riverside Church Elects New Leader|last=Otterman|first=Sharon|date=June 8, 2014|work=The New York Times|access-date=July 16, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> During this period, in 2012, the church and its annexes were listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]].<ref name=\"nrhp\" /> \n\n[[Amy Butler (minister)|Amy K. Butler]] was selected as the church's seventh senior minister in June 2014, becoming the first woman to hold that job.<ref name=\"NYT-Butler-2014\" /> In September 2018, it was announced that Riverside would buy the neighboring [[McGiffert Hall]] at Claremont Avenue and 122nd Street for $45 million. The dormitory was located on land that had been donated by John Rockefeller Jr. to the Union Theological Seminary, and under the donation agreement, the church had the [[Right of first refusal|right of first offer]] to buy the building should it ever come up for sale.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2018/09/18/riverside-church-to-buy-neighboring-dorm-for-45m/|title=Riverside Church to buy neighboring dorm for $45M|last=Weiss|first=Lois|date=September 19, 2018|website=New York Post|language=en|access-date=November 11, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://therealdeal.com/2018/09/19/thanks-to-john-d-rockefeller-this-church-beat-out-a-developer-for-a-45m-dorm/|title=Riverside Church {{!}} Union Theological Seminary {{!}} 97 Claremont|date=September 19, 2018|website=The Real Deal New York|language=en-US|access-date=November 11, 2019}}</ref> In July 2019, the church's governing council announced that Butler's contract would not be renewed. At the time, the Church Council and Butler released a joint letter stating that Butler's resignation was mutual. A former church council member later described how Butler was fired after she and several other female staff members had been the victim of sexual harassment by another former council member, Dr. Edward Lowe.<ref name=\"NYT-Butler-2019\">{{cite news|last=Rojas|first=Rick|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/07/11/nyregion/riverside-church-nyc-sexual-harassment.html|title=Pastor's Exit Exposes Cultural Rifts at a Leading Liberal Church|date=July 11, 2019|work=The New York Times|access-date=July 12, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/social-issues/riverside-church-congregants-call-for-reinstatement-of-first-female-minister-after-her-dismissal-following-a-sex-shop-visit/2019/07/14/1c2c23da-a632-11e9-86dd-d7f0e60391e9_story.html|title=Riverside Church congregants call for reinstatement of first female minister after her exit following a sex shop visit|last=Natanson|first=Hannah|date=July 15, 2019|website=The Washington Post|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-29}}</ref> The former council member claimed that despite the Council previously launching an extensive investigation into Lowe's conduct, the Council had not conducted as thorough of an investigation into allegations against Butler before voting to break off contract negotiations.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://baptistnews.com/article/the-stained-glass-cliff-and-the-riverside-church-a-double-standard-for-our-first-female-senior-minister/|title=The stained-glass cliff and the Riverside Church: a double standard for our first female senior minister|date=2019-10-17|website=Baptist News Global|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-26}}</ref> However, media outlets later reported that Butler had taken subordinate staffers to a sex-themed shop during a conference in Minneapolis, and in so doing, bought female subordinates vibrators and waved a church credit card as she paid for the spree.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nypost.com/2019/07/11/pastor-out-at-famed-riverside-church-after-sex-toy-harassment-accusations/|title=Pastor Our at Famed Riverside Church|date=2019-07-11|website=New York Post|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-11}}</ref>\n\n== Design ==\n[[File:Grants Tomb Riverside Church NY1.jpg|thumb|alt=A landscape of Riverside Park; behind the park's trees is the tower of Riverside Church, at center|The tower of Riverside Church (center) rises above the tree-line of [[Riverside Park (Manhattan)|Riverside Park]]. [[Grant's Tomb]] (left) and [[the Interchurch Center]] (right) can also be seen.]]\nRiverside Church takes up a {{Convert|454|x|100|ft|abbr=|adj=on}} lot<ref name=\"NYCL p. 8\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|2000|ps=.|p=8}}</ref> between [[Riverside Drive (Manhattan)|Riverside Drive]] to the west, 122nd Street to the north, [[Claremont Avenue]] to the east, and 120th Street to the south.<ref name=\"Nash 1999\">{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/manhattanskyscra00nash_0|url-access=registration|title=Manhattan skyscrapers|last=Nash|first=Eric|publisher=Princeton Architectural Press|year=1999|isbn=978-1-56898-181-9|location=New York|page=[https://archive.org/details/manhattanskyscra00nash_0/page/69 69]|oclc=40298497}}</ref> Riverside Church's main architects, Henry C. Pelton, Francis R. Allen, and Charles Collens, created the general plan for the church.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 1\" /> Pelton was most involved with tactical planning, while Collens was most involved in the Gothic detail.<ref name=\"Dolkart p. 77\" /> Sculptural elements were designed by [[Robert Garrison (sculptor)|Robert Garrison]] and carried out by local studios such as the [[Piccirilli Brothers]],<ref name=\"NYCL p. 5\" /><ref>{{harvnb|ps=.|Paris et al.|2004|p=148}}</ref> while the interior was designed by [[Burnham Hoyt]].<ref name=\"NYCL p. 6\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|2000|ps=.|p=6}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1960/04/08/archives/burnham-hoyt-73-dies-architect-designed-interior-of-riverside.html|title=Burnham Hoyt, 73, Dies; Architect Designed Interior of Riverside Church|last=|first=|date=April 8, 1960|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 9, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The Martin Luther King Jr. (MLK) Wing to the south of the original building was designed by Collens, Willis & Beckonert, while the Stone Gym to the southeast was designed by Louis E. Jallade.<ref name=\"NPS p. 3\" /> {{As of|2017||df=}}, Riverside Church is the tallest church in the United States (and among the [[List of tallest churches in the world|tallest churches in the world]]),<ref>{{Cite book |last=Levitt |first=Ellen |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=A1y9CQAAQBAJ&pg=PA228 |title=Walking Manhattan: 30 Strolls Exploring Cultural Treasures, Entertainment Centers, and Historical Sites in the Heart of New York City |date=2015-06-30 |publisher=Wilderness Press |isbn=978-0-89997-763-8 |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book |last=Bauman |first=Robert |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=3wOQDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA92 |title=Fighting to Preserve a Nation's Soul: America's Ecumenical War on Poverty |date=2019 |publisher=University of Georgia Press |isbn=978-0-8203-5487-3 |page=92 |language=en}}</ref> with a tower rising {{convert|392|ft}}.<ref name=\"Dolkart p. 77\" /><ref name=\"NYT-Plans-Approved-1926\" /><ref name=\"D&C-Chimes-1928\" />\n\nPelton and Collens chose a [[Gothic architecture|Gothic architectural]] style for Riverside Church's exterior; by contrast, the internal structure incorporated modern [[Curtain wall (architecture)|curtain walls]] and a steel frame.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 5\" /><ref name=\"Dolkart p. 79\">{{harvnb|Dolkart|1998|ps=.|p=79}}</ref> Fosdick later said that the exterior Gothic style was suited to \"make people pray\", and that the church had \"not outgrown Gothic\" in that regard.<ref>{{harvnb|ps=.|Miller|1985|p=211}}</ref> Riverside Church's design is partially derived from France's [[Chartres Cathedral]], but also draws from several Gothic churches in France and Spain.<ref name=\"NYT-Plans-Approved-1926\" /><ref>{{harvnb|Carder|1930|p=9}}; {{harvnb|Dolkart|1998|pp=78&ndash;79}}; {{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|2000|p=5}}; {{harvnb|National Park Service|2012|p=12}}; {{harvnb|Paris et al.|2004|ps=.|p=140}}</ref> Pelton and Collens said that Chartres would provide the \"fundamental principles\" for the design of Riverside Church, but that Chartres and Riverside would have a completely different outline.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 5\" /><ref name=\"Carder p. 9\" /> The features inspired by Chartres included the detailing of the three Riverside Drive entrances, as well as the lack of decorative elements on the facade, except for the stained glass windows on the walls and the sculptural elements around each portal. The massive single bell tower was inspired by the two western towers at Chartres.<ref name=\"NYT-Plans-Approved-1926\" /><ref name=\"NYCL p. 5\" /> The rest of the facade consists of [[Indiana Limestone]].<ref name=\"NYCL p. 8\" />\n\nUpon Riverside Church's completion, its design received both praise and criticism.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 7\" /> ''The American Architect'' published pieces in mid-1931 that featured a critical viewpoint from Columbia architecture professor [[Walter A. Taylor]], and a rebuttal from architect Charles Crane, who had worked on the project with Pelton. While Taylor believed that the design should have been more [[Modernist architecture|modernist]],<ref name=\"Dolkart p. 79\" /><ref>{{cite journal|last=Taylor|first=Walter|date=June 1931|title=A Criticism ... of the Riverside Church|url=|journal=American Architect|volume=139|pages=32|via=}}</ref> Crane defended Pelton's Gothic design as being \"fundamentally Christian\".<ref name=\"Dolkart p. 79\" /><ref>{{cite journal|last=Crane|first=Charles|date=July 1931|title=Why We Made It Gothic|url=|journal=American Architect|volume=140|pages=26|via=}}</ref> The writers of the 1939 ''[[American Guide Series|WPA Guide]] to New York City'' said that the tower's features make the \"building itself seem smaller than it is, so that its scale is scarcely impressive, even when seen at close range.\"<ref name=\"WPA1939\">{{cite fednyc|pages=387\u2013389}}</ref> Other critics called the building's exterior overly opulent,<ref name=\"AIA5\">{{Cite aia5|page=505}}</ref> and one critic stated that when considered along the progressive ideology, the Gothic design \"can only be interpreted as an outward confession that religion is dead.\"<ref name=\"Dolkart p. 80\" /> Conversely, ''[[The New York Sun]]'' referred to the building as among the \"most outstanding additions\" to New York City's [[church architecture]] \"in recent years\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=|title=The Churches of New York, No. 26: Riverside|last=|first=|date=May 16, 1931|work=New York Sun|access-date=|page=7}}</ref> Eric Nash, in his book ''Manhattan Skyscrapers'', called Riverside Church \"Manhattan's last great eclectic skyscraper\",<ref name=\"Nash 1999\" /> while the ''[[AIA Guide to New York City]]'' dubbed the church \"easily the most prominent architectural work along the [[Hudson River|Hudson (River)]] from [[Midtown Manhattan|midtown]] to the [[George Washington Bridge]]\".<ref name=\"AIA5\" />\n\n== Architectural features ==\n\n=== Main building ===\nThe main structure is centered around the church's [[nave]], which is aligned on a north\u2013south axis, closer to Riverside Avenue on the western portion of the block. The [[chapel]] and [[narthex]] are located to the south, closer to 120th Street, while the [[chancel]] (which contains the altar) and [[ambulatory]] are located to the north, closer to 122nd Street.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 8\" />\n\n==== Facade ====\n[[File:The Riverside Church.jpg|thumb|The northern [[facade]] of Riverside Church, seen from 122nd Street at the eastern side of the [[ambulatory]]]]\nThe western facade of the nave runs along Riverside Drive.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 8\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 4\" /> At the time of Riverside Church's construction, the church did not own the lots along 120th Street to the south. As a result, the three entrances are on the west, facing Riverside Drive, rather than at the back of the nave to the south, as in other churches. The entrances are located atop a small flight of steps leading from the street.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 5\" /><ref name=\"Carder p. 5\" /> The west-facing main entrance, below the tower's base, is through a set of double wooden doors with recessed wooden panel.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 8\" /> The figures sculpted in the concentric [[archivolt]]s of the doorway represent leading religious, scientific, and philosophical figures, while an elaborate [[Tympanum (architecture)|tympanum]] is located below the arches (see {{Section link||Sculpted elements}}).<ref name=\"NYCL p. 5\" /><ref name=\"Paris et al. pp. 155-156\">{{harvnb|Paris et al.|2004|ps=.|pp=155\u2013156}}</ref> To the south is the entrance to the narthex, which contains a single door.<ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 156\" /> Directly south of the narthex entrance is another double-door entrance leads to the chapel,<ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 156\">{{harvnb|Paris et al.|2004|ps=.|p=156}}</ref><ref name=\"NPS p. 15\">{{harvnb|National Park Service|2012|ps=.|p=15}}</ref> and contains two archivolts and a simpler tympanum.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 8\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 4\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 15\" /> The northern portion of the western facade, adjacent to the nave, contains five sets of windows (see {{Section link||Nave}}).<ref name=\"NYCL p. 6\" /><ref name=\"Carder p. 18\" />\n\nThe view of the southern facade is mostly blocked by the MLK Wing to the south. The top portions of four narrow, arched stained-glass windows can be seen above the hip roof of the structure that connects the two sections. Above these stained glass windows are three recessed, arched windows topped by a pediment containing a circular window.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 8\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 4\" />\n\nThe eastern facade is similar to the western facade, in that it also has five groupings of windows facing the nave.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 6\" /><ref name=\"Carder p. 18\" /> However, much of this facade is blocked by McGiffert Hall, which faces directly onto Claremont Avenue and 122nd Street.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 9\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 6\">{{harvnb|National Park Service|2012|ps=.|p=6}}</ref> On the eastern facade of the nave is a cloistered passageway leading to Claremont Avenue (see {{Section link||Cloister passageway}}).<ref name=\"NPS p. 3\" /><ref name=\"NYCL p. 9\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|2000|ps=.|p=9}}</ref> A rose window is located on the eastern facade above the cloister section.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 8\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 4\" />\n\nThe northern facade surrounds the chancel and ambulatory. An arched entrance called the \"Woman's Porch\" is located in the western (left) portion of the north facade and contains carvings of biblical women. Above the entrance arch is an ornate [[belt course]], followed by two lancet windows.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 9\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 5\">{{harvnb|National Park Service|2012|ps=.|p=5}}</ref> Another entrance is located in the eastern (right) portion of the north facade.<ref name=\"NPS p. 5\" /> Between the two entrances is the ambulatory, with two tiers of window groupings, each with a rose window above a pair of lancet windows. The lower section has three sets of windows, while the upper [[clerestory]] section has five sets of windows. Vertical [[buttress]]es, which separate each window grouping, end in [[finial]]s above the roofline.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 9\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 5\" />\n\n==== Nave ====\n[[File:Interior of Riverside Church 01.JPG|thumb|The [[nave]] (foreground) looking toward the [[chancel]] (background)]]\nThe nave takes a Gothic model inspired by France's [[Albi Cathedral]],<ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 147\">{{harvnb|Paris et al.|2004|ps=.|p=147}}</ref> and measures {{Convert|100|ft||abbr=}} high by {{Convert|89|ft||abbr=}} wide and {{Convert|215|ft||abbr=}} long.<ref name=\"NPS p. 7\">{{harvnb|National Park Service|2012|ps=.|p=7}}</ref> The width between the overhanging clerestory walls is {{Convert|60|ft||abbr=}}.<ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 147\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 7\" /><ref name=\"Dolkart p. 79\" /> The low and wide form of the nave is inspired by southern French and Spanish churches.<ref name=\"Dolkart pp. 78-79\">{{harvnb|Dolkart|1998|ps=.|pp=78&ndash;79}}</ref> The nave contains a metal roof, whose base is surrounded by a shallow [[Arcade (architecture)|arcade]].<ref name=\"NYCL p. 8\" /> Its interior contains an Indiana limestone finish, while the ceilings of its vaults are lined with [[Guastavino tile|Guastavino terracotta tiles]], and its floor is made of marble.<ref name=\"NPS p. 7\" />\n\nThe nave's western and eastern walls comprise three main vertical sections, which are split by buttresses.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 8\" /> Along the bottom portion of the nave (adjacent to the aisles), there are five architectural bays each on the western and eastern walls, with each bay containing a pointed-arch window.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 6\" /><ref name=\"Carder p. 18\">{{harvnb|Carder|1930|ps=.|p=18}}</ref><ref name=\"NPS p. 8\">{{harvnb|National Park Service|2012|ps=.|p=8}}</ref> Above the stained-glass windows, each bay contains a [[triforium]] gallery with three [[colonette]]s, followed by two adjacent [[lancet window]]s in the [[clerestory]], and topped by a [[rose window]].<ref name=\"NYCL p. 8\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 8\" /><ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 170\" /> Pointed arches, resting on piers that contain [[engaged column]]s, support each of the clerestory bays as well as serve as the bases for the [[Rib vault|ribs]] under the vaulted ceiling.<ref name=\"NPS p. 7\" /> The engaged columns are surmounted by [[Corinthian order|Corinthian capitals]] that are decorated with scenes from the [[Book of Jeremiah]]. The ceilings of the vaults underneath the triforium galleries are faced with Guastavino tile,<ref name=\"NPS p. 8\" /> and contain lighting.<ref name=\"NPS p. 9\">{{harvnb|National Park Service|2012|ps=.|p=9}}</ref>[[File:Riverside Narthex.jpg|thumb|View of the galleries above the [[nave]], looking south. The sculpture at the back wall can be seen, while the [[Riverside Church#Organ|Trompeta Majestatis organ]] on the eastern wall can be seen at left.|alt=|left]]The ceiling of the nave, above the clerestory, is eight stories high.<ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 151\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 13\">{{harvnb|National Park Service|2012|ps=.|p=13}}</ref> It consists of several vaults, which are each divided into four segments by diagonally interlocking [[transverse rib]]s, which do not provide structural support.<ref name=\"NPS p. 8\" /> Eight iron lanterns hang from the transverse ribs and descend to below the level of the triforium gallery.<ref name=\"NPS p. 9\" /> The vaults contain a finish of acoustic Guastavino tiles, which are mostly gray.<ref name=\"NPS p. 8\" /> The tiles above the chancel and the nave's northernmost two bays are brown, because a sealant was applied in that section in 1953 to increase the acoustical reach of the organ, and had turned yellow over time.<ref name=\"NPS p. 9\" />\n\nThe nave was built with a [[seating capacity]] of either 2,408<ref name=\"NYT-Pew-Phones-1930\" /> or 2,500.<ref name=\"Dolkart p. 77\" /> The ground level contains 38 rows of pews, made of oak wood with Gothic decoration, although five additional rows of pews used to exist at the front of the nave.<ref name=\"NPS p. 9\" /> Two seating galleries overhang the back (southern portion) of the nave.<ref name=\"NPS p. 9\" /><ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 151\">{{harvnb|Paris et al.|2004|ps=.|p=151}}</ref> The lower gallery is made of carved wood, with rows of oak pews on a downward slope, and contains a wooden ceiling with nine lamps. The upper gallery is also made of carved wood and contains oak pews on a slope, but does not contain a canopy above it.<ref name=\"NPS p. 10\">{{harvnb|National Park Service|2012|ps=.|p=10}}</ref> The upper gallery is illuminated with four lanterns, similar to the eight above the main section of the nave. Behind the southern wall are six double-tiered niches with stone sculptures of ministers and [[Jacob Epstein]]'s ''Christ in Majesty'' sculpture. The [[Riverside Church#Organ|Trompeta Majestatis organ]] projects from the wall beneath the niches.<ref name=\"NPS p. 11\">{{harvnb|National Park Service|2012|ps=.|p=11}}</ref>\n\n==== Chancel, ambulatory, and apse ====\n[[File:Riverside Apse.jpg|thumb|The [[chancel]], seen from toward the front of the [[nave]]. The chancel screen is located in the background while the choir stalls are in front of the screen. The [[Eucharist|communion]] table, [[Immersion baptism|baptismal]] pool, and altar can be seen in front of the chancel screen's central bay.]]\nThe chancel is located directly to the north of the nave and is raised by a few steps. A limestone railing with 20 [[quatrefoil]] medallions separates the chancel and the nave. The western portion of the rail contains a [[pulpit]] with a wooden canopy and three carved limestone blocks.<ref name=\"NPS p. 9\" /><ref>{{harvnb|Paris et al.|2004|ps=.|p=159}}</ref> A [[labyrinth]] composed of three types of marble, inspired by a similar design at Chartres Cathedral, is inlaid in the middle of the chancel floor. Flanking the labyrinth on either side are four rows of choir stalls, made of oak with carvings of [[Psalms]] texts.<ref name=\"NPS p. 9\" /><ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 162\">{{harvnb|Paris et al.|2004|ps=.|p=162}}</ref> Behind the choir stalls (to the north) is the organ console.<ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 162\" /> A [[communion table]] of [[Caen stone]] is located toward the back of the chancel, in the center. A [[baptism]]al pool is located behind the communion table.<ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 162\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 10\" />\n\nThe back of the chancel contains a convex polygonal wall. The wall includes seven bays, each with three vertical tiers that are a few feet above the corresponding tiers in the nave. The bottom tier contains pointed arches with [[Riverside Church#Chancel screen|an elaborate stone chancel screen]]; the middle tier contains [[arch#Type of arches|cusped arches]] with colonettes; and the top tier serves as the clerestory.<ref name=\"NPS p. 9\" /> The three center bays behind the chancel screen each contain one window group on the lower tier. These window groups each contain two lancet windows topped by a rose window, and are divided by vertical buttresses. The apse clerestory, the upper section of the ambulatory, is recessed slightly inward. The upper section's [[Fenestration (architecture)|fenestration]] is similar in form, in that it each window grouping contains a rose window above a pair of lancet windows, but the window groupings are located on five sides of the polygon.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 9\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 5\" /> The vertical piers of the chancel wall converge above the clerestory level, creating an [[apse]] above the chancel and ambulatory.<ref name=\"NPS p. 10\" />\n\n==== Narthex ====\n[[File:Riverside Church, New York City (2014) - 16.JPG|alt=|left|thumb|The chapel, facing the altar]]\nThe narthex, designed in the late Gothic style with a [[Romanesque architecture|Romanesque]] layout,<ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 156\" /> is located directly south of the nave and can be accessed from the church's West Portal. The narthex is split into four vaults with [[Guastavino tile]]d ceilings, supported by simple limestone columns.<ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 156\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 7\" /> A stone spiral staircase on the west side of the narthex, directly south of the West Portal, leads down to the basement.<ref name=\"NPS p. 7\" /> There are two [[grisaille]] windows and one rose window on each of the western and eastern sides of the narthex.<ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 170\" /> The eastern wall contains four 16th-century lancet windows, previously located in the Park Avenue Baptist Church and were the only windows in Riverside Church not built specifically for the church.<ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 156\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 8\" /> Stairs leading both upward and downward are located on the eastern side of the narthex, while a mortuary chapel is located on the northeastern corner.<ref name=\"NPS p. 8\" /> The mortuary chapel is known as the [[Gethsemane|Gethsemane Chapel]], but prior to 1959 was called the Christ Chapel.<ref name=\"NPS p. 7\" />{{efn|There are two chapels that have been known as the Christ Chapel: the mortuary chapel, which was once known as the Christ Chapel, and the main chapel, which was the second to receive the name Christ Chapel.<ref>{{harvnb|ps=.|National Park Service|2012|pp=7\u20138}}</ref>|name=\"Christ Chapel\"}}\n\n==== Chapel ====\nThe chapel to the south of the narthex, known since 1959 as the Christ Chapel,<ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 156\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 11\" />{{efn||name=\"Christ Chapel\"}} was inspired by the [[Basilica of Saints Nazarius and Celsus]] in France.<ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 156\" /> Its design was inspired by [[Carcassonne Cathedral]]'s pointed [[Romanesque architecture|Romanesque]] nave. Described by architectural historian [[Andrew Dolkart]] as \"earlier than Gothic\", the design is intended to give the impression that the rest of the sanctuary was built after the chapel.<ref name=\"Dolkart p. 79\" /> The chapel is subdivided into four bays and has a [[Barrel vault|barrel-vaulted]] ceiling with Guastavino tiles, while the walls and floor contain a limestone finish. The southern wall, adjacent to the MLK Wing, contains four arched, back-lit stained-glass windows, one in each bay. Double doors to the west lead to Riverside Drive while a passage to the south leads to the MLK Wing.<ref name=\"NPS p. 11\" /> There are [[engaged column]]s on the north and south walls between each of the four bays, as well as eight lanterns hanging from the columns.<ref name=\"NPS p. 12\" /> \n\nThe eastern end of the chapel contains an [[altar]], located four steps above the main level of the chapel. There is a [[lectern]] to the right of the altar and a pulpit to the left.<ref name=\"NPS p. 12\" /><ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 158\">{{harvnb|Paris et al.|2004|ps=.|p=158}}</ref> Several sculpted representations are located above the altar.<ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 158\" /> A baptismal pool and a [[reredos]] are located behind the altar, through an arched opening, while an alcove to the narthex is located to the left (north) of the altar.<ref name=\"NPS p. 12\" />\n\n{{Clear left}}\n\n=== Tower and carillon ===\n[[File:Riverside Church Belltower at dusk (5328618641).jpg|thumb|The tower, seen from the east]]\n\nThe {{Convert|392|ft||abbr=|adj=on}} tower was named after [[Laura Spelman Rockefeller]], the mother of John D. Rockefeller Jr.<ref name=\"Dolkart p. 77\" /><ref name=\"NYT-Plans-Approved-1926\" /><ref name=\"D&C-Chimes-1928\" /> The tower contains 21 usable floors, which include 80 classrooms and office rooms.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 7\" /><ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 149\">{{harvnb|Paris et al.|2004|ps=.|p=149}}</ref> There are four elevators in the tower, two that rise only to the 10th floor, and two that go to the 20th floor.<ref name=\"NPS p. 12\" /><ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 149\" /> The 20-floor-tall elevators, rising {{Convert|355|ft||abbr=}}, were described in 1999 as the world's tallest elevators inside a church.<ref name=\"Nash 1999\" /> Two staircases ascend from ground level: one on the western side of the tower, which ends at the ninth floor, and one on the eastern side, which continues to the carillon.<ref name=\"NPS p. 12\" /> Balconies are located at either southern corner on the 8th floor, and on all sides of the 10th floor except the north side.<ref name=\"NPS p. 13\" />\n\nOn the western elevation of the tower's base is the main entrance, flanked by projecting vertical [[Pier (architecture)|piers]] (see {{Section link||Facade}}). Seven arched niches, each containing statues of kings, are located above the main entrance. A large rose window is located above the statuary grouping.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 8\" /> The top of the tower is fitted with [[aircraft warning lights]].<ref name=\"Nash 1999\" /> Above the tenth floor, there are five tiers of window arrangements on each floor, with higher tiers being progressively narrower. From bottom to top, the successive tiers contain 2, 4, 3, 4, and 5 windows on each side. There are narrow canopied niches in each corner of the tower, with one statue inside each niche. At the top of the tower is a conical metal roof.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 9\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 5\" />\n\n==== Tower stories ====\nMost of the tower's stories consist of plaster floors, steel doors, steel window frames, and iron lighting fixtures hanging from each ceiling. There are elevator lobbies with vaulted ceilings on several stories of the tower. On the stories that contain common spaces, including the 9th and 10th floors, the floors are finished with stone, [[terrazzo]], and wood, with wooden doors. Over the years, several spaces have been used by outside entities, who carpeted floors and installed fluorescent lighting fixtures in some office rooms.<ref name=\"NPS p. 13\" />\n\nOriginally, the 4th through 14th floors held Riverside Church's school, while the 15th floor and above contained various staff and clergy offices, as well as spaces for group activities.<ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 151\" /> The 2nd floor connects to the nave's lower seating gallery, while the 3rd floor leads to the upper seating gallery. The 4th through 8th floors are located below the height of the nave's ceiling, and contained the nursery, junior high, and high school departments of the church's school. The 9th and 10th floors included the double-story school kitchen, school offices, and storage rooms over the nave.<ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 151\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 13\" /> The 9th floor also includes a library and wooden furniture in both the kitchen and library.<ref name=\"NPS p. 13\" /> The main structure's roof is located above the 10th floor, and the tower rises independently above that point.<ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 151\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 13\" /> The 11th through 14th floors originally contained the church's elementary school, while the 15th and 16th floors respectively contained the young people's meeting room and the social room.<ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 151\" /> These were later converted into office space, with several floors subdivided and leased out.<ref name=\"NPS p. 13\" /> The 17th through 20th floors include meeting rooms, though the 17th floor also contains offices. The 21st floor includes the carilloneur's studio, and the 22nd floor is devoted to mechanical space.<ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 151\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 13\" />\n\n==== Carillon ====\nThe 23rd floor of the tower contains a three-level [[Belfry (architecture)|belfry]].<ref name=\"NPS p. 12\" /> The belfry houses a [[carillon]] whose final complement of 74&nbsp;bronze bells, at the time of construction the largest carillon of bells in the world, includes the 20-ton, {{Convert|122|in|m|-diameter|abbr=|adj=mid}} [[bourdon (bell)|bourdon]], the world's largest tuned bell.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 7\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/03/23/nyregion/restoring-the-spirit-with-the-sound-of-big-bells-high-over-manhattan.html|title=Restoring the Spirit With the Sound of Big Bells High Over Manhattan|last=Barron|first=James|date=March 22, 2015|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 8, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Though other carillons with more bells have been commissioned,{{efn|The carillon at Hyechon College in [[Daejeon]], South Korea, contains 78 bells.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.carillon.org/eng/dynamic_frame_eng.htm?https://www.carillon.org/eng/actueel/taejon_1.htm |title=World Carillon Federation - Hyechon College |website=www.carillon.org |access-date=March 1, 2020}}</ref> [[Kirk in the Hills]] in [[Bloomfield Township, Oakland County, Michigan]], contains 77 bells.<ref>{{Cite book |last=Rombouts |first=Luc |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jQ-RCAAAQBAJ&pg=PA287 |title=Singing Bronze: A History of Carillon Music |date=2014-05-23 |publisher=Leuven University Press |isbn=978-90-5867-956-7 |page=287 |language=en}}</ref>}} Riverside Church's carillon is still the largest in the world by aggregate weight: the bells and associated mechanisms weight a combined {{Convert|500,000|lb|kg|abbr=}}.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 7\" /><ref name=\"AIA5\" /> Of the carillon's bells, 53 were made for the original Park Avenue church by English founders [[Gillett & Johnston]].<ref name=\"D&C-Chimes-1928\" /><ref name=\"NYCL p. 7\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 13\" /> Another 19 were made for Riverside Church when it opened,<ref name=\"NYCL p. 7\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 13\" /> and two additional bells were added in 1955, whereupon 58 treble bells were replaced by bell founders Van Bergen.<ref name=\"NPS p. 13\" /> The bells were replaced again by [[Whitechapel Bell Foundry]] in 2004.<ref name=\"NPS p. 13\" /> The bells can reportedly be heard from a distance of up to {{Convert|8|mi||abbr=}}.<ref name=\"NYT-Carillon-1931\" /><ref name=\"NYCL p. 7\" />\n\nA mechanical power room and control room are located in the belfry, while the clavier cabin is located at the top, above the carillon.<ref name=\"NPS p. 14\">{{harvnb|National Park Service|2012|ps=.|p=14}}</ref> Due to the weight of the carillon, the heaviest steel beams used in the construction of Riverside Church were used in the tower. The north facade, which overhangs the nave, is supported by a single cross truss that weighs {{Convert|60|ST|LT t|abbr=}}.<ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 149\" /> Outside the carillon, the facade of the tower contains ornate Neo-Gothic detailing, with features such as [[gargoyle]]s.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 9\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 5\" /> There was also a public observation deck on top of the carillon.<ref name=\"AIA5\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 14\" /> The deck was closed after the [[September 11 attacks|September 11, 2001, attacks]] due to security concerns,<ref name=\"AIA5\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 14\" /> but the church resumed tours in January 2020.<ref>{{cite web | last=Clark | first=Roger | title=Riverside Church Bell Tower Tours Return | publisher=Spectrum News NY1 | date=January 6, 2020 | url=https://www.ny1.com/nyc/all-boroughs/news/2020/01/06/riverside-church-bell-tower-tours-return | access-date=February 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n=== Cloister passageway ===\nThe cloister passageway leads from the southern portion of the nave to Claremont Avenue in the east. It contains four pointed-arch bays, each with a Corinthian-style colonette topped by a [[grisaille]] window opening on the south wall.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 9\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 6\" /> The north and south walls also contain stained-glass windows, though the north wall's windows are artificially illuminated. Inside the cloister passageway are five vaults, illuminated by six lanterns.<ref name=\"NPS p. 14\" /> The entrance to the passageway is a small two-story structure with two arched doorways facing Claremont Avenue, and a set of double doors facing a short wheelchair ramp to the south. The top of the cloister entrance's eastern facade contains three niches with figures of [[Theological virtues|Faith, Hope, and Charity]], while the southeast corner contains a figure of [[Maaseiah]].<ref name=\"NPS p. 6\" /><ref name=\"NYCL p. 10\">{{harvnb|Landmarks Preservation Commission|2000|ps=.|p=10}}</ref> There is also a gift shop adjacent to the cloister passageway, while sculptures of the architects and builder are located above the doorway leading to the tower's base.<ref name=\"NPS p. 14\" />\n\n=== Martin Luther King Jr. Wing ===\n[[File:Riverside Church at dusk.jpg|thumb|Seen from Riverside Drive; the MLK Wing is located on the right, south of the tower]]\nThe Martin Luther King Jr. (MLK) Wing is a seven-story annex located to the south of the main structure, facing 120th Street along the southern boundary of the plot.<ref name=\"NYDN-Wing-1959\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 14\" /> The MLK Wing is shaped like an \"L\", with the longer arm running north\u2013south adjacent to Riverside Drive, and the shorter arm running west\u2013east next to 120th Street. It connects to the original church building to the north and the Stone Gym to the east. The area between the MLK Wing and the cloister form a small courtyard or [[Garth (architecture)|garth]], which is enclosed on the east by a metal fence.<ref name=\"NPS p. 14\" /> Inside are children's chapels, space for the school, a rooftop recreation area, space for a radio station, community areas such as a gymnasium and assembly room, and a basement with a parking lot.<ref name=\"Dolkart p. 83\" /><ref name=\"NYDN-Wing-1959\" /><ref name=\"NYT-South-1959\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1959/11/23/archives/riverside-church-to-dedicate-wing-south-structure-will-house-school.html|title=Riverside Church to Dedicate Wing; South Structure Will House School, Nursery, Theatre and Radio Station|last=Wicklein|first=John|date=November 23, 1959|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 9, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nThe structure, designed by Collens, Willis and Beckonert and built by Vermilea-Brown,<ref name=\"Dolkart p. 83\" /><ref name=\":1\" /> is a simplified version of Allen and Collens' original church design and was perceived as being \"modern Gothic\".<ref name=\":1\">{{harvnb|Paris et al.|2004|ps=.|p=174}}</ref> It was known simply as the South Wing until 1985, when it was renamed for civil rights leader [[Martin Luther King Jr.]].<ref name=\"NPS p. 3\" /><ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 175\" />\n\n==== Facade ====\nThe facade is clad with Indiana limestone, while the foundation is made of stone and concrete, and the structure is supported by a steel frame. The main entrance is through the chapel doors on Riverside Drive to the west, and there are also entrances to the basement from 120th Street.<ref name=\"NPS p. 14\" /> The basement through second floors of the western facade contains eight architectural bays, each with one small lancet window, which are recessed between projecting buttresses and located under a set of arches. The two outermost bays project slightly outward and do not contain recessed arches. The section of the MLK Wing above the second floor is [[Setback (architecture)|set back]] from Riverside Drive, and the windows on the third through sixth floors are also recessed between buttressed arches, while the seventh-floor windows are flush with the buttresses. The two outermost bays contain two sets of windows instead of a single window on each floor, and project slightly outward.<ref name=\"NPS p. 15\" />\n\nThe southern and eastern facades are designed in a similar fashion to the upper portion of the western facade, in that the seventh-floor windows are flush with the buttresses, while the windows below are located in recessed arched bays. The southern facade contains eight window bays, six of which are recessed. There are no windows into the first or second floors on the westernmost four bays of the southern facade, but the eastern four bays do contain windows into these floors. On the far eastern portion of the southern facade are two pointed-arched openings that lead to the church's underground parking garage (see {{Section link||Basement}}).<ref name=\"NPS p. 16\">{{harvnb|National Park Service|2012|ps=.|p=16}}</ref> The eastern facade is separated into two sections. The section at the end of the \"L\"'s shorter arm contains four recessed window bays. The section next to the north\u2013south axis of the \"L\" contains six window bays, four of which are recessed.<ref name=\"NPS p. 16\" />\n\n==== Interior ====\nThe northern arm of the MLK Wing's first floor includes the South Hall Lobby, which includes a two-story-high [[coffer|coffered ceiling]] supported by a pointed-arch [[Arcade (architecture)|arcade]], as well as walls made of gray plaster. An elevator bank and an auditorium called the South Hall are located south of the lobby. The South Hall's walls are made of wood paneling below limestone, and nine stained-glass lancet windows on the western side. Two mezzanine levels below the South Hall's ceiling are located to the east of the auditorium, while a sealed tunnel leading to [[the Interchurch Center]] across 120th Street is also accessible from the auditorium.<ref name=\"NPS p. 17\">{{harvnb|National Park Service|2012|ps=.|p=17}}</ref>\n\nThe third through seventh floors include classrooms, except for the fifth floor, which contains offices.<ref name=\"NYDN-Wing-1959\" /><ref name=\"NYT-South-1959\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 17\" /> The floors are made of [[terrazzo]] in the hallways and [[resilient flooring]] in the individual rooms (except for the fifth floor rooms, which contain carpeted rooms), and each level contains [[dropped ceiling]]s.<ref name=\"NPS p. 17\" /> Chapels for children are located on the third floor's southwest corner and on the sixth floor's southern side.<ref name=\"NYDN-Wing-1959\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 17\" /> The roof contains a [[Terrace (building)|solarium]] and a play area.<ref name=\"NYDN-Wing-1959\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 18\">{{harvnb|National Park Service|2012|ps=.|p=18}}</ref>\n\n=== Stone Gym ===\n[[File:Riverside Church 007.JPG|thumb|Stone Gym (center), MLK Wing (left), and tower (center-right)]]\nThe Stone Gymnasium is a {{Frac|1|1|2}}-story [[English Gothic architecture|English Gothic]] building located at 120th Street and Claremont Avenue, east of the Martin Luther King Jr. Wing. The gym was built in 1912 to a design by [[Louis E. Jallade]] and originally was used by the Union Theological Seminary. Its architectural details include a facade of schist with limestone decoration, as well as a metal hip roof.<ref name=\"NPS p. 3\" /> The structure measures five bays long on the eastern facade and one bay wide on the southern and northern facades.<ref name=\"NPS p. 18\" /> In 1957, Rockefeller donated the building to the church, and five years later, it reopened as a [[gym]]nasium and community facility.<ref name=\"NPS p. 3\" /><ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 255\" /> The interior contains a basketball court with synthetic flooring, as well as offices and lockers in its northern end.<ref name=\"NPS p. 3\" />\n\n=== Basement ===\nRiverside Church's basement includes several modern amenities such as a 250-seat [[movie theater]] and a gymnasium with a full-size [[basketball court]].<ref name=\"Nash 1999\" /> The section of the basement under the nave contains a double-height ceiling; an assembly hall is located on the south side of this space, while the gymnasium is located on the north side. The assembly hall includes a stone floor and stone walls, with six arched stained-glass windows on the eastern wall and one rectangular stained glass window on the south wall, as well as cabinets that contain two [[Heinrich Hofmann (painter)|Heinrich Hofmann]] paintings (see {{Section link||Paintings}}). It also contains a wooden ceiling supported by stone arches, with lanterns suspended from the ceiling; and a stage in the northern portion. A kitchen is located east of the stage, and a corridor runs adjacent to the western wall of the assembly room and gymnasium.<ref name=\"NPS p. 12\" />\n\nThe basement also originally included a four-lane [[bowling alley]] adjacent to the assembly floor.<ref name=\"Nash 1999\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 12\" /> It was later removed<ref name=\"Nash 1999\" /> and converted into storage space.<ref name=\"NPS p. 12\" /> There is also a two-story parking lot<ref name=\"Dolkart p. 83\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 17\" /> with 150 spaces underneath the MLK Wing.<ref name=\"NYDN-Wing-1959\" /><ref name=\"Nash 1999\" />\n\n== Organs {{anchor|Organ}} ==\nThere are two organs in Riverside Church: one in the chancel and the other in the seating gallery.<ref name=\"NYCAGO\" /> The chancel organ is the 14th&nbsp;largest in the world {{as of|2017|lc=y}}.<ref name=\"Abdolhamidi 2017\">{{cite web|url=https://untappedcities.com/2017/01/24/the-top-10-secrets-of-nycs-riverside-church/|title=The Top 10 Secrets of NYC's Riverside Church|last=Abdolhamidi|first=Shervin|date=January 24, 2017|website=Untapped New York|access-date=November 8, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://nyc-architecture.com/HAR/HAR009.htm |title=New York Architecture - Riverside Church |website=nyc-architecture.com |access-date=March 1, 2020}}</ref> [[Hook and Hastings]] furnished the original chancel organ in 1930,<ref name=\"NYCAGO\">{{cite web|url=http://www.nycago.org/Organs/NYC/html/RiversideChurch.html#AeolianSkinner1118C|title=The Riverside Church|website=New York City Chapter of the American Guild of Organists|access-date=November 17, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 319\">{{harvnb|Paris et al.|2004|ps=.|p=319}}</ref> though it was originally criticized as being mediocre.<ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 319\" /> [[Aeolian-Skinner]] built an [[organ console]] in the chancel in 1948 and replaced the chancel organ in 1953\u20131954.<ref name=\"NYCAGO\" /> At this time, the ceiling above the chancel and the front of the nave was coated with sealant to improve the chancel's acoustic qualities.<ref name=\"NPS p. 9\" /> Another Aeolian-Skinner organ was installed in 1964 within the eastern wall of the nave's seating gallery, and three years later, Anthony A. Bufano installed a five-manual console for the gallery organ.<ref name=\"NYCAGO\" /> [[M. P. Moller]] built another organ for the gallery, the Trompeta Majestatis, in 1978.<ref name=\"NPS p. 11\" /><ref name=\"NYCAGO\" /> Two years later, the chancel received a new principal chorus, with the addition of the Grand Chorus division. In the 1990s, the console was rewired, the chancel organ was cleaned, and the ceiling was covered with ten sealant layers.<ref name=\"NYCAGO\" />\n\nThe Director of Music and organist is Christopher Johnson {{as of|2019|lc=y}}.<ref>{{cite web | title=2019 Summer Organ Series | website=Riverside Church | date=May 7, 2019 | url=https://www.trcnyc.org/2019summerorganseries/ | access-date=November 18, 2019}}</ref> Past organists at the Riverside Church have included [[Virgil Fox]] (1946\u20131965),<ref>{{harvnb|Paris et al.|2004|ps=.|p=320}}</ref> [[Frederick Swann]] (1957\u20131982),<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/08/04/arts/music/04swan.html|title=Frederick Swann at Riverside Church: A Master of the Organ, With the Curtain Pulled Back|last=Schweitzer|first=Vivien|date=August 4, 2006|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 11, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> [[John Walker (organist)|John Walker]] (1979\u20131992),<ref>{{harvnb|Paris et al.|2004|ps=.|p=322}}</ref> and Timothy Smith (1992\u20132008).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.columbia.edu/cu/earl/music_organist.html|title=Music at St. Paul's|work=Office of the University Chaplain|publisher=[[Columbia University]]|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081229164907/http://www.columbia.edu/cu/earl/music_organist.html|archivedate=December 29, 2008|accessdate=April 9, 2009}}</ref>\n\n== Art and sculpture ==\n\n=== Paintings ===\n[[File:Christ in Gethsemane.jpg|thumb|[[Heinrich Hofmann (painter)|Heinrich Hofmann]], ''[[Agony in the Garden|Christ in Gethsemane]]'', 1886]]\nRiverside Church contains paintings by [[Heinrich Hofmann (painter)|Heinrich Hofmann]] that were purchased by Rockefeller Jr. and donated to the church in November 1930.<ref name=\"NYT-Paintings-1930\" />  ''Christ in the Temple'' (1871) and ''Christ and the Young Rich Man'' (1889) are located in the assembly hall beneath the nave and are usually locked within the cabinets there.<ref name=\"NPS p. 12\">{{harvnb|National Park Service|2012|ps=.|p=12}}</ref> A copy of ''Christ in Gethsemane'' (1890) is located in the Gethsemane chapel.<ref name=\"NPS p. 7\" />\n\n=== Stained glass ===\nRiverside Church's main building contains 51 [[stained glass]] windows, excluding smaller grisaille windows.<ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 170\">{{harvnb|Paris et al.|2004|ps=.|pp=170, 172}} For a diagram showing the layout of the windows, see {{harvnb|Paris et al.|2004|ps=.|p=173}}</ref> These were created in a mosaic style, which was becoming more popular at the time of the church's construction.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 6\" /> Of these, 34 windows are located in the nave, most of which contain religious iconography. Generally, the \"richer\"-colored windows were located on the western side, considered the \"light\" side, while the more muted colors were located on the eastern \"dark\" side.<ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 170\" />\n\nTwo French glassmakers, Jacques Simon from [[Reims Cathedral]] and Charles Lorin from Chartres Cathedral, were hired to create the glass for the clerestory windows in the nave.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 6\" /><ref name=\"Carder p. 18\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 8\" />   Lorin designed the stained-glass windows on the western side of the clerestory while Simon designed the windows on the eastern side. Both sets of windows depict general religious and government themes, and they incorporate secular iconography as well as depictions of non-Christians.<ref name=\"NPS p. 8\" /> The clerestory windows closely resemble those at Chartres, and contain a rose with [[lancet window]]s.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 6\" /><ref name=\"Carder p. 18\" /> The other windows in the nave were created by [[Reynolds, Francis and Rohnstock]], a [[Boston]]-based firm, and depict over 138 scenes from both religious and non-religious contexts.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 6\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 8\" /> The three groups of stained glass windows in the apse were created by [[Harry Wright Goodhue]],<ref name=\"NYCL p. 6\" /> as were the nine stained glass windows in the South Hall.<ref name=\"NPS p. 17\" />\n\n=== Mosaics ===\n[[Gregor T. Goethals]] created two mosaics for the fourth and seventh floors of the MLK Wing. The fourth-floor mosaic shows the [[Old Testament]] while the seventh-floor mosaic shows the Creation.<ref name=\"NPS p. 17\" />\n\n=== Sculpted elements ===\n\n==== Exterior elements ====\n[[File:Riverside Church doorway (4684840329).jpg|thumb|Front doorway at the base of the tower. At the bottom are [[archivolt]]s (directly under the arch), [[Tympanum (architecture)|tympanum]], and [[jamb]]s (bottom, to either side of the doors). At the top is the circular [[rose window]], and niches with the sculptures of [[King of Rome#Kings of Rome (753\u2013509 BC)|seven kings]]]]\nThe most prominent sculptural details are located on the Riverside Drive facade. The main entrance, located beneath the tower, is topped by five concentric [[archivolt]]s, with sculptures of [[Jesus]]'s [[Followers of Christ|followers]] and [[Prophets of Christianity|prophets]] inlaid within each section of the archivolts.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 5\" /> The third arch of the main entrance contains depictions of philosophers including [[Ralph Waldo Emerson]], [[Immanuel Kant]], and [[Pythagoras]], while the second arch depicts scientists like [[Albert Einstein]], [[Charles Darwin]], and [[Hippocrates]].<ref name=\"NYCL p. 5\" /><ref name=\"Dolkart p. 80\" /> Other figures depict the 12 months of the year.<ref name=\"Paris et al. pp. 155-156\" /> The columns framing the door [[jamb]]s, located under the archivolts, are also decorated with capitals and gargoyles at the top and bottom, and a single figure in the middle. A seated figure of Christ is located in the [[tympanum (architecture)|tympanum]] above the doors and below the archivolts, and is flanked by the symbols of the [[Four Evangelists|Evangelists]].<ref name=\"NYCL p. 8\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 4\">{{harvnb|National Park Service|2012|ps=.|p=4}}</ref>\n\nWhen Riverside Church was completed, there was controversy over the inclusion of Einstein, a Jewish man who was still alive when the church was constructed, as the other figures represented figures who had since died.<ref name=\"Carder p. 18\" /><ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 154\">{{harvnb|Paris et al.|2004|ps=.|p=154}}</ref> The publication ''Church Monthly'' said that during construction, the committee tasked with the church's iconography had proposed 20 scientists to be depicted on the facade, of which Einstein was not part.<ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 154\" /> However, the faculty had unanimously decided that Einstein should be included, as he was indisputably one of 14 \"leading scientists of all time\".<ref name=\"Carder p. 18\" />\n\nThe chapel entrance, located on Riverside Drive south of the main entrance, contains two archivolts supported by two sets of columns. The archivolts contain symbols of the [[zodiac]], and the second archivolt contains an elaborate decorative molding. A tympanum relief below the archivolts depicts the [[Mary, mother of Jesus|Virgin Mary]] flanked by two [[angel]]s who are mirror images of each other.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 8\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 4\" />\n\nIn addition, sculpted elements are placed within niches spread across the church's facade. Above the main entrance on the western facade, there are sculptures of seven kings.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 8\" /> More statues are located within niches in the tower itself,<ref name=\"NYCL p. 9\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 5\" /> as well as in niches on the facade of the cloister entrance to the east.<ref name=\"NPS p. 6\" /><ref name=\"NYCL p. 10\" /> Also placed on the facade are gargoyles, located outside the carillon near the top of the tower.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 9\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 5\" /> The northern section of the nave's roof contains a bronze statue, ''Angel of the Resurrection'', which depicts a trumpeter atop a pedestal.<ref name=\"NYCL p. 8\" />\n\n==== Interior elements ====\nThe various carvings inside different portions of the church correspond to the respective uses of these portions. For instance, the 20 quatrefoil medallions inscribed on the chancel railing depict the typical \"interests, emphases, activities, rites, and ceremonies\" that are conducted within the chancel.<ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 162\" /> Around the pulpit are ten [[Old Testament]] prophets.<ref name=\"NPS p. 9\" /><ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 162\" /> Above the nave, the southern wall of the upper seating gallery contains multi-tiered niches, whose upper tiers contain sculpted figures of ministers. The center two niches contain a cast of Epstein's gilded-plaster sculpture ''Christ in Majesty''.<ref name=\"NPS p. 11\" />\n\n{{Anchor|Chancel screen}}There is a seven-paneled [[chancel screen]] at the back of the chancel, carved in [[Caen stone]].<ref name=\"NPS p. 9\" /> It depicts numerous influential figures such as the composer [[Johann Sebastian Bach]], the U.S. president [[Abraham Lincoln]], the artist [[Michelangelo]], the social reformer [[Florence Nightingale]], and the author [[Booker T. Washington]].<ref name=\"NYCL p. 6\" /><ref name=\"NPS p. 10\" /> From left to right, the panels depict physicians, teachers, prophets, humanitarians, missionaries, reformers, and lovers-of-beauty.<ref name=\"NPS p. 10\" /><ref>{{harvnb|Paris et al.|2004|ps=.|p=164}}</ref>\n\nAbove the doorway between the cloister and the tower base are statues of architects Henry Pelton and Charles Collens, as well as general contractor Robert Eidlitz.<ref name=\"NPS p. 14\" />\n\n<div align=\"center\">\n<gallery heights=\"250\" mode=\"packed\" caption=\"Carving details\">\nFile:Riverside-Church-sculpture.jpg|Stone carving detail\nFile:Riverside-Church-sculpture-4.png|Several sculptures like these adorn the church\nFile:Interior of Riverside Church 05.JPG|Sculpted figures inside the gallery\n</gallery></div>\n\n=== Sculpture ===\nWhen the Martin Luther King Jr. Wing was built, [[Jacob Epstein]]'s sculpture ''Madonna and Child'' was placed in the courtyard between the MLK Wing and the cloistered entrance.<ref name=\"NPS p. 17\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1959/12/30/archives/church-gets-madonna-by-epstein.html|title=Church Gets Madonna by Epstein|date=December 30, 1959|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 9, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> The sculpture was originally commissioned in 1927.<ref name=\"NPS p. 17\" /><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TzlIAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA1|title=Sculpture of Jacob Epstein: The Eisenberg-Robbins Collection|last=Epstein|first=J.|author2=Corcoran Gallery of Art|publisher=Corcoran Gallery of Art|year=1973|series=Sculpture of Jacob Epstein: The Eisenberg-Robbins Collection|page=1|access-date=November 17, 2019|issue=2}}</ref>\n\n== Social services ==\n[[File:Correctionalfacilityvolunteers.JPG|thumb|Some of Riverside's Prison Ministry volunteers at a prison]]The church was conceived as a complex social services center from the outset, with meeting rooms and classrooms, a daycare center, a kindergarten, library, auditorium and gym. It was described by ''[[The New York Times]]'' in 2008 as \"a stronghold of activism and political debate throughout its 75-year history&nbsp;... influential on the nation's religious and political landscapes.\"<ref name=\"NYT8408\">{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2008/08/04/nyregion/04riverside.html?_r=1&scp|title=Riverside Church Selects a New Leader|last=Buettner|first=Russ|date=August 4, 2008|work=The New York Times|accessdate=August 4, 2008|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> Riverside Church continues to provide various social services, including a [[food bank]], barber training, clothing distribution, a shower project, and confidential [[HIV tests]] and HIV counseling.<ref name=\"Riverside Church Ministries\">{{cite web|url=https://www.trcnyc.org/ministries/|title=Ministries|website=Riverside Church|access-date=November 15, 2019}}</ref> In 2007, the ''Times'' said that Riverside has frequently \"been likened to the Vatican for America\u2019s mainstream Protestants.\"<ref name=\"NYT-Rebuilding-2007\" />\n\n=== Social justice ministries ===\n\n==== Charity and shelter ====\nRiverside has two prisoner-related ministries. Riverside's Prison Ministry and Family Advocacy Program conducts worship services in the [[New York State Department of Corrections and Community Supervision]]; helps prisoners and their families; links prisoners to their communities; holds various workshops, [[support group]]s, and events; and lobbies for [[prison reform]] and humane [[legislation]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.trcnyc.org/ministries/prisonministry/|title=Prison Ministry|date=November 20, 2017|website=Riverside Church|access-date=November 18, 2019}}</ref> Riverside's Coming Home ministry helps prisoners after they have been released.<ref name=\"RpcVv\">{{cite web|url=https://www.trcnyc.org/ministries/cominghome/|title=Riverside Coming Home|website=Riverside Church|access-date=November 18, 2019}}</ref> The prison ministries date from 1971, when the Council on Christian Social Relations created a [[prison reform]] and [[Rehabilitation (penology)|rehabilitation]] task force.<ref>{{harvnb|Paris et al.|2004|ps=.|p=207}}</ref>\n\nRiverside's Coming Home ministry, founded in 1985, deals with [[homelessness in New York City]].<ref name=\"RpcVv\" /> Riverside's advocacy of the homeless originated from a similar ministry, the Clothing Room and Food Pantry, which was a subdivision of the Social Services Department. The church began sheltering homeless people overnight from 1984 until 1994, when it was closed due to the decreasing homeless population and a staff shortage.<ref>{{harvnb|Paris et al.|2004|ps=.|pp=217\u2013218}}</ref>\n\nRiverside participated in the [[Sanctuary movement]] during the 1980s, being among numerous congregations nationwide that sheltered and assisted [[Undocumented immigrants of New York City|undocumented immigrants]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1984/10/02/nyregion/riverside-church-gives-sanctuary.html|title=Riverside Church Gives Sanctuary|last=Briggs|first=Kenneth A.|date=1984-10-02|work=The New York Times|access-date=2019-11-18|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> As part of the New Sanctuary Coalition, volunteers at Riverside Church and other participating houses of worship assist detained [[asylum seekers]] and those on [[parole]] from [[immigration detention]].<ref>{{cite web | title=Welcome to New Sanctuary Coalition | website=New Sanctuary Coalition | date=July 1, 2018 | url=https://www.newsanctuarynyc.org/ | access-date=November 18, 2019}}</ref> In 2011, as part of a movement called [[Occupy Faith]], Riverside Church donated tents to [[Occupy Wall Street]] protesters, as well as sheltered them during cold or inclement weather and after the evacuation of [[Zuccotti Park]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/11/18/nyregion/occupy-wall-street-protesters-even-in-churches-cant-escape-watch-of-police.html|title=Occupy Wall Street Protesters, Even in Churches, Can't Escape Watch of Police|last=Otterman|first=Sharon|date=November 17, 2011|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 11, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n==== Social and cultural ====\n[[File:Riverside Pride Float.JPG|thumb|Riverside's Pride Parade Float|alt=]]\n\nRiverside Church's [[LGBT]] ministry is named [[Maranatha]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.trcnyc.org/ministries/maranathatrc/|title=Maranatha|website=Riverside Church|access-date=November 18, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1985/05/26/nyregion/sex-issue-divides-riverside-church.html|title=Sex Issue Divides Riverside Church|date=May 26, 1985|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 18, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> It was founded in 1978 in response to growing demand from gay and lesbian congregants.<ref name=\"Paris et al. pp. 220-221\">{{harvnb|Paris et al.|2004|ps=.|pp=220\u2013221}}</ref> Maranatha hosts several activities, workshops, and events, and marches annually in the [[NYC Pride March]].<ref name=\"Paris et al. pp. 220-221\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=//columbiaspectator.com/2012/02/13/riverside-church-celebrates-30-years-pro-lgbt-ministry/|title=Riverside Church celebrates 30 years of pro-LGBT ministry|last=|first=|date=February 13, 2012|website=Columbia Daily Spectator|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=November 18, 2019}}</ref> In the 1980s, when the [[HIV/AIDS in New York City|HIV/AIDS epidemic in New York City]] was at its peak, there was some backlash against Maranatha, as the LGBT community was negatively associated with the epidemic. These events led to the founding of the separate [[HIV/AIDS]] ministry,<ref>{{harvnb|Paris et al.|2004|ps=.|p=222}}</ref> which hosts a support forum; provides testing, counseling, and referral programs; and collaborates with several other programs.<ref name=\"Riverside Church Ministries\" />\n\nRiverside Church's African Fellowship and Ministry sponsors educational forums about issues facing the continent of Africa and advocates on behalf of [[African diaspora]].<ref name=\"Riverside Church Ministries\" /> The Sharing and Densford Funds advocate on behalf of [[Native Americans in the United States]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.trcnyc.org/ministries/sharingfund/|title=Sharing & Densford Funds|website=Riverside Church|access-date=November 18, 2019}}</ref> Other ministries at Riverside include support groups for [[South Africa]]ns and for [[Hispanic and Latino Americans]].<ref name=\"Riverside Church Ministries\" />\n\n==== Other activism ====\nRiverside has several other social justice ministries. The Beloved Earth ministry is an [[environmentalist]] ministry with a focus on [[Individual and political action on climate change|climate change activism]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.trcnyc.org/ministries/belovedearth/|title=Beloved Earth|website=Riverside Church|access-date=November 18, 2019}}</ref> The Wellbotics ministry helps the families of cancer patients.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.trcnyc.org/ministries/wellbotics/|title=Wellbotics|website=Riverside Church|access-date=November 18, 2019}}</ref> Riverside also has several pacifist task forces. The Anti-Death Penalty Task Force is in [[opposition to capital punishment in the United States]]. An \"Overcoming Violence\" task force is dedicated to fostering dialogue with the [[New York City Police Department]].<ref name=\"Riverside Church Ministries\" /> Riverside Church also participates in the [[National Religious Campaign Against Torture]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.trcnyc.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/torture.pdf|title=The Riverside Church Statement On Torture And Policies Enabling Torture|publisher=Riverside Church|date=April 2017|access-date=November 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\n=== Former programming ===\nWhen Riverside Church's Martin Luther King Jr. Wing was completed in 1959, it included space for a radio station planned by the church.<ref name=\"NYDN-Wing-1959\" /> The [[Federal Communications Commission]] (FCC) granted the church a FM broadcasting license in 1960,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1960/07/21/archives/riverside-church-gets-fm.html|title=Riverside Church Gets FM|date=July 21, 1960|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 9, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> and the following year, Riverside Church started operating the radio station [[WLTW|WRVR]] (106.7 [[FM broadcasting|FM]]).<ref name=\"NYCL p. 7\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1961/01/08/archives/growth-of-fm-new-radio-station-of-riverside-church-illustrates.html|title=Growth of FM; New Radio Station of Riverside Church Illustrates Diversity of System|last=Gould|first=Jack|date=January 8, 1961|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 9, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/61-OCR/1961-01-23-BC-OCR-Page-0053.pdf|title=Riverside Church fm station on-the-air|date=January 23, 1961|page=53|accessdate=March 3, 2019|periodical=Broadcasting}}</ref> WRVR originally broadcast from Riverside Church's carillon before being relocated to the [[Empire State Building]] in 1971 to increase the range of the broadcast signal. Originally a noncommercial station, WRVR broadcast sermons, as well as programming from cultural and higher-education institutions in New York City.<ref>{{harvnb|Paris et al.|2004|ps=.|pp=209\u2013213}}</ref> However, WRVR incurred a net loss for Riverside Church each year, and in 1971, was turned into a \"limited commercial operation\", which also failed to be profitable.<ref name=\"Paris et al. pp. 214-216\">{{harvnb|Paris et al.|2004|ps=.|pp=214\u2013216}}</ref> Riverside Church decided to sell its radio station in 1975,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.americanradiohistory.com/hd2/IDX-Business/Magazines/Archive-BC-IDX/75-OCR/1975-07-07-BC-OCR-Page-0025.pdf|title=In brief|date=July 7, 1975|page=27|accessdate=March 3, 2019|periodical=Broadcasting}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1975/07/04/archives/station-wrvrfm-sold-to-sonderling-by-riverside-church.html|title=Station WRVR\u2010FM Sold to Sonderling By Riverside Church|date=July 4, 1975|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 8, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> the sale being finalized the following year.<ref name=\"Paris et al. pp. 214-216\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1976/10/28/archives/sonderlings-purchase-of-wrvr-from-church-approved-by-fcc.html|title=Sonderling's Purchase of WRVR From Church Approved by F.C.C.|date=October 28, 1976|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 8, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\nStarting in November 1976, Riverside Church hosted the Riverside Dance Festival. The program was a continuation of previous dance ministries hosted by the church, and normally offered 34 weeks of programming from over 60 dance companies.<ref>{{harvnb|Paris et al.|2004|ps=.|p=326}}</ref> The program ended in June 1987 because of a $900,000 funding shortfall.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/02/10/arts/riverside-dance-to-close.html|title=Riverside Dance to Close|last=Dunning|first=Jennifer|date=February 10, 1987|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 9, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n\n==Called senior ministers {{Anchor|Clergy}}==\n[[File:Harry Emerson Fosdick.jpg|thumb|[[Harry Emerson Fosdick]]]]\nIn chronological order, the called senior ministers at Riverside Church have been:\n* [[Harry Emerson Fosdick]] (1925\u20131945)<ref name=\"NYT-FosdickAccepts-1925\" /><ref name=\"NYT-Fosdick-1945\" />\n* Robert J. McCracken (1946\u20131967)<ref name=\"NYT-McCracken-1946\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1967/05/25/archives/mcracken-bids-riverside-adieu-congregation-gives-retiring-minister.html|title=M'Cracken Bids Riverside Adieu; Congregation Gives Retiring Minister $10,000 Born in Scotland|last=Adams|first=Val|date=May 25, 1967|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 9, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n* Ernest T. Campbell (1968\u20131976)<ref name=\"NYT-Campbell-1968\" /><ref name=\"NYT-Campbell-1976\" />\n* [[William Sloane Coffin]] (1977\u20131987)<ref name=\"NYT-Coffin-1977\" /><ref name=\"NYT-Coffin-1987\" />\n* [[James A. Forbes]] (1989\u20132007)<ref name=\"NYT-Forbes-1989\" /><ref name=\"NYT-Forbes-2007\" />\n* Brad R. Braxton (2008\u20132009)<ref name=\"NYT8408\" /><ref name=\"NYT-Braxton-2009\">{{cite news|last=Vitello|first=Paul|date=June 30, 2009|title=Pastor at Riverside Church Ends Stormy Tenure With Unexpected Resignation|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/07/01/nyregion/01pastor.html|work=The New York Times|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331 |access-date=July 17, 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Amy Butler (minister)|Amy Butler]] (2014\u20132019)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://time.com/2864118/meet-riverside-churchs-first-female-pastor/|title=Meet Riverside Church's First Female Pastor|last=Berenson|first=Tessa|date=|website=Time|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=November 11, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/social-issues/riverside-church-congregants-call-for-reinstatement-of-first-female-minister-after-her-dismissal-following-a-sex-shop-visit/2019/07/14/1c2c23da-a632-11e9-86dd-d7f0e60391e9_story.html|title=Riverside Church Congregants Call for Reinstatement of First Female Minister after Her Exit Following a Sex Shop Visit|last=Natanson|first=Hannah|date=July 15, 2019|work=Washington Post|access-date=July 16, 2019|location=}}</ref>\n\n== Notable speakers ==\n\nOn April 4, 1967, [[Martin Luther King Jr.]] gave a speech at Riverside called [[Beyond Vietnam: A Time to Break Silence]], where he voiced his opposition to the [[Vietnam War]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thekingcenter.org/archive/document/letter-robert-j-mccracken-mlk|title=Letter from Robert J McCracken to MLK|publisher=[[King Center for Nonviolent Social Change]]|accessdate=April 12, 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last=Scruggs | first=Afi-Odelia | title=Beyond Vietnam: The MLK speech that caused an uproar | website=USA Today | date=January 13, 2017 | url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation-now/2017/01/13/martin-luther-king-jr-beyond-vietnam-speech/96501636/ | access-date=November 19, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title=Martin Luther King, Jr.,'s Searing Antiwar Speech, Fifty Years Later | website=The New Yorker |date=2017-04-03 | url=https://www.newyorker.com/culture/culture-desk/martin-luther-king-jr-s-searing-antiwar-speech-fifty-years-later | access-date=November 19, 2019}}</ref> The Rev. [[Jesse Jackson]] gave the eulogy at [[Jackie Robinson]]'s funeral service in 1972.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1972/10/28/archives/new-jerjey-pages-but-on-that-dash-is-where-we-live-sports-of-the.html|title=But on That Dash Is Where We Live|date=October 28, 1972|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 10, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> [[Nelson Mandela]], anti-apartheid activist and later South African president, spoke at Riverside in 1991 following his release from prison.<ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 55\">{{harvnb|Paris et al.|2004|ps=.|p=55}}</ref>  [[Secretary-General of the United Nations]] [[Kofi Annan]] spoke there after the September 11, 2001 attacks,<ref>{{cite book | last=Welch | first=R. | last2=Penn | first2=E. | title=New York: A Pictorial Celebration | publisher=Sterling Pub. | year=2007 | isbn=978-1-4027-2383-4 | url=https://archive.org/details/newyorkpictorial0000welc | url-access=registration | access-date=February 29, 2020 | page=[https://archive.org/details/newyorkpictorial0000welc/page/80 80]}}</ref> and former U.S. president [[Bill Clinton]] spoke at the church in 2004.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2004/08/30/us/republicans-convention-new-york-clintons-after-sharing-white-house-sharing.html|title=The Republicans: The Convention In New York - The Clintons; After Sharing the White House, Sharing a Critique of the G.O.P.|last=Hernandez|first=Raymond|date=August 30, 2004|work=The New York Times|access-date=November 10, 2019|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.cnn.com/2004/ALLPOLITICS/09/03/clinton.tests/|title=Bill Clinton awaits heart surgery next week|last=|first=|date=September 4, 2004|website=CNN|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=November 10, 2019}}</ref> Speakers have also included theologians such as [[Paul Tillich]], who taught nearby,<ref>{{harvnb|Paris et al.|2004|ps=.|p=279}}</ref> as well as [[Reinhold Niebuhr]].<ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 55\" /> Other past speakers include civil-rights activists [[Cesar Chavez]];<ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 55\" /> human-rights activist [[Desmond Tutu]];<ref name=\"Paris et al. p. 55\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=http://spectatorarchive.library.columbia.edu/?a=d&d=cs19880421-01.2.4&|title=Desmond Tutu will speak at Riverside Church April 29|last=|first=|date=April 21, 1988|website=Columbia Spectator|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=November 10, 2019}}</ref> Cuban president [[Fidel Castro]];<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/nov/27/fidel-castro-new-york-malcolm-x|title=Fidel Castro in the US: cars, cigars and a meeting with Malcolm X|last=Smith|first=David|date=November 27, 2016|work=The Guardian|access-date=November 10, 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> the [[14th Dalai Lama]];<ref name=\"NYT-Forbes-2007\" /> and [[Abdullah II of Jordan]].<ref name=\"NYT-Forbes-2007\" />\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of Baptist churches]]\n* [[List of New York City Designated Landmarks in Manhattan above 110th Street]]\n* [[National Register of Historic Places listings in Manhattan above 110th Street]]\n\n== References ==\n=== Notes ===\n{{notelist}}\n\n=== Citations ===\n{{reflist|1=30em}}\n\n=== Sources ===\n{{refbegin}}\n# {{Cite book|title=Architecture and symbolism of the Riverside Church|last=Carder|first=Eugene Clayton|last2=Church monthly (N.Y.)|date=1930|publisher=Riverside Church|location=New York|language=English|oclc=3940539|ref={{harvid|Carder|1930}}}}\n# {{cite morningside|ref=harv}}\n# {{cite web|url=https://s3.amazonaws.com/NARAprodstorage/lz/electronic-records/rg-079/NPS_NY/12001036.pdf|title=Historic Structures Report: Riverside Church|date=December 21, 2012|publisher=[[National Register of Historic Places]], [[National Park Service]]|ref={{harvid|National Park Service|2012}}}}\n# {{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/harryemersonfosd0000mill|url-access=registration|title=Harry Emerson Fosdick: Preacher, Pastor, Prophet|last=Miller|first=R.M.|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=1985|isbn=978-0-19-536523-8|page=|ref={{harvid|Miller|1985}}}}\n# {{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jtoegDGyJcgC|title=The History of the Riverside Church in the City of New 