{"title_page": "Dagoberto Rodr\u00edguez Barrera", "text_new": "[[File:Reuni\u00f3n de trabajo entre autoridades de Canciller\u00eda y Vicecanciller cubano, Dagoberto Rodr\u00edguez (5009644154).jpg|thumb|2010]]\n'''Dagoberto Rodriguez Barrera''' (born 1955 in [[Cuba]]) is a Cuban [[diplomat]]. From August 2001 to 2007, he was the Chief of the [[Cuban Interests Section]]. Prior to being the Chief of the Cuban Interests Section he was the Head of the Cuban Foreign Ministry's Department on North America.  He is currently the Cuban Ambassador in Venezuela.\n\n==References==\n* ''Veteran Cuban Diplomat Being Sent To Post In Cuba'', '''The Miami Herald''', November 7, 2007, Page 7A\n* ''Cambios En Seccion De Intereses Cubana'', '''El Nuevo Herald''', July 12, 2001, Page 3A (Spanish)\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box|before=[[Fernando Rem\u00ecrez de Estenoz-Barciela]]|title=[[Cuban Interests Section|Chief of Cuban Interests Section]]|years=2001-2007|after=[[Jorge Bola\u00f1os]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Commons category}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rodriguez Barrera, Dagoberto}}\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Cuban diplomats]]\n\n\n{{Cuba-diplomat-stub}}\n", "text_old": "[[File:Reuni\u00f3n de trabajo entre autoridades de Canciller\u00eda y Vicecanciller cubano, Dagoberto Rodr\u00edguez (5009644154).jpg|thumb|2010]]\n'''Dagoberto Rodriguez Barrera''' (born 1955 in [[Cuba]]) is a Cuban [[diplomat]]. From August 2001 to 2007, he was the Chief of the [[Cuban Interests Section]]. Prior to being the Chief of the Cuban Interests Section he was the Head of the Cuban Foreign Ministry\u2019s Department on North America.  He is currently the Cuban Ambassador in Venezuela.\n\n==References==\n* ''Veteran Cuban Diplomat Being Sent To Post In Cuba'', '''The Miami Herald''', November 7, 2007, Page 7A\n* ''Cambios En Seccion De Intereses Cubana'', '''El Nuevo Herald''', July 12, 2001, Page 3A (Spanish)\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{succession box|before=[[Fernando Rem\u00ecrez de Estenoz-Barciela]]|title=[[Cuban Interests Section|Chief of Cuban Interests Section]]|years=2001-2007|after=[[Jorge Bola\u00f1os]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Commons category}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rodriguez Barrera, Dagoberto}}\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Cuban diplomats]]\n\n\n{{Cuba-diplomat-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dagoberto_Rodr%C3%ADguez_Barrera"}
{"title_page": "WZMG", "text_new": "{{Infobox radio station\n| name             = WZMG\n| image            = Fox Sports.png\n| caption          = \n| image_size       = 200px\n| city             = [[Pepperell, Alabama]]\n| area             = [[Opelika, Alabama]]<br>[[Columbus, Georgia]]\n| branding         = ''Fox Sports 910am-1310am The Game''\n| slogan           = Your Home for East AL/West GA Sports\n| frequency        = 910 [[kHz]]\n| airdate          = \n| format           = [[Sports radio|Sports]]\n| power            = 650 [[watt]]s (day)<br>56 watts (night)\n| class            = D\n| facility_id      = 24255\n| coordinates      = {{coord|32|39|26|N|85|25|27|W|region:US-AL_type:landmark}}\n| callsign_meaning = \n| former_callsigns = \n| affiliations     = [[Fox Sports]]\n| owner            = [[iHeartMedia, Inc.]]\n| licensee         = AMFM Radio Licenses, L.L.C.\n| sister_stations  = [[WCJM-FM]], [[WKKR]], [[WMXA]], [[WPCH (AM)|WPCH]], [[WTLM]]\n| webcast          = {{url|https://www.iheart.com/live/fox-sports-the-game-6770}}\n| website          = {{url|https://foxsportsthegame.iheart.com}}\n}}\n'''WZMG''' (910 [[AM broadcasting|AM]], \"Fox Sports 910am-1310am The Game\") is a [[radio station]] broadcasting [[sports]] and a Fox Sports  affiliate.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fcc.gov/fcc-bin/amq?call=WZMG |title=WZMG Facility Record |work=United States [[Federal Communications Commission]], audio division}}</ref> Licensed to [[Pepperell, Alabama]], United States, the station serves the [[Auburn Metropolitan Area]].  The station is currently owned by [[iHeartMedia, Inc.]], through licensee AMFM Radio Licenses, L.L.C.  WZMG features some programming from [[Citadel Media]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.arbitron.com |title=Station Information Profile |work=Arbitron}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nIn August 1998, Fuller Broadcasting Company, Inc., reached an agreement to sell this station to Root Communications License Company, L.P., as part of a five-station deal.<ref>{{cite news |first=Cecil G.|last=Brumley |work=Daytona Beach News-Journal |title=Root Communications buying five more stations |date=August 5, 1998 |page=12A}}</ref>  The deal was approved by the FCC on October 5, 1998, and the transaction was consummated in December 1998.<ref>{{cite web |publisher=FCC Media Bureau |title=Broadcast Actions Report No. 44343 |url=http://www.fcc.gov/Bureaus/Mass_Media/Public_Notices/Brdcst_Actions/ac981008.txt |date=October 8, 1998}}</ref>  Gary Fuller, president and CEO of Fuller Broadcasting Company from 1985 until he sold the company in December 1998, was elected mayor of [[Opelika, Alabama]], in August 2004.<ref>{{cite web |publisher=The City of Opelika |title=A little about Mayor Gary Fuller |url=http://www.opelika.org/Default.asp?ID=315&pg=Mayor |accessdate=December 21, 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2003, Root Communications License Company, L.P., reached an agreement to sell this station to Qantum Communications subsidiary Qantum of Auburn License Company, LLC, as part of a 26 station deal valued at $82.2 million.<ref name=\"bcg3\">{{cite news |date=March 17, 2003 |url=http://www.broadcastingcable.com/article/CA284625.html |work=Broadcasting & Cable |title=Changing Hands - 3/17/2003}}</ref>  The deal was approved by the FCC on April 30, 2003, and the transaction was consummated on July 2, 2003.<ref>{{cite web |publisher=FCC Media Bureau |title=Application Search Details (BALH-20030307ACE) |url=http://fjallfoss.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/ws.exe/prod/cdbs/pubacc/prod/app_det.pl?Application_id=656276 |date=July 2, 2003}}</ref>\n\nOn May 15, 2014, Qantum Communications announced that it would sell its 29 stations, including WZMG, to Clear Channel Communications (now iHeartMedia), in a transaction connected to Clear Channel's sale of [[WLID|WALK AM]]-[[WALK-FM|FM]] in [[Patchogue, New York]] to [[Connoisseur Media]] via Qantum.<ref name=ri-saletocc>{{cite news|last=Venta|first=Lance|title=Qantum Sells To Clear Channel; Connoisseur Expands In Long Island|url=http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/88656/qantum-sells-to-clear-channel-connoisseur-expands-in-long-island/|accessdate=May 15, 2014|newspaper=RadioInsight|date=May 15, 2014}}</ref> The transaction was consummated on September 9, 2014.\n\nOn December 15, 2015 WZMG changed their format to gospel, branded as \"Hallelujah 910\".<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/95530/wzmg-flips-to-gospel/ WZMG Flips to Gospel]</ref>\n\nOn July 1, 2019 WZMG changed their format to sports, branded as \"Fox Sports 910am-1310am The Game\".\n\n==Previous logo==\n[[File:WZMG-AM logo.png]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{AM station data|WZMG}}\n\n{{Auburn Radio}}\n{{Columbus GA Radio}}\n{{IHeartMedia}}\n\n[[Category:Radio stations in Alabama|ZMG]]\n[[Category:Lee County, Alabama]]\n[[Category:Radio stations established in 1998]]\n[[Category:IHeartMedia radio stations]]\n\n\n{{Alabama-radio-station-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox radio station\n| name             = WZMG \n| image            = [[File:Fox Sports.png|thumb|Logo for FOX Sports The Game 910-1310 AM radio station]]\n| image_size       = 200px\n| city             = [[Pepperell, Alabama]]\n| area             = [[Opelika, Alabama]]<br>[[Columbus, Georgia]]\n| branding         = ''Fox Sports 910am-1310am The Game''\n| slogan           = Your Home for East AL/West GA Sports \n| frequency        = 910 [[kHz]] \n| airdate          = \n| format           = [[Sports radio|Sports]]\n| power            = 650 [[watt]]s (day)<br>56 watts (night)  \n| class            = D \n| facility_id      = 24255 \n| coordinates      = {{coord|32|39|26|N|85|25|27|W|region:US-AL_type:landmark}} \n| callsign_meaning = \n| former_callsigns = \n| affiliations     = [[Fox Sports]] \n| owner            = [[iHeartMedia, Inc.]]\n| licensee         = AMFM Radio Licenses, L.L.C.\n| sister_stations  = [[WCJM-FM]], [[WKKR]], [[WMXA]], [[WPCH (AM)|WPCH]], [[WTLM]]\n| webcast          = [https://www.iheart.com/live/fox-sports-the-game-6770/]\n| website          = [https://foxsportsthegame.iheart.com]\n}}\n'''WZMG''' (910 [[AM broadcasting|AM]], \"Fox Sports 910am-1310am The Game\") is a [[radio station]] broadcasting [[Sports]] and a Fox Sports  affiliate.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fcc.gov/fcc-bin/amq?call=WZMG |title=WZMG Facility Record |work=United States [[Federal Communications Commission]], audio division}}</ref> Licensed to [[Pepperell, Alabama]], United States, the station serves the [[Auburn Metropolitan Area]].  The station is currently owned by [[iHeartMedia, Inc.]], through licensee AMFM Radio Licenses, L.L.C.  WZMG features some programming from [[Citadel Media]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.arbitron.com |title=Station Information Profile |work=Arbitron}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nIn August 1998, Fuller Broadcasting Company, Inc., reached an agreement to sell this station to Root Communications License Company, L.P., as part of a five-station deal.<ref>{{cite news |first=Cecil G.|last=Brumley |work=Daytona Beach News-Journal |title=Root Communications buying five more stations |date=August 5, 1998 |page=12A}}</ref>  The deal was approved by the FCC on October 5, 1998, and the transaction was consummated in December 1998.<ref>{{cite web |publisher=FCC Media Bureau |title=Broadcast Actions Report No. 44343 |url=http://www.fcc.gov/Bureaus/Mass_Media/Public_Notices/Brdcst_Actions/ac981008.txt |date=October 8, 1998}}</ref>  Gary Fuller, president and CEO of Fuller Broadcasting Company from 1985 until he sold the company in December 1998, was elected mayor of [[Opelika, Alabama]], in August 2004.<ref>{{cite web |publisher=The City of Opelika |title=A little about Mayor Gary Fuller |url=http://www.opelika.org/Default.asp?ID=315&pg=Mayor |accessdate=December 21, 2008}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2003, Root Communications License Company, L.P., reached an agreement to sell this station to Qantum Communications subsidiary Qantum of Auburn License Company, LLC, as part of a 26 station deal valued at $82.2 million.<ref name=\"bcg3\">{{cite news |date=March 17, 2003 |url=http://www.broadcastingcable.com/article/CA284625.html |work=Broadcasting & Cable |title=Changing Hands - 3/17/2003}}</ref>  The deal was approved by the FCC on April 30, 2003, and the transaction was consummated on July 2, 2003.<ref>{{cite web |publisher=FCC Media Bureau |title=Application Search Details (BALH-20030307ACE) |url=http://fjallfoss.fcc.gov/cgi-bin/ws.exe/prod/cdbs/pubacc/prod/app_det.pl?Application_id=656276 |date=July 2, 2003}}</ref>\n\nOn May 15, 2014, Qantum Communications announced that it would sell its 29 stations, including WZMG, to Clear Channel Communications (now iHeartMedia), in a transaction connected to Clear Channel's sale of [[WLID|WALK AM]]-[[WALK-FM|FM]] in [[Patchogue, New York]] to [[Connoisseur Media]] via Qantum.<ref name=ri-saletocc>{{cite news|last=Venta|first=Lance|title=Qantum Sells To Clear Channel; Connoisseur Expands In Long Island|url=http://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/88656/qantum-sells-to-clear-channel-connoisseur-expands-in-long-island/|accessdate=May 15, 2014|newspaper=RadioInsight|date=May 15, 2014}}</ref> The transaction was consummated on September 9, 2014.\n\nOn December 15, 2015 WZMG changed their format to gospel, branded as \"Hallelujah 910\".<ref>[https://radioinsight.com/blog/headlines/95530/wzmg-flips-to-gospel/ WZMG Flips to Gospel]</ref>\n\nOn July 1, 2019 WZMG changed their format to sports, branded as \"Fox Sports 910am-1310am The Game\".\n\n==Previous logo==\n[[File:WZMG-AM logo.png]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{AM station data|WZMG}}\n\n{{Auburn Radio}}\n{{Columbus GA Radio}}\n{{IHeartMedia}}\n\n[[Category:Radio stations in Alabama|ZMG]]\n[[Category:Lee County, Alabama]]\n[[Category:Radio stations established in 1998]]\n[[Category:IHeartMedia radio stations]]\n\n\n{{Alabama-radio-station-stub}}\n", "name_user": "MB", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fix infobox image syntax", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WZMG"}
{"title_page": "Earle Courtenay Rattray", "text_new": "{{refimprove|date=March 2017}}{{like-resume|date=March 2017}}\n{{Infobox Officeholder\n| honorific-prefix =\n|name= Earle Courtenay Rattray\n| native_name =  \n| honorific-suffix =\n|image=\n|caption=\n\n|office=[[Jamaican Ambassador to China]]<br>of {{flag|Jamaica}} <br>to {{flag|China}}\n|term_start= {{dts|1972|06|}}\n|term_end= {{dts|1977|08|}}\n|predecessor=[[Wayne McCook]]\n|successor=[[Ralph Samuel Thomas]]\n\n|office2=[[Jamaican Permanent Representative to the United Nations]]<br>of {{flag|Jamaica}} <br>to {{flag|United Nations}}\n|term_start2= {{dts|1977|08|}}\n|term_end2= \n|predecessor2=[[Raymond Wolfe]]\n|successor2=\n\n|birth_date= {{birth date and age|1959|10|21}}\n|birth_place= [[London]]\n|death_date=\n|death_place=\n|father=\n|mother=\n|spouse= married\n|children= four\n|education=\n|alma_mater=[[Master of Science]] in international business from South Bank University in London as well as a Bachelor of Arts in international studies from West Virginia Wesleyan College, and is currently pursuing Master of Arts studies at Tufts University\u2019s Fletcher School of Law and Diplomacy in the United States.\n}}\n\n'''Earle Courtenay Rattray''' (born October 21, 1959) is a [[Jamaica]]n  [[Ambassador]].\n*From 2001 to 2005 he was Deputy Chief of Jamaica's Embassy in [[Washington, D.C.]].\n*From 2005 to 2008 he was Director of the Bilateral Relations Department in the Ministry of Industry and Investment, in Kingston.\n*From 2008 to April 25, 2013 he was ambassador in [[Beijing]].\n*Since April 25, 2013 he is the Permanent Representative to the [[Headquarters of the United Nations]].<ref>The new Permanent Representative of Jamaica to the United Nations, Courtenay Rattray,[https://www.un.org/press/en/2013/bio4485.doc.htm]</ref>\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rattray, Earle Courtenay}}\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Jamaica to China]]\n[[Category:Permanent Representatives of Jamaica to the United Nations]]\n\n\n{{Jamaica-diplomat-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{refimprove|date=March 2017}}{{like-resume|date=March 2017}}\n{{Infobox Officeholder\n| honorific-prefix =\n|name= Earle Courtenay Rattray\n| native_name =  \n| honorific-suffix =\n|image=\n|caption=\n\n|office=[[Jamaican Ambassador to China]]<br>of {{flag|Jamaica}} <br>to {{flag|China}}\n|term_start= {{dts|1972|06|}}\n|term_end= {{dts|1977|08|}}\n|predecessor=[[Wayne McCook]]\n|successor=[[Ralph Samuel Thomas]]\n\n|office2=[[Jamaican Permanent Representative to the United Nations]]<br>of {{flag|Jamaica}} <br>to {{flag|United Nations}}\n|term_start2= {{dts|1977|08|}}\n|term_end2= \n|predecessor2=[[Raymond Wolfe]]\n|successor2=\n\n|birth_date= {{birth date and age|1959|10|21}}\n|birth_place= [[London]]\n|death_date=\n|death_place=\n|father=\n|mother=\n|spouse= married\n|children= four\n|education=\n|alma_mater=[[Master of Science]] in international business from South Bank University in London as well as a Bachelor of Arts in international studies from West Virginia Wesleyan College, and is currently pursuing Master of Arts studies at Tufts University\u2019s Fletcher School of Law and Diplomacy in the United States.\n}}\n\n'''Earle Courtenay Rattray''' (born October 21, 1959) is a [[Jamaica]]n  [[Ambassador]].\n*From 2001 to 2005 he was Deputy Chief of Jamaica\u2019s Embassy in [[Washington, D.C.]].\n*From 2005 to 2008 he was Director of the Bilateral Relations Department in the Ministry of Industry and Investment, in Kingston.\n*From 2008 to April 25, 2013 he was ambassador in [[Beijing]].\n*Since April 25, 2013 he is the Permanent Representative to the [[Headquarters of the United Nations]].<ref>The new Permanent Representative of Jamaica to the United Nations, Courtenay Rattray,[https://www.un.org/press/en/2013/bio4485.doc.htm]</ref>\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Rattray, Earle Courtenay}}\n[[Category:1959 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Jamaica to China]]\n[[Category:Permanent Representatives of Jamaica to the United Nations]]\n\n\n{{Jamaica-diplomat-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Earle_Courtenay_Rattray"}
{"title_page": "Sigurd von Numers", "text_new": "[[File:J\u00e4rnefelt-Eero+Numer-Sigurd-von.jpg|thumb|upright=1.2|Envoy [[Eero J\u00e4rnefelt (diplomat)|Eero J\u00e4rnefelt]] (left) and Secretary of Security, Sigurd von Numers, drank a [[bowl]] in honor of [[Pehr Evind Svinhufvud]]'s 75th anniversary in [[Washington, D.C.]], 1936.]]\n'''Sigurd Valdemar von Numers''' (20 March 1903<ref name=\"oit\"/> &ndash; 1983)  was a Finnish diplomat, a Doctor of Law from 1928. He was awarded the title of the Consul General in 1944.<ref>[http://www.kysy.fi/kysymys/tasavallan-presidentin-myontamat-paakonsulin-arvonimetkeita-ovat Kysy.fi]</ref> \n\nvon Numers was born in [[Viipuri]]. He served as Charg\u00e9 d'Affaires  in [[Ottawa]], [[Canada]], from 1954 to 1959, to [[India]] in New Delhi from 1959 to 1960, Ambassador to the [[United States]] from 1960 to 1961<ref name=\"oit\">Otavan Iso tietosanakirja, Otava 1968, osa 6, palsta 515</ref> and in the [[Netherlands]] as ambassador 1964\u20131970.<ref>[http://formin.finland.fi/public/default.aspx?nodeid=30937&contentlan=1&culture=fi-FI Ulkoasiainministeri\u00f6]</ref> Before and after international commissions he was head of the Legal Department of the [[Ministry for Foreign Affairs (Finland)|Ministry for Foreign Affairs]] from 1949 to 1954 and again from 1961.<ref name=\"oit\"/>\n\nDuring the 1930s, in [[Stockholm]], as a secretary of state, von Numers interfered with the so-called Maydell affair, for example, by granting [[Nansen passport]] to [[Russian citizen]] residing in [[Germany]],  Baron Karl Frederick Karl Viktor von Maydell-Felks (born 1899)  who was dubious to make a film in Finland.<ref name=ennenyt>[http://www.ennenjanyt.net/1-02/maydell.htm Jari Sedergren: Maydell-juttu. Ennen ja nyt 1/2002]</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{diplomat-stub}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Numers, Sigurd von}}\n[[Category:Finnish lawyers]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Finland to the Netherlands]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Finland to the United States]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Finland to India]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Finland to Thailand]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Finland to Indonesia]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Finland to Ireland]]\n[[Category:1903 births]]\n[[Category:1983 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Vyborg]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:J\u00e4rnefelt-Eero+Numer-Sigurd-von.jpg|thumb|upright=1.2|Envoy [[Eero J\u00e4rnefelt (diplomat)|Eero J\u00e4rnefelt]] (left) and Secretary of Security, Sigurd von Numers, drank a [[bowl]] in honor of [[Pehr Evind Svinhufvud]]'s 75th anniversary in [[Washington, D.C.]], 1936.]]\n'''Sigurd Valdemar von Numers''' (20 March 1903<ref name=\"oit\"/> &ndash; 1983)  was a Finnish diplomat, a Doctor of Law from 1928. He was awarded the title of the Consul General in 1944.<ref>[http://www.kysy.fi/kysymys/tasavallan-presidentin-myontamat-paakonsulin-arvonimetkeita-ovat Kysy.fi]</ref> \n\nvon Numers was born in [[Viipuri]]. He served as Charg\u00e9 d'Affaires  in [[Ottawa]], [[Canada]], from 1954 to 1959, to [[India]] in New Delhi from 1959 to 1960, Ambassador to the [[United States]] from 1960 to 1961<ref name=\"oit\">Otavan Iso tietosanakirja, Otava 1968, osa 6, palsta 515</ref> and in the [[Netherlands]] as ambassador 1964-1970.<ref>[http://formin.finland.fi/public/default.aspx?nodeid=30937&contentlan=1&culture=fi-FI Ulkoasiainministeri\u00f6]</ref> Before and after international commissions he was head of the Legal Department of the [[Ministry for Foreign Affairs (Finland)|Ministry for Foreign Affairs]] from 1949 to 1954 and again from 1961.<ref name=\"oit\"/>\n\nDuring the 1930s, in [[Stockholm]], as a secretary of state, von Numers interfered with the so-called Maydell affair, for example, by granting [[Nansen passport]] to [[Russian citizen]] residing in [[Germany]],  Baron Karl Frederick Karl Viktor von Maydell-Felks (born 1899)  who was dubious to make a film in Finland.<ref name=ennenyt>[http://www.ennenjanyt.net/1-02/maydell.htm Jari Sedergren: Maydell-juttu. Ennen ja nyt 1/2002]</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{diplomat-stub}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Numers, Sigurd von}}\n[[Category:Finnish lawyers]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Finland to the Netherlands]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Finland to the United States]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Finland to India]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Finland to Thailand]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Finland to Indonesia]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Finland to Ireland]]\n[[Category:1903 births]]\n[[Category:1983 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Vyborg]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 1964-1970 \u2192 1964\u20131970", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sigurd_von_Numers"}
{"title_page": "King's Bench jurisdiction", "text_new": "'''King's Bench jurisdiction''' or '''King's Bench power''' is the extraordinary jurisdiction of an individual state's [[State supreme court|highest court]] over its inferior courts. In the [[United States]], the states of [[Pennsylvania]], [[Virginia]], [[Florida]], [[New Mexico]], [[New York (state)|New York]], [[Oklahoma]] and [[Wisconsin]]<ref name=\"aopc-kingsbench\">{{cite web |url=http://www.courts.state.pa.us/NR/rdonlyres/96F816DA-D829-4485-960E-642C92E866E5/0/8395AOPCChiefCounselTestifiesonKingsBenchAuthorityasSafetyValve.pdf |title=AOPC Chief Counsel Testifies on \"King's Bench\" Authority as an Important Safety Valve |date=August 3, 1995 |publisher=Administrative Office of Pennsylvania Courts |accessdate=2009-08-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/62TSIk5BI?url=http://www.courts.state.pa.us/NR/rdonlyres/96F816DA-D829-4485-960E-642C92E866E5/0/8395AOPCChiefCounselTestifiesonKingsBenchAuthorityasSafetyValve.pdf |archivedate=October 16, 2011 }}</ref> use the term to describe the extraordinary jurisdiction of their highest court, called the Court of Appeals in New York or the [[Supreme court|Supreme Court]] in the other states, over the courts below it. King's Bench jurisdiction includes the power to [[vacated judgment|vacate]] the judgments of inferior courts when acting in extraordinary circumstances, for example, where the importance of an issue to public well-being or the expediency with which action must be taken in the interest of justice requires superseding normal judicial or [[appellate court|appellate]] procedures. Federal courts in the United States possess the power to issue similar extraordinary writs under the [[All Writs Act]]. The term originates from the English [[Court of King's Bench (England)|Court of King\u2019s Bench]].\n[[File:Court of King's Bench.JPG|thumb|right|upright|250px|The Court of King's Bench at work.  This [[illuminated manuscript]] from about 1460 is the earliest known depiction of the English court. It shows the judges of the court, clerks, lawyers and, at the bottom of the illustration, guards watching chained prisoners awaiting trial.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.innertemplelibrary.org.uk/collections/manuscript-collection/manuscript-collection.htm |title=Manuscript Collection |publisher=[[Inner Temple Library]] |accessdate=26 August 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100822181850/http://www.innertemplelibrary.org.uk/collections/manuscript-collection/manuscript-collection.htm |archive-date=22 August 2010 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref>]]\n==Pennsylvania==\nThe [[Province of Pennsylvania]], also known as the [[Pennsylvania Colony]], was an [[Kingdom of England|English]] [[proprietary colony]] from the time of its [[royal charter]] in 1681 until the [[American Revolution]] in 1776 when Pennsylvania adopted its first [[Pennsylvania Constitution|Constitution]]. In Pennsylvania, King's Bench power refers to an [[Kingdom of England|English]] [[common law]] authority which the General Assembly recognized and explicitly bestowed in 1722 on the [[Supreme Court of Pennsylvania]], granting that court by [[charter]] constitutional authority over legal and supervisory aspects of the court system in the English [[colony]].<ref name=king>{{cite news |url=http://www.mcall.com/news/nationworld/pennsylvania/mc-pa-mccaffery-spended-porne-email-reaction-20141022-story.html#page=1 |title=McCaffery suspension may pit King's Power against will of the people |newspaper=The Morning Call |date=October 22, 2014 |accessdate=22 Feb 2015}}</ref> \n\nAs presently-codified, Pennsylvania statutes state that, \"Notwithstanding any other provision of law, the Supreme Court may, on its own motion or upon petition of any party, in any matter pending before any court ... involving an issue of immediate public importance, assume plenary jurisdiction of such matter at any stage thereof and enter a final order or otherwise cause right and justice to be done.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.vindy.com/news/2015/mar/09/pa-governors-moratorium-on-executions-tr |title=Pa. governor's moratorium on executions triggers legal battle |newspaper=The Youngstown Vindicator |date=March 9, 2015 |accessdate=18 Mar 2015}}</ref><ref>[http://www.legis.state.pa.us/cfdocs/legis/LI/consCheck.cfm?txtType=HTM&ttl=42&div=0&chpt=7&sctn=26&subsctn=0 Pennsylvania Statutes, Title 42, \u00a7 726. Extraordinary jurisdiction. ]</ref>\n\nThe King`s Bench Powers also are described in Pennsylvania Statutes Title 42, \u00a7 502, in language taken from the 1722 Act: \n\n{{quote|The Supreme Court shall have and exercise the powers vested in it by the Constitution of Pennsylvania, including the power generally to minister justice to all persons and to exercise the powers of the court, as fully and amply, to all intents and purposes, as the justices of the Court of King's Bench, Common Pleas and Exchequer, at Westminster, or any of them, could or might do on May 22, 1722. \u2002The Supreme Court shall also have and exercise the following powers: (1)\u2002All powers necessary or appropriate in aid of its original and appellate jurisdiction which are agreeable to the usages and principles of law. (2)\u2002The powers vested in it by statute, including the provisions of this title.}}\n\nThe Pennsylvania Supreme Court held in ''In re Bruno,'' 101 A.3d 635, 677, 627 Pa. 505, 575 (2014), however, that its King`s Bench powers are constitutionally-inherent and are not dependent upon any statute:\n\n{{quote|[T]he jurisdiction necessary to the exercise of the Court's King's Bench powers\u2014constitutionally-granted powers that are by nature comprehensive and inherently vested in the highest authority of the judicial branch\u2014may be divested only by the people, expressly or by necessary implication. See ''Ebersoll,'' 3 Binn. at 531 (\u201cIt is fully settled that the jurisdiction of the Court of King's Bench is not ousted unless by express words.\u201d); accord ''Stander,'' 250 A.2d at 487 (Roberts, J., concurring) (General Assembly has no constitutional authority to diminish, curtail or interfere with functions of Supreme Court); ''Robinson Twp.,'' 83 A.3d at 977 (citing ''Commonwealth ex rel. Carroll v. Tate,'' 442 Pa. 45, 274 A.2d 193, 196\u201397 (1971) ) (General Assembly has no authority to remove by statute attributes of governmental entity implicitly necessary to carry into effect entity's constitutional duties).}}\n\nTroubles and public feuds involved the supreme court in the early 1990s,<ref name=nyt>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/10/29/us/justice-charged-in-a-drug-scheme.html |title=Justice Charged In A Drug Scheme |newspaper=The New York Times |date=October 29, 1993}}</ref> specifically including Justice [[Rolf Larsen]], who was criminally convicted and impeached by the house, then subsequently convicted and removed from office by the state senate,<ref name=larsen>{{cite web |url=http://www.pennlive.com/politics/index.ssf/2014/08/rolf_larsen_remembered_for_imp.html |title=Rolf Larsen remembered for impact on state policy, not his impeachment |publisher=PennLive.com |date=August 13, 2014}}</ref>. The public image of Larsen illustrated the need for court reform. The upheaval surrounding Justice Larsen's time on the bench served as a catalyst for a change in the state judicial discipline system.<ref name=larsen /> Pennsylvanians for Modern Courts credits the public turmoil he caused with leading to the overwhelming passage of a constitutional amendment that strengthened the way judges are disciplined for misconduct.<ref name=larsen /> In 1993, Pennsylvania voters amended the state constitution. The change created a new system for the oversight of judges through a state Judicial Conduct Board, which independently investigates misconduct complaints, and a Court of Judicial Discipline, which independently determines a Pennsylvania judge's innocence or guilt,<ref name=king />. The supreme court, nevertheless, retains ultimate power over the Commonwealth`s judicial system and judges.\n\nFor an example of the exercise of King's Bench jurisdiction, see the Pennsylvania [[Kids for cash scandal|\"kids for cash\" scandal]].\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== News Articles ==\n*{{cite news |url=http://www.mcall.com/news/nationworld/pennsylvania/mc-pa-mccaffery-spended-porne-email-reaction-20141022-story.html#page=1 |title=Justice McCaffery suspension may pit King's Power against will of the people | newspaper=The Morning Call |date=October 22, 2014}}\n\n[[Category:State court systems of the United States]]\n", "text_old": "'''King's Bench jurisdiction''' or '''King's Bench power''' is the extraordinary jurisdiction of an individual state's [[State supreme court|highest court]] over its inferior courts. In the [[United States]], the states of [[Pennsylvania]], [[Virginia]], [[Florida]], [[New Mexico]], [[New York (state)|New York]], [[Oklahoma]] and [[Wisconsin]]<ref name=\"aopc-kingsbench\">{{cite web |url=http://www.courts.state.pa.us/NR/rdonlyres/96F816DA-D829-4485-960E-642C92E866E5/0/8395AOPCChiefCounselTestifiesonKingsBenchAuthorityasSafetyValve.pdf |title=AOPC Chief Counsel Testifies on \"King's Bench\" Authority as an Important Safety Valve |date=August 3, 1995 |publisher=Administrative Office of Pennsylvania Courts |accessdate=2009-08-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/62TSIk5BI?url=http://www.courts.state.pa.us/NR/rdonlyres/96F816DA-D829-4485-960E-642C92E866E5/0/8395AOPCChiefCounselTestifiesonKingsBenchAuthorityasSafetyValve.pdf |archivedate=October 16, 2011 }}</ref> use the term to describe the extraordinary jurisdiction of their highest court, called the Court of Appeals in New York or the [[Supreme court|Supreme Court]] in the other states, over the courts below it. King's Bench jurisdiction includes the power to [[vacated judgment|vacate]] the judgments of inferior courts when acting in extraordinary circumstances, for example, where the importance of an issue to public well-being or the expediency with which action must be taken in the interest of justice requires superseding normal judicial or [[appellate court|appellate]] procedures. Federal courts in the United States possess the power to issue similar extraordinary writs under the [[All Writs Act]]. The term originates from the English [[Court of King's Bench (England)|Court of King`s Bench]].\n[[File:Court of King's Bench.JPG|thumb|right|upright|250px|The Court of King's Bench at work.  This [[illuminated manuscript]] from about 1460 is the earliest known depiction of the English court. It shows the judges of the court, clerks, lawyers and, at the bottom of the illustration, guards watching chained prisoners awaiting trial.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.innertemplelibrary.org.uk/collections/manuscript-collection/manuscript-collection.htm |title=Manuscript Collection |publisher=[[Inner Temple Library]] |accessdate=26 August 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100822181850/http://www.innertemplelibrary.org.uk/collections/manuscript-collection/manuscript-collection.htm |archive-date=22 August 2010 |url-status=dead |df= }}</ref>]]\n==Pennsylvania==\nThe [[Province of Pennsylvania]], also known as the [[Pennsylvania Colony]], was an [[Kingdom of England|English]] [[proprietary colony]] from the time of its [[royal charter]] in 1681 until the [[American Revolution]] in 1776 when Pennsylvania adopted its first [[Pennsylvania Constitution|Constitution]]. In Pennsylvania, King's Bench power refers to an [[Kingdom of England|English]] [[common law]] authority which the General Assembly recognized and explicitly bestowed in 1722 on the [[Supreme Court of Pennsylvania]], granting that court by [[charter]] constitutional authority over legal and supervisory aspects of the court system in the English [[colony]].<ref name=king>{{cite news |url=http://www.mcall.com/news/nationworld/pennsylvania/mc-pa-mccaffery-spended-porne-email-reaction-20141022-story.html#page=1 |title=McCaffery suspension may pit King's Power against will of the people |newspaper=The Morning Call |date=October 22, 2014 |accessdate=22 Feb 2015}}</ref> \n\nAs presently-codified, Pennsylvania statutes state that, \"Notwithstanding any other provision of law, the Supreme Court may, on its own motion or upon petition of any party, in any matter pending before any court ... involving an issue of immediate public importance, assume plenary jurisdiction of such matter at any stage thereof and enter a final order or otherwise cause right and justice to be done.\"<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.vindy.com/news/2015/mar/09/pa-governors-moratorium-on-executions-tr |title=Pa. governor's moratorium on executions triggers legal battle |newspaper=The Youngstown Vindicator |date=March 9, 2015 |accessdate=18 Mar 2015}}</ref><ref>[http://www.legis.state.pa.us/cfdocs/legis/LI/consCheck.cfm?txtType=HTM&ttl=42&div=0&chpt=7&sctn=26&subsctn=0 Pennsylvania Statutes, Title 42, \u00a7 726. Extraordinary jurisdiction. ]</ref>\n\nThe King`s Bench Powers also are described in Pennsylvania Statutes Title 42, \u00a7 502, in language taken from the 1722 Act: \n\n{{quote|The Supreme Court shall have and exercise the powers vested in it by the Constitution of Pennsylvania, including the power generally to minister justice to all persons and to exercise the powers of the court, as fully and amply, to all intents and purposes, as the justices of the Court of King's Bench, Common Pleas and Exchequer, at Westminster, or any of them, could or might do on May 22, 1722. \u2002The Supreme Court shall also have and exercise the following powers: (1)\u2002All powers necessary or appropriate in aid of its original and appellate jurisdiction which are agreeable to the usages and principles of law. (2)\u2002The powers vested in it by statute, including the provisions of this title.}}\n\nThe Pennsylvania Supreme Court held in ''In re Bruno,'' 101 A.3d 635, 677, 627 Pa. 505, 575 (2014), however, that its King`s Bench powers are constitutionally-inherent and are not dependent upon any statute:\n\n{{quote|[T]he jurisdiction necessary to the exercise of the Court's King's Bench powers\u2014constitutionally-granted powers that are by nature comprehensive and inherently vested in the highest authority of the judicial branch\u2014may be divested only by the people, expressly or by necessary implication. See ''Ebersoll,'' 3 Binn. at 531 (\u201cIt is fully settled that the jurisdiction of the Court of King's Bench is not ousted unless by express words.\u201d); accord ''Stander,'' 250 A.2d at 487 (Roberts, J., concurring) (General Assembly has no constitutional authority to diminish, curtail or interfere with functions of Supreme Court); ''Robinson Twp.,'' 83 A.3d at 977 (citing ''Commonwealth ex rel. Carroll v. Tate,'' 442 Pa. 45, 274 A.2d 193, 196\u201397 (1971) ) (General Assembly has no authority to remove by statute attributes of governmental entity implicitly necessary to carry into effect entity's constitutional duties).}}\n\nTroubles and public feuds involved the supreme court in the early 1990s,<ref name=nyt>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1993/10/29/us/justice-charged-in-a-drug-scheme.html |title=Justice Charged In A Drug Scheme |newspaper=The New York Times |date=October 29, 1993}}</ref> specifically including Justice [[Rolf Larsen]], who was criminally convicted and impeached by the house, then subsequently convicted and removed from office by the state senate,<ref name=larsen>{{cite web |url=http://www.pennlive.com/politics/index.ssf/2014/08/rolf_larsen_remembered_for_imp.html |title=Rolf Larsen remembered for impact on state policy, not his impeachment |publisher=PennLive.com |date=August 13, 2014}}</ref>. The public image of Larsen illustrated the need for court reform. The upheaval surrounding Justice Larsen's time on the bench served as a catalyst for a change in the state judicial discipline system.<ref name=larsen /> Pennsylvanians for Modern Courts credits the public turmoil he caused with leading to the overwhelming passage of a constitutional amendment that strengthened the way judges are disciplined for misconduct.<ref name=larsen /> In 1993, Pennsylvania voters amended the state constitution. The change created a new system for the oversight of judges through a state Judicial Conduct Board, which independently investigates misconduct complaints, and a Court of Judicial Discipline, which independently determines a Pennsylvania judge's innocence or guilt,<ref name=king />. The supreme court, nevertheless, retains ultimate power over the Commonwealth`s judicial system and judges.\n\nFor an example of the exercise of King's Bench jurisdiction, see the Pennsylvania [[Kids for cash scandal|\"kids for cash\" scandal]].\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== News Articles ==\n*{{cite news |url=http://www.mcall.com/news/nationworld/pennsylvania/mc-pa-mccaffery-spended-porne-email-reaction-20141022-story.html#page=1 |title=Justice McCaffery suspension may pit King's Power against will of the people | newspaper=The Morning Call |date=October 22, 2014}}\n\n[[Category:State court systems of the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Gabrieldawiki", "label": "safe", "comment": "Minor punctuation fix", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/King%27s_Bench_jurisdiction"}
{"title_page": "Rafael Molina Morillo", "text_new": "{{cleanup-biography|date=April 2017}}\n'''Dr. Rafael Molina Morillo''' (March 30, 1930 \u2013 2 April 2017) was a [[lawyer]], [[journalist]], [[diplomat]], and newspaper editor from the [[Dominican Republic]].  He created Ahora! Publications which published [[El Nacional (Santo Domingo)|El Nacional]] newspaper and Ahora! magazine. He also was editor of [[List\u00edn Diario]] newspaper and El Dia, a free newspaper in the Dominican Republic.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.diariolibre.com/noticias/muere-emblematico-periodista-rafael-molina-morillo-YE6723100|title=Muere emblem\u00e1tico periodista Rafael Molina Morillo|date=2 April 2017|work=Diario Libre|access-date=2017-04-14|language=es-ES}}</ref>\n\nMorillo was president of the [[Inter-American Press Association]] for the year 2006\u201307,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sipiapa.com/v4/index.php?page=cont_multimedia&idioma=sp&seccion=detalle&gal=5&id=12|title=Inicio- Sociedad Interamericana de Prensa|work=sipiapa.com|accessdate=5 April 2017}}</ref> succeeding [[Diana Daniels]], of [[The Washington Post]]. He died on 2 April 2017.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.listindiario.com/la-republica/2017/04/12/461722/sip-rendira-homenaje-a-rafael-molina-morillo-por-trayectoria|title=SIP rendir\u00e1 homenaje a Rafael Molina Morillo por trayectoria|last=Herrera|first=Dalton|date=12 April 2017|work=Listin Diario|access-date=2017-04-14|language=es}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Molina Morillo, Rafael}}\n[[Category:1930 births]]\n[[Category:2017 deaths]]\n[[Category:Dominican Republic diplomats]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of the Dominican Republic to the United States]]\n{{DominicanRepublic-diplomat-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{cleanup-biography|date=April 2017}}\n'''Dr. Rafael Molina Morillo''' (March 30, 1930 \u2013 2 April 2017) was a [[lawyer]], [[journalist]], [[diplomat]], and newspaper editor from the [[Dominican Republic]].  He created Ahora! Publications which published [[El Nacional (Santo Domingo)|El Nacional]] newspaper and Ahora! magazine. He also was editor of [[List\u00edn Diario]] newspaper and El Dia, a free newspaper in the Dominican Republic.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.diariolibre.com/noticias/muere-emblematico-periodista-rafael-molina-morillo-YE6723100|title=Muere emblem\u00e1tico periodista Rafael Molina Morillo|date=2 April 2017|work=Diario Libre|access-date=2017-04-14|language=es-ES}}</ref>\n\nMorillo was president of the [[Inter-American Press Association]] for the year 2006-07,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://sipiapa.com/v4/index.php?page=cont_multimedia&idioma=sp&seccion=detalle&gal=5&id=12|title=Inicio- Sociedad Interamericana de Prensa|work=sipiapa.com|accessdate=5 April 2017}}</ref> succeeding [[Diana Daniels]], of [[The Washington Post]]. He died on 2 April 2017.<ref name=\":0\" /><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.listindiario.com/la-republica/2017/04/12/461722/sip-rendira-homenaje-a-rafael-molina-morillo-por-trayectoria|title=SIP rendir\u00e1 homenaje a Rafael Molina Morillo por trayectoria|last=Herrera|first=Dalton|date=12 April 2017|work=Listin Diario|access-date=2017-04-14|language=es}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Molina Morillo, Rafael}}\n[[Category:1930 births]]\n[[Category:2017 deaths]]\n[[Category:Dominican Republic diplomats]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of the Dominican Republic to the United States]]\n{{DominicanRepublic-diplomat-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 2006-07 \u2192 2006\u201307", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rafael_Molina_Morillo"}
{"title_page": "Eric Schmitt", "text_new": "{{about|the politician|others|Eric Schmitt (disambiguation)}}\n{{short description|American politician and lawyer}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{Blacklisted-links|1=\n*http://www.lawyers.com/Missouri/Clayton/Lathrop-and-Gage-L.C.-5129555-f.html\n*:''Triggered by <code>\\blawyers\\.com\\b</code> on the local blacklist''|bot=Cyberbot II|invisible=true}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name          = Eric Schmitt\n|image         = Open Schmitt2020.png\n|office        = [[List of Attorneys General of Missouri|43rd]] [[Missouri Attorney General]]\n|governor      = [[Mike Parson]]\n|term_start    = January 3, 2019\n|term_end      = \n|predecessor   = [[Josh Hawley]]\n|successor     = \n|office1       = 46th [[State Treasurer of Missouri|Treasurer of Missouri]]\n|governor1     = [[Eric Greitens]]<br>Mike Parson\n|term_start1   = January 9, 2017\n|term_end1     = January 3, 2019\n|predecessor1  = [[Clint Zweifel]]\n|successor1    = [[Scott Fitzpatrick]]\n|state_senate2 = Missouri\n|district2     = 15th\n|term_start2   = January 7, 2009\n|term_end2     = January 4, 2017\n|predecessor2  = [[Michael R. Gibbons]]\n|successor2    = [[Andrew Koenig (politician)|Andrew Koenig]]\n|office3       = Member of the [[Glendale, Missouri|Glendale]] City Council<br>from Ward 3\n|term_start3   = 2005\n|term_end3     = 2008\n|predecessor3  = Richard Magee<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.glendalemo.org:80/Files/mayor&board.htm |title=Mayor & Board |publisher=City of Glendale, Missouri |archive-date=February 5, 2005 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050205051821/http://www.glendalemo.org/Files/mayor%26board.htm |access-date=August 10, 2019 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n|successor3    = Dan Sullivan<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.glendalemo.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/Glendale-Guide-Summer-2008.pdf |magazine=Glendale Guide |date=Summer 2008 |title=Sullivan elected new alderman for Ward III |access-date=January 9, 2019 |publisher=City of Glendale, Missouri |page=1 }}</ref>\n|birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1975|6|20}}\n|birth_place   = [[Bridgeton, Missouri]], U.S.\n|death_date    = \n|death_place   = \n|party         = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|spouse        = Jaime Schmitt\n|children      = 3\n|education     = [[Truman State University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br>[[Saint Louis University]] ([[Juris Doctor|JD]])\n|website       = {{url|http://www.ago.mo.gov/|Government website}}\n}}\n'''Eric S. Schmitt''' (born June 20, 1975) is an American politician who has been serving as the [[Missouri Attorney General|43rd Attorney General of Missouri]] since 2019. He previously served as the [[State Treasurer of Missouri|46th State Treasurer of Missouri]] from 2017 to 2019. Before that, he was a member of the [[Missouri Senate]], representing [[Missouri|Missouri's]] 15th State Senate District from 2009 to 2017. He had also previously served as an [[alderman]] for [[Glendale, Missouri]] from 2005 to 2008, where he was one of two aldermen for Ward 3.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.webstercountycitizen.com/news/article_fb16fd20-0f9e-11e9-b588-0f57c31fa636.html|title=Eric Schmitt sworn in as Missouri\u2019s 43rd Attorney General|website=Webster County Citizen|access-date=January 23, 2019}}</ref> On November 13, 2018, Schmitt was named Attorney General of Missouri by [[Governor of Missouri|Governor]] [[Mike Parson]], after the incumbent, [[Josh Hawley]], was [[2018 United States Senate election in Missouri|elected]] to the [[United States Senate]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.stltoday.com/news/local/govt-and-politics/state-treasurer-eric-schmitt-to-become-missouri-ag-after-hawley/article_aaa317fe-6919-5fe8-b48b-9b0a738fea37.html |title= State Treasurer Eric Schmitt to become Missouri AG after Hawley elected to Senate |newspaper=[[St. Louis Post-Dispatch]] |first=Jack |last=Suntrup |date=November 13, 2018 |access-date=November 13, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.kcur.org/post/missouris-next-attorney-general-will-be-state-treasurer-eric-schmitt |title= Missouri's Next Attorney General Will Be State Treasurer Eric Schmitt |publisher=[[KCUR-FM]] |date=November 13, 2018 |first=Samuel |last=King |access-date=November 13, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nBorn in [[Bridgeton, Missouri]], Schmitt is a sixth-generation Missourian and a lifelong resident of [[St. Louis County, Missouri|St. Louis County]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://schmittformissouri.com/meet-eric/|title=Meet Eric Schmitt - Eric Schmitt|access-date=September 19, 2016}}</ref>\n\nSchmitt graduated from [[DeSmet Jesuit High School]] in 1993 and from [[Truman State University]] in 1997, where he earned a [[Bachelor of Arts]] ''[[cum laude]]'' in [[political science]]. At Truman, Schmitt was a member of the [[Alpha Kappa Lambda]] fraternity, played football and baseball, and was a founding member of Truman's [[Habitat for Humanity]] chapter. He received a scholarship to attend [[Saint Louis University School of Law]], where he earned his [[Juris Doctor]] in 2000.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.senate.mo.gov/15info/Members/D15/bio.htm|title=Senator Eric Schmitt|website=www.senate.mo.gov|access-date=September 19, 2016}}</ref> Schmitt was an editor of the law review and published an article analyzing the [[Supreme Court of the United States|Supreme Court]] decision in ''[[Clinton v. New York]]''.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Schmitt|first=Eric S.|title=There Is No Joy in D.C., The Mighty Court Struck Out: An Analysis of ''Clinton v. City of New York'', The Line Item Veto Act and the Court's Failure to Uphold Constitutionally Legitimate Means to a Viable End|journal=St. Louis University Law Journal|volume=44|date=Winter 2000|page=167}}</ref>\n\nSchmitt lives in Glendale and attends Mary, Queen of Peace Catholic Church with his wife, Jaime, and their three children, Stephen, Sophia and Olivia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://schmittformissouri.com/meet-eric/|title=Meet Eric Schmitt - Eric Schmitt|access-date=September 19, 2016}}</ref>  He is currently an adjunct professor in the Department of Philosophy at [[Saint Louis University]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.stltoday.com/news/local/education/notes-from-campus/missouri-treasurer-picks-up-a-class-at-slu-as-the/article_54da2d1c-a2c3-5742-b628-27d60bf5e0c6.html|title=Missouri treasurer picks up a class at SLU \u2014 as the teacher |last=Jost |first=Ashley|work=stltoday.com|access-date=February 20, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Legal career==\nSchmitt was [[Admission to the bar in the United States|admitted to the Missouri bar]] in 2000. He was a partner at the firm [[Lathrop & Gage|Lathrop & Gage, LLP]], in [[Clayton, Missouri]], where he focused on land use, real estate, business disputes, and administrative appeals. In his community, he has been an active member for the boards of DeSmet Jesuit High School, Nurses for Newborns Foundation, St. Louis Crisis Nursery, and a Parents as Teachers Program. He had previously been elected chairman of the Young Lawyer Section Council of the Missouri Bar, led a statewide [[Giving Tree]] effort to benefit [[Big Brothers Big Sisters of America]], and created a Special Needs Advocacy Task Force. He has also been involved with the TS (Tuberous Sclerosis) Alliance, the Gateway Chapter of the [[Autism Society of America]], Habitat for Humanity, and local Chambers of Commerce.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://claytontimes.com/lathrop-gage-congratulates-schmitt-being-appointed-attorney-general/|title=Lathrop Gage congratulates Schmitt being appointed Attorney General|last=Franklin|first=Danielle Mae|date=November 13, 2018|website=Clayton Times|access-date=January 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==State Senate (2009\u20132017)==\nSchmitt served as an alderman for Glendale, Missouri, from 2005 to 2008. On November 4, 2008, Schmitt was elected to the Missouri Senate. When sworn in, Schmitt became one of the youngest members ever to serve in the state's upper chamber. He represented Missouri's 15th State Senate district, which includes parts of central and western [[St. Louis County, Missouri|St. Louis County]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.senate.mo.gov/15info/Members/D15/bio.htm|title=Senator Eric Schmitt|website=www.senate.mo.gov|access-date=September 19, 2016}}</ref> Following the [[2010 United States Census|2010 census]], Schmitt's district was redrawn, although it is still centered around central St. Louis County. On February 28, 2012, Schmitt filed for reelection in the 15th district. He ran unopposed in both the primary and general elections in 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sos.mo.gov/CandidatesonWeb/DisplayCandidatesPlacement.aspx?OfficeCode=SE-N15&ElectionCode=750002299|title=Certified Candidate List - State Senator - District 15|publisher=Missouri Secretary of State|accessdate=June 15, 2012}}</ref>\n\nSchmitt served in Senate Leadership as Majority Caucus Chairman and was Chairman of the Jobs, Economic Development and Local Government Committee. He also served on the Committee on Gubernatorial Appointments; the Committee on Judicial, Civil, and Criminal Jurisprudence; Veterans\u2019 Affairs and Health Committee; and Chaired the Joint Committee on Administrative Rules.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.senate.mo.gov/15info/Members/D15/bio.htm|title=Senator Eric Schmitt|website=www.senate.mo.gov|access-date=September 19, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn addition, Schmitt worked to enact the federal ABLE Act, to provide 529 savings account opportunities to families with children with special needs, to cover their future costs and allow them to be more financially independent and self-sufficient. The Missouri ABLE program allows anyone to make a tax-deductible contribution of up to $8,000 for an individual or $16,000 for married couples to another person's ABLE account.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.semissourian.com/story/2209170.html|title=Governor signs bill allowing savings accounts for disabilities|date=June 30, 2015|access-date=September 23, 2016}}</ref> The bill sponsored by Schmitt was signed by the Governor in 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://themissouritimes.com/19154/missouri-legislators-continue-autism-successes-with-bill-signature/|title=Missouri legislators continue autism successes with bill signature - The Missouri Times|website=themissouritimes.com |access-date=September 23, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Schmitt sponsored a bill (S.B. 572) that set a limit on the percent of revenue that Missouri local governments could obtain from non-traffic fines (such as fines for violation of city ordinances). Existing state law had set a revenue limit on the percent of revenue that municipalities could obtain from traffic fines The bill passed the state Senate in a 25\u20136 vote in January 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stltoday.com/news/local/govt-and-politics/cap-on-non-traffic-violation-revenue-passed-by-missouri-senate/article_093cffb2-67a6-54f6-97b8-7bc6f4e3a986.html|title=Cap on non-traffic violation revenue passed by Missouri Senate |last=Stuckey|first=Alex|access-date=September 19, 2016}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the unrest in Ferguson, Schmitt identified that too many municipalities were too reliant on fines to fund their budgets. He led the bipartisan legislative effort to bar cities, counties and law-enforcement agencies from setting traffic-ticket quotas as well as taxation by citation. Schmitt worked with Democratic Sen. Jamilah Nasheed and others on the legislation, which passed the state Senate in February 2016 and was enacted into law. <ref>https://www.stltoday.com/news/local/govt-and-politics/attorney-general-seeks-to-revive-ferguson-inspired-police-and-court/article_59777f9a-484e-575b-b92c-67643921e859.amp.html</ref> <ref>https://news.stlpublicradio.org/post/nixon-signs-bill-mandating-municipal-court-changes-and-setting-standards#stream/0</ref> <ref>https://www.wsj.com/articles/taxation-by-citation-undermines-trust-between-cops-and-citizens-1438987412</ref>\n\nSchmitt was absent in the 2013 failed vote to pass the [[LGBT rights in Missouri|Missouri Nondiscrimination Act]], and supported a 2016 failed measure to protect businesses that oppose same-sex marriages for religious reasons.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stltoday.com/news/local/govt-and-politics/missouri-attorney-general-challenges-nationwide-expansion-of-lgbt-rights-by/article_d147f283-329f-5624-a814-baf956a902c9.html|title=Missouri attorney general challenges nationwide expansion of LGBT rights by the courts|last=Suntrup|first=Jack|date=2019-08-26|website=St. Louis Post-Dispatch|language=en|access-date=2019-08-26}}</ref>\n\n==2016 election for State Treasurer==\nSchmitt did not run for re-election to the [[Missouri Senate|Missouri State Senate]] in 2016 because he was term-limited. Instead, Schmitt filed to run for [[State Treasurer of Missouri|Treasurer of Missouri]] in the [[2016 Missouri State Treasurer election|2016 elections]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://krcgtv.com/news/local/schmitt-running-for-mo-treasurer-in-2016|title=Schmitt running for MO treasurer in 2016|last=Group|first=Sinclair Broadcast|language=en-US|access-date=September 29, 2016}}</ref> Schmitt ran as a Republican and was unopposed in the Republican primary.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://s1.sos.mo.gov/candidatesonweb/DisplayCandidatesPlacement.aspx?OfficeCode=SW20&ElectionCode=750003666|title=SOS, Missouri - Elections: Offices Filed in Candidate Filing|website=s1.sos.mo.gov |access-date=September 29, 2016}}</ref> He defeated opponents Democrat [[Judy Baker]] and Libertarian Sean O'Toole in the general election.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://enrarchives.sos.mo.gov/enrnet/|title=State of Missouri - Election Night Results |website=enrarchives.sos.mo.gov|access-date=September 29, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Missouri State Treasurer (2017\u20132019)==\nAs State Treasurer, Schmitt oversaw the state's $3.6 billion investment portfolio as its Chief Financial Officer and also managed a number of different programs and initiatives.\n\n===Missouri Economic Dashboard===\n\nThe Missouri State Treasurer's Office developed a dashboard that shows economic data and trends, including unemployment, GDP, exports, housing starts, and other indicators.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.govtech.com/internet/Missouri-Treasurers-Dashboard-Compares-State-National-Financial-Metrics.html|title=Missouri Treasurer's Dashboard Compares State, National Financial Metrics |website=www.govtech.com|access-date=April 4, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Unclaimed property===\n\nSchmitt returned more unclaimed property in his first year than any previous treasurer in Missouri history. Treasurer Schmitt returned $45 million in unclaimed property during his first year in office, surpassing the previous record of $29 million.\n\nMost unclaimed property consists of cash from bank accounts, stocks, bonds and contents of safe deposit boxes that have been abandoned.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.treasurer.mo.gov/newsroom/news-and-events/2018/01/09/schmitt-returns-$45-million-of-unclaimed-property-in-first-year-as-treasurer-breaking-previous-record|title=Schmitt returns $45 million of Unclaimed Property in first year as treasurer, breaking previous record|website=www.treasurer.mo.gov|language=en|access-date=April 4, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Missouri ABLE===\nIn 2014, Congress passed the Stephen Beck Jr., Achieving a Better Life Experience (ABLE) Act to allow eligible individuals with disabilities to save money while still allowing those individuals to be eligible for federal needs-based benefits. In June 2015, then-Senator Eric Schmitt passed the state legislation, making the state a leader in the ABLE movement. Missouri ABLE was launched in April 2017.\n\nIndividuals receiving support through Social Security, Medicaid and other publicly funded programs are often disqualified from that support if they have more than $2,000 worth of resources or assets. The MO ABLE program allows qualified individuals with disabilities to save up to $14,000 a year in an ABLE account without jeopardizing their eligibility for federally funded means tested benefits, such as Supplemental Security Income (SSI) and Medicaid. The funds in the account can be used for disability-related expenses that assist the beneficiary in increasing and/or maintaining his or her health, independence or quality of life.\n\nMissouri residents who contribute to a MO ABLE account may deduct up to $8,000 (single) or $16,000 (joint) on the state income tax deduction.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ablenrc.org/news/missouri-becomes-20th-state-launch-able-program|title=Missouri Becomes 20th State to Launch ABLE Program {{!}} ABLE National Resource Center|website=www.ablenrc.org|language=en|access-date=April 4, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Missouri FIRST===\n\nSchmitt launched the Missouri FIRST initiative in March 2018. Missouri FIRST (Financing Investment in our Rural, Small Business and Technology communities) was aimed at allowing Schmitt to invest more in Main Street Missouri by revamping the state's linked deposit program, which partners with local lenders to provide low-interest financing to small business and agricultural operations. The changes implemented through Missouri FIRST focused on cutting red tape, expanding access and modernizing the linked deposit system.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.treasurer.mo.gov/content/low-interest-loans|title=Missouri State Treasurer's Office - Missouri Linked Deposit Program|website=www.treasurer.mo.gov|language=en|access-date=April 4, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===MOST 529===\n\nAs State Treasurer, Schmitt administered MOST 529, a tax-advantaged program that empowers Missouri families to save for a child's K-12 tuition and other qualified higher education expenses. Missourians who contribute to MOST 529 accounts are eligible for a tax deduction of up to $8,000 or $16,000 if married and filing jointly. Earnings in 529 accounts are also not subject to federal income tax, so long as funds are spent on qualified expenses.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.missourimost.org/home/basics-of-529s/529-basics.html|title=529 basics {{!}} MOST 529|website=MOST\u2014Missouri's 529 College Savings Plan|access-date=April 4, 2018}}</ref>\n\nPrior to the passage of federal tax reform in December 2017, MOST 529 plans were limited to higher education expenses. Included in the Tax Cuts and Jobs Act of 2017 was language that allowed states to expand their programs to K-12 tuition, which Schmitt implemented in Missouri.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.missourimost.org|title=MOST\u2014Missouri's 529 College Savings Plan {{!}} MOST 529|website=MOST\u2014Missouri's 529 College Savings Plan|access-date=April 4, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Missouri Attorney General==\nSchmitt was appointed to the office of [[Missouri Attorney General|Attorney General of Missouri]] by Governor [[Mike Parson]] to succeed [[Josh Hawley]], who was [[2018 United States Senate election in Missouri|elected]] to the [[United States Senate]] in 2018. Schmitt took office in January 2019.\n\n===First Amendment===\nIn August 2019, Schmitt withdrew a legal brief that argued that the [[First Amendment to the United States Constitution|First Amendment]] allowed government officials to withhold records from a [[Sunshine Law]] request, following criticism from transparency advocates who noted that the brief did not cite any case law.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.columbiamissourian.com/news/state_news/schmitt-withdraws-first-amendment-argument-in-lawsuit/article_1f829093-3294-5c02-9289-332ab3ddccf8.html|title=Schmitt withdraws First Amendment argument in lawsuit|last=Associated Press|date=Aug 20, 2019|website=Columbia Missourian|language=en|access-date=2019-08-26}}</ref> A Freedom Center of Missouri representative raised concern that the argument is similar to a case involving governor [[Mike Parson]], which Schmitt had not yet ruled on.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.kansascity.com/news/politics-government/article234150042.html|title=Missouri AG Schmitt cites First Amendment to block release of public records|last=Hancock|first=Jason|date=August 20, 2019|work=The Kansas City Star|access-date=2019-08-26}}</ref>\n\n===LGBTQ policies===\nSchmitt is among 14 attorney general signatories on a Supreme Court brief stating that the [[Civil Rights Act of 1964]] does not protect LGBTQ people from employment discrimination.<ref name=Hancock>{{Cite news|url=https://www.kansascity.com/news/politics-government/article234388257.html|title=Missouri attorney general says federal law doesn't ban LGBTQ discrimination|last=Hancock|first=Jason|date=August 26, 2019|work=The Kansas City Star|access-date=2019-08-26}}</ref> Schmitt said his signature \"should not be interpreted as speaking to the merits of the issue, but rather the interpretation of the law that is written,\" and that he believes \"every person, no matter their race, creed, ZIP code or gender, should be treated with dignity under the law\",<ref name=\"Hancock\" /> however critics dismiss this as \"legalese\" and \"on the wrong side of history.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.kansascity.com/opinion/editorials/article234396897.html|title=Missouri AG justifies LGBT discrimination with legalese. He's on wrong side of history|author=Editorial Board|date=August 27, 2019|work=The Kansas City Star|url-status=live|url-access=subscription|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190914023906/https://www.kansascity.com/opinion/editorials/article234396897.html|archive-date=September 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Religious freedom===\nIn 2019, Schmitt spoke in defense of a Missouri high school coach who was being attacked by the [[Freedom From Religion Foundation]]. The foundation accused the football coach of violating the [[Constitution of the United States|U.S. Constitution]] by leading students in prayer before and after games. In a letter, Schmitt said he would support the coach, school, and school district in a lawsuit if necessary and noted no one was forcing students and players to participate in prayer in public spaces.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://apnews.com/8163541b1efe40a9fd0944adcf588683 |title=Missouri attorney general backs high school football prayer |agency=Associated Press |date=December 6, 2019 |access-date=January 20, 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite press release |url=https://ago.mo.gov/docs/default-source/press-releases/2019/2019-12-3-ltr-cameronschooldistrict.pdf |date=December 3, 2019 |first=Eric |last=Schmitt |title=Letter to Cameron School District |access-date=January 20, 2020 |publisher=Attorney General of Missouri }}</ref>\n\n===Human trafficking ===\n\nSchmitt's Attorney General office has partnered with the FBI's Child Exploitation and Human Trafficking Task Force to combat human trafficking in Missouri.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.missourinet.com/2019/05/21/missouri-attorney-generals-office-joins-fb-efforts-to-fight-human-trafficking-exploiting-children/ |title=Missouri Attorney General's office joins FBI efforts to fight human trafficking, exploiting children |date=May 21, 2019 |website=Missourinet |first=Alisa |last=Nelson |access-date=February 7, 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ktvo.com/news/local/missouri-attorney-general-eric-schmitt-working-to-combat-human-trafficking |title=Missouri Attorney General Eric Schmitt working to combat human trafficking |date=May 14, 2019 |publisher=KTVO |first=Ashley |last=Hoak |access-date=February 7, 2020 }}</ref>\n\n===Prosecution of Antonio Muldrew===\nIn January 2020, Schmitt successfully prosecuted a murder case in the City of St. Louis. The jury returned a quick verdict finding Antonio Muldrew guilty of first-degree murder for shooting and killing Ethiopian refugee Abdulrauf Kadir at a convenience store in 2014. This was the first time a Missouri attorney general prosecuted a murder case in the City of St. Louis.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://fox2now.com/2020/01/09/missouri-attorney-general-obtains-guilty-verdict-in-st-louis-murder-case/ |title=Missouri attorney general obtains guilty verdict in St. Louis murder case |date=January 9, 2020 |first=Vic |last=Faust |publisher=Fox News |access-date=January 20, 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.ksdk.com/article/news/crime/ethiopian-refugee-dutchtown-store-guilty-murder/63-0ce6a782-27d3-4bd1-b29d-77894f0e50f7 |title=Man accused of killing Ethiopian refugee in Dutchtown store found guilty of murder, 5 other charges |first=Sam |last=Clancy |date=January 8, 2020 |publisher=KSDK |access-date=January 20, 2020 }}</ref>\n\n===Google antitrust investigation===\n \nIn September 2019, Schmitt and Attorneys General from throughout the U.S. launched an antitrust investigation against Google. The bipartisan group of state Attorneys General accuse Google of prioritizing searches for companies that advertise on the search engine platform.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.stlpublicradio.org/post/schmitt-joins-state-attorneys-general-investigating-google#stream/0 |title=Schmitt Joins State Attorneys General Investigating Google |date=September 9, 2019 |publisher=St. Louis Public Radio |first=Jaclyn |last=Driscoll |access-date=February 12, 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://molawyersmedia.com/2019/09/10/big-tech-faces-a-new-set-of-foes-nearly-all-50-u-s-states-2/ |title=Big Tech faces a new set of foes: nearly all 50 U.S. states |date=September 10, 2019 |website=Missouri Lawyers Media |agency=Associated Press |access-date=February 12, 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.ozarksfirst.com/attorney-general-eric-schmitt-apart-of-team-investigating-large-tech-companies |title=Attorney General Eric Schmitt apart of team investigating large tech companies |date=September 7, 2019 |access-date=February 12, 2020 |website=Ozarks First }}</ref>\n\n===Safer Streets Initiative===\n \nThe Safer Streets Initiative was unveiled in January 2019 by Schmitt to help get violent criminals off the street faster. The initiative is designed to address violent crime in St. Louis, Kansas City and Springfield, which have been ranked in the Top 15 for per capita violent crime rates. Schmitt says this is the first partnership in the country between the Missouri Attorney General's Office, U.S. Attorney's Office and various local law enforcement units to address violent crime.<ref>{{cite press release |url=https://www.ago.mo.gov/home/news-archives/2019/06/13/ag-schmitt-announces-safer-streets-initiative |title=AG Schmitt Announces Safer Streets Initiative |date=June 13, 2019 |publisher=Missouri Attorney General's Office |access-date=February 12, 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://fox4kc.com/2019/10/10/missouris-attorney-general-says-kcs-catch-and-release-of-criminals-must-end/ |title=Missouri's attorney general says KC's 'catch and release' of criminals must end |date=October 10, 2019 |website=FOX4 KC |first=John |last=Pepitone |access-date=February 12, 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.kmov.com/news/missouri-attorney-general-schmitt-unveils-safer-streets-initiative/article_d00aebd6-1e40-11e9-bce4-f33d50862a85.html |title=Missouri Attorney General Schmitt unveils 'Safer Streets' initiative |date=January 22, 2019 |publisher=KMOV |access-date=February 12, 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.stltoday.com/opinion/columnists/working-toward-safer-streets/article_aa2a676c-a208-5136-84e2-fa975f04c43b.html |title=Working toward safer streets |date=February 5, 2019 |newspaper=St. Louis Post-Dispatch |first=Eric |last=Schmitt |access-date=February 12, 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.ktrs.com/five-u-s-attorneys-sworn-in-for-safer-streets-initiative/ |title=Five U.S. Attorneys Sworn In for Safer Streets Initiative |date=April 11, 2019 |publisher=KTRS |access-date=February 12, 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.stltoday.com/news/local/crime-and-courts/joint-federal-state-effort-getting-violent-criminals-off-st-louis/article_aab47fa9-5b7c-5523-a948-2e23691e0ebe.html |title=Joint federal-state effort getting violent criminals off St. Louis streets, prosecutors say |date=October 8, 2019 |first=Robert |last=Patrick |newspaper=St. Louis Post-Dispatch |access-date=February 12, 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.stltoday.com/news/state-and-regional/indictments-brought-under-st-louis-anti-crime-effort/article_7ab5f825-f102-504e-b21c-893deb53bf2c.html |title=58 indictments brought under St. Louis anti-crime effort |newspaper=St. Louis Post-Dispatch |date=October 8, 2019 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191008225009/https://www.stltoday.com/news/state-and-regional/indictments-brought-under-st-louis-anti-crime-effort/article_7ab5f825-f102-504e-b21c-893deb53bf2c.html |archive-date=October 8, 2019 }}</ref>\n\n===Coronavirus Response===\n \nIn a letter to Circuit Attorney Kimberly M. Gardner, Schmitt expressed deep concern about inmates with violent felonies being released from jail during the coronavirus pandemic. He identified ten examples of violent criminals included in a list of over 100 people he said he has serious questions about. Schmitt said the record shows Gardner did not object to the release of these criminals and in many cases the victims or their families were not notified about the releases. <ref>https://www.stltoday.com/news/local/crime-and-courts/attorney-general-demands-list-of-defendants-released-from-st-louis-jails/article_2e683676-e2ec-5cad-835d-6c936de02ad0.html</ref> <ref>https://www.kmov.com/news/mother-of-hit-and-run-victim-furious-after-suspect-released-from-jail-due-to-covid/article_4fabb29c-7469-11ea-99e1-5b5cc05baedd.html?fbclid=IwAR0KstwO7X4OlwTd2-dW51se5A5Bzoa7FhC5i64SiWDPhxrmud6wfMxFWDw</ref> <ref>https://www.ksdk.com/article/news/crime/kim-gardner-st-louis-inmates-released-coronavirus-eric-schmitt/63-da823a97-a248-4a53-8890-242c0437fe17</ref>\n\nSchmitt partnered with private sector retailers including Amazon to combat scammers and price gougers attempting to profiteer off COVID-19.  The effort led to civil investigative demands for sellers in Missouri charging 2 to 19 times the prices they charged prior to the pandemic on items such as face masks and hand sanitizer. <ref>https://fox2now.com/news/coronavirus/missouri-attorney-general-reviewing-price-gouging-complaints/?fbclid=IwAR1Oun1G1AXksuacrr391nrkYikJE-09Cjqqucg8TdIA1YvKbYMAio6vbyA</ref> <ref>https://www.kfvs12.com/2020/03/30/attorney-general-schmitt-continues-war-price-gouging/?fbclid=IwAR1wmspnxBFeHhgV6lprjMPxY_cFQtBBCrLi9en_JEppx7eHktaNl5gJSAs</ref> <ref>https://www.joplinglobe.com/opinion/editorials/our-view-state-is-right-to-go-after-price-gouging-and-scams-during-pandemic/article_0f30c5af-c04d-59e6-b531-861d628d5072.html</ref>\n\nSchmitt ordered a Springfield-area man to cease-and-desist price gouging on N95 medical face masks. In addition to stopping the man from selling the masks, the effort led to a return to retailers at least 600 masks he had been hoarding. <ref>https://abc17news.com/news/coronavirus/2020/03/25/state-attorney-general-orders-springfield-man-to-stop-price-gouging-for-surgical-masks/</ref> <ref>https://www.ozarksfirst.com/local-news/eric-schmitt-issues-cease-and-desist-letter-to-springfield-man/</ref> \n\nIn March 2020, Schmitt filed a lawsuit against televangelist Jim Bakker and Morningside Church Productions, Inc. for misrepresentations about the effectiveness of \u201cSilver Solution\u201d as a treatment for COVID-19. <ref>https://thehill.com/regulation/court-battles/486865-missouri-ag-sues-jim-bakker-for-coronavirus-cure-claims</ref> <ref>https://news.stlpublicradio.org/post/missouri-sues-televangelist-jim-bakker-selling-fake-coronavirus-cure#stream/0</ref>\n\n==Electoral history==\n{{Election box begin | title=2008 Missouri State Senate - District 15<ref>{{cite web |publisher=Missouri Secretary of State |url=http://www.sos.mo.gov/enrweb/raceresults.asp?eid=256&oid=56352&arc=1 |title=State Senator - District 15 - Summary |accessdate=June 15, 2012}}</ref>}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n|  |party      = Republican Party (United States)\n  |candidate  = Eric Schmitt\n  |votes      = 51,366\n  |percentage = 54.7\n  |change     = \n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n|  |party      = Democratic Party (United States)\n  |candidate  = James Trout\n  |votes      = 42,469\n  |percentage = 45.3\n  |change     = \n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n{{Election box begin|title=2012 Missouri State Senate - District 15<ref>{{cite web |publisher=Missouri Secretary of State |url=http://enrarchives.sos.mo.gov/enrnet/PickaRace.aspx |title=State Senator - District 15 - Summary |accessdate=June 15, 2012}}</ref>}}{{Election box winning candidate with party link||candidate=Eric Schmitt|party=Republican Party (United States)|votes=77,745|percentage=100|change=+45.3}}{{Election box end}}\n\n{{Election box begin |title=Missouri Treasurer Election 2016<ref>{{cite web |url=https://enrarchives.sos.mo.gov/enrnet/default.aspx?eid=750003949 |title=State of Missouri - General Election, November 08, 2016 |date=December 12, 2016 |publisher=Missouri Secretary of State |access-date=November 13, 2018}}</ref>}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n  | |party = Republican Party (US)\n  |candidate  = Eric Schmitt\n  |votes      = 1,545,582\n  |percentage = 56.447%\n  |change     = Winner\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n  | |party = Democratic Party (US)\n  |candidate  = Judy Baker\n  |votes      = 1,078,063\n  |percentage = 39.372%\n  |change     = \n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n  | |party = Libertarian Party (US)\n  |candidate  = Sean O'Toole\n  |votes      = 78,543\n  |percentage = 2.868%\n  |change     = \n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n  | |party = Green Party (US)\n  |candidate  = Carol Hexem\n  |votes      = 66,490\n  |percentage = 1.312%\n  |change     = \n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090102055848/http://www.lathropgage.com/eschmitt/ Lathrop & Gage LLP - People - Eric S. Schmitt] biography at his law firm\n*[http://www.votesmart.org/bio.php?can_id=104474 Project vote smart] biography\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.statesurge.com/members/197832-eric-schmitt-missouri|title=Eric Schmitt - Missouri Senator|accessdate=April 6, 2009|work=[[StateSurge]]|publisher=LobbyAssist LLC}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.smartvoter.org/2008/11/04/mo/state/vote/schmitt_e|title=Voter Information for Eric Schmitt.  November 4, 2008 Election|accessdate=April 6, 2009|work=[[SmartVoter]]|publisher=League of Women Voters of California Education Fund}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-civ}}\n{{s-bef|before=Richard Magee}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[Glendale, Missouri|Glendale]] City Council<br>from Ward 3|years=2005\u20132008}}\n{{s-aft|after=Dan Sullivan}}\n|-\n{{s-par|us-mo-sen}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Michael R. Gibbons|Michael Gibbons]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[Missouri Senate]]<br>from the 15th district|years=2009\u20132017}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Andrew Koenig (politician)|Andrew Koenig]]}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Clint Zweifel]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title={{nowrap|[[State Treasurer of Missouri|Treasurer of Missouri]]}}|years=2017\u20132019}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Scott Fitzpatrick]]}}\n|-\n{{s-legal}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Josh Hawley]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Missouri Attorney General|Attorney General of Missouri]]|years=2019\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{MOAttorneysGeneral}}\n{{Current Missouri statewide political officials}}\n{{U.S. state attorneys general}}\n{{MOTreasurers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Schmitt, Eric}}\n[[Category:1975 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Missouri Attorneys General]]\n[[Category:Missouri lawyers]]\n[[Category:Missouri Republicans]]\n[[Category:Missouri state senators]]\n[[Category:People from St. Louis County, Missouri]]\n[[Category:Saint Louis University School of Law alumni]]\n[[Category:State treasurers of Missouri]]\n[[Category:Truman State University alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{about|the politician|others|Eric Schmitt (disambiguation)}}\n{{short description|American politician and lawyer}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2019}}\n{{Blacklisted-links|1=\n*http://www.lawyers.com/Missouri/Clayton/Lathrop-and-Gage-L.C.-5129555-f.html\n*:''Triggered by <code>\\blawyers\\.com\\b</code> on the local blacklist''|bot=Cyberbot II|invisible=true}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name          = Eric Schmitt\n|image         = Open Schmitt2020.png\n|office        = [[List of Attorneys General of Missouri|43rd]] [[Missouri Attorney General]]\n|governor      = [[Mike Parson]]\n|term_start    = January 3, 2019\n|term_end      = \n|predecessor   = [[Josh Hawley]]\n|successor     = \n|office1       = 46th [[State Treasurer of Missouri|Treasurer of Missouri]]\n|governor1     = [[Eric Greitens]]<br>Mike Parson\n|term_start1   = January 9, 2017\n|term_end1     = January 3, 2019\n|predecessor1  = [[Clint Zweifel]]\n|successor1    = [[Scott Fitzpatrick]]\n|state_senate2 = Missouri\n|district2     = 15th\n|term_start2   = January 7, 2009\n|term_end2     = January 4, 2017\n|predecessor2  = [[Michael R. Gibbons]]\n|successor2    = [[Andrew Koenig (politician)|Andrew Koenig]]\n|office3       = Member of the [[Glendale, Missouri|Glendale]] City Council<br>from Ward 3\n|term_start3   = 2005\n|term_end3     = 2008\n|predecessor3  = Richard Magee<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.glendalemo.org:80/Files/mayor&board.htm |title=Mayor & Board |publisher=City of Glendale, Missouri |archive-date=February 5, 2005 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050205051821/http://www.glendalemo.org/Files/mayor%26board.htm |access-date=August 10, 2019 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n|successor3    = Dan Sullivan<ref>{{cite magazine |url=http://www.glendalemo.org/wp-content/uploads/2016/10/Glendale-Guide-Summer-2008.pdf |magazine=Glendale Guide |date=Summer 2008 |title=Sullivan elected new alderman for Ward III |access-date=January 9, 2019 |publisher=City of Glendale, Missouri |page=1 }}</ref>\n|birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1975|6|20}}\n|birth_place   = [[Bridgeton, Missouri]], U.S.\n|death_date    = \n|death_place   = \n|party         = [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]]\n|spouse        = Jaime Schmitt\n|children      = 3\n|education     = [[Truman State University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])<br>[[Saint Louis University]] ([[Juris Doctor|JD]])\n|website       = {{url|http://www.ago.mo.gov/|Government website}}\n}}\n'''Eric S. Schmitt''' (born June 20, 1975) is an American politician who has been serving as the [[Missouri Attorney General|43rd Attorney General of Missouri]] since 2019. He previously served as the [[State Treasurer of Missouri|46th State Treasurer of Missouri]] from 2017 to 2019. Before that, he was a member of the [[Missouri Senate]], representing [[Missouri|Missouri's]] 15th State Senate District from 2009 to 2017. He had also previously served as an [[alderman]] for [[Glendale, Missouri]] from 2005 to 2008, where he was one of two aldermen for Ward 3.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.webstercountycitizen.com/news/article_fb16fd20-0f9e-11e9-b588-0f57c31fa636.html|title=Eric Schmitt sworn in as Missouri\u2019s 43rd Attorney General|website=Webster County Citizen|access-date=January 23, 2019}}</ref> On November 13, 2018, Schmitt was named Attorney General of Missouri by [[Governor of Missouri|Governor]] [[Mike Parson]], after the incumbent, [[Josh Hawley]], was [[2018 United States Senate election in Missouri|elected]] to the [[United States Senate]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.stltoday.com/news/local/govt-and-politics/state-treasurer-eric-schmitt-to-become-missouri-ag-after-hawley/article_aaa317fe-6919-5fe8-b48b-9b0a738fea37.html |title= State Treasurer Eric Schmitt to become Missouri AG after Hawley elected to Senate |newspaper=[[St. Louis Post-Dispatch]] |first=Jack |last=Suntrup |date=November 13, 2018 |access-date=November 13, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.kcur.org/post/missouris-next-attorney-general-will-be-state-treasurer-eric-schmitt |title= Missouri's Next Attorney General Will Be State Treasurer Eric Schmitt |publisher=[[KCUR-FM]] |date=November 13, 2018 |first=Samuel |last=King |access-date=November 13, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nBorn in [[Bridgeton, Missouri]], Schmitt is a sixth-generation Missourian and a lifelong resident of [[St. Louis County, Missouri|St. Louis County]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://schmittformissouri.com/meet-eric/|title=Meet Eric Schmitt - Eric Schmitt|access-date=September 19, 2016}}</ref>\n\nSchmitt graduated from [[DeSmet Jesuit High School]] in 1993 and from [[Truman State University]] in 1997, where he earned a [[Bachelor of Arts]] ''[[cum laude]]'' in [[political science]]. At Truman, Schmitt was a member of the [[Alpha Kappa Lambda]] fraternity, played football and baseball, and was a founding member of Truman's [[Habitat for Humanity]] chapter. He received a scholarship to attend [[Saint Louis University School of Law]], where he earned his [[Juris Doctor]] in 2000.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.senate.mo.gov/15info/Members/D15/bio.htm|title=Senator Eric Schmitt|website=www.senate.mo.gov|access-date=September 19, 2016}}</ref> Schmitt was an editor of the law review and published an article analyzing the [[Supreme Court of the United States|Supreme Court]] decision in ''[[Clinton v. New York]]''.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Schmitt|first=Eric S.|title=There Is No Joy in D.C., The Mighty Court Struck Out: An Analysis of ''Clinton v. City of New York'', The Line Item Veto Act and the Court's Failure to Uphold Constitutionally Legitimate Means to a Viable End|journal=St. Louis University Law Journal|volume=44|date=Winter 2000|page=167}}</ref>\n\nSchmitt lives in Glendale and attends Mary, Queen of Peace Catholic Church with his wife, Jaime, and their three children, Stephen, Sophia and Olivia.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://schmittformissouri.com/meet-eric/|title=Meet Eric Schmitt - Eric Schmitt|access-date=September 19, 2016}}</ref>  He is currently an adjunct professor in the Department of Philosophy at [[Saint Louis University]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.stltoday.com/news/local/education/notes-from-campus/missouri-treasurer-picks-up-a-class-at-slu-as-the/article_54da2d1c-a2c3-5742-b628-27d60bf5e0c6.html|title=Missouri treasurer picks up a class at SLU \u2014 as the teacher |last=Jost |first=Ashley|work=stltoday.com|access-date=February 20, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Legal career==\nSchmitt was [[Admission to the bar in the United States|admitted to the Missouri bar]] in 2000. He was a partner at the firm [[Lathrop & Gage|Lathrop & Gage, LLP]], in [[Clayton, Missouri]], where he focused on land use, real estate, business disputes, and administrative appeals. In his community, he has been an active member for the boards of DeSmet Jesuit High School, Nurses for Newborns Foundation, St. Louis Crisis Nursery, and a Parents as Teachers Program. He had previously been elected chairman of the Young Lawyer Section Council of the Missouri Bar, led a statewide [[Giving Tree]] effort to benefit [[Big Brothers Big Sisters of America]], and created a Special Needs Advocacy Task Force. He has also been involved with the TS (Tuberous Sclerosis) Alliance, the Gateway Chapter of the [[Autism Society of America]], Habitat for Humanity, and local Chambers of Commerce.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://claytontimes.com/lathrop-gage-congratulates-schmitt-being-appointed-attorney-general/|title=Lathrop Gage congratulates Schmitt being appointed Attorney General|last=Franklin|first=Danielle Mae|date=November 13, 2018|website=Clayton Times|access-date=January 23, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==State Senate (2009\u20132017)==\nSchmitt served as an alderman for Glendale, Missouri, from 2005 to 2008. On November 4, 2008, Schmitt was elected to the Missouri Senate. When sworn in, Schmitt became one of the youngest members ever to serve in the state's upper chamber. He represented Missouri's 15th State Senate district, which includes parts of central and western [[St. Louis County, Missouri|St. Louis County]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.senate.mo.gov/15info/Members/D15/bio.htm|title=Senator Eric Schmitt|website=www.senate.mo.gov|access-date=September 19, 2016}}</ref> Following the [[2010 United States Census|2010 census]], Schmitt's district was redrawn, although it is still centered around central St. Louis County. On February 28, 2012, Schmitt filed for reelection in the 15th district. He ran unopposed in both the primary and general elections in 2012.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sos.mo.gov/CandidatesonWeb/DisplayCandidatesPlacement.aspx?OfficeCode=SE-N15&ElectionCode=750002299|title=Certified Candidate List - State Senator - District 15|publisher=Missouri Secretary of State|accessdate=June 15, 2012}}</ref>\n\nSchmitt served in Senate Leadership as Majority Caucus Chairman and was Chairman of the Jobs, Economic Development and Local Government Committee. He also served on the Committee on Gubernatorial Appointments; the Committee on Judicial, Civil, and Criminal Jurisprudence; Veterans\u2019 Affairs and Health Committee; and Chaired the Joint Committee on Administrative Rules.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.senate.mo.gov/15info/Members/D15/bio.htm|title=Senator Eric Schmitt|website=www.senate.mo.gov|access-date=September 19, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn addition, Schmitt worked to enact the federal ABLE Act, to provide 529 savings account opportunities to families with children with special needs, to cover their future costs and allow them to be more financially independent and self-sufficient. The Missouri ABLE program allows anyone to make a tax-deductible contribution of up to $8,000 for an individual or $16,000 for married couples to another person's ABLE account.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.semissourian.com/story/2209170.html|title=Governor signs bill allowing savings accounts for disabilities|date=June 30, 2015|access-date=September 23, 2016}}</ref> The bill sponsored by Schmitt was signed by the Governor in 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://themissouritimes.com/19154/missouri-legislators-continue-autism-successes-with-bill-signature/|title=Missouri legislators continue autism successes with bill signature - The Missouri Times|website=themissouritimes.com |access-date=September 23, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Schmitt sponsored a bill (S.B. 572) that set a limit on the percent of revenue that Missouri local governments could obtain from non-traffic fines (such as fines for violation of city ordinances). Existing state law had set a revenue limit on the percent of revenue that municipalities could obtain from traffic fines The bill passed the state Senate in a 25\u20136 vote in January 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stltoday.com/news/local/govt-and-politics/cap-on-non-traffic-violation-revenue-passed-by-missouri-senate/article_093cffb2-67a6-54f6-97b8-7bc6f4e3a986.html|title=Cap on non-traffic violation revenue passed by Missouri Senate |last=Stuckey|first=Alex|access-date=September 19, 2016}}</ref>\n\nFollowing the unrest in Ferguson, Schmitt identified that too many municipalities were too reliant on fines to fund their budgets. He led the bipartisan legislative effort to bar cities, counties and law-enforcement agencies from setting traffic-ticket quotas as well as taxation by citation. Schmitt worked with Democratic Sen. Jamilah Nasheed and others on the legislation, which passed the state Senate in February 2016 and was enacted into law. <ref>https://www.stltoday.com/news/local/govt-and-politics/attorney-general-seeks-to-revive-ferguson-inspired-police-and-court/article_59777f9a-484e-575b-b92c-67643921e859.amp.html</ref> <ref>https://news.stlpublicradio.org/post/nixon-signs-bill-mandating-municipal-court-changes-and-setting-standards#stream/0</ref> <ref>https://www.wsj.com/articles/taxation-by-citation-undermines-trust-between-cops-and-citizens-1438987412</ref>\n\nSchmitt was absent in the 2013 failed vote to pass the [[LGBT rights in Missouri|Missouri Nondiscrimination Act]], and supported a 2016 failed measure to protect businesses that oppose same-sex marriages for religious reasons.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stltoday.com/news/local/govt-and-politics/missouri-attorney-general-challenges-nationwide-expansion-of-lgbt-rights-by/article_d147f283-329f-5624-a814-baf956a902c9.html|title=Missouri attorney general challenges nationwide expansion of LGBT rights by the courts|last=Suntrup|first=Jack|date=2019-08-26|website=St. Louis Post-Dispatch|language=en|access-date=2019-08-26}}</ref>\n\n==2016 election for State Treasurer==\nSchmitt did not run for re-election to the [[Missouri Senate|Missouri State Senate]] in 2016 because he was term-limited. Instead, Schmitt filed to run for [[State Treasurer of Missouri|Treasurer of Missouri]] in the [[2016 Missouri State Treasurer election|2016 elections]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://krcgtv.com/news/local/schmitt-running-for-mo-treasurer-in-2016|title=Schmitt running for MO treasurer in 2016|last=Group|first=Sinclair Broadcast|language=en-US|access-date=September 29, 2016}}</ref> Schmitt ran as a Republican and was unopposed in the Republican primary.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://s1.sos.mo.gov/candidatesonweb/DisplayCandidatesPlacement.aspx?OfficeCode=SW20&ElectionCode=750003666|title=SOS, Missouri - Elections: Offices Filed in Candidate Filing|website=s1.sos.mo.gov |access-date=September 29, 2016}}</ref> He defeated opponents Democrat [[Judy Baker]] and Libertarian Sean O'Toole in the general election.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://enrarchives.sos.mo.gov/enrnet/|title=State of Missouri - Election Night Results |website=enrarchives.sos.mo.gov|access-date=September 29, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Missouri State Treasurer (2017\u20132019)==\nAs State Treasurer, Schmitt oversaw the state's $3.6 billion investment portfolio as its Chief Financial Officer and also managed a number of different programs and initiatives.\n\n===Missouri Economic Dashboard===\n\nThe Missouri State Treasurer's Office developed a dashboard that shows economic data and trends, including unemployment, GDP, exports, housing starts, and other indicators.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.govtech.com/internet/Missouri-Treasurers-Dashboard-Compares-State-National-Financial-Metrics.html|title=Missouri Treasurer's Dashboard Compares State, National Financial Metrics |website=www.govtech.com|access-date=April 4, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Unclaimed property===\n\nSchmitt returned more unclaimed property in his first year than any previous treasurer in Missouri history. Treasurer Schmitt returned $45 million in unclaimed property during his first year in office, surpassing the previous record of $29 million.\n\nMost unclaimed property consists of cash from bank accounts, stocks, bonds and contents of safe deposit boxes that have been abandoned.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.treasurer.mo.gov/newsroom/news-and-events/2018/01/09/schmitt-returns-$45-million-of-unclaimed-property-in-first-year-as-treasurer-breaking-previous-record|title=Schmitt returns $45 million of Unclaimed Property in first year as treasurer, breaking previous record|website=www.treasurer.mo.gov|language=en|access-date=April 4, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Missouri ABLE===\nIn 2014, Congress passed the Stephen Beck Jr., Achieving a Better Life Experience (ABLE) Act to allow eligible individuals with disabilities to save money while still allowing those individuals to be eligible for federal needs-based benefits. In June 2015, then-Senator Eric Schmitt passed the state legislation, making the state a leader in the ABLE movement. Missouri ABLE was launched in April 2017.\n\nIndividuals receiving support through Social Security, Medicaid and other publicly funded programs are often disqualified from that support if they have more than $2,000 worth of resources or assets. The MO ABLE program allows qualified individuals with disabilities to save up to $14,000 a year in an ABLE account without jeopardizing their eligibility for federally funded means tested benefits, such as Supplemental Security Income (SSI) and Medicaid. The funds in the account can be used for disability-related expenses that assist the beneficiary in increasing and/or maintaining his or her health, independence or quality of life.\n\nMissouri residents who contribute to a MO ABLE account may deduct up to $8,000 (single) or $16,000 (joint) on the state income tax deduction.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ablenrc.org/news/missouri-becomes-20th-state-launch-able-program|title=Missouri Becomes 20th State to Launch ABLE Program {{!}} ABLE National Resource Center|website=www.ablenrc.org|language=en|access-date=April 4, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Missouri FIRST===\n\nSchmitt launched the Missouri FIRST initiative in March 2018. Missouri FIRST (Financing Investment in our Rural, Small Business and Technology communities) was aimed at allowing Schmitt to invest more in Main Street Missouri by revamping the state's linked deposit program, which partners with local lenders to provide low-interest financing to small business and agricultural operations. The changes implemented through Missouri FIRST focused on cutting red tape, expanding access and modernizing the linked deposit system.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.treasurer.mo.gov/content/low-interest-loans|title=Missouri State Treasurer's Office - Missouri Linked Deposit Program|website=www.treasurer.mo.gov|language=en|access-date=April 4, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===MOST 529===\n\nAs State Treasurer, Schmitt administered MOST 529, a tax-advantaged program that empowers Missouri families to save for a child's K-12 tuition and other qualified higher education expenses. Missourians who contribute to MOST 529 accounts are eligible for a tax deduction of up to $8,000 or $16,000 if married and filing jointly. Earnings in 529 accounts are also not subject to federal income tax, so long as funds are spent on qualified expenses.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.missourimost.org/home/basics-of-529s/529-basics.html|title=529 basics {{!}} MOST 529|website=MOST\u2014Missouri's 529 College Savings Plan|access-date=April 4, 2018}}</ref>\n\nPrior to the passage of federal tax reform in December 2017, MOST 529 plans were limited to higher education expenses. Included in the Tax Cuts and Jobs Act of 2017 was language that allowed states to expand their programs to K-12 tuition, which Schmitt implemented in Missouri.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.missourimost.org|title=MOST\u2014Missouri's 529 College Savings Plan {{!}} MOST 529|website=MOST\u2014Missouri's 529 College Savings Plan|access-date=April 4, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Missouri Attorney General==\nSchmitt was appointed to the office of [[Missouri Attorney General|Attorney General of Missouri]] by Governor [[Mike Parson]] to succeed [[Josh Hawley]], who was [[2018 United States Senate election in Missouri|elected]] to the [[United States Senate]] in 2018. Schmitt took office in January 2019.\n\n===First Amendment===\nIn August 2019, Schmitt withdrew a legal brief that argued that the [[First Amendment to the United States Constitution|First Amendment]] allowed government officials to withhold records from a [[Sunshine Law]] request, following criticism from transparency advocates who noted that the brief did not cite any case law.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.columbiamissourian.com/news/state_news/schmitt-withdraws-first-amendment-argument-in-lawsuit/article_1f829093-3294-5c02-9289-332ab3ddccf8.html|title=Schmitt withdraws First Amendment argument in lawsuit|last=Associated Press|date=Aug 20, 2019|website=Columbia Missourian|language=en|access-date=2019-08-26}}</ref> A Freedom Center of Missouri representative raised concern that the argument is similar to a case involving governor [[Mike Parson]], which Schmitt had not yet ruled on.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.kansascity.com/news/politics-government/article234150042.html|title=Missouri AG Schmitt cites First Amendment to block release of public records|last=Hancock|first=Jason|date=August 20, 2019|work=The Kansas City Star|access-date=2019-08-26}}</ref>\n\n===LGBTQ policies===\nSchmitt is among 14 attorney general signatories on a Supreme Court brief stating that the [[Civil Rights Act of 1964]] does not protect LGBTQ people from employment discrimination.<ref name=Hancock>{{Cite news|url=https://www.kansascity.com/news/politics-government/article234388257.html|title=Missouri attorney general says federal law doesn't ban LGBTQ discrimination|last=Hancock|first=Jason|date=August 26, 2019|work=The Kansas City Star|access-date=2019-08-26}}</ref> Schmitt said his signature \"should not be interpreted as speaking to the merits of the issue, but rather the interpretation of the law that is written,\" and that he believes \"every person, no matter their race, creed, ZIP code or gender, should be treated with dignity under the law\",<ref name=\"Hancock\" /> however critics dismiss this as \"legalese\" and \"on the wrong side of history.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.kansascity.com/opinion/editorials/article234396897.html|title=Missouri AG justifies LGBT discrimination with legalese. He's on wrong side of history|author=Editorial Board|date=August 27, 2019|work=The Kansas City Star|url-status=live|url-access=subscription|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190914023906/https://www.kansascity.com/opinion/editorials/article234396897.html|archive-date=September 14, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Religious freedom===\nIn 2019, Schmitt spoke in defense of a Missouri high school coach who was being attacked by the [[Freedom From Religion Foundation]]. The foundation accused the football coach of violating the [[Constitution of the United States|U.S. Constitution]] by leading students in prayer before and after games. In a letter, Schmitt said he would support the coach, school, and school district in a lawsuit if necessary and noted no one was forcing students and players to participate in prayer in public spaces.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://apnews.com/8163541b1efe40a9fd0944adcf588683 |title=Missouri attorney general backs high school football prayer |agency=Associated Press |date=December 6, 2019 |access-date=January 20, 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite press release |url=https://ago.mo.gov/docs/default-source/press-releases/2019/2019-12-3-ltr-cameronschooldistrict.pdf |date=December 3, 2019 |first=Eric |last=Schmitt |title=Letter to Cameron School District |access-date=January 20, 2020 |publisher=Attorney General of Missouri }}</ref>\n\n===Human trafficking ===\n\nSchmitt's Attorney General office has partnered with the FBI's Child Exploitation and Human Trafficking Task Force to combat human trafficking in Missouri.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.missourinet.com/2019/05/21/missouri-attorney-generals-office-joins-fb-efforts-to-fight-human-trafficking-exploiting-children/ |title=Missouri Attorney General's office joins FBI efforts to fight human trafficking, exploiting children |date=May 21, 2019 |website=Missourinet |first=Alisa |last=Nelson |access-date=February 7, 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ktvo.com/news/local/missouri-attorney-general-eric-schmitt-working-to-combat-human-trafficking |title=Missouri Attorney General Eric Schmitt working to combat human trafficking |date=May 14, 2019 |publisher=KTVO |first=Ashley |last=Hoak |access-date=February 7, 2020 }}</ref>\n\n===Prosecution of Antonio Muldrew===\nIn January 2020, Schmitt successfully prosecuted a murder case in the City of St. Louis. The jury returned a quick verdict finding Antonio Muldrew guilty of first-degree murder for shooting and killing Ethiopian refugee Abdulrauf Kadir at a convenience store in 2014. This was the first time a Missouri attorney general prosecuted a murder case in the City of St. Louis.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://fox2now.com/2020/01/09/missouri-attorney-general-obtains-guilty-verdict-in-st-louis-murder-case/ |title=Missouri attorney general obtains guilty verdict in St. Louis murder case |date=January 9, 2020 |first=Vic |last=Faust |publisher=Fox News |access-date=January 20, 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.ksdk.com/article/news/crime/ethiopian-refugee-dutchtown-store-guilty-murder/63-0ce6a782-27d3-4bd1-b29d-77894f0e50f7 |title=Man accused of killing Ethiopian refugee in Dutchtown store found guilty of murder, 5 other charges |first=Sam |last=Clancy |date=January 8, 2020 |publisher=KSDK |access-date=January 20, 2020 }}</ref>\n\n===Google antitrust investigation===\n \nIn September 2019, Schmitt and Attorneys General from throughout the U.S. launched an antitrust investigation against Google. The bipartisan group of state Attorneys General accuse Google of prioritizing searches for companies that advertise on the search engine platform.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://news.stlpublicradio.org/post/schmitt-joins-state-attorneys-general-investigating-google#stream/0 |title=Schmitt Joins State Attorneys General Investigating Google |date=September 9, 2019 |publisher=St. Louis Public Radio |first=Jaclyn |last=Driscoll |access-date=February 12, 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://molawyersmedia.com/2019/09/10/big-tech-faces-a-new-set-of-foes-nearly-all-50-u-s-states-2/ |title=Big Tech faces a new set of foes: nearly all 50 U.S. states |date=September 10, 2019 |website=Missouri Lawyers Media |agency=Associated Press |access-date=February 12, 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.ozarksfirst.com/attorney-general-eric-schmitt-apart-of-team-investigating-large-tech-companies |title=Attorney General Eric Schmitt apart of team investigating large tech companies |date=September 7, 2019 |access-date=February 12, 2020 |website=Ozarks First }}</ref>\n\n===Safer Streets Initiative===\n \nThe Safer Streets Initiative was unveiled in January 2019 by Schmitt to help get violent criminals off the street faster. The initiative is designed to address violent crime in St. Louis, Kansas City and Springfield, which have been ranked in the Top 15 for per capita violent crime rates. Schmitt says this is the first partnership in the country between the Missouri Attorney General's Office, U.S. Attorney's Office and various local law enforcement units to address violent crime.<ref>{{cite press release |url=https://www.ago.mo.gov/home/news-archives/2019/06/13/ag-schmitt-announces-safer-streets-initiative |title=AG Schmitt Announces Safer Streets Initiative |date=June 13, 2019 |publisher=Missouri Attorney General's Office |access-date=February 12, 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://fox4kc.com/2019/10/10/missouris-attorney-general-says-kcs-catch-and-release-of-criminals-must-end/ |title=Missouri's attorney general says KC's 'catch and release' of criminals must end |date=October 10, 2019 |website=FOX4 KC |first=John |last=Pepitone |access-date=February 12, 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.kmov.com/news/missouri-attorney-general-schmitt-unveils-safer-streets-initiative/article_d00aebd6-1e40-11e9-bce4-f33d50862a85.html |title=Missouri Attorney General Schmitt unveils 'Safer Streets' initiative |date=January 22, 2019 |publisher=KMOV |access-date=February 12, 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.stltoday.com/opinion/columnists/working-toward-safer-streets/article_aa2a676c-a208-5136-84e2-fa975f04c43b.html |title=Working toward safer streets |date=February 5, 2019 |newspaper=St. Louis Post-Dispatch |first=Eric |last=Schmitt |access-date=February 12, 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.ktrs.com/five-u-s-attorneys-sworn-in-for-safer-streets-initiative/ |title=Five U.S. Attorneys Sworn In for Safer Streets Initiative |date=April 11, 2019 |publisher=KTRS |access-date=February 12, 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.stltoday.com/news/local/crime-and-courts/joint-federal-state-effort-getting-violent-criminals-off-st-louis/article_aab47fa9-5b7c-5523-a948-2e23691e0ebe.html |title=Joint federal-state effort getting violent criminals off St. Louis streets, prosecutors say |date=October 8, 2019 |first=Robert |last=Patrick |newspaper=St. Louis Post-Dispatch |access-date=February 12, 2020 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.stltoday.com/news/state-and-regional/indictments-brought-under-st-louis-anti-crime-effort/article_7ab5f825-f102-504e-b21c-893deb53bf2c.html |title=58 indictments brought under St. Louis anti-crime effort |newspaper=St. Louis Post-Dispatch |date=October 8, 2019 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191008225009/https://www.stltoday.com/news/state-and-regional/indictments-brought-under-st-louis-anti-crime-effort/article_7ab5f825-f102-504e-b21c-893deb53bf2c.html |archive-date=October 8, 2019 }}</ref>\n\n==Electoral history==\n{{Election box begin | title=2008 Missouri State Senate - District 15<ref>{{cite web |publisher=Missouri Secretary of State |url=http://www.sos.mo.gov/enrweb/raceresults.asp?eid=256&oid=56352&arc=1 |title=State Senator - District 15 - Summary |accessdate=June 15, 2012}}</ref>}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n|  |party      = Republican Party (United States)\n  |candidate  = Eric Schmitt\n  |votes      = 51,366\n  |percentage = 54.7\n  |change     = \n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n|  |party      = Democratic Party (United States)\n  |candidate  = James Trout\n  |votes      = 42,469\n  |percentage = 45.3\n  |change     = \n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n{{Election box begin|title=2012 Missouri State Senate - District 15<ref>{{cite web |publisher=Missouri Secretary of State |url=http://enrarchives.sos.mo.gov/enrnet/PickaRace.aspx |title=State Senator - District 15 - Summary |accessdate=June 15, 2012}}</ref>}}{{Election box winning candidate with party link||candidate=Eric Schmitt|party=Republican Party (United States)|votes=77,745|percentage=100|change=+45.3}}{{Election box end}}\n\n{{Election box begin |title=Missouri Treasurer Election 2016<ref>{{cite web |url=https://enrarchives.sos.mo.gov/enrnet/default.aspx?eid=750003949 |title=State of Missouri - General Election, November 08, 2016 |date=December 12, 2016 |publisher=Missouri Secretary of State |access-date=November 13, 2018}}</ref>}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n  | |party = Republican Party (US)\n  |candidate  = Eric Schmitt\n  |votes      = 1,545,582\n  |percentage = 56.447%\n  |change     = Winner\n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n  | |party = Democratic Party (US)\n  |candidate  = Judy Baker\n  |votes      = 1,078,063\n  |percentage = 39.372%\n  |change     = \n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n  | |party = Libertarian Party (US)\n  |candidate  = Sean O'Toole\n  |votes      = 78,543\n  |percentage = 2.868%\n  |change     = \n}}\n{{Election box candidate with party link\n  | |party = Green Party (US)\n  |candidate  = Carol Hexem\n  |votes      = 66,490\n  |percentage = 1.312%\n  |change     = \n}}\n{{Election box end}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikiquote}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20090102055848/http://www.lathropgage.com/eschmitt/ Lathrop & Gage LLP - People - Eric S. Schmitt] biography at his law firm\n*[http://www.votesmart.org/bio.php?can_id=104474 Project vote smart] biography\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.statesurge.com/members/197832-eric-schmitt-missouri|title=Eric Schmitt - Missouri Senator|accessdate=April 6, 2009|work=[[StateSurge]]|publisher=LobbyAssist LLC}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://www.smartvoter.org/2008/11/04/mo/state/vote/schmitt_e|title=Voter Information for Eric Schmitt.  November 4, 2008 Election|accessdate=April 6, 2009|work=[[SmartVoter]]|publisher=League of Women Voters of California Education Fund}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-civ}}\n{{s-bef|before=Richard Magee}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[Glendale, Missouri|Glendale]] City Council<br>from Ward 3|years=2005\u20132008}}\n{{s-aft|after=Dan Sullivan}}\n|-\n{{s-par|us-mo-sen}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Michael R. Gibbons|Michael Gibbons]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Member of the [[Missouri Senate]]<br>from the 15th district|years=2009\u20132017}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Andrew Koenig (politician)|Andrew Koenig]]}}\n|-\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Clint Zweifel]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title={{nowrap|[[State Treasurer of Missouri|Treasurer of Missouri]]}}|years=2017\u20132019}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Scott Fitzpatrick]]}}\n|-\n{{s-legal}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Josh Hawley]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Missouri Attorney General|Attorney General of Missouri]]|years=2019\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{MOAttorneysGeneral}}\n{{Current Missouri statewide political officials}}\n{{U.S. state attorneys general}}\n{{MOTreasurers}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Schmitt, Eric}}\n[[Category:1975 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Missouri Attorneys General]]\n[[Category:Missouri lawyers]]\n[[Category:Missouri Republicans]]\n[[Category:Missouri state senators]]\n[[Category:People from St. Louis County, Missouri]]\n[[Category:Saint Louis University School of Law alumni]]\n[[Category:State treasurers of Missouri]]\n[[Category:Truman State University alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Cocap31", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eMissouri Attorney General", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eric_Schmitt"}
{"title_page": "Anne Meskanen", "text_new": "{{Update|date=March 2020}}\n'''Anne Meskanen''' is a Finnish diplomat. She is the Finnish Ambassador to [[Kabul]], [[Afghanistan]] and has been in charge since 1 September 2015.<ref name=\"tpk\">[http://www.tpk.fi/Public/default.aspx?contentid=322399&nodeid=44810&contentlan=1&culture=fi-FI Tasavallan presidentin esittely 6.3.2015.] Viitattu 18.4.2017</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.acci.org.af/component/content/article/38-news/626-leadership-of-acci-met-with-her-excellency-anne-meskanen-ambassador-of-finland-to-afghanistan.html|title=Leadership of ACCI met with Her Excellency Anne Meskanen Ambassador of Finland to Afghanistan|website=www.acci.org.af|language=en-gb|access-date=2017-12-22}}</ref> The mission was closed in March 2017 when [[March 2017 Kabul attack|a terrorist attack]] took place nearby.<ref>[http://yle.fi/uutiset/3-9497178 Suomen suurl\u00e4hetyst\u00f6 Afganistanissa suljettiin maaliskuussa 2017, kun 500 metrin p\u00e4\u00e4ss\u00e4 oli tapahtunut hy\u00f6kk\u00e4ys. Ylen uutiset] 8.3.2017. Viitattu 18.4.2017</ref>\n\nMeskanen has worked in Finland at the [[Ministry for Foreign Affairs (Finland)|Ministry for Foreign Affairs]]' General Global Affairs Unit.<ref name=\"formin\">[http://www.finland.lt/public/default.aspx?contentid=87331&nodeid=38422&contentlan=1&culture=fi-FI Marjatta Rasi kutsuttu YK:n rauhanrakentamisrahaston neuvonantajaksi. Suomen suurl\u00e4hetyst\u00f6, Vilna.] 12.3.2007. Viitattu 18.4.2017</ref>\n\n==Biography==\n\nMeskanen earned a master's degree in Political Science from the University of Helsinki before working as a journalist and foreign correspondent for the [[Demokraatti|Demari Newspaper]].<ref name=\"EWC\">{{cite web |title=ANNE MESKANEN: LITERACY ENHANCES WOMEN'S OPPORTUNITIES |url=http://eawfpress.ru/en/anne-meskanen-literacy-enhances-women-s-opportunities/ |website=Eurasian Women\u2019s Community |accessdate=6 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULT