 Science from the University of Helsinki before working as a journalist and foreign correspondent for the [[Demokraatti|Demari Newspaper]].<ref name=\"EWC\">{{cite web |title=ANNE MESKANEN: LITERACY ENHANCES WOMEN'S OPPORTUNITIES |url=http://eawfpress.ru/en/anne-meskanen-literacy-enhances-women-s-opportunities/ |website=Eurasian Women\u2019s Community |accessdate=6 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n== References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Meskanen, Anne}}\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Finland to Afghanistan]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Finnish women diplomats]]\n[[Category:Finnish women ambassadors]]\n[[Category:University of Helsinki alumni]]\n[[Category:Finnish women journalists]]\n[[Category:Finnish reporters and correspondents]]\n\n\n{{Finland-bio-stub}}\n{{diplomat-stub}}\n\n{{Improve categories|date=March 2020}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eBiography:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: master\u2019s degree \u2192 master's degree", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anne_Meskanen"}
{"title_page": "Elleck Mashingaidze", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=December 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2016}}\n'''Elleck Kufakunesu Mashingaidze''' (born 4 Apr|il 1939) is a historian and [[diplomat]] from [[Zimbabwe]]. He served as Zimbabwe's first [[Zimbabwean Ambassador to the United States|Ambassador to the United States of America]] and Zimbabwe's first Permanent Representative to the [[United Nations]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Zimbabwe Is Welcomed Into U.N. |url= |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=26 August 1980 |page=A4 }}</ref> He twice held the post of President of the [[United Nations Security Council]] (1983 and 1984).\n\nHe earned a [[PhD]] from the [[University of York]].\n\nHe co-authored the history book \"From Iron Age to Independence\" ({{ISBN|9780582651111}})\n\nHe was born in [[Mberengwa (District)|Mberengwa]], [[Zimbabwe]] and is a member of the [[Lemba people|Lemba]] tribe. He is married to Sylvia Jane Mashingaidze (d. September 2009). They have two children: Kundai Mashingaidze and Tapiwa Mashingaidze.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[http://www.wheelers.co.nz/books/9780582651111-from-iron-age-to-independence-history-of-central-africa/ From Iron Age to Independence]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mashingaidze, Elleck}}\n[[Category:1939 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Zimbabwe to the United States]]\n[[Category:Permanent Representatives of Zimbabwe to the United Nations]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of York]]\n\n\n{{Zimbabwe-politician-stub}}\n{{africa-diplomat-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=December 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2016}}\n'''Elleck Kufakunesu Mashingaidze''' (born 4 Apr|il 1939) is a historian and [[diplomat]] from [[Zimbabwe]]. He served as Zimbabwe\u2019s first [[Zimbabwean Ambassador to the United States|Ambassador to the United States of America]] and Zimbabwe\u2019s first Permanent Representative to the [[United Nations]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Zimbabwe Is Welcomed Into U.N. |url= |work=[[The New York Times]] |date=26 August 1980 |page=A4 }}</ref> He twice held the post of President of the [[United Nations Security Council]] (1983 and 1984).\n\nHe earned a [[PhD]] from the [[University of York]].\n\nHe co-authored the history book \"From Iron Age to Independence\" ({{ISBN|9780582651111}})\n\nHe was born in [[Mberengwa (District)|Mberengwa]], [[Zimbabwe]] and is a member of the [[Lemba people|Lemba]] tribe. He is married to Sylvia Jane Mashingaidze (d. September 2009). They have two children: Kundai Mashingaidze and Tapiwa Mashingaidze.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[http://www.wheelers.co.nz/books/9780582651111-from-iron-age-to-independence-history-of-central-africa/ From Iron Age to Independence]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mashingaidze, Elleck}}\n[[Category:1939 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of Zimbabwe to the United States]]\n[[Category:Permanent Representatives of Zimbabwe to the United Nations]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of York]]\n\n\n{{Zimbabwe-politician-stub}}\n{{africa-diplomat-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's (2)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Elleck_Mashingaidze"}
